{"title_page": "The Voice in the Wilderness", "text_new": "{{short description|1991 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Voice in the Wilderness\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Vigen Chaldranyan]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = [[Aghasi Ayvazyan]]\n| starring       = [[Vigen Chaldranyan]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|1991}}\n| runtime        = 132 minutes\n| country        = Armenia\n| language       = Armenian\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Voice in the Wilderness''''' ({{lang-hy|'''Dzayn barbaro...'''}}) is a 1991 Armenian [[drama film]] directed by [[Vigen Chaldranyan]]. It was entered into the [[18th Moscow International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Moscow1993\">{{cite web |url=http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1993 |title=18th Moscow International Film Festival (1993) |accessdate=9 March 2013 |work=MIFF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140403093721/http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1993 |archivedate=3 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Vigen Chaldranyan]] as Martiros\n* [[Marine Ghukasyan]] as Colombina / Woman from East / Cornelia / Fortuneteller\n* [[Mikael Pogosyan]] as Tomazo (as Mikael Poghosyan)\n* [[Karen Dzhanibekyan]] as Yunus\n* [[Ara Stepanyan]] as Old Armenian pilgrim\n* [[Vladimir Msryan]]\n* [[Rafael Kotanjyan]]\n* [[Rudolf Gevondyan]] as Mustafa (as Rudolf Ghevondyan)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0104157|The Voice in the Wilderness}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Voice In The Wilderness}}\n[[Category:1991 films]]\n[[Category:1991 drama films]]\n[[Category:Armenian films]]\n[[Category:Armenian-language films]]\n[[Category:Armenian drama films]]\n\n\n{{Armenia-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1991 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Voice in the Wilderness\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Vigen Chaldranyan]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = [[Aghasi Ayvazyan]]\n| starring       = [[Vigen Chaldranyan]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|1991}}\n| runtime        = 132 minutes\n| country        = Armenia\n| language       = Armenian\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Voice in the Wilderness''''' ({{lang-hy|'''Dzayn barbaro...'''}}) is a 1991 Armenian [[drama film]] directed by [[Vigen Chaldranyan]]. It was entered into the [[18th Moscow International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Moscow1993\">{{cite web |url=http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1993 |title=18th Moscow International Film Festival (1993) |accessdate=9 March 2013 |work=MIFF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140403093721/http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1993 |archivedate=3 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Vigen Chaldranyan]] as Martiros\n* [[Marine Ghukasyan]] as Colombina / Woman from East / Cornelia / Fortuneteller\n* [[Mikael Pogosyan]] as Tomazo (as Mikael Poghosyan)\n* [[Karen Dzhanibekyan]] as Yunus\n* [[Ara Stepanyan]] as Old Armenian pilgrim\n* [[Vladimir Msryan]]\n* [[Rafael Kotanjyan]]\n* [[Rudolf Gevondyan]] as Mustafa (as Rudolf Ghevondyan)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0104157|The Voice in the Wilderness}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Voice In The Wilderness}}\n[[Category:1991 films]]\n[[Category:1991 drama films]]\n[[Category:Armenian films]]\n[[Category:Armenian-language films]]\n[[Category:Armenian drama films]]\n\n\n{{Armenia-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Voice_in_the_Wilderness"}
{"title_page": "James John Joicey", "text_new": "{{short description|English amateur entomologist (1870\u20131932)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = James John Joicey\n| honorific_suffix   = [[Fellow of the Royal Geographical Society|FRGS]] [[Linnean Society of London|FLS]] [[Zoological Society of London|FZS]] [[Royal Entomological Society|FES]] [[Royal Horticultural Society|FRHS]]\n| image              = BulletinHillMuseum1921HillMuseumJoicey cropped.jpg\n| alt                = Sepia portrait photograph of middle-aged gentleman in suit and hat in 1920\n| birth_date         = 28 December 1870\n| birth_place        = [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], England\n| death_date         = 10 March 1932\n| death_place        = The Hill, [[Witley]], [[Surrey]], England\n| burial_place       = Holy Trinity Church, [[Sunningdale]]\n| occupation         = Amateur [[entomologist]]\n| known_for          = Assembling a collection of over 1.5 million [[Lepidoptera]] specimens, his Hill Museum research output, and his presentations from his collection to the [[Natural History Museum]]\n| notable_works      = ''The Bulletin of the Hill Museum'' 1921\u20131932<ref name=\"Bulletin1\"/><ref name=\"Bulletin2\"/><ref name=\"Bulletin3\"/><ref name=\"Bulletin4\"/>\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Maud Muriel Fisher|1896}}\n| relatives          = [[James Joicey, 1st Baron Joicey|1st Baron Joicey]] (father's cousin)<ref name=\"Major\"/>\n}}\n\n'''James John Joicey''' [[Royal Entomological Society|FES]] (28 December 1870 \u2013 10 March 1932) was an English amateur [[entomologist]], who assembled an extensive collection of [[Lepidoptera]] in his private research museum, called the Hill Museum, in [[Witley]], [[Surrey]]. His collection, 40 years in the making, was considered to have been the second largest in the world held privately and to have numbered over 1.5 million [[Biological specimen|specimens]]. Joicey was a [[fellow]] of the [[Zoological Society of London]], the [[Fellow of the Royal Geographical Society|Royal Geographical Society]], the [[Royal Entomological Society]], the [[Royal Horticultural Society]], and the [[Linnean Society of London]].\n\nJoicey employed specialist entomologists including [[George Talbot (entomologist)|George Talbot]] to curate his collection and financed numerous expeditions throughout the world to obtain previously unknown varieties. Over 190 scientific articles were produced during the active period of the Hill Museum. This body of research was described as \"a contribution to the study of the exotic Lepidoptera of very great scientific value.\"<ref name=\"Riley\" />{{Rp|144}}\n\nJoicey's donations from his collection, made both during his life and following his death, contributed significantly to the quality and numerical predominance of the Lepidoptera collection held by the [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]], [[London]]. Joicey's obituary in ''[[Royal Entomological Society|The Entomologist]]'' described him as \"undoubtedly the most lavish patron of Entomology, in so far as butterflies and moths are concerned, that this country has ever boasted\".<ref name=\"Riley\" />{{Rp|142}}\n\n==Life==\n===Background===\nJames John Joicey was born on 28 December 1870 in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], the only child of Major William James Joicey, a wealthy coal owner, and Mary Anne Joicey n\u00e9e Clark.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Births|last=|first=|date=6 January 1871|work=The Newcastle Courant|access-date=|page=8}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Marriages|last=|first=|date=20 March 1868|work=The Newcastle Courant|access-date=|page=8}}</ref><ref name=\"Major\" /> He was educated at [[Aysgarth School]], [[Yorkshire]], and [[Hertford College, Oxford|Hertford College]], [[Oxford]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Mr. J. J. Joicey Owner of \u00a350,000 Collection of Butterflies|last=|first=|date=12 March 1932|work=Yorkshire Post and Leeds Intelligencer|access-date=|page=14}}</ref> and was an Associate Member of the [[Institution of Mining Engineers|Institute of Mining Engineers]] from 1891.<ref name=\"IME\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1913|title=List of Members, August 3, 1912|url=https://archive.org/details/transactions62nort/page/n361/mode/1up|journal=Transactions of the North of England Institute of Mining and Mechanical Engineers|volume=LXII|pages=xlvi|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> He was also a member of the [[Junior Carlton Club]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/countyfamiliesof591919walf|title=Walford's County Families of the United Kingdom|last=|first=|publisher=Ballantyne & Co. Ltd.|year=1919|isbn=|location=London|pages=[https://archive.org/details/countyfamiliesof591919walf/page/734 734]|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nJoicey married Maud Muriel Fisher (later Baroness de Satg\u00e9) in London in 1896.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Marriages|last=|first=|date=20 October 1896|work=The Standard|access-date=|page=1}}</ref> He lived at The Hill in [[Witley]], [[Surrey]], from about 1912.{{Refn|The 1911 Census of England shows another family living at The Hill in April 1911 and Joicey had notified the Institute of Mining Engineers of his address at The Hill by August 1912.<ref name=\"IME\"/> He is also listed in London electoral registers from 1920 to 1925 at [[Marble Arch#Marble Arch area|Marble Arch]] as Admiral Joicey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ancestry.com|title=London, England, Electoral Registers, 1832\u20131965: Paddington and St Marylebone, Polling District F, No. 5, Bryanston Square Ward, 1921\u20131925|last=|first=|date=|website=ancestry.com|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n===Collecting===\nJoicey's boyhood interest in insects was encouraged by his parents and at the age of sixteen he put together a small collection of British and foreign [[Butterfly|butterflies]].<ref name=\"Riley\">{{Cite journal|last=Riley|first=N. D.|date=1932|title=Obituary: James John Joicey|url=|journal=The Entomologist|volume=65|pages=142\u2013144|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article90080883|title=A \u00a3100,000 Hobby. The Rarest Pair of Wings in the World. Facing Death for a Butterfly|last=|first=|date=24 September 1927|work=The Adelaide Chronicle|access-date=22 November 2019|url-status=live|page=76}}</ref> As an adult, he happened upon the forgotten cabinets of his boyhood collection and was inspired to start collecting in earnest,<ref name=\":9\" /> his active interest dating from 1906.<ref name=\"Bulletin1\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/bulletinofh112192122hill/page/n9|title=The Bulletin of the Hill Museum: A Magazine of Lepidoptera|last=|first=|publisher=John Bale, Sons and Danielsson Ltd|year=1924|isbn=|editor-last=Joicey|editor-first=J. J.|volume=1|location=London|pages=|access-date=6 December 2019|editor-last2=Talbot|editor-first2=G.}}</ref> He used his resources to \"indulge a taste for collecting butterflies and [[moth]]s which remained with him throughout his life.\" He travelled \"in the East\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Obituary \u2013 Mr. J. J. Joicey \u2013 Gifts to the Natural History Museum|last=|first=|date=16 March 1932|work=The Times|access-date=|page=9}}</ref> as a young man and, although he employed experts to collect most of his specimens, also collected \"on his own account both here and abroad\"<ref name=\":9\" /> and \"travelled widely in Europe, India, China, Japan, Burma and America\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=|title=\u00a350,000 Collection of Butterflies. Death of an Eminent Naturalist|last=|first=|date=12 March 1932|work=Sheffield Independent|access-date=|page=5}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=Who Was Who: 1929\u20131940|last=|first=|publisher=Adam & Charles Black|year=1960|isbn=|location=London|pages=722}}</ref> In 1913, he built and financed a private research museum, the Hill Museum, at his home in Witley, employing a [[curator]] and seven assistants.<ref name=\":1\" /> In one twelve-month period he collected some 17,000 specimens from across the world and was spending up to \u00a310,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=10000|start_year=1919|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}) a year on the collection.<ref name=\":9\" /> Joicey said:\n\n<blockquote>How did I manage to spend \u00a310,000 a year on this collection? Well, these did not come from my back garden. I have had to send collectors to the far ends of the earth. ... When my work is done \u2013 that is, when I die \u2013 I will present the collection to the nation.<ref name=\":6\" />{{pb}}The work has been the ruling passion of my life, ... I don't think I am extravagant, as my researches and investigations will be of great value to the nation.<ref name=\":0\" /></blockquote>\n\nJoicey became a fellow of the Zoological Society of London in 1890,<ref>{{Cite book|title=A List of the Fellows of the Zoological Society of London|last=|first=|publisher=William Clowes and Sons, Limited|year=1924|isbn=|location=London|pages=85}}</ref> a fellow of the Royal Geographical Society in 1903,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1903|title=Meetings of the Royal Geographical Society, Sessions 1903\u20131904|url=https://archive.org/details/geographicaljou40britgoog/page/n744/mode/1up|journal=The Geographical Journal|volume=XXII|pages=709|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> a fellow of the Entomological Society in 1908 (council member 1920\u20131923),<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/transactionsofen1915roya/page/n23|title=Transactions of the Entomological Society of London 1915|last=|first=|publisher=Longmans, Green & Co.|year=1915|isbn=|location=London|pages=xix|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref> a fellow of the Royal Horticultural Society in 1912,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1912|title=Extracts from the Proceedings of the Royal Horticultural Society|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.240657/page/n779/mode/1up|journal=The Journal of the Royal Horticultural Society|volume=xxxviii|pages=xxii|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> a fellow of the Linnean Society of London in 1913,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1914|title=December 4th, 1913|url=https://archive.org/details/proceedingsoflin191215linn/page/n174/mode/1up|journal=Proceedings of the Linnean Society|volume=126|pages=3|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> a life member of the [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 entomologique de France]] in 1921,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1931|title=Liste des membres de la soci\u00e9t\u00e9 entomologique de France arr\u00eat\u00e9e au 10 janvier 1930|url=https://www.persee.fr/doc/bsef_0037-928x_1931_num_36_1_28972|journal=Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 entomologique de France|volume=36|issue=1|pages=XXVIII|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> and a member of the [http://lnhs.org.uk/ London Natural History Society] in 1928.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1932|title=Obituary|url=https://archive.org/details/londonnaturalist1931lond/page/n51/mode/1up|journal=The London Naturalist|volume=1931|pages=38|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref>\n\nAs well as amateur entomologist, Joicey was a well-known amateur [[Orchidaceae|orchidist]] and exhibited at meetings of the Royal Horticultural Society.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1932|title=Obituary|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=7nUhAQAAIAAJ&q=joicey|journal=The Orchid Review|volume=40|pages=118|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref>\n\n===Finances===\nJoicey could afford to build his collection of Lepidoptera through his family connection with the firm of \"Messrs. James Joicey & Co., Ltd, coalowners, Newcastle\", founded by his grandfather.<ref name=\"Major\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Major Joicey Dead. His Association with Local Coal Industry. Popular Turf Personality|last=|first=|date=24 January 1912|work=The Newcastle Daily Chronicle|access-date=|url-status=live|page=7}}</ref> Although described as having been \"nominally on the [[Stock exchange|Stock Exchange]] from 1896 to 1899\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Unable to Live on \u00a38,000 a Year|last=|first=|date=9 July 1910|work=Framlingham Weekly News|access-date=|url-status=live|page=4}}</ref> then, in 1901, as a \"coal owner & ship owner\",<ref>1901 Census of England and Wales. RG12/814</ref> and, in 1913, as a director of the family coal mining firm,<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=James Joicey & Co. Limited|last=|first=|date=1 December 1913|work=The Times|access-date=|page=10}}</ref> Joicey effectively had no occupation and throughout his life subsisted on substantial allowances from his parents. However, his income proved insufficient for his \"extravagance in living\" and the interest rates charged by money-lenders. Joicey became [[Bankruptcy|bankrupt]] in 1909 with a deficiency of over \u00a3185,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=185000|start_year=1909|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}), and again in 1922 with a deficiency of over \u00a3430,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=430000|start_year=1922|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}) despite his mother having given him \u00a3300,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=300000|start_year=1921|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}) in the interim.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=King's Bench Division. In re Joicey|last=|first=|date=8 July 1910|work=The Times|access-date=|page=3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Borrowed Half a Million. Young Man's Dealings with Moneylenders|last=|first=|date=8 February 1922|work=Daily Mail|access-date=|url-status=live|page=6}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Millionaire's Son Again Bankrupt|last=|first=|date=10 February 1922|work=The Times|access-date=|page=7}}</ref> The latter bankruptcy was discharged in October 1931.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Mr. J. J. Joicey's Bankruptcy|last=|first=|date=16 October 1926|work=The Times|access-date=|page=4}}</ref><ref name=\":7\" />\n\n{{Quote box\n| quote = The son of a millionaire, for him money meant only one thing \u2013 more butterflies, still rarer specimens than he had already.\n| source = [[George Talbot (entomologist)|George Talbot]], Joicey's head curator, 1932<ref name=\"Insects\" />\n| align = right\n| width = 300px\n}}\n\nJoicey's father, at one time a millionaire, had left over \u00a3700,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=700000|start_year=1912|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}) in his [[Estate (law)|estate]] in 1912, but his will ensured that no money went directly to his son.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Man Unable to Live on \u00a320,000 a Year|last=|first=|date=15 October 1926|work=Western Morning News|access-date=|url-status=live|page=3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Will of the Late Major W. J. Joicey|last=|first=|date=27 March 1912|work=Newcastle Daily Chronicle|access-date=|page=2}}</ref> The Witley house and estate were bought for Joicey after his first bankruptcy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Wild Extravagance. Debts of \u00a3400,000 in Second Bankruptcy. Remarkable Figures|last=|first=|date=15 October 1926|work=Western Times|access-date=|page=12}}</ref> When sued by [[creditor]]<nowiki/>s in 1919, the judge said, \"He seems hardly to have grown up. He seems to have infantile tastes which his mother helps him gratify.\" When [[counsel]] stated that Joicey was \"susceptible to the wiles of the money-lenders\", the judge responded, \"And to the wiles of the butterflies.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=King's Bench Division. A Butterfly Collector and Moneylenders. Jacobs Brothers v. Joicey|last=|first=|date=31 March 1919|work=The Times|access-date=|url-status=live|page=4}}</ref> During the 1922 bankruptcy hearing, Joicey said, \"I think the money seems to have gone like snow in an oven.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Money Went Like Snow in Oven|last=|first=|date=7 March 1922|work=Pall Mall Gazette|access-date=|page=5}}</ref>\n\n===Death===\nJoicey's mother died in 1930, leaving an estate valued at over \u00a3300,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=300000|start_year=1930|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://probatesearch.service.gov.uk/Calendar#calendar|title=Find a will|last=Joicey|first=Mary|date=1930|website=GOV.UK|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 November 2019}}</ref> Towards the end of his life, Joicey became an \"invalid\".<ref name=\"Insects\">{{Cite news|url=|title=\u00a310,000 A Year for Butterflies \u2013 Insects Men Died to Get \u2013 Wonder Collection for Nation|last=|first=|date=15 March 1932|work=Dundee Evening Telegraph|access-date=|page=9}}</ref> He died of heart failure on 10 March 1932 at his home, The Hill, in Witley, Surrey, aged 61.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=21 March 1932|title=Milestones|url=|journal=Time Magazine|volume=XIX|issue=12|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Deaths|last=|first=|date=14 March 1932|work=The Times|access-date=|page=1}}</ref> He was buried at Holy Trinity Church, [[Sunningdale]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Arrangements for Today|last=|first=|date=16 March 1932|work=The Times|access-date=|page=17}}</ref> Joicey's estate was valued at \u00a31,151 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=1151|start_year=1932|r=-2|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://probatesearch.service.gov.uk/Calendar#calendar|title=Find a will|last=Joicey|first=James John|date=1932|website=GOV.UK|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 November 2019}}</ref> his collection and museum having been principally paid for and owned by his mother.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Museum Bequest of Northern Bankrupt|last=|first=|date=7 June 1932|work=Sunderland Daily Echo and Shipping Gazette|access-date=|page=1}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Hambledon and Witley Estates|last=|first=|date=28 May 1932|work=The Surrey Advertiser and County Times|access-date=|page=7}}</ref>\n\n== Collections ==\n{{Quote box\n| quote = The primary object of Mr. Joicey in making this collection of Lepidoptera is to advance in some way our scientific knowledge. ... The formation of a large collection has its value, because without access to plenty of material studies can only be incomplete and results are often erroneous. ... <br/>\nNo apology should be needed for amassing large collections ...\n| source = George Talbot, 1924<ref name=\"Bulletin1\" />{{Rp|5}}\n| width = 300px\n}}\n\nAs an adult, Joicey began collecting Lepidoptera in 1906{{Refn|According to Miller,<ref name=\"Miller\" /> Joicey first competed with [[Walter Rothschild]] to build the world's premier orchid collection but when Joicey went bankrupt the judge made him promise to abandon collecting orchids. However, the details of the anecdote do not match Joicey's known bankruptcies and the story is currently uncorroborated.|group=lower-alpha}} and by 1908 was advertising as far away as Australia for:\n\n::Fresh-caught Specimens of Butterflies and Large Moths, in papers. Send Samples and state price per hundred.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/163231414?searchTerm=%22james%20joicey%22|title=Wanted|last=|first=|date=30 December 1908|work=The Sydney Mail and New South Wales Advertiser|access-date=6 December 2019|page=1683}}</ref>\n\nHe acquired the [[Henley Grose-Smith]] collection in 1910. Two years later he purchased the [[Herbert Druce]] collection. To house his growing collection, he founded the Hill Museum at his [[Witley]] home in 1913.<ref name=\"Bulletin1\" />{{Rp|3}}<ref name=\":1\" /> Joicey employed curators, including [[Alfred Noakes]] (from 1906)<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Lance\u2013Corpl. Noakes Killed|last=|first=|date=20 November 1916|work=Surrey Advertiser|access-date=|page=3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1913|title=Proceedings of the Entomological Society of London for 1912: Wednesday, October 16th, 1912|url=https://archive.org/details/transactionsofen1912roya/page/n1141/mode/1up|journal=Transactions of the Entomological Society of London|volume=1912|pages=xcvi|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> and George Talbot (from 1915),<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1954|title=President's Address. 28th January 1953|url=https://archive.org/details/proceedingstrans19501953sout/page/62|journal=Proceedings and Transactions of the South London Entomological and Natural History Society|volume=1952\u201353|pages=62|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> with a staff of assistants.<ref name=\"Riley\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Natural History Society|last=|first=|date=8 August 1914|work=Surrey Advertiser|access-date=|page=2}}</ref>\n\n[[File:BulletinHillMuseumPlate9.jpg|thumb|338x338px|New butterflies from [[Buru]] and [[New Guinea]]<ref name=\"Bulletin1\" />{{Rp|592}} (Joicey Collection). Top left: [[Troides prattorum]]. Top right: [[Charaxes mars|Charaxes madensis]]. Both were described by Talbot at The Hill to a reporter in 1932 shortly after Joicey's death.<ref name=\"Insects\" />|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|left]]\n\nBetween 1913 and 1921 Joicey bought further collections: those of [[Ernst Suffert]], {{Circa|1913}}, [[Fritz Ludwig Otto Wichgraf]], 1913, [[Charles Swinhoe|Col. Charles Swinhoe]], 1916, [[Roland Trimen]], 1917, [[Charles George Nurse|Lt.-Col. C. G. Nurse]], 1919, [[Hamilton Herbert Druce|Hamilton Druce]], 1919, [[Heinrich Riffarth]], 1919, [[Henry John Elwes]], 1920, and [[Paul Dognin]], 1921. He added to these by sending special collectors to explore various regions on his behalf; for example, the [[Antwerp Edgar Pratt|Pratt family]] to [[South America]] and [[New Guinea]], and [[T. A. Barns]] to [[Central Africa]] (Barns dedicated his [[iarchive:wonderlandofeast00barnrich/page/n7|1922 book]] on the Eastern [[Belgian Congo|Congo]] to Joicey, his \"friend and patron\"). Mr. W. J. C. Frost, who visited the Islands of [[Tanimbar Islands|Tenimber]], Am, Key, [[Misool|Misol]], Obi and Sula during 1915\u20131918, donated his collection. Another collector, Mr. C. Talbot Bowring,<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Weddings Today. Mr C. T. Bowring and Miss Parker|last=|first=|date=29 October 1908|work=The Globe|access-date=|page=8}}</ref> sent many thousands of specimens from Hainan Island (1918\u20131920).<ref name=\"Bulletin1\" />{{Rp|3\u20134}}\n\nIn 1916, when granting Joicey's curator conditional exemption from military service, [[Josceline Wodehouse|General Sir J. Wodehouse]] described the collection as \"probably the finest of its kind in England\", and Oxford professor [[Edward Bagnall Poulton|E. B. Poulton]] wrote that \"to leave the collection without a competent head would be a national disaster.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Expensive Butterflies|last=|first=|date=31 August 1916|work=Illustrated Police News|access-date=|page=10}}</ref> \n\nIn 1919, the collection was valued at \u00a350,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=50000|start_year=1919|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}). It consisted of 1.5 million specimens held in a room containing chests of drawers with \"5000 compartments neatly arranged round the room, and in addition 4000 cases, all carefully labelled.\"<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/star/1919/06/06/4|title=A Fortune for Butterflies. A Collector's Mania. Spends \u00a310,000 a Year|last=|first=|date=6 June 1919|work=The Star|access-date=20 November 2019|url-status=live|page=4}}</ref> It was reported that,\n\n<blockquote>Here were butterflies of all sizes, of all colours \u2013 all arranged in an effective colour grouping. In one compartment were ... great winged beauties half a foot from wing tip to wing tip. In another were creatures so small that it needed a microscope to discern their beauty.<ref name=\":6\" /></blockquote>\n\nAn annexe to the museum \"over eighty feet long by twenty feet wide\" (approximately 24 by 6 m) was built in 1920.<ref name=\"Bulletin1\" />{{Rp|4}} In 1927 it was reported that the main building of the Museum was \"as large as a dance hall. The specimens are kept in special cabinets stacked almost to the roof. Here, all day long, Mr. Joicey and his assistants ... work at arranging and naming the fresh arrivals.\" Some specimens dated from the 1830s, others were obtained on the [[Henry Morton Stanley|Stanley]] expedition of 1871. Some were caught over 1,000 miles (1,600 km) from land, others had perished on the Alpine snowfields. They ranged in size from 1/2 inch to 10 inches (approximately 1 cm to 25 cm) wing spread.<ref name=\":9\" /> By 1930 the Hill Museum contained upwards of 380,000 specimens.<ref name=\"Riley\" />\n\n[[File:JJ Joicey butterfly cabinet Haslemere Educational Museum.jpg|thumb|Butterflies from the Joicey collection in a contemporary cabinet at the [http://www.haslemeremuseum.co.uk/ Haslemere Educational Museum].|alt=Photograph of multi-drawer butterfly display cabinet with some drawers open]]\n\nJoicey and his Hill Museum colleagues published over 190 scientific articles on world Lepidoptera (see [[James John Joicey#Works|Works]] below) and \"produced some excellent work, especially on the Lepidoptera of New Guinea, [[Hainan]] Island, and Central and [[East Africa|Eastern Africa]].\"<ref name=\"Miller\">{{Cite journal|last=Miller|first=Lee D.|date=1986|title=Presidential Address, 1984: A Tribute to the Amateur|url=http://images.peabody.yale.edu/lepsoc/jls/1980s/1986/1986-40(1)1-Miller.pdf|journal=Journal of the Lepidopterists' Society|volume=40|issue=1|pages=1\u20137|access-date=20 November 2019|via=}}</ref>{{Rp|4}} Joicey and Talbot co-edited four volumes of ''The Bulletin of the Hill Museum'', 1921\u20131932<ref name=\"Bulletin1\" /><ref name=\"Bulletin2\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.28174/page/n5|title=The Bulletin of the Hill Museum: A Magazine of Lepidoptera|last=|first=|publisher=John Bale, Sons and Danielsson Ltd|year=1928|isbn=|editor-last=Joicey|editor-first=J. J.|volume=2|location=London|pages=|access-date=6 December 2019|editor-last2=Talbot|editor-first2=G.}}</ref><ref name=\"Bulletin3\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.28172/page/n5|title=The Bulletin of the Hill Museum: A Magazine of Lepidoptera|last=|first=|publisher=John Bale, Sons and Danielsson Ltd|year=1929|isbn=|editor-last=Joicey|editor-first=J. J.|volume=3|location=London|pages=|access-date=6 December 2019|editor-last2=Talbot|editor-first2=G.}}</ref><ref name=\"Bulletin4\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.28175/page/n5|title=The Bulletin of the Hill Museum: A Magazine of Lepidoptera|last=|first=|publisher=John Bale, Sons and Danielsson Ltd|year=1932|isbn=|editor-last=Joicey|editor-first=J. J.|volume=4|location=London|pages=|access-date=6 December 2019|editor-last2=Talbot|editor-first2=G.}}</ref> and [[Alfred George Gabriel]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Many Local Names in New Year Honours List. Entomologist|last=|first=|date=9 January 1958|work=Harrow Observer|access-date=|url-status=live|page=9}}</ref> published ''A Catalogue of the Type Specimens of Lepidoptera Rhopalocera in the Hill Museum'' in 1932.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nDuring his lifetime, Joicey \"presented to the Nation\" between 200,000 and 300,000 Lepidoptera specimens including about 75,000 to the Natural History Museum. The latter figure included 15,500 moths and a number butterflies (1923), his whole collection of over 30,000 [[Skipper (butterfly)|Hesperiidae]] butterflies (1926), 6,000 [[Lymantriinae|Lymantriidae]] moths (1928), and, in 1931, a series of 800 [[Type (biology)|type]] butterflies being \"the most valuable, both scientifically and intrinsically ... received for the past two decades\", some thousands of moths including over 600 type and [[paratype]] moths, and 1,500 butterflies including 750 type specimens. In 1932, the collection numbered over 500,000 specimens.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=The Sale Room \u2013 Joicey Collection|last=|first=|date=29 April 1932|work=The Times|access-date=|page=7}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/catalogueofmanus00harv_0|title=A Catalogue of Manuscripts in the Entomology Library of the Natural History Museum, London|last=Harvey|first=Julie M.V.|last2=Gilbert|first2=Pamela|last3=Martin|first3=Kathy|publisher=Mansell Publishing Limited|year=1996|isbn=0-7201-2290-2|location=London|pages=[https://archive.org/details/catalogueofmanus00harv_0/page/114 114]\u2013115|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nHowever, shortly after Joicey's death in 1932 the Hill Museum was closed and the property sold by his mother's [[executor]]s.<ref name=\":5\" /> Joicey's obituary in ''The Entomologist'' stated that,\n\n<blockquote>The closing of the Hill Museum and the disbanding of its staff are events which will have serious repercussions throughout the ranks of lepidopterists in all parts of the world, and will definitely retard the advance of this science. In a comparatively short space of time Mr Joicey accomplished much for his favourite study.<ref name=\"Riley\" />{{Rp|144}}</blockquote>\n\n<gallery caption=\"The Hill Museum\">\nFile:BulletinHillMuseum1921HillMuseumExterior.jpg|alt=Sepia photograph of the outside of building with four arched windows|Hill Museum: Exterior\nFile:BulletinHillMuseum1921HillMuseumAnnexe.jpg|alt=Sepia photograph of a long single-story barracks hut in a field|Hill Museum: Annexe\nFile:BulletinHillMuseum1921HillMuseumInterior.jpg|alt=Sepia photograph of a room crowded with display cabinets and work benches|Hill Museum: A part of the interior\nFile:BulletinHillMuseum1921HillMuseumPhotomicrography.jpg|alt=Sepia photograph of man adjusting photographic equipment on a bench|Hill Museum: Photomicrographic Department under Mr. H. J. Campbell\nFile:BulletinHillMuseum1923.jpg|alt=Sepia photograph of six gentlemen standing outside on pathway stairs|Joicey (second from left) and other entomologists at the Hill Museum in 1920\n</gallery>\n<gallery caption=\"Joicey Collection examples\">\nFile:BMNH(E)983480 Delias joiceyi Talb. female3 ventral-S.jpg|alt=Photograph of a pinned butterfly with notes below|''[[Delias]] joiceyi''\nFile:BMNH(E)983400 Delias maudei J.&N. male ventral-S.jpg|alt=Photograph of a pinned butterfly with notes below|''Delias maudei''\nFile:BMNH(E)141732 Delias mariae J.&T. AT female ventral-S.jpg|alt=Photograph of a pinned butterfly with notes below|''Delias mariae''\nFile:Ornithoptera goliath samson f. joiceyi Noakes & Talbot, 1915.jpg|alt=Photograph of a pinned butterfly with notes below|''[[Ornithoptera goliath]] samson'' f. ''joiceyi''\nFile:Annalsmagazineof8151915lond 0649.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|''Ornithoptera joyceyi'' (male), two ''Delias''\nFile:Annalsmagazineof8151915lond 0651.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of a butterfly specimen|''Ornithoptera joiceyi'' (female)\nFile:DeudorixMaudeiMFJoiceyTalbot1916.JPG|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|''[[Deudorix]] maudei''\nFile:Deudorix littoralis TypesMFUpAC1.jpg|alt=Photograph of two pinned butterflies with notes above|''Deudorix littoralis'' (male & female types)\nFile:Bulletin of the Hill Museum v1 1921 Plate VI.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|New ''Delias'' from Buru\nFile:Bulletin of the Hill Museum v1 1921 Plate VII.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|New ''Delias'' from New Guinea and Buru\nFile:Bulletin of the Hill Museum v1 1921 Plate VIII.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|New ''Delias'' from New Guinea\nFile:Bull Hill Mus v1 Plate IX.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|New butterflies from Buru and New Guinea\nFile:Bull Hill Mus v1 p594 Plate X.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of moth specimens|New [[Sphingidae]]\nFile:Bull Hill Mus v1 p594 Plate XI.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of moth specimens|New Sphingidae\nFile:Bull Hill Mus v1 Plate XII.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|New [[Zygaenidae]]\nFile:Annalsmagazineof8151915lond 0665 with explanation.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|''[[Milionia]]'', four others\nFile:JJ Joicey cabinet Haslemere Educational Museum drawer no 14.jpg|alt=Photograph of a drawer of pinned butterflies|South American ''[[Papilio]]''\nFile:JJ Joicey cabinet Haslemere Educational Museum drawer no 14 close-up.jpg|alt=Photograph of pinned butterflies with notes under each|South American ''Papilio'' (detail)    \n</gallery>\n\n==Legacy==\nJoicey's Hill Museum produced over 190 research articles which were published in a range of scientific journals.<ref name=\"Riley\" /> In 1934, the Natural History Museum received more than 300,000 specimens as part of the Joicey [[Bequest]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Natural History Museum: Gift of Butterfly Collection|last=|first=|date=27 March 1934|work=The Times|access-date=|page=17}}</ref> Together with the [[Charles Oberthur|Oberth\u00fcr]] and [[Walter Rothschild, 2nd Baron Rothschild|Rothschild]] collections, the Joicey collection contributed to the quality and numerical predominance of the Lepidoptera collection held by the Natural History Museum, London.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"Miller\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhm.ac.uk/our-science/collections/entomology-collections/lepidoptera-collections.html|title=Lepidoptera collections|last=|first=|date=|website=National History Museum|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=9 April 1932|title=Mr. J. J. Joicey|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/129535a0.pdf|journal=Nature|volume=129|issue=3258|pages=535|doi=10.1038/129535a0|access-date=22 November 2019|via=}}</ref>\n\nA report in ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'' stated that,\n\n<blockquote>During his life-time, the late J. J. Joicey probably did more to stimulate the study of butterflies and moths, especially those of Africa, than any other private individual in Great Britain.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=31 March 1934|title=Recent Acquisitions at the Natural History Museum|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/133490b0.pdf|journal=Nature|volume=133|issue=3361|pages=490|doi=10.1038/133490b0|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Works==\n===Joicey and Talbot (partial list)===\n*New Species of Heterocera from Dutch New Guinea. ''Annals and Magazine of Natural History'' (Eighth series) '''15''' (87): [[iarchive:annalsmagazineof8151915lond/page/295|295\u2013301]], pl. [[iarchive:annalsmagazineof8151915lond/page/n662/mode/1up|XII]] (1915)\n*New Lepidoptera from the Dutch New Guinea (with A. Noakes). ''Transactions of the Entomological Society of London'' '''63''' (3,4): [[iarchive:transactionsofen1915roya/page/361/mode/1up|361\u2013386]], pls [[iarchive:transactionsofen1915roya/page/n587|LV\u2013LXII]] (1916)\n*New Lepidoptera from the Schouten Islands. ''Transactions of the Entomological Society of London'' '''64''' (1): [[iarchive:transactionsofen1916roya/page/65/mode/1up|65\u201383]], pls [[iarchive:transactionsofen1916roya/page/n151|3\u20136]] (1916)\n*New Heterocera from Dutch New Guinea. ''Annals and Magazine of Natural History'' (Eighth series) '''20''' (115): [[iarchive:annalsmagazineof8201917lond/page/50|50\u201387]], pls [[iarchive:annalsmagazineof8201917lond/page/n484/mode/1up|1\u20134]] (1917)\n*New Lepidoptera from Waigeu, Dutch New Guinea and Biak. ''Annals and Magazine of Natural History'' (Eighth series) '''20''' (117): [[iarchive:annalsmagazineof8201917lond/page/216|216\u2013229]] (1917)\n*New South-American Rhopalocera. ''Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London'' '''1917''': [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/259/mode/1up|259\u2013264]], pl [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/n363/mode/1up|I]] (1918)\n*New South-American Arctiidae. ''Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London'' '''1917''': [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/265/mode/1up|265\u2013270]], pl [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/n363/mode/1up|I]] (1918)\n*New butterflies from Africa and the east. ''Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London'' '''1917''': [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/271/mode/1up|271\u2013272]] (1918)\n*A Gynandromorph of ''Papilio lycophron'' Hbn. ''Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London'' '''1917''': [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/273/mode/1up|273]], pl [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/n379/mode/1up|II]] (1918)\n*Three Aberrations of Lepidoptera. ''Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London'' '''1917''': [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/275/mode/1up|275\u2013276]], pl [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/n363/mode/1up|I]] (1918)\n*New forms of Indo-Australian butterflies. ''Bulletin of the Hill Museum'' '''1''' (3): [https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/565/mode/1up 565\u2013569] (1924)\n*New forms of Lepidoptera Rhopalocera. ''Encyclopedia of Entomology'' (B III Lepidoptera) '''2''': 1\u201314 (1926)\n*New forms of Rhopalocera in the Hill Museum. ''Bulletin of the Hill Museum'' '''2''' (1): [[iarchive:in.ernet.dli.2015.28174/page/n29|19\u201327]] (1928)\n*Also see the [http://bionames.org/authors/J%20J%20Joicey BioNames database] linking taxonomic names to their original descriptions\n\n{{Quote box\n| quote = The majority of the papers are of a purely [[Systematics|systematic]] nature, consisting of the description of new [[species]] or the revision of various [[Genus|genera]]; but there are several of principally [[Fauna|faunistic]] interest, as, for example, the Catalogue of the Lepidoptera of Hainan. They represent a contribution to the study of the exotic Lepidoptera of very great scientific value.\n| source = Joicey's obituary in ''The Entomologist'', 1932<ref name=\"Riley\" />{{Rp|144}}\n| align = right\n| width = 300px\n}}\n\n===Associated with the Hill Museum===\n'''''The Bulletin of the Hill Museum''''' (111 articles and 80 plates<ref name=\"Riley\" />)\n*[https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/n12/mode/1up 1921]\n*[https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/n13/mode/2up 1921\u20131924]\n*[https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/n15/mode/2up 1924]\n*[[iarchive:in.ernet.dli.2015.28174/page/n7/mode/2up|1928]]\n*[[iarchive:in.ernet.dli.2015.28172/page/n7/mode/2up|1929]]\n*[[iarchive:in.ernet.dli.2015.28175/page/n7/mode/1up|1931]]\n\n'''''Other journals''''' (82 articles<ref name=\"Riley\" />) (partial list)\n\n*[https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/13/mode/1up 1914\u20131916]\n*[https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/14/mode/2up 1916\u20131921]\n*[https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/572/mode/1up 1921\u20131924]\n*[[iarchive:in.ernet.dli.2015.28174/page/n207/mode/2up|1924\u20131927]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==Summaries==\n*Anon. 1932: [Joicey, J. J.] ''Entomological News'' '''43''': [[iarchive:entomologicalnew42amer/page/140/mode/1up|140]]\n*Anon. 1932: [Joicey, J. J.] ''London Naturalist'' '''1931''': [[iarchive:londonnaturalist1931lond/page/n51/mode/1up|38]]\n*Anon. 1932: [Joicey, J. J.] ''Nature'' '''129''': [https://www.nature.com/articles/129535a0.pdf 535], [https://www.nature.com/articles/129896a0.pdf 896]\n*Anon. 1932: [Joicey J. J.]  ''Orchid Review'' '''40''': [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=7nUhAQAAIAAJ&q=joicey 118]\n*Anon. 1932: [Joicey J. J.] ''The Times'' (16 March) p.&nbsp;9\n*Gilbert, P.  2000: ''Butterfly Collectors and Painters: Four Centuries of Colour Plates from the Library Collections of the Natural History Museum, London''. Singapore, Beaumont Publishing Pte Ltd: X+166 S, pp. [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=WQBNAAAAYAAJ&dq=%22Butterfly+Collectors+and+Painters.+Four+centuries+of+colour+plates+from+The+Library+Collections+of+The+Natural+History+Museum%2C+London.%22&q=joicey 31]\u201333\n*Riley, N. D. 1932: [Joicey, J. J.] ''Entomologist'' '''65''': 142\u2013144\n*Turner, H. J. 1932: [Joicey, J. J.] ''Entomologist's Record & Journal of Variation'' '''44''': [[iarchive:entomologistsr441932tutt/page/68/mode/1up|68]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=James John Joicey}}\n*[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/205188852/james-john-joicey Grave site]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Joicey, James John}}\n[[Category:1870 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:British entomologists]]\n[[Category:English lepidopterists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Entomological Society]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Zoological Society of London]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Geographical Society]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Linnean Society of London]]\n[[Category:People from Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English amateur entomologist (1870\u20131932)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = James John Joicey\n| honorific_suffix   = [[Fellow of the Royal Geographical Society|FRGS]] [[Linnean Society of London|FLS]] [[Zoological Society of London|FZS]] [[Royal Entomological Society|FES]] [[Royal Horticultural Society|FRHS]]\n| image              = BulletinHillMuseum1921HillMuseumJoicey cropped.jpg\n| alt                = Sepia portrait photograph of middle-aged gentleman in suit and hat in 1920\n| birth_date         = 28 December 1870\n| birth_place        = [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], England\n| death_date         = 10 March 1932\n| death_place        = The Hill, [[Witley]], [[Surrey]], England\n| burial_place       = Holy Trinity Church, [[Sunningdale]]\n| occupation         = Amateur [[entomologist]]\n| known_for          = Assembling a collection of over 1.5 million [[Lepidoptera]] specimens, his Hill Museum research output, and his presentations from his collection to the [[Natural History Museum]]\n| notable_works      = ''The Bulletin of the Hill Museum'' 1921\u20131932<ref name=\"Bulletin1\"/><ref name=\"Bulletin2\"/><ref name=\"Bulletin3\"/><ref name=\"Bulletin4\"/>\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Maud Muriel Fisher|1896}}\n| relatives          = [[James Joicey, 1st Baron Joicey|1st Baron Joicey]] (father's cousin)<ref name=\"Major\"/>\n}}\n\n'''James John Joicey''' [[Royal Entomological Society|FES]] (28 December 1870 \u2013 10 March 1932) was an English amateur [[entomologist]], who assembled an extensive collection of [[Lepidoptera]] in his private research museum, called the Hill Museum, in [[Witley]], [[Surrey]]. His collection, 40 years in the making, was considered to have been the second largest in the world held privately and to have numbered over 1.5 million [[Biological specimen|specimens]]. Joicey was a [[fellow]] of the [[Zoological Society of London]], the [[Fellow of the Royal Geographical Society|Royal Geographical Society]], the [[Royal Entomological Society]], the [[Royal Horticultural Society]], and the [[Linnean Society of London]].\n\nJoicey employed specialist entomologists including [[George Talbot (entomologist)|George Talbot]] to curate his collection and financed numerous expeditions throughout the world to obtain previously unknown varieties. Over 190 scientific articles were produced during the active period of the Hill Museum. This body of research was described as \"a contribution to the study of the exotic Lepidoptera of very great scientific value.\"<ref name=\"Riley\" />{{Rp|144}}\n\nJoicey's donations from his collection, made both during his life and following his death, contributed significantly to the quality and numerical predominance of the Lepidoptera collection held by the [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]], [[London]]. Joicey's obituary in ''[[Royal Entomological Society|The Entomologist]]'' described him as \"undoubtedly the most lavish patron of Entomology, in so far as butterflies and moths are concerned, that this country has ever boasted\".<ref name=\"Riley\" />{{Rp|142}}\n\n==Life==\n===Background===\nJames John Joicey was born on 28 December 1870 in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], the only child of Major William James Joicey, a wealthy coal owner, and Mary Anne Joicey n\u00e9e Clark.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Births|last=|first=|date=6 January 1871|work=The Newcastle Courant|access-date=|page=8}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Marriages|last=|first=|date=20 March 1868|work=The Newcastle Courant|access-date=|page=8}}</ref><ref name=\"Major\" /> He was educated at [[Aysgarth School]], [[Yorkshire]], and [[Hertford College, Oxford|Hertford College]], [[Oxford]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Mr. J. J. Joicey Owner of \u00a350,000 Collection of Butterflies|last=|first=|date=12 March 1932|work=Yorkshire Post and Leeds Intelligencer|access-date=|page=14}}</ref> and was an Associate Member of the [[Institution of Mining Engineers|Institute of Mining Engineers]] from 1891.<ref name=\"IME\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1913|title=List of Members, August 3, 1912|url=https://archive.org/details/transactions62nort/page/n361/mode/1up|journal=Transactions of the North of England Institute of Mining and Mechanical Engineers|volume=LXII|pages=xlvi|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> He was also a member of the [[Junior Carlton Club]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/countyfamiliesof591919walf|title=Walford's County Families of the United Kingdom|last=|first=|publisher=Ballantyne & Co. Ltd.|year=1919|isbn=|location=London|pages=[https://archive.org/details/countyfamiliesof591919walf/page/734 734]|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nJoicey married Maud Muriel Fisher (later Baroness de Satg\u00e9) in London in 1896.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Marriages|last=|first=|date=20 October 1896|work=The Standard|access-date=|page=1}}</ref> He lived at The Hill in [[Witley]], [[Surrey]], from about 1912.{{Refn|The 1911 Census of England shows another family living at The Hill in April 1911 and Joicey had notified the Institute of Mining Engineers of his address at The Hill by August 1912.<ref name=\"IME\"/> He is also listed in London electoral registers from 1920 to 1925 at [[Marble Arch#Marble Arch area|Marble Arch]] as Admiral Joicey.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ancestry.com|title=London, England, Electoral Registers, 1832\u20131965: Paddington and St Marylebone, Polling District F, No. 5, Bryanston Square Ward, 1921\u20131925|last=|first=|date=|website=ancestry.com|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 December 2019}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n===Collecting===\nJoicey's boyhood interest in insects was encouraged by his parents and at the age of sixteen he put together a small collection of British and foreign [[Butterfly|butterflies]].<ref name=\"Riley\">{{Cite journal|last=Riley|first=N. D.|date=1932|title=Obituary: James John Joicey|url=|journal=The Entomologist|volume=65|pages=142\u2013144|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article90080883|title=A \u00a3100,000 Hobby. The Rarest Pair of Wings in the World. Facing Death for a Butterfly|last=|first=|date=24 September 1927|work=The Adelaide Chronicle|access-date=22 November 2019|url-status=live|page=76}}</ref> As an adult, he happened upon the forgotten cabinets of his boyhood collection and was inspired to start collecting in earnest,<ref name=\":9\" /> his active interest dating from 1906.<ref name=\"Bulletin1\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/bulletinofh112192122hill/page/n9|title=The Bulletin of the Hill Museum: A Magazine of Lepidoptera|last=|first=|publisher=John Bale, Sons and Danielsson Ltd|year=1924|isbn=|editor-last=Joicey|editor-first=J. J.|volume=1|location=London|pages=|access-date=6 December 2019|editor-last2=Talbot|editor-first2=G.}}</ref> He used his resources to \"indulge a taste for collecting butterflies and [[moth]]s which remained with him throughout his life.\" He travelled \"in the East\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Obituary \u2013 Mr. J. J. Joicey \u2013 Gifts to the Natural History Museum|last=|first=|date=16 March 1932|work=The Times|access-date=|page=9}}</ref> as a young man and, although he employed experts to collect most of his specimens, also collected \"on his own account both here and abroad\"<ref name=\":9\" /> and \"travelled widely in Europe, India, China, Japan, Burma and America\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=|title=\u00a350,000 Collection of Butterflies. Death of an Eminent Naturalist|last=|first=|date=12 March 1932|work=Sheffield Independent|access-date=|page=5}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=Who Was Who: 1929\u20131940|last=|first=|publisher=Adam & Charles Black|year=1960|isbn=|location=London|pages=722}}</ref> In 1913, he built and financed a private research museum, the Hill Museum, at his home in Witley, employing a [[curator]] and seven assistants.<ref name=\":1\" /> In one twelve-month period he collected some 17,000 specimens from across the world and was spending up to \u00a310,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=10000|start_year=1919|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}) a year on the collection.<ref name=\":9\" /> Joicey said:\n\n<blockquote>How did I manage to spend \u00a310,000 a year on this collection? Well, these did not come from my back garden. I have had to send collectors to the far ends of the earth. ... When my work is done \u2013 that is, when I die \u2013 I will present the collection to the nation.<ref name=\":6\" />{{pb}}The work has been the ruling passion of my life, ... I don't think I am extravagant, as my researches and investigations will be of great value to the nation.<ref name=\":0\" /></blockquote>\n\nJoicey became a fellow of the Zoological Society of London in 1890,<ref>{{Cite book|title=A List of the Fellows of the Zoological Society of London|last=|first=|publisher=William Clowes and Sons, Limited|year=1924|isbn=|location=London|pages=85}}</ref> a fellow of the Royal Geographical Society in 1903,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1903|title=Meetings of the Royal Geographical Society, Sessions 1903\u20131904|url=https://archive.org/details/geographicaljou40britgoog/page/n744/mode/1up|journal=The Geographical Journal|volume=XXII|pages=709|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> a fellow of the Entomological Society in 1908 (council member 1920\u20131923),<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/transactionsofen1915roya/page/n23|title=Transactions of the Entomological Society of London 1915|last=|first=|publisher=Longmans, Green & Co.|year=1915|isbn=|location=London|pages=xix|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref> a fellow of the Royal Horticultural Society in 1912,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1912|title=Extracts from the Proceedings of the Royal Horticultural Society|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.240657/page/n779/mode/1up|journal=The Journal of the Royal Horticultural Society|volume=xxxviii|pages=xxii|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> a fellow of the Linnean Society of London in 1913,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1914|title=December 4th, 1913|url=https://archive.org/details/proceedingsoflin191215linn/page/n174/mode/1up|journal=Proceedings of the Linnean Society|volume=126|pages=3|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> a life member of the [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 entomologique de France]] in 1921,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1931|title=Liste des membres de la soci\u00e9t\u00e9 entomologique de France arr\u00eat\u00e9e au 10 janvier 1930|url=https://www.persee.fr/doc/bsef_0037-928x_1931_num_36_1_28972|journal=Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 entomologique de France|volume=36|issue=1|pages=XXVIII|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> and a member of the [http://lnhs.org.uk/ London Natural History Society] in 1928.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1932|title=Obituary|url=https://archive.org/details/londonnaturalist1931lond/page/n51/mode/1up|journal=The London Naturalist|volume=1931|pages=38|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref>\n\nAs well as amateur entomologist, Joicey was a well-known amateur [[Orchidaceae|orchidist]] and exhibited at meetings of the Royal Horticultural Society.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1932|title=Obituary|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=7nUhAQAAIAAJ&q=joicey|journal=The Orchid Review|volume=40|pages=118|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref>\n\n===Finances===\nJoicey could afford to build his collection of Lepidoptera through his family connection with the firm of \"Messrs. James Joicey & Co., Ltd, coalowners, Newcastle\", founded by his grandfather.<ref name=\"Major\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Major Joicey Dead. His Association with Local Coal Industry. Popular Turf Personality|last=|first=|date=24 January 1912|work=The Newcastle Daily Chronicle|access-date=|url-status=live|page=7}}</ref> Although described as having been \"nominally on the [[Stock exchange|Stock Exchange]] from 1896 to 1899\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Unable to Live on \u00a38,000 a Year|last=|first=|date=9 July 1910|work=Framlingham Weekly News|access-date=|url-status=live|page=4}}</ref> then, in 1901, as a \"coal owner & ship owner\",<ref>1901 Census of England and Wales. RG12/814</ref> and, in 1913, as a director of the family coal mining firm,<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=James Joicey & Co. Limited|last=|first=|date=1 December 1913|work=The Times|access-date=|page=10}}</ref> Joicey effectively had no occupation and throughout his life subsisted on substantial allowances from his parents. However, his income proved insufficient for his \"extravagance in living\" and the interest rates charged by money-lenders. Joicey became [[Bankruptcy|bankrupt]] in 1909 with a deficiency of over \u00a3185,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=185000|start_year=1909|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}), and again in 1922 with a deficiency of over \u00a3430,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=430000|start_year=1922|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}) despite his mother having given him \u00a3300,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=300000|start_year=1921|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}) in the interim.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=King's Bench Division. In re Joicey|last=|first=|date=8 July 1910|work=The Times|access-date=|page=3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Borrowed Half a Million. Young Man's Dealings with Moneylenders|last=|first=|date=8 February 1922|work=Daily Mail|access-date=|url-status=live|page=6}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Millionaire's Son Again Bankrupt|last=|first=|date=10 February 1922|work=The Times|access-date=|page=7}}</ref> The latter bankruptcy was discharged in October 1931.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Mr. J. J. Joicey's Bankruptcy|last=|first=|date=16 October 1926|work=The Times|access-date=|page=4}}</ref><ref name=\":7\" />\n\n{{Quote box\n| quote = The son of a millionaire, for him money meant only one thing \u2013 more butterflies, still rarer specimens than he had already.\n| source = [[George Talbot (entomologist)|George Talbot]], Joicey's head curator, 1932<ref name=\"Insects\" />\n| align = right\n| width = 300px\n}}\n\nJoicey's father, at one time a millionaire, had left over \u00a3700,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=700000|start_year=1912|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}) in his [[Estate (law)|estate]] in 1912, but his will ensured that no money went directly to his son.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Man Unable to Live on \u00a320,000 a Year|last=|first=|date=15 October 1926|work=Western Morning News|access-date=|url-status=live|page=3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Will of the Late Major W. J. Joicey|last=|first=|date=27 March 1912|work=Newcastle Daily Chronicle|access-date=|page=2}}</ref> The Witley house and estate were bought for Joicey after his first bankruptcy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Wild Extravagance. Debts of \u00a3400,000 in Second Bankruptcy. Remarkable Figures|last=|first=|date=15 October 1926|work=Western Times|access-date=|page=12}}</ref> When sued by [[creditor]]<nowiki/>s in 1919, the judge said, \"He seems hardly to have grown up. He seems to have infantile tastes which his mother helps him gratify.\" When [[counsel]] stated that Joicey was \"susceptible to the wiles of the money-lenders\", the judge responded, \"And to the wiles of the butterflies.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=King's Bench Division. A Butterfly Collector and Moneylenders. Jacobs Brothers v. Joicey|last=|first=|date=31 March 1919|work=The Times|access-date=|url-status=live|page=4}}</ref> During the 1922 bankruptcy hearing, Joicey said, \"I think the money seems to have gone like snow in an oven.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Money Went Like Snow in Oven|last=|first=|date=7 March 1922|work=Pall Mall Gazette|access-date=|page=5}}</ref>\n\n===Death===\nJoicey's mother died in 1930, leaving an estate valued at over \u00a3300,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=300000|start_year=1930|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://probatesearch.service.gov.uk/Calendar#calendar|title=Find a will|last=Joicey|first=Mary|date=1930|website=GOV.UK|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 November 2019}}</ref> Towards the end of his life, Joicey became an \"invalid\".<ref name=\"Insects\">{{Cite news|url=|title=\u00a310,000 A Year for Butterflies \u2013 Insects Men Died to Get \u2013 Wonder Collection for Nation|last=|first=|date=15 March 1932|work=Dundee Evening Telegraph|access-date=|page=9}}</ref> He died of heart failure on 10 March 1932 at his home, The Hill, in Witley, Surrey, aged 61.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=21 March 1932|title=Milestones|url=|journal=Time Magazine|volume=XIX|issue=12|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Deaths|last=|first=|date=14 March 1932|work=The Times|access-date=|page=1}}</ref> He was buried at Holy Trinity Church, [[Sunningdale]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Arrangements for Today|last=|first=|date=16 March 1932|work=The Times|access-date=|page=17}}</ref> Joicey's estate was valued at \u00a31,151 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=1151|start_year=1932|r=-2|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://probatesearch.service.gov.uk/Calendar#calendar|title=Find a will|last=Joicey|first=James John|date=1932|website=GOV.UK|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 November 2019}}</ref> his collection and museum having been principally paid for and owned by his mother.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Museum Bequest of Northern Bankrupt|last=|first=|date=7 June 1932|work=Sunderland Daily Echo and Shipping Gazette|access-date=|page=1}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Hambledon and Witley Estates|last=|first=|date=28 May 1932|work=The Surrey Advertiser and County Times|access-date=|page=7}}</ref>\n\n== Collections ==\n{{Quote box\n| quote = The primary object of Mr. Joicey in making this collection of Lepidoptera is to advance in some way our scientific knowledge. ... The formation of a large collection has its value, because without access to plenty of material studies can only be incomplete and results are often erroneous. ... <br/>\nNo apology should be needed for amassing large collections ...\n| source = George Talbot, 1924<ref name=\"Bulletin1\" />{{Rp|5}}\n| width = 300px\n}}\n\nAs an adult, Joicey began collecting Lepidoptera in 1906{{Refn|According to Miller,<ref name=\"Miller\" /> Joicey first competed with [[Walter Rothschild]] to build the world's premier orchid collection but when Joicey went bankrupt the judge made him promise to abandon collecting orchids. However, the details of the anecdote do not match Joicey's known bankruptcies and the story is currently uncorroborated.|group=lower-alpha}} and by 1908 was advertising as far away as Australia for:\n\n::Fresh-caught Specimens of Butterflies and Large Moths, in papers. Send Samples and state price per hundred.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/163231414?searchTerm=%22james%20joicey%22|title=Wanted|last=|first=|date=30 December 1908|work=The Sydney Mail and New South Wales Advertiser|access-date=6 December 2019|page=1683}}</ref>\n\nHe acquired the [[Henley Grose-Smith]] collection in 1910. Two years later he purchased the [[Herbert Druce]] collection. To house his growing collection, he founded the Hill Museum at his [[Witley]] home in 1913.<ref name=\"Bulletin1\" />{{Rp|3}}<ref name=\":1\" /> Joicey employed curators, including [[Alfred Noakes]] (from 1906)<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Lance\u2013Corpl. Noakes Killed|last=|first=|date=20 November 1916|work=Surrey Advertiser|access-date=|page=3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1913|title=Proceedings of the Entomological Society of London for 1912: Wednesday, October 16th, 1912|url=https://archive.org/details/transactionsofen1912roya/page/n1141/mode/1up|journal=Transactions of the Entomological Society of London|volume=1912|pages=xcvi|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> and George Talbot (from 1915),<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=1954|title=President's Address. 28th January 1953|url=https://archive.org/details/proceedingstrans19501953sout/page/62|journal=Proceedings and Transactions of the South London Entomological and Natural History Society|volume=1952\u201353|pages=62|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref> with a staff of assistants.<ref name=\"Riley\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Natural History Society|last=|first=|date=8 August 1914|work=Surrey Advertiser|access-date=|page=2}}</ref>\n\n[[File:BulletinHillMuseumPlate9.jpg|thumb|338x338px|New butterflies from [[Buru]] and [[New Guinea]]<ref name=\"Bulletin1\" />{{Rp|592}} (Joicey Collection). Top left: [[Troides prattorum]]. Top right: [[Charaxes mars|Charaxes madensis]]. Both were described by Talbot at The Hill to a reporter in 1932 shortly after Joicey's death.<ref name=\"Insects\" />|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|left]]\n\nBetween 1913 and 1921 Joicey bought further collections: those of [[Ernst Suffert]], {{Circa|1913}}, [[Fritz Ludwig Otto Wichgraf]], 1913, [[Charles Swinhoe|Col. Charles Swinhoe]], 1916, [[Roland Trimen]], 1917, [[Charles George Nurse|Lt.-Col. C. G. Nurse]], 1919, [[Hamilton Herbert Druce|Hamilton Druce]], 1919, [[Heinrich Riffarth]], 1919, [[Henry John Elwes]], 1920, and [[Paul Dognin]], 1921. He added to these by sending special collectors to explore various regions on his behalf; for example, the [[Antwerp Edgar Pratt|Pratt family]] to [[South America]] and [[New Guinea]], and [[T. A. Barns]] to [[Central Africa]] (Barns dedicated his [[iarchive:wonderlandofeast00barnrich/page/n7|1922 book]] on the Eastern [[Belgian Congo|Congo]] to Joicey, his \"friend and patron\"). Mr. W. J. C. Frost, who visited the Islands of [[Tanimbar Islands|Tenimber]], Am, Key, [[Misool|Misol]], Obi and Sula during 1915\u20131918, donated his collection. Another collector, Mr. C. Talbot Bowring,<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Weddings Today. Mr C. T. Bowring and Miss Parker|last=|first=|date=29 October 1908|work=The Globe|access-date=|page=8}}</ref> sent many thousands of specimens from Hainan Island (1918\u20131920).<ref name=\"Bulletin1\" />{{Rp|3\u20134}}\n\nIn 1916, when granting Joicey's curator conditional exemption from military service, [[Josceline Wodehouse|General Sir J. Wodehouse]] described the collection as \"probably the finest of its kind in England\", and Oxford professor [[Edward Bagnall Poulton|E. B. Poulton]] wrote that \"to leave the collection without a competent head would be a national disaster.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Expensive Butterflies|last=|first=|date=31 August 1916|work=Illustrated Police News|access-date=|page=10}}</ref> \n\nIn 1919, the collection was valued at \u00a350,000 (approximately {{Inflation|index=UK|value=50000|start_year=1919|r=-3|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}}). It consisted of 1.5 million specimens held in a room containing chests of drawers with \"5000 compartments neatly arranged round the room, and in addition 4000 cases, all carefully labelled.\"<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/star/1919/06/06/4|title=A Fortune for Butterflies. A Collector's Mania. Spends \u00a310,000 a Year|last=|first=|date=6 June 1919|work=The Star|access-date=20 November 2019|url-status=live|page=4}}</ref> It was reported that,\n\n<blockquote>Here were butterflies of all sizes, of all colours \u2013 all arranged in an effective colour grouping. In one compartment were ... great winged beauties half a foot from wing tip to wing tip. In another were creatures so small that it needed a microscope to discern their beauty.<ref name=\":6\" /></blockquote>\n\nAn annexe to the museum \"over eighty feet long by twenty feet wide\" (24 by 6 m) was built in 1920.<ref name=\"Bulletin1\" />{{Rp|4}} In 1927 it was reported that the main building of the Museum was \"as large as a dance hall. The specimens are kept in special cabinets stacked almost to the roof. Here, all day long, Mr. Joicey and his assistants ... work at arranging and naming the fresh arrivals.\" Some specimens dated from the 1830s, others were obtained on the [[Henry Morton Stanley|Stanley]] expedition of 1871. Some were caught over 1,000 miles (1,600 km) from land, others had perished on the Alpine snowfields. They ranged in size from 1/2 inch to 10 inches (1 cm to 25 cm) wing spread.<ref name=\":9\" /> By 1930 the Hill Museum contained upwards of 380,000 specimens.<ref name=\"Riley\" />\n\n[[File:JJ Joicey butterfly cabinet Haslemere Educational Museum.jpg|thumb|Butterflies from the Joicey collection in a contemporary cabinet at the [http://www.haslemeremuseum.co.uk/ Haslemere Educational Museum].|alt=Photograph of multi-drawer butterfly display cabinet with some drawers open]]\n\nJoicey and his Hill Museum colleagues published over 190 scientific articles on world Lepidoptera (see [[James John Joicey#Works|Works]] below) and \"produced some excellent work, especially on the Lepidoptera of New Guinea, [[Hainan]] Island, and Central and [[East Africa|Eastern Africa]].\"<ref name=\"Miller\">{{Cite journal|last=Miller|first=Lee D.|date=1986|title=Presidential Address, 1984: A Tribute to the Amateur|url=http://images.peabody.yale.edu/lepsoc/jls/1980s/1986/1986-40(1)1-Miller.pdf|journal=Journal of the Lepidopterists' Society|volume=40|issue=1|pages=1\u20137|access-date=20 November 2019|via=}}</ref>{{Rp|4}} Joicey and Talbot co-edited four volumes of ''The Bulletin of the Hill Museum'', 1921\u20131932<ref name=\"Bulletin1\" /><ref name=\"Bulletin2\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.28174/page/n5|title=The Bulletin of the Hill Museum: A Magazine of Lepidoptera|last=|first=|publisher=John Bale, Sons and Danielsson Ltd|year=1928|isbn=|editor-last=Joicey|editor-first=J. J.|volume=2|location=London|pages=|access-date=6 December 2019|editor-last2=Talbot|editor-first2=G.}}</ref><ref name=\"Bulletin3\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.28172/page/n5|title=The Bulletin of the Hill Museum: A Magazine of Lepidoptera|last=|first=|publisher=John Bale, Sons and Danielsson Ltd|year=1929|isbn=|editor-last=Joicey|editor-first=J. J.|volume=3|location=London|pages=|access-date=6 December 2019|editor-last2=Talbot|editor-first2=G.}}</ref><ref name=\"Bulletin4\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.28175/page/n5|title=The Bulletin of the Hill Museum: A Magazine of Lepidoptera|last=|first=|publisher=John Bale, Sons and Danielsson Ltd|year=1932|isbn=|editor-last=Joicey|editor-first=J. J.|volume=4|location=London|pages=|access-date=6 December 2019|editor-last2=Talbot|editor-first2=G.}}</ref> and [[Alfred George Gabriel]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Many Local Names in New Year Honours List. Entomologist|last=|first=|date=9 January 1958|work=Harrow Observer|access-date=|url-status=live|page=9}}</ref> published ''A Catalogue of the Type Specimens of Lepidoptera Rhopalocera in the Hill Museum'' in 1932.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nDuring his lifetime, Joicey \"presented to the Nation\" between 200,000 and 300,000 Lepidoptera specimens including about 75,000 to the Natural History Museum. The latter figure included 15,500 moths and a number butterflies (1923), his whole collection of over 30,000 [[Skipper (butterfly)|Hesperiidae]] butterflies (1926), 6,000 [[Lymantriinae|Lymantriidae]] moths (1928), and, in 1931, a series of 800 [[Type (biology)|type]] butterflies being \"the most valuable, both scientifically and intrinsically ... received for the past two decades\", some thousands of moths including over 600 type and [[paratype]] moths, and 1,500 butterflies including 750 type specimens. In 1932, the collection numbered over 500,000 specimens.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=The Sale Room \u2013 Joicey Collection|last=|first=|date=29 April 1932|work=The Times|access-date=|page=7}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/catalogueofmanus00harv_0|title=A Catalogue of Manuscripts in the Entomology Library of the Natural History Museum, London|last=Harvey|first=Julie M.V.|last2=Gilbert|first2=Pamela|last3=Martin|first3=Kathy|publisher=Mansell Publishing Limited|year=1996|isbn=0-7201-2290-2|location=London|pages=[https://archive.org/details/catalogueofmanus00harv_0/page/114 114]\u2013115|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nHowever, shortly after Joicey's death in 1932 the Hill Museum was closed and the property sold by his mother's [[executor]]s.<ref name=\":5\" /> Joicey's obituary in ''The Entomologist'' stated that,\n\n<blockquote>The closing of the Hill Museum and the disbanding of its staff are events which will have serious repercussions throughout the ranks of lepidopterists in all parts of the world, and will definitely retard the advance of this science. In a comparatively short space of time Mr Joicey accomplished much for his favourite study.<ref name=\"Riley\" />{{Rp|144}}</blockquote>\n\n<gallery caption=\"The Hill Museum\">\nFile:BulletinHillMuseum1921HillMuseumExterior.jpg|alt=Sepia photograph of the outside of building with four arched windows|Hill Museum: Exterior\nFile:BulletinHillMuseum1921HillMuseumAnnexe.jpg|alt=Sepia photograph of a long single-story barracks hut in a field|Hill Museum: Annexe\nFile:BulletinHillMuseum1921HillMuseumInterior.jpg|alt=Sepia photograph of a room crowded with display cabinets and work benches|Hill Museum: A part of the interior\nFile:BulletinHillMuseum1921HillMuseumPhotomicrography.jpg|alt=Sepia photograph of man adjusting photographic equipment on a bench|Hill Museum: Photomicrographic Department under Mr. H. J. Campbell\nFile:BulletinHillMuseum1923.jpg|alt=Sepia photograph of six gentlemen standing outside on pathway stairs|Joicey (second from left) and other entomologists at the Hill Museum in 1920\n</gallery>\n<gallery caption=\"Joicey Collection examples\">\nFile:BMNH(E)983480 Delias joiceyi Talb. female3 ventral-S.jpg|alt=Photograph of a pinned butterfly with notes below|''[[Delias]] joiceyi''\nFile:BMNH(E)983400 Delias maudei J.&N. male ventral-S.jpg|alt=Photograph of a pinned butterfly with notes below|''Delias maudei''\nFile:BMNH(E)141732 Delias mariae J.&T. AT female ventral-S.jpg|alt=Photograph of a pinned butterfly with notes below|''Delias mariae''\nFile:Ornithoptera goliath samson f. joiceyi Noakes & Talbot, 1915.jpg|alt=Photograph of a pinned butterfly with notes below|''[[Ornithoptera goliath]] samson'' f. ''joiceyi''\nFile:Annalsmagazineof8151915lond 0649.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|''Ornithoptera joyceyi'' (male), two ''Delias''\nFile:Annalsmagazineof8151915lond 0651.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of a butterfly specimen|''Ornithoptera joiceyi'' (female)\nFile:DeudorixMaudeiMFJoiceyTalbot1916.JPG|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|''[[Deudorix]] maudei''\nFile:Deudorix littoralis TypesMFUpAC1.jpg|alt=Photograph of two pinned butterflies with notes above|''Deudorix littoralis'' (male & female types)\nFile:Bulletin of the Hill Museum v1 1921 Plate VI.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|New ''Delias'' from Buru\nFile:Bulletin of the Hill Museum v1 1921 Plate VII.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|New ''Delias'' from New Guinea and Buru\nFile:Bulletin of the Hill Museum v1 1921 Plate VIII.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|New ''Delias'' from New Guinea\nFile:Bull Hill Mus v1 Plate IX.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|New butterflies from Buru and New Guinea\nFile:Bull Hill Mus v1 p594 Plate X.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of moth specimens|New [[Sphingidae]]\nFile:Bull Hill Mus v1 p594 Plate XI.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of moth specimens|New Sphingidae\nFile:Bull Hill Mus v1 Plate XII.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|New [[Zygaenidae]]\nFile:Annalsmagazineof8151915lond 0665 with explanation.jpg|alt=Book page showing watercolour plate of butterfly specimens|''[[Milionia]]'', four others\nFile:JJ Joicey cabinet Haslemere Educational Museum drawer no 14.jpg|alt=Photograph of a drawer of pinned butterflies|South American ''[[Papilio]]''\nFile:JJ Joicey cabinet Haslemere Educational Museum drawer no 14 close-up.jpg|alt=Photograph of pinned butterflies with notes under each|South American ''Papilio'' (detail)    \n</gallery>\n\n==Legacy==\nJoicey's Hill Museum produced over 190 research articles which were published in a range of scientific journals.<ref name=\"Riley\" /> In 1934, the Natural History Museum received more than 300,000 specimens as part of the Joicey [[Bequest]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Natural History Museum: Gift of Butterfly Collection|last=|first=|date=27 March 1934|work=The Times|access-date=|page=17}}</ref> Together with the [[Charles Oberthur|Oberth\u00fcr]] and [[Walter Rothschild, 2nd Baron Rothschild|Rothschild]] collections, the Joicey collection contributed to the quality and numerical predominance of the Lepidoptera collection held by the Natural History Museum, London.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"Miller\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhm.ac.uk/our-science/collections/entomology-collections/lepidoptera-collections.html|title=Lepidoptera collections|last=|first=|date=|website=National History Museum|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=9 April 1932|title=Mr. J. J. Joicey|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/129535a0.pdf|journal=Nature|volume=129|issue=3258|pages=535|doi=10.1038/129535a0|access-date=22 November 2019|via=}}</ref>\n\nA report in ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'' stated that,\n\n<blockquote>During his life-time, the late J. J. Joicey probably did more to stimulate the study of butterflies and moths, especially those of Africa, than any other private individual in Great Britain.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=31 March 1934|title=Recent Acquisitions at the Natural History Museum|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/133490b0.pdf|journal=Nature|volume=133|issue=3361|pages=490|doi=10.1038/133490b0|access-date=6 December 2019|via=}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Works==\n===Joicey and Talbot (partial list)===\n*New Species of Heterocera from Dutch New Guinea. ''Annals and Magazine of Natural History'' (Eighth series) '''15''' (87): [[iarchive:annalsmagazineof8151915lond/page/295|295\u2013301]], pl. [[iarchive:annalsmagazineof8151915lond/page/n662/mode/1up|XII]] (1915)\n*New Lepidoptera from the Dutch New Guinea (with A. Noakes). ''Transactions of the Entomological Society of London'' '''63''' (3,4): [[iarchive:transactionsofen1915roya/page/361/mode/1up|361\u2013386]], pls [[iarchive:transactionsofen1915roya/page/n587|LV\u2013LXII]] (1916)\n*New Lepidoptera from the Schouten Islands. ''Transactions of the Entomological Society of London'' '''64''' (1): [[iarchive:transactionsofen1916roya/page/65/mode/1up|65\u201383]], pls [[iarchive:transactionsofen1916roya/page/n151|3\u20136]] (1916)\n*New Heterocera from Dutch New Guinea. ''Annals and Magazine of Natural History'' (Eighth series) '''20''' (115): [[iarchive:annalsmagazineof8201917lond/page/50|50\u201387]], pls [[iarchive:annalsmagazineof8201917lond/page/n484/mode/1up|1\u20134]] (1917)\n*New Lepidoptera from Waigeu, Dutch New Guinea and Biak. ''Annals and Magazine of Natural History'' (Eighth series) '''20''' (117): [[iarchive:annalsmagazineof8201917lond/page/216|216\u2013229]] (1917)\n*New South-American Rhopalocera. ''Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London'' '''1917''': [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/259/mode/1up|259\u2013264]], pl [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/n363/mode/1up|I]] (1918)\n*New South-American Arctiidae. ''Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London'' '''1917''': [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/265/mode/1up|265\u2013270]], pl [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/n363/mode/1up|I]] (1918)\n*New butterflies from Africa and the east. ''Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London'' '''1917''': [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/271/mode/1up|271\u2013272]] (1918)\n*A Gynandromorph of ''Papilio lycophron'' Hbn. ''Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London'' '''1917''': [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/273/mode/1up|273]], pl [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/n379/mode/1up|II]] (1918)\n*Three Aberrations of Lepidoptera. ''Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London'' '''1917''': [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/275/mode/1up|275\u2013276]], pl [[iarchive:proceedingsofzoo19171338zool/page/n363/mode/1up|I]] (1918)\n*New forms of Indo-Australian butterflies. ''Bulletin of the Hill Museum'' '''1''' (3): [https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/565/mode/1up 565\u2013569] (1924)\n*New forms of Lepidoptera Rhopalocera. ''Encyclopedia of Entomology'' (B III Lepidoptera) '''2''': 1\u201314 (1926)\n*New forms of Rhopalocera in the Hill Museum. ''Bulletin of the Hill Museum'' '''2''' (1): [[iarchive:in.ernet.dli.2015.28174/page/n29|19\u201327]] (1928)\n*Also see the [http://bionames.org/authors/J%20J%20Joicey BioNames database] linking taxonomic names to their original descriptions\n\n{{Quote box\n| quote = The majority of the papers are of a purely [[Systematics|systematic]] nature, consisting of the description of new [[species]] or the revision of various [[Genus|genera]]; but there are several of principally [[Fauna|faunistic]] interest, as, for example, the Catalogue of the Lepidoptera of Hainan. They represent a contribution to the study of the exotic Lepidoptera of very great scientific value.\n| source = Joicey's obituary in ''The Entomologist'', 1932<ref name=\"Riley\" />{{Rp|144}}\n| align = right\n| width = 300px\n}}\n\n===Associated with the Hill Museum===\n'''''The Bulletin of the Hill Museum''''' (111 articles and 80 plates<ref name=\"Riley\" />)\n*[https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/n12/mode/1up 1921]\n*[https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/n13/mode/2up 1921\u20131924]\n*[https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/n15/mode/2up 1924]\n*[[iarchive:in.ernet.dli.2015.28174/page/n7/mode/2up|1928]]\n*[[iarchive:in.ernet.dli.2015.28172/page/n7/mode/2up|1929]]\n*[[iarchive:in.ernet.dli.2015.28175/page/n7/mode/1up|1931]]\n\n'''''Other journals''''' (82 articles<ref name=\"Riley\" />) (partial list)\n\n*[https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/13/mode/1up 1914\u20131916]\n*[https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/14/mode/2up 1916\u20131921]\n*[https://archive.org/stream/bulletinofh112192122hill#page/572/mode/1up 1921\u20131924]\n*[[iarchive:in.ernet.dli.2015.28174/page/n207/mode/2up|1924\u20131927]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==Summaries==\n*Anon. 1932: [Joicey, J. J.] ''Entomological News'' '''43''': [[iarchive:entomologicalnew42amer/page/140/mode/1up|140]]\n*Anon. 1932: [Joicey, J. J.] ''London Naturalist'' '''1931''': [[iarchive:londonnaturalist1931lond/page/n51/mode/1up|38]]\n*Anon. 1932: [Joicey, J. J.] ''Nature'' '''129''': [https://www.nature.com/articles/129535a0.pdf 535], [https://www.nature.com/articles/129896a0.pdf 896]\n*Anon. 1932: [Joicey J. J.]  ''Orchid Review'' '''40''': [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=7nUhAQAAIAAJ&q=joicey 118]\n*Anon. 1932: [Joicey J. J.] ''The Times'' (16 March) p.&nbsp;9\n*Gilbert, P.  2000: ''Butterfly Collectors and Painters: Four Centuries of Colour Plates from the Library Collections of the Natural History Museum, London''. Singapore, Beaumont Publishing Pte Ltd: X+166 S, pp. [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=WQBNAAAAYAAJ&dq=%22Butterfly+Collectors+and+Painters.+Four+centuries+of+colour+plates+from+The+Library+Collections+of+The+Natural+History+Museum%2C+London.%22&q=joicey 31]\u201333\n*Riley, N. D. 1932: [Joicey, J. J.] ''Entomologist'' '''65''': 142\u2013144\n*Turner, H. J. 1932: [Joicey, J. J.] ''Entomologist's Record & Journal of Variation'' '''44''': [[iarchive:entomologistsr441932tutt/page/68/mode/1up|68]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=James John Joicey}}\n*[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/205188852/james-john-joicey Grave site]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Joicey, James John}}\n[[Category:1870 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:British entomologists]]\n[[Category:English lepidopterists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Entomological Society]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Zoological Society of London]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Geographical Society]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Linnean Society of London]]\n[[Category:People from Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n", "name_user": "RLO1729", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCollections:revised text", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_John_Joicey"}
{"title_page": "Granny Smith", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Infobox cultivar\n| name = ''Malus'' 'Granny Smith'\n| image = Granny smith and cross section.jpg\n| hybrid = Thought to be<br/>''[[Malus pumila]]'' \u00d7 ''[[Malus sylvestris|M. sylvestris]]''\n| cultivar = 'Granny Smith'\n| origin = [[Maria Ann Smith]]<br/>[[Australia]], 1868\n}}\n\nThe '''Granny Smith''' is a tip-bearing [[apple]] [[cultivar]], which originated in [[Australia]] in 1868.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/smith-maria-ann-13199 |title=Smith, Maria Ann (1799\u20131870) |work=[[Australian Dictionary of Biography]]|accessdate=2012-01-23}}</ref>  It is named after [[Maria Ann Smith]], who [[Fruit tree propagation|propagated]] the cultivar from a [[chance seedling]]. The tree is thought to be a [[Hybrid (biology)|hybrid]] of ''[[Malus sylvestris]]'', the European wild apple, with the domesticated apple ''[[Malus pumila]]'' as the [[polleniser]].{{cn|date=October 2018}}\n\nThe fruit is hard, with a light green skin and crisp, juicy flesh. The flavour is tart and acidic. It remains firm when baked, making it a very popular [[cooking apple]]<ref>http://dish.allrecipes.com/apples/</ref> used in pies, where it can be sweetened.  The apple goes from being completely green to turning yellow when overripe.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://journal.ashspublications.org/content/123/2/305.full.pdf |title=Temperature affects postharvest colour changes of apple |author=J. Dixon |author2=E. W. Hewett |publisher=Massey University |location=Palmerston, New Zealand |year=1998}}</ref>\n\nIt is claimed to be the third most popular apple in America by the [[US Apple Association]].<ref>Grondine, Tracy (2018). [http://usapple.org/after-50-years-red-delicious-falls-to-2-as-most-grown-u-s-apple-gala-takes-1-spot/ \"After 50+ years, red delicious falls to #2 as most grown U.S. apple, gala takes #1 spot\"]. U.S. Apple Association. Retrieved Sept. 24, 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Granny Smith  was one of four apples honored by the [[United States Postal Service]] in a 2013 set of four 33\u00a2 stamps commemorating historic strains, joined by [[Northern Spy (apple)|Northern Spy]], [[Baldwin (apple)|Baldwin]], and [[Golden Delicious]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://about.usps.com/news/national-releases/2013/pr13_004.htm |title=Postal Service Issues Apples Postcard Stamps; Release No. 13-004 |date=January 17, 2013 |author1=art by Derry Noyes  |author2=John Burgoyne  |lastauthoramp=yes |accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Granny Smith.jpg|thumb|left|160px|Maria Ann \"Granny\" Smith (1799\u20131870)]]\nThe Granny Smith Cultivar originated in [[Eastwood, New South Wales]], Australia (now a suburb of [[Sydney]]) in 1868. Its discoverer, [[Maria Ann Smith]], had emigrated to the district from [[Beckley, East Sussex]] in 1839 with her husband Thomas.<ref name=Christie>{{cite book|last=Christie|first=Michael|title=The Sydney Markets 1788-1988|date=1988|publisher=Sydney Markets Authority|location=Sydney, NSW|isbn=0-7305-5714-6|pages=64\u201365}}</ref>  They purchased a small orchard in the area in 1855-1856 and began cultivating fruit, for which the area was a well known centre in [[colonial Australia]]. Smith had eight children and was a prominent figure in the district, earning the nickname \"Granny\" Smith in her advanced years.<ref name= RydeCouncil>{{cite web|url=http://www.ryde.nsw.gov.au/About+Ryde/Historic+Ryde/Historic+Figures/Granny+Smith|title=Granny Smith|publisher=City of Ryde|accessdate=2012-09-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102071535/http://www.ryde.nsw.gov.au/About+Ryde/Historic+Ryde/Historic+Figures/Granny+Smith|archive-date=2 November 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nWeird\nThe first description of the origin of the Granny Smith apple was not published until 1924. In that year, ''Farmer and Settler'' published the account of a local historian who had interviewed two men who had known Smith. One of those interviewed recalled that, in 1868, he (then twelve years old) and his father had been invited to Smith's farm to inspect a [[chance seedling]] that had sprung near a creek. Smith had dumped there, among the ferns, the remains of French [[Malus|crab-apples]] that had been grown in [[Tasmania]].<ref name=\"Martin 2005\">{{cite book|last=Martin|first=Megan|title=Smith, Maria Ann (1799\u20131870)|year=2005|publisher=Australian Dictionary of Biography|location=Canberra, ACT|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/smith-maria-ann-13199}}</ref> Another story recounted that Smith had been testing French crab-apples for cooking, and, throwing the apple cores out her window as she worked, had found that the new cultivar had sprung up underneath her kitchen windowsill. Whatever the case, Smith took it upon herself to [[Fruit tree propagation|propagate]] the new cultivar on her property, finding the apples good for cooking and for general consumption.<ref name =Symons>{{cite book|last=Symons|first=Michael|title=One Continuous Picnic: A Gastronomic History of Australia|year=2007|publisher=Melbourne University Press|location=Carlton, Victoria|isbn=978-0522853230|pages=110\u2013112|edition=2nd}}</ref> Having \"all the appearances of a cooking apple,\" they were not tart but instead were \"sweet and crisp to eat.\"<ref name=Christie/> She took a stall at Sydney's George Street market, where the apples stored \"exceptionally well and became popular\" and \"once a week sold her produce there.\"<ref name=Christie/>\nMoo\nSmith died only a couple of years after her discovery (in 1870), but her work had been noticed by other local planters. Edward Gallard was one such planter, who extensively planted Granny Smith trees on his property and bought the Smith farm when Thomas died in 1876. Gallard was successful in marketing the apple locally, but it did not receive widespread attention until 1890. In that year, it was exhibited as \"Smith's Seedling\" at the [[Castle Hill, New South Wales|Castle Hill]] Agricultural and Horticultural Show, and the following year it won the prize for cooking apples under the name ''\"Granny'' Smith's Seedling.\" The apple was so highly successful that the following year, many were exhibiting Granny Smith apples at horticultural shows.<ref name= RydeCouncil/>\n\nIn 1895, the New South Wales Department of Agriculture recognised the cultivar and had begun growing the trees at the Government Experimental Station in [[Bathurst, New South Wales]], recommending the gazette its properties as a late-picking cooking apple for potential export. Over the following years the government actively promoted the apple, leading to its widespread adoption.<ref name=\"Martin 2005\"/> Its worldwide fame grew from the fact that it could be picked from March and stored till November. Enterprising fruit merchants in the 1890s and the 1900s experimented with methods to transport the apples overseas in cold storage. Because of its excellent [[shelf life]], the Granny Smith could be exported long distances and most times of the year, at a time when Australian food exports were growing dramatically on the back of international demand. Granny Smiths were exported in enormous quantities after the [[World War I|First World War]], and by 1975, 40 percent of Australia's apple crop was Granny Smith.<ref name =Symons/>\nBy this time, it was being grown intensely elsewhere in the [[Southern Hemisphere]], as well as in [[France]] and the [[United States]]. The advent of the Granny Smith apple is now celebrated annually in Eastwood with the [[Granny Smith Festival]].\n\n==Properties==\n{{nutritionalvalue | name=Apple, raw, with skin | kJ=218 | protein=0.26 g | fat=0.17 g | carbs=13.81 g | fiber=2.4 g | | sugars=10.39 g | iron_mg=0.12 | calcium_mg=6 | magnesium_mg=5 | phosphorus_mg=11 | potassium_mg=107 | zinc_mg=0.04 | vitC_mg=4.6 | pantothenic_mg=0.061 | vitB6_mg=0.041 | folate_ug=3 | thiamin_mg=0.017 | riboflavin_mg=0.026 | niacin_mg=0.091 | right=1 | source_usda=1 }}\nSeedling apples are genetically variable. They are often poor in quality, and varieties do not come true from seed. To preserve the exact genetic variation, [[grafting]] is the usual method of propagation (and [[cutting (plant)|cuttings]] are sometimes used). All the Granny Smith apple trees grown today are [[cloning|clones]] from the original Smith tree in Sydney.<ref>{{cite book|last=Stirzaker|first=Richard|title=Out of the Scientist's Garden: A Story of Water and Food|year=2010|publisher=CSIRO Pub.|location=Collingwood, VIC|isbn=978-0643096585|page=27}}</ref>\n\nGranny Smith apples are light green in colour. They are popularly used in many [[List of apple dishes|apple dishes]], such as [[apple pie]], apple [[cobbler (food)|cobbler]], [[apple crumble]], and [[apple cake]].  They are also commonly eaten raw as [[table apple]]s, and at least one company ([[Woodchuck Hard Cider]]) makes Granny Smith [[varietal]] [[cider]].\n\nIt is moderately susceptible to [[fire blight]] and is highly prone to [[apple scab|scab]],<ref>Dr. Stephen Miller of the USDA Fruit Research Lab in Kearneysville, West Virginia.</ref> [[powdery mildew]], and [[cedar apple rust]].\n\nGranny Smith is much more easily preserved in storage than other apples, a factor which has greatly contributed to its success in export markets. Its long storage life has been attributed to its fairly low levels of [[ethylene]] production, and in the right conditions Granny Smiths can be stored without loss of quality for as long as a year. This cultivar needs fewer winter [[chilling requirement|chill hours]] and a longer season to mature the fruit, so it is favoured for the milder areas of the apple growing regions. However, they are susceptible to superficial scald and bitter pit. Superficial scald may be controlled by treatment with [[diphenylamine]] before storage.<ref>Hall.E.G. Scott, K.J.and Coote, G.G. (1961) Control of superficial scald with Diphenylamine. Aust.J. Agric.Res. 12 :834-857</ref> It can also be controlled with low-oxygen storage.<ref>Little., C.R. And Holmes, R.J. (2000) Storage technology of apples and pears. Institute for Horticultural Development, Knoxfield Vic Australia</ref> Pit can be controlled with calcium sprays during the growing season and with postharvest calcium dips.<ref>Scott, K.J. O'Loughlin, J. England, B.and Roberts, E.A. (1985) Effects of water rinses after Calcium Chloride dips, with and without additives in the control of bitter pit of apples. Aust.J. Agric. Res.36 : 305-313</ref>\n\n===Health benefits===\n[[File:Granny smith.jpg|thumb|Granny Smith are distinctive in being bright green when ripe]]\n\nGranny Smith is one of several apple cultivars that are high in [[antioxidant]] activity, and they have the highest concentration of [[phenols]] amongst the apple breeds.<ref>Olson, Samantha (2014). An apple a day keeps the fat away; Granny Smith's fiber and polyphenol count promote overall health. Medical Daily Newsletter. Retrieved Sept. 24, 2019. https://www.medicaldaily.com/apple-day-keeps-fat-away-granny-smiths-fiber-and-polyphenol-count-promote-overall-health-305654</ref> Some sources recommend Granny Smiths (among other apples) as a particularly efficient source of antioxidants, particularly the [[flavonoid]]s [[cyanidin]] and [[epicatechin]], especially if eaten with the skin intact.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irishhealth.com/article.html?id=15976|title=Granny Smith is healthiest apple|accessdate=2013-02-27}}</ref> Granny Smiths are also naturally low in calories and high in [[dietary fiber]] and [[potassium]], making them commonly recommended as a component of healthy and weight-loss diets.<ref>{{cite news|last=Coffman|first=Melody Anne|title=The Health Benefits of Granny Smith Apples|url=http://healthyeating.sfgate.com/health-benefits-granny-smith-apples-3334.html|accessdate=22 June 2013|newspaper=Healthy Eating}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[US Apple Association]] website, it is one of the fifteen most popular apple cultivars in the United States.<ref>[http://www.usapple.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=21&Itemid=21 Apple varieties] by [[US Apple Association]]</ref>\n\n==Cultural references==\nIn 1968 the pop/rock band [[The Beatles]] used an image of a Granny Smith apple as the logo for their corporation, Apple Corps Limited. For their record label, Apple Records, one side of vinyl albums featured the exterior of the fruit whilst the other side of the recording featured a cross-section of the apple.<ref>Camm-Jones, Ben (2011). Apple applies for Beatles' Granny Smith logo trademark. CIO. Retrieved Sept. 24, 2019. https://www.cio.com/article/2410206/apple-applies-for-beatles--granny-smith-logo-trademark.html</ref>\n\n[[Yoko Ono]]'s 1966 artwork ''[[Apple (artwork)|Apple]]'' used a Granny Smith apple in its 2015 recreation at New York City's [[Museum of Modern Art]]. [[John Lennon]] had taken a bite from the apple on display in its 1966 incarnation at the [[Indica Gallery]] in London.<ref name=VF15>{{cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/culture/2015/05/yoko-ono-moma-exhibit-review|title=The Two Must-See, Must-Do, Must Step-On Works at Yoko Ono's MoMA Show|date=May 2015|author=Bruce Handy|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|accessdate=10 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Candy apple]]\n*[[List of apple dishes]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Commons category|Granny Smith}}\n\n{{Apples|state=collapsed}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2011}}\n\n[[Category:Australian apples]]\n[[Category:Cooking apples]]\n[[Category:Granny Smith]]\n[[Category:Apple Corps]]\n[[Category:Apple cultivars]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Infobox cultivar\n| name = ''Malus'' 'Granny Smith'\n| image = Granny smith and cross section.jpg\n| hybrid = Thought to be<br/>''[[Malus pumila]]'' \u00d7 ''[[Malus sylvestris|M. sylvestris]]''\n| cultivar = 'Granny Smith'\n| origin = [[Maria Ann Smith]]<br/>[[Australia]], 1868\n}}\n\nThe '''Granny Smith''' is a tip-bearing [[apple]] [[cultivar]], which originated in [[Australia]] in 1868.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/smith-maria-ann-13199 |title=Smith, Maria Ann (1799\u20131870) |work=[[Australian Dictionary of Biography]]|accessdate=2012-01-23}}</ref>  It is named after [[Maria Ann Smith]], who [[Fruit tree propagation|propagated]] the cultivar from a [[chance seedling]]. The tree is thought to be a [[Hybrid (biology)|hybrid]] of ''[[Malus sylvestris]]'', the European wild apple, with the domesticated apple ''[[Malus pumila]]'' as the [[polleniser]].{{cn|date=October 2018}}\n\nThe fruit is hard, with a light green skin and crisp, juicy flesh. The flavour is tart and acidic. It remains firm when baked, making it a very popular [[cooking apple]]<ref>http://dish.allrecipes.com/apples/</ref> used in pies, where it can be sweetened.  The apple goes from being completely green to turning yellow when overripe.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://journal.ashspublications.org/content/123/2/305.full.pdf |title=Temperature affects postharvest colour changes of apple |author=J. Dixon |author2=E. W. Hewett |publisher=Massey University |location=Palmerston, New Zealand |year=1998}}</ref>\n\nIt is claimed to be the third most popular apple in America by the [[US Apple Association]].<ref>Grondine, Tracy (2018). [http://usapple.org/after-50-years-red-delicious-falls-to-2-as-most-grown-u-s-apple-gala-takes-1-spot/ \"After 50+ years, red delicious falls to #2 as most grown U.S. apple, gala takes #1 spot\"]. U.S. Apple Association. Retrieved Sept. 24, 2019.</ref>\n\nThe Granny Smith  was one of four apples honored by the [[United States Postal Service]] in a 2013 set of four 33\u00a2 stamps commemorating historic strains, joined by [[Northern Spy (apple)|Northern Spy]], [[Baldwin (apple)|Baldwin]], and [[Golden Delicious]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://about.usps.com/news/national-releases/2013/pr13_004.htm |title=Postal Service Issues Apples Postcard Stamps; Release No. 13-004 |date=January 17, 2013 |author1=art by Derry Noyes  |author2=John Burgoyne  |lastauthoramp=yes |accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Granny Smith.jpg|thumb|left|160px|Maria Ann \"Granny\" Smith (1799\u20131870)]]\nThe Granny Smith Cultivar originated in [[Eastwood, New South Wales]], Australia (now a suburb of [[Sydney]]) in 1868. Its discoverer, [[Maria Ann Smith]], had emigrated to the district from [[Beckley, East Sussex]] in 1839 with her husband Thomas.<ref name=Christie>{{cite book|last=Christie|first=Michael|title=The Sydney Markets 1788-1988|date=1988|publisher=Sydney Markets Authority|location=Sydney, NSW|isbn=0-7305-5714-6|pages=64\u201365}}</ref>  They purchased a small orchard in the area in 1855-1856 and began cultivating fruit, for which the area was a well known centre in [[colonial Australia]]. Smith had eight children and was a prominent figure in the district, earning the nickname \"Granny\" Smith in her advanced years.<ref name= RydeCouncil>{{cite web|url=http://www.ryde.nsw.gov.au/About+Ryde/Historic+Ryde/Historic+Figures/Granny+Smith|title=Granny Smith|publisher=City of Ryde|accessdate=2012-09-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102071535/http://www.ryde.nsw.gov.au/About+Ryde/Historic+Ryde/Historic+Figures/Granny+Smith|archive-date=2 November 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe first description of the origin of the Granny Smith apple was not published until 1924. In that year, ''Farmer and Settler'' published the account of a local historian who had interviewed two men who had known Smith. One of those interviewed recalled that, in 1868, he (then twelve years old) and his father had been invited to Smith's farm to inspect a [[chance seedling]] that had sprung near a creek. Smith had dumped there, among the ferns, the remains of French [[Malus|crab-apples]] that had been grown in [[Tasmania]].<ref name=\"Martin 2005\">{{cite book|last=Martin|first=Megan|title=Smith, Maria Ann (1799\u20131870)|year=2005|publisher=Australian Dictionary of Biography|location=Canberra, ACT|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/smith-maria-ann-13199}}</ref> Another story recounted that Smith had been testing French crab-apples for cooking, and, throwing the apple cores out her window as she worked, had found that the new cultivar had sprung up underneath her kitchen windowsill. Whatever the case, Smith took it upon herself to [[Fruit tree propagation|propagate]] the new cultivar on her property, finding the apples good for cooking and for general consumption.<ref name =Symons>{{cite book|last=Symons|first=Michael|title=One Continuous Picnic: A Gastronomic History of Australia|year=2007|publisher=Melbourne University Press|location=Carlton, Victoria|isbn=978-0522853230|pages=110\u2013112|edition=2nd}}</ref> Having \"all the appearances of a cooking apple,\" they were not tart but instead were \"sweet and crisp to eat.\"<ref name=Christie/> She took a stall at Sydney's George Street market, where the apples stored \"exceptionally well and became popular\" and \"once a week sold her produce there.\"<ref name=Christie/>\n\nSmith died only a couple of years after her discovery (in 1870), but her work had been noticed by other local planters. Edward Gallard was one such planter, who extensively planted Granny Smith trees on his property and bought the Smith farm when Thomas died in 1876. Gallard was successful in marketing the apple locally, but it did not receive widespread attention until 1890. In that year, it was exhibited as \"Smith's Seedling\" at the [[Castle Hill, New South Wales|Castle Hill]] Agricultural and Horticultural Show, and the following year it won the prize for cooking apples under the name ''\"Granny'' Smith's Seedling.\" The apple was so highly successful that the following year, many were exhibiting Granny Smith apples at horticultural shows.<ref name= RydeCouncil/>\n\nIn 1895, the New South Wales Department of Agriculture recognised the cultivar and had begun growing the trees at the Government Experimental Station in [[Bathurst, New South Wales]], recommending the gazette its properties as a late-picking cooking apple for potential export. Over the following years the government actively promoted the apple, leading to its widespread adoption.<ref name=\"Martin 2005\"/> Its worldwide fame grew from the fact that it could be picked from March and stored till November. Enterprising fruit merchants in the 1890s and the 1900s experimented with methods to transport the apples overseas in cold storage. Because of its excellent [[shelf life]], the Granny Smith could be exported long distances and most times of the year, at a time when Australian food exports were growing dramatically on the back of international demand. Granny Smiths were exported in enormous quantities after the [[World War I|First World War]], and by 1975, 40 percent of Australia's apple crop was Granny Smith.<ref name =Symons/>\nBy this time, it was being grown intensely elsewhere in the [[Southern Hemisphere]], as well as in [[France]] and the [[United States]]. The advent of the Granny Smith apple is now celebrated annually in Eastwood with the [[Granny Smith Festival]].\n\n==Properties==\n{{nutritionalvalue | name=Apple, raw, with skin | kJ=218 | protein=0.26 g | fat=0.17 g | carbs=13.81 g | fiber=2.4 g | | sugars=10.39 g | iron_mg=0.12 | calcium_mg=6 | magnesium_mg=5 | phosphorus_mg=11 | potassium_mg=107 | zinc_mg=0.04 | vitC_mg=4.6 | pantothenic_mg=0.061 | vitB6_mg=0.041 | folate_ug=3 | thiamin_mg=0.017 | riboflavin_mg=0.026 | niacin_mg=0.091 | right=1 | source_usda=1 }}\nSeedling apples are genetically variable. They are often poor in quality, and varieties do not come true from seed. To preserve the exact genetic variation, [[grafting]] is the usual method of propagation (and [[cutting (plant)|cuttings]] are sometimes used). All the Granny Smith apple trees grown today are [[cloning|clones]] from the original Smith tree in Sydney.<ref>{{cite book|last=Stirzaker|first=Richard|title=Out of the Scientist's Garden: A Story of Water and Food|year=2010|publisher=CSIRO Pub.|location=Collingwood, VIC|isbn=978-0643096585|page=27}}</ref>\n\nGranny Smith apples are light green in colour. They are popularly used in many [[List of apple dishes|apple dishes]], such as [[apple pie]], apple [[cobbler (food)|cobbler]], [[apple crumble]], and [[apple cake]].  They are also commonly eaten raw as [[table apple]]s, and at least one company ([[Woodchuck Hard Cider]]) makes Granny Smith [[varietal]] [[cider]].\n\nIt is moderately susceptible to [[fire blight]] and is highly prone to [[apple scab|scab]],<ref>Dr. Stephen Miller of the USDA Fruit Research Lab in Kearneysville, West Virginia.</ref> [[powdery mildew]], and [[cedar apple rust]].\n\nGranny Smith is much more easily preserved in storage than other apples, a factor which has greatly contributed to its success in export markets. Its long storage life has been attributed to its fairly low levels of [[ethylene]] production, and in the right conditions Granny Smiths can be stored without loss of quality for as long as a year. This cultivar needs fewer winter [[chilling requirement|chill hours]] and a longer season to mature the fruit, so it is favoured for the milder areas of the apple growing regions. However, they are susceptible to superficial scald and bitter pit. Superficial scald may be controlled by treatment with [[diphenylamine]] before storage.<ref>Hall.E.G. Scott, K.J.and Coote, G.G. (1961) Control of superficial scald with Diphenylamine. Aust.J. Agric.Res. 12 :834-857</ref> It can also be controlled with low-oxygen storage.<ref>Little., C.R. And Holmes, R.J. (2000) Storage technology of apples and pears. Institute for Horticultural Development, Knoxfield Vic Australia</ref> Pit can be controlled with calcium sprays during the growing season and with postharvest calcium dips.<ref>Scott, K.J. O'Loughlin, J. England, B.and Roberts, E.A. (1985) Effects of water rinses after Calcium Chloride dips, with and without additives in the control of bitter pit of apples. Aust.J. Agric. Res.36 : 305-313</ref>\n\n===Health benefits===\n[[File:Granny smith.jpg|thumb|Granny Smith are distinctive in being bright green when ripe]]\n\nGranny Smith is one of several apple cultivars that are high in [[antioxidant]] activity, and they have the highest concentration of [[phenols]] amongst the apple breeds.<ref>Olson, Samantha (2014). An apple a day keeps the fat away; Granny Smith's fiber and polyphenol count promote overall health. Medical Daily Newsletter. Retrieved Sept. 24, 2019. https://www.medicaldaily.com/apple-day-keeps-fat-away-granny-smiths-fiber-and-polyphenol-count-promote-overall-health-305654</ref> Some sources recommend Granny Smiths (among other apples) as a particularly efficient source of antioxidants, particularly the [[flavonoid]]s [[cyanidin]] and [[epicatechin]], especially if eaten with the skin intact.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irishhealth.com/article.html?id=15976|title=Granny Smith is healthiest apple|accessdate=2013-02-27}}</ref> Granny Smiths are also naturally low in calories and high in [[dietary fiber]] and [[potassium]], making them commonly recommended as a component of healthy and weight-loss diets.<ref>{{cite news|last=Coffman|first=Melody Anne|title=The Health Benefits of Granny Smith Apples|url=http://healthyeating.sfgate.com/health-benefits-granny-smith-apples-3334.html|accessdate=22 June 2013|newspaper=Healthy Eating}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[US Apple Association]] website, it is one of the fifteen most popular apple cultivars in the United States.<ref>[http://www.usapple.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=21&Itemid=21 Apple varieties] by [[US Apple Association]]</ref>\n\n==Cultural references==\nIn 1968 the pop/rock band [[The Beatles]] used an image of a Granny Smith apple as the logo for their corporation, Apple Corps Limited. For their record label, Apple Records, one side of vinyl albums featured the exterior of the fruit whilst the other side of the recording featured a cross-section of the apple.<ref>Camm-Jones, Ben (2011). Apple applies for Beatles' Granny Smith logo trademark. CIO. Retrieved Sept. 24, 2019. https://www.cio.com/article/2410206/apple-applies-for-beatles--granny-smith-logo-trademark.html</ref>\n\n[[Yoko Ono]]'s 1966 artwork ''[[Apple (artwork)|Apple]]'' used a Granny Smith apple in its 2015 recreation at New York City's [[Museum of Modern Art]]. [[John Lennon]] had taken a bite from the apple on display in its 1966 incarnation at the [[Indica Gallery]] in London.<ref name=VF15>{{cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/culture/2015/05/yoko-ono-moma-exhibit-review|title=The Two Must-See, Must-Do, Must Step-On Works at Yoko Ono's MoMA Show|date=May 2015|author=Bruce Handy|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|accessdate=10 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Candy apple]]\n*[[List of apple dishes]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Commons category|Granny Smith}}\n\n{{Apples|state=collapsed}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2011}}\n\n[[Category:Australian apples]]\n[[Category:Cooking apples]]\n[[Category:Granny Smith]]\n[[Category:Apple Corps]]\n[[Category:Apple cultivars]]\n", "name_user": "Firekongiscool2", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Granny_Smith"}
{"title_page": "The Whirlwind (1933 film)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|1933 film}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Whirlwind\n| image          = The Whirlwind 1933.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[D. Ross Lederman]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = [[Walter J. Coburn]]<br>[[Stuart Anthony]]\n| starring       = [[Tim McCoy]]\n| distributor    = [[Columbia Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1933|4|14}}\n| runtime        = 62 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n| gross          =\n}}\n\n'''''The Whirlwind''''' is a 1933 American [[Pre-Code]] [[Western (genre)|Western film]] directed by [[D. Ross Lederman]] and starring [[Tim McCoy]].<ref name=\"NYTimes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/116699/The-Whirlwind/overview|title=The Whirlwind|accessdate=November 29, 2014|work=New York Times}}</ref>{{dead link|date=July 2019}}\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Tim McCoy]] as Tim Reynolds\n* Alice Dahl as Mollie Curtis\n* Patrick H. O'Malley, Jr. as Pat Patrick\n* [[J. Carrol Naish]] as 'Injun' (as Carol Naish)\n* [[Matthew Betz]] as Sheriff Tate Hurley\n* [[Joseph W. Girard]] as Mr. Reynolds (as Joseph Girard)\n* [[Mary Gordon (actress)|Mary Gordon]] as Mrs. Curtis\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0024767|The Whirlwind}}\n\n{{D. Ross Lederman |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whirlwind, The}}\n[[Category:1933 films]]\n[[Category:1930s Western (genre) films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American Western (genre) films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by D. Ross Lederman]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films made before the MPAA Production Code]]\n\n{{1930s-Western-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1933 film}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Whirlwind\n| image          = The Whirlwind 1933.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[D. Ross Lederman]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = [[Walter J. Coburn]]<br>[[Stuart Anthony]]\n| starring       = [[Tim McCoy]]\n| distributor    = [[Columbia Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1933|4|14}}\n| runtime        = 62 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n| gross          =\n}}\n\n'''''The Whirlwind''''' is a 1933 American [[Pre-Code]] [[Western (genre)|Western film]] directed by [[D. Ross Lederman]] and starring [[Tim McCoy]].<ref name=\"NYTimes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/116699/The-Whirlwind/overview|title=The Whirlwind|accessdate=November 29, 2014|work=New York Times}}</ref>{{dead link|date=July 2019}}\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Tim McCoy]] as Tim Reynolds\n* Alice Dahl as Mollie Curtis\n* Patrick H. O'Malley, Jr. as Pat Patrick\n* [[J. Carrol Naish]] as 'Injun' (as Carol Naish)\n* [[Matthew Betz]] as Sheriff Tate Hurley\n* [[Joseph W. Girard]] as Mr. Reynolds (as Joseph Girard)\n* [[Mary Gordon (actress)|Mary Gordon]] as Mrs. Curtis\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0024767|The Whirlwind}}\n\n{{D. Ross Lederman |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whirlwind, The}}\n[[Category:1933 films]]\n[[Category:1930s Western (genre) films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American Western (genre) films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by D. Ross Lederman]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films made before the MPAA Production Code]]\n\n{{1930s-Western-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Whirlwind_(1933_film)"}
{"title_page": "Andhra Pradesh Public Service Commission", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2015}}\n{{short description|State government agency}}\n{{Infobox organization\n|name           = Andhra Pradesh State Public Service Commission\n|size           =\n|logo           =\n|alt            = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n|caption        =\n|map            =\n|msize          = <!-- map size, optional, default 200px -->\n|malt           =\n|mcaption       =\n|abbreviation   = APPSC\n|motto          =\n|formation      = 1956<!--{{Start date and years ago|df=yes|1923|MM|dd}}-->\n|extinction     = <!-- date of extinction, optional -->\n|type           = Constitutional body\n|status         = <!-- ad hoc, treaty, foundation, etc -->\n|purpose        = Recruitment\n|headquarters   =\n|location       = APPSC Office, M.G. Road(Bandhar Road), Vijayawada-520 010 Andhra Pradesh.\n|coords         = \n|region_served  = Andhra Pradesh\n|membership     =\n|leader_title1  = Chairman\n|leader_name1   = Dr.Uday Bhaskar\n|num_staff      = \n|num_volunteers =\n|budget         =\n|website        = {{URL|https://psc.ap.gov.in/}}\n|remarks        =\n}}\n\n'''Andhra Pradesh Public Service Commission (APPSC)''' was formed when the state of [[Andhra Pradesh]] formed on 1 November 1956.  Earlier, the commission was known as the ''Andhra Service Commission'' (formed in 1953) which is based on the regulations of ''Madras Public Service Commission''. Later in 1956, APPSC was formed by merging the Andhra Public Service Commission and [[Hyderabad State|Hyderabad]] Public Service Commissions.\n\n== History ==\nOn the eve of formation of Andhra Pradesh Public Service Commission, Andhra Public Service Commission was functioning with a Chairman and two Members and Hyderabad Public Service Commission was functioning with one Member. Hence, A.P. Public Service Commission was constituted with a Chairman and 3 Members. With increasing work load, Government enhanced the strength of the Commission to Chairman and 5 Members in the year 1981 and later to Chairman and 7 Members in the year 1983. Government again reviewed the strength in 1994 and enhanced it to Chairman and 9 Members. This is the present strength also.<ref>{{cite web|title=History of APPSC|url=http://website.apspsc.gov.in/history.appsc|website=APPSC|publisher=APPSC|accessdate=17 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150107162204/http://website.apspsc.gov.in/history.appsc|archive-date=7 January 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Duties and functions ==\nWidely known as APPSC which is a part of Andhra Pradesh government.\nThe Public Service Commissions had been established under Article 315 of the Constitution of India. The functions of the Commission are enumerated in the Article 320 of the Constitution.\n\n=== The statutory functions of the Commission are as follows ===\nDirect Recruitment (Article 320 (1))\nRecruitment by transfer (Article 320(3)(b))\nStatutory rules relating to services (Article 320 (3)(a) and (b))\nDisciplinary cases (Article 320 (3)(c) and regulations 17 (1)(a) to (e))\nReimbursement of legal expenses (Article 320 (3)(d))\nWound and extraordinary pension cases (Article 320 (3)(e))\n\n=== Commission is entrusted with the following items of work ===\nConduct of departmental tests for several departments\nConduct of examination for admission to RIMC, Dehradun.\nConduct of half yearly examination for [[Indian Administrative Service|IAS]] and [[Indian Police Service|IPS]] Officers and proficiency tests for [[All India Services|AIS]] Officers.\nWatching of temporary appointments exceeding 3 months and according concurrence for their continuance (regulation 16)\nConsultation in cases of appointment of contract extending over 5 years (regulation 16).<ref>{{cite web|title=Position under the Constitution|url=http://website.apspsc.gov.in/posUnderConstitution.appsc|website=APPSC|publisher=APPSC|accessdate=17 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118052922/http://website.apspsc.gov.in/posUnderConstitution.appsc|archive-date=18 November 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Telangana State Public Service Commission]]\n* [[Union Public Service Commission]]\n* [[Staff Selection Commission]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130926034308/http://website.apspsc.gov.in/home.appsc Official website of the APPSC]\n*[https://www.gainwgkguru.com/2020/04/ap-panchayat-secretary-syllabus-pdf.html APPSC Panchayat Secretary (Grade-IV) Syllabus]\n* [https://www.gainwgkguru.com/2020/04/appsc-group-2-syllabus-2020-pdf.html Appsc Group - II Exam Pattern 2020]\n*[https://www.gainwgkguru.com/2020/04/ap-dsc-2020-syllabus-pdf-download.html Appsc School Asst (SE), SGT, PGT, TGT & Other Exam Pattern 2020]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130929155355/http://website.apspsc.gov.in/home.appsc APPSC Other Post Exam Pattern 2020]\n{{Public Service Commissions in India}}\n[[Category:State agencies of Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:State public service commissions of India]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2015}}\n{{short description|State government agency}}\n{{Infobox organization\n|name           = Andhra Pradesh State Public Service Commission\n|size           =\n|logo           =\n|alt            = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n|caption        =\n|map            =\n|msize          = <!-- map size, optional, default 200px -->\n|malt           =\n|mcaption       =\n|abbreviation   = APPSC\n|motto          =\n|formation      = 1956<!--{{Start date and years ago|df=yes|1923|MM|dd}}-->\n|extinction     = <!-- date of extinction, optional -->\n|type           = Constitutional body\n|status         = <!-- ad hoc, treaty, foundation, etc -->\n|purpose        = Recruitment\n|headquarters   =\n|location       = APPSC Office, M.G. Road(Bandhar Road), Vijayawada-520 010 Andhra Pradesh.\n|coords         = \n|region_served  = Andhra Pradesh\n|membership     =\n|leader_title1  = Chairman\n|leader_name1   = Dr.Uday Bhaskar\n|num_staff      = \n|num_volunteers =\n|budget         =\n|website        = {{URL|https://psc.ap.gov.in/}}\n|remarks        =\n}}\n\n'''Andhra Pradesh Public Service Commission (APPSC)''' was formed when the state of [[Andhra Pradesh]] formed on 1 November 1956.  Earlier, the commission was known as the ''Andhra Service Commission'' (formed in 1953) which is based on the regulations of ''Madras Public Service Commission''. Later in 1956, APPSC was formed by merging the Andhra Public Service Commission and [[Hyderabad State|Hyderabad]] Public Service Commissions.\n\n== History ==\nOn the eve of formation of Andhra Pradesh Public Service Commission, Andhra Public Service Commission was functioning with a Chairman and two Members and Hyderabad Public Service Commission was functioning with one Member. Hence, A.P. Public Service Commission was constituted with a Chairman and 3 Members. With increasing work load, Government enhanced the strength of the Commission to Chairman and 5 Members in the year 1981 and later to Chairman and 7 Members in the year 1983. Government again reviewed the strength in 1994 and enhanced it to Chairman and 9 Members. This is the present strength also.<ref>{{cite web|title=History of APPSC|url=http://website.apspsc.gov.in/history.appsc|website=APPSC|publisher=APPSC|accessdate=17 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150107162204/http://website.apspsc.gov.in/history.appsc|archive-date=7 January 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Duties and functions ==\nWidely known as APPSC which is a part of Andhra Pradesh government.\nThe Public Service Commissions had been established under Article 315 of the Constitution of India. The functions of the Commission are enumerated in the Article 320 of the Constitution.\n\n=== The statutory functions of the Commission are as follows ===\nDirect Recruitment (Article 320 (1))\nRecruitment by transfer (Article 320(3)(b))\nStatutory rules relating to services (Article 320 (3)(a) and (b))\nDisciplinary cases (Article 320 (3)(c) and regulations 17 (1)(a) to (e))\nReimbursement of legal expenses (Article 320 (3)(d))\nWound and extraordinary pension cases (Article 320 (3)(e))\n\n=== Commission is entrusted with the following items of work ===\nConduct of departmental tests for several departments\nConduct of examination for admission to RIMC, Dehradun.\nConduct of half yearly examination for [[Indian Administrative Service|IAS]] and [[Indian Police Service|IPS]] Officers and proficiency tests for [[All India Services|AIS]] Officers.\nWatching of temporary appointments exceeding 3 months and according concurrence for their continuance (regulation 16)\nConsultation in cases of appointment of contract extending over 5 years (regulation 16).<ref>{{cite web|title=Position under the Constitution|url=http://website.apspsc.gov.in/posUnderConstitution.appsc|website=APPSC|publisher=APPSC|accessdate=17 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118052922/http://website.apspsc.gov.in/posUnderConstitution.appsc|archive-date=18 November 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Telangana State Public Service Commission]]\n* [[Union Public Service Commission]]\n* [[Staff Selection Commission]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130926034308/http://website.apspsc.gov.in/home.appsc Official website of the APPSC]\n{{Public Service Commissions in India}}\n[[Category:State agencies of Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:State public service commissions of India]]\n", "name_user": "\u0930\u093e\u091c\u093e \u092f\u093e\u0926\u0935", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andhra_Pradesh_Public_Service_Commission"}
{"title_page": "Blue jay", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| image = Cyanocitta-cristata-004.jpg\n| image_caption = In [[Algonquin Provincial Park]], Canada\n| image2 = Cyanocitta cristata - Blue Jay - XC109601.ogg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22705611/0 |title=''Cyanocitta cristata'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=November 26, 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Cyanocitta\n| species = cristata\n| authority = ([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]])\n| range_map = Blue_Jay-rangemap.gif\n| range_map_caption = Global range<br/>{{leftlegend|#FFFF00|Breeding range|outline=gray}}{{leftlegend|#00BE03|Year-round range|outline=gray}}{{leftlegend|#0000FF|Wintering range|outline=gray}}See also [[#Distribution and habitat|text]] for recent range expansion.\n| subdivision_ranks = Subspecies\n| subdivision = 4 sspp., see [[#Subspecies|text]]\n| synonyms = ''Corvus cristatus'' {{small|Linnaeus,&nbsp;1758}}\n}}\n\nThe '''blue jay''' (''Cyanocitta cristata'') is a [[passerine]] [[bird]] in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Corvidae]], native to North America. It resides through most of eastern and central United States, although western populations may be migratory. Resident populations are also found in Newfoundland, Canada, while breeding populations can be found across southern Canada. It breeds in both [[deciduous]] and [[coniferous]] forests, and is common in residential areas. It is predominantly blue with a white chest and underparts, and a blue crest; it has a black, U-shaped collar around its neck and a black border behind the crest. Males and females are similar in size and plumage, and plumage does not vary throughout the year. Four subspecies of the blue jay have been recognized.\n\nThe blue jay mainly feeds on nuts and seeds such as [[acorn]]s, soft fruits, [[arthropods]], and occasionally small vertebrates. It typically [[gleaning (birds)|gleans]] food from trees, shrubs, and the ground, though it sometimes [[hawking (birds)|hawks]] insects from the air. Like squirrels, blue jays are known to hide nuts for later consumption.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/seriouslyscience/2014/05/07/blue-jays-coming-hide-kids-hide-nuts/|title=The blue jays are coming! Hide yo kids, hide yo nuts!|work=Seriously, Science?}}</ref> It builds an open cup nest in the branches of a tree, which both sexes participate in constructing. The clutch can contain two to seven eggs, which are blueish or light brown with brown spots. Young are [[altricial]], and are brooded by the female for 8\u201312 days after hatching. They may remain with their parents for one to two months.\n\nThe name \"jay\" derives from its noisy, garrulous nature and has been applied to other birds of the same family, which are also mostly gregarious.<ref>{{cite book |last=Coues |first=Elliot |title=Key to North American birds |edition=5th |date=1890 |publisher=Estes and Lauriat |location=Boston, MA |oclc=469020022 |page=326}}</ref> It is sometimes called a \"jaybird\".<ref>{{cite web |title=jaybird \u2013 definition of jaybird by the Free Online Dictionary, Thesaurus and Encyclopedia|url=http://www.thefreedictionary.com/jaybird |accessdate=April 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe blue jay was first described as  ''Pica glandaria c\u00e6rulea cristata'' in [[England|English]] naturalist [[Mark Catesby]]'s 1731 publication of ''Natural History of Carolina, Florida, and the Bahamas''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Catesby|first=Mark|authorlink=Mark Catesby|title=Natural History of Carolina, Florida, and the Bahamas|edition=1st|date=1731|publisher=Royal Society House|location=[[London]]|page=87|url=http://dc.lib.unc.edu/cdm/compoundobject/collection/dmisc/id/1658/show/1487}}</ref> It was later described as ''Corvus cristatus'' in [[Carl Linnaeus]]' 1758 edition of ''[[Systema Naturae]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Linnaeus|first=C.|authorlink=Carl Linnaeus|title=Systema Naturae per Regna Tria Naturae, Secundum Classes, Ordines, Genera, Species, cum Characteribus, Differentiis, Synonymis, Locis. Tomus I. Editio Decima, Reformata| publisher=Laurentius Salvius|location=[[Stockholm|Holmiae]]|language=Latin| year=1758|page=106|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/727076#page/124/mode/1up}}</ref> In the 19th century, the jay was described by [[France|French]] ornithologist [[Charles Lucien Bonaparte]] in 1838 as ''Cyanocorax cristatus'' in ''A geographical and comparative list of the birds of Europe and North America'',<ref>{{cite book|last=Bonaparte|first=Charles L.|authorlink=Charles Lucien Bonaparte|title=A geographical and comparative list of the birds of Europe and North America|publisher=J. Van Voorst|location=London|year=1838|page=27|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/71558#page/39/mode/1up}}</ref> and given its modern scientific name ''Cyanocitta cristata'' by [[Hugh Edwin Strickland]] in 1845.<ref>{{cite book|title=Bulletin of the National History Survey, Issues 4-6|edition=|date=1900|publisher=Chicago Academy of Sciences|location=Chicago|page=120|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x4YbAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PA120&q=Cyanocitta%20cristata%20Linnaeus%201758}}</ref> The genus name ''Cyanocitta'' derives from the [[Greek language|Greek]] words 'kyaneos' (blue) and the 'kitta' and 'kissa' (chattering bird, jay), and the term 'blue chatterer' refers to the bright blue plumage of the head, nape, back, and tail of the bird. The specific name ''cristata'' (crested, tufted) derives from [[Latin language|Latin]] referring to the prominent blue crest of the jay.<ref name=\"Sandrock\">{{cite book|last=Sandrock|first=James|title=The Scientific Nomenclature of Birds in the Upper Midwest|publisher=University of Iowa Press|year=2014|page=48|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GsTpAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA48|isbn=978-1609382254}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:102 Blue Jay.jpg|thumb|150px|[[John James Audubon]] drawing circa 1830s]] \nThe blue jay measures {{convert|22|-|30|cm|abbr=on|0}} from bill to tail and weighs {{convert|70|-|100|g|abbr=on}}, with a wingspan of {{convert|34|-|43|cm|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"CLO\"/><ref name=\"Frysinger\"/> Consistent with [[Bergmann's rule]], jays from [[Connecticut]] averaged {{convert|92.4|g|oz|abbr=on}} in mass, while jays from warmer southern [[Florida]] averaged {{convert|73.7|g|oz|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Jewell |first=S. D. |title=Weights and wing lengths in Connecticut Blue Jays |date=1986 |journal=Connecticut Warbler |volume=6 |number=4 |pages=47\u201349}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Fisk | first1 = E.J. | year = 1979 | title = Fall and winter birds near Homestead, Florida | url = | journal = Bird-Banding | volume = 50 | issue = 3| pages = 224\u2013303 | doi=10.2307/4512458| jstor = 4512458 }}</ref> There is a pronounced [[Crest (feathers)|crest]] on the head, a crown of feathers, which may be raised or lowered according to the bird's mood. When excited or aggressive, the crest will be fully raised. When frightened, the crest bristles outwards, brushlike. When the bird is feeding among other jays or resting, the crest is flattened on the head.<ref name=\"nero1991\"/>\n\nIts plumage is lavender-blue to mid-blue in the crest, back, wings, and tail, and its face is white. The underside is off-white and the neck is collared with black which extends to the sides of the head. The [[remiges|wing primaries]] and tail are strongly barred with black, sky-blue and white. The bill, legs, and eyes are all black. Males and females are almost identical, but the male is slightly larger.<ref name=\"Frysinger\"/><ref name=\"Madge\"/>\n\nAs with most other blue-hued birds, the blue jay's coloration is not derived from [[pigment]]s but is the result of light [[Interference (wave propagation)|interference]] due to the internal structure of the feathers;<ref>{{cite web |last=Carpenter |first=Anita |title=What Color is a Bluejay? |date=February 2003 |work=Wisconsin Natural Resources Magazine |url=http://dnr.wi.gov/wnrmag/html/stories/2003/feb03/jays.htm}}</ref> if a blue feather is crushed, the blue disappears because the structure is destroyed.<ref name=\"CLO\"/> This is referred to as [[structural coloration]].\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe blue jay occurs from southern Canada (including the southern areas of provinces from Alberta eastward to Quebec and throughout the Atlantic provinces) and throughout the eastern and central United States south to [[Florida]] and northeastern [[Texas]]. The western edge of the range stops where the [[arid]] pine forest and scrub [[habitat]] of the closely related [[Steller's jay]] (''C. stelleri'') begins, generally in the eastern foothills of the Rocky Mountains. Recently, the range of the blue jay has extended northwestwards so that it is now a rare but regularly seen winter visitor along the northern US and southern Canadian [[Pacific]] Coast.<ref name=CLO/> As the two species' ranges now overlap, ''C. cristata'' may sometimes [[hybrid (biology)|hybridize]] with Steller's jay.<ref name=Rhymer/> The increase in trees throughout the Great Plains during the past century due to fire suppression and tree planting facilitated the western range expansion of the blue jay<ref>Smith GH. 1978. Range extension of the Blue Jay into western North America. Bird-Banding 49:208\u2013214.</ref><ref>Tarvin KA, Woolfenden GE. 1999. Blue Jay (''Cyanocitta cristata''), no. 469. In: A. Poole (ed.). The Birds of North America Online. Cornell Lab of Ornithology, Ithaca, New York.</ref> as well as range expansions of many other species of birds.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Livezey | first1 = KB | year = 2009a | title = Range expansion of Barred Owls, part I: chronology and distribution | url = | journal = American Midland Naturalist | volume = 161 | issue = | pages = 49\u201356 | doi=10.1674/0003-0031-161.1.49}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Livezey | first1 = KB | year = 2009b | title = Range expansion of Barred Owls, part 2: facilitating ecological changes | url = | journal = American Midland Naturalist | volume = 161 | issue = 2| pages = 323\u2013349 | doi=10.1674/0003-0031-161.2.323}}</ref><ref>Livezey KB. 2010. Killing barred owls to help spotted owls II: implications for many other range-expanding species. Northwestern Naturalist 91:251\u2013270.</ref>\n\nThe northernmost [[subspecies]] ''C. c. bromia'' is [[bird migration|migratory]], subject to necessity. It may withdraw several hundred kilometres south in the northernmost parts of its range. Thousands of blue jays have been observed to migrate in flocks along the Great Lakes and Atlantic coasts. It migrates during the daytime, in loose flocks of 5 to 250 birds. Much about their migratory behavior remains a mystery. Some are present throughout winter in all parts of their range. Young jays may be more likely to migrate than adults, but many adults also migrate. Some individual jays migrate south one year, stay north the next winter, and then migrate south again the next year. To date, no one has concretely worked out why they migrate when they do. Likely, it is related to weather conditions and how abundant the winter food sources are, which can determine whether other northern birds will move south.<ref name=eggeater/>\n\nThe blue jay occupies a variety of habitats within its large range, from the [[pine]] woods of Florida to the [[spruce]]-[[fir]] forests of northern Ontario. It is less abundant in denser forests, preferring mixed woodlands with [[oak]]s and [[beech]]es.<ref name=nero1991/> It has expertly adapted to human activity, occurring in parks and residential areas, and can adapt to wholesale [[deforestation]] with relative ease if human activity creates other means for the jays to get by.<ref name=henninger1906/>\n\n==Subspecies==\nFour [[subspecies]] are generally accepted, though the variation within this species is rather subtle and essentially [[cline (population genetics)|clinal]]. No firm boundaries can be drawn between the inland subspecies. The ranges of the coastal races are better delimited.<ref name=Madge/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Image !! Subspecies!! Common Name !! Description !!Distribution\n|-\n|[[File:Bluejay (Cyanocitta cristata) (1547) - Relic38.jpg|120px]] ||''Cyanocitta cristata bromia'' ||Northern blue jay || The largest subspecies, with fairly dull plumage. Blue is rather pale. ||Canada and northern United States.\n|-\n|[[File:Blue Jay Ash RWD5.jpg|120px]] || ''Cyanocitta cristata cristata''||Coastal blue jay || Mid-sized and vivid blue. ||Coastal USA from [[North Carolina]] to [[Texas]], except southern [[Florida]]\n|-\n|[[File:Cyanocitta cristata FWS.jpg|120px]] || ''Cyanocitta cristata cyanotephra''||Interior blue jay || Mid-sized, quite dark blue on mantle contrasting cleanly with very white underside. ||Inland USA, intergrading with ''C. c. bromia'' to the north.\n|-\n|[[File:Geai bleu.jpg|120px]] || ''Cyanocitta cristata semplei''|| Florida blue jay||The smallest subspecies, much like ''C. c. bromia'' in color. ||Southern Florida.\n|-\n|}\n\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Blue Jay-27527.jpg|''Cyanocitta cristata cristata'' in [[Johnston County, North Carolina]]\nFile:Young blue jay.jpg|''C. c. bromia'', Northern blue jay, juvenile, in [[Ontario]], Canada\nFile:Blue jay.jpg|''C. c. bromia'', Northern blue jay in Ontario, Canada\nFile:Blue Jay, Melbourne FLorida.jpg|Blue Jay, Melbourne Florida\n</gallery>\n\n==Behavior==\n[[File:MerlinchasingBlueJay08.jpg|thumb|right|[[Merlin (bird)|Merlin]] chasing a blue jay]]\nThthis bird sucks'\n\n==Diet==\n[[File:Blue Jay with Peanut.jpg|thumb|left|Whole [[peanut]]s and other shelled food items are carried off in the beak to be dealt with at leisure.]]\n[[File:Blue jay - nut cracking.ogv|Blue jay cracking nuts|right|Blue jay cracking nuts|thumb]]\nBlue jays have strong black bills which they use for cracking nuts, usually while holding them with their feet, and for eating corn, grains and seeds. Its food is sought both on the ground and in trees and includes virtually all known types of plant and animal sources, such as [[acorn]]s and [[beech]] mast, [[weed]] seeds, [[grain]], [[fruit]]s and other [[berry|berries]], [[peanut]]s, bread, meat, small [[invertebrate]]s of many types, scraps in town parks, [[bird-table]] food and rarely [[egg (biology)|eggs]] and nestlings.<ref name=\"eggeater\" >[http://www.birds.cornell.edu/AllAboutBirds/BirdGuide/Blue_Jay.html Blue Jay]. birds.cornell.edu</ref> Blue jays will sometimes [[cache (biology)|cache]] food, though to what extent differs widely among individuals.<ref>[http://www.allaboutbirds.org/guide/Blue_Jay/id AllAboutBirds.org \u2013 Blue Jay] The Cornell Lab of Ornithology</ref> Although seemingly contentious in their general behavior, blue jays are frequently subservient to other medium-sized birds who visit bird-feeders. In [[Florida]], blue jays were dominated at feeders by [[Eastern gray squirrel]]s, [[Florida scrub-jay]]s, [[common grackle]]s and [[red-headed woodpecker]]s, all of which were occasionally observed to aggressively prevent the jays from feeding.<ref name=eggeater/>\n\n==Reproduction==\n[[File:Blue Jays nest.jpg|thumb|right|Nest in the top of a little pine]]\n[[File:Cyanocitta cristata MWNH 1384.JPG|thumb|Eggs, Collection [[Museum Wiesbaden]]]]\nThe mating season begins in mid-March, peaks in mid-April to May, and extends into July. Any suitable tree or large bush may be used for nesting, though an evergreen is preferred. The nest is preferentially built at a height in the trees of {{convert|3|to|10|m|ft|abbr=on}}. It is cup-shaped and composed of twigs, small roots, bark strips, moss, other plant material, cloth, paper, and feathers, with occasional mud added to the cup.\n\nBlue jays are not very picky about nesting locations. If no better place is available \u2013 e.g. in a heavily [[deforestation|deforested]] area \u2013 they will even use places like the large [[Letter box|mailboxes]] typical of the rural United States.<ref name=henninger1906/> They also appropriate nests of other mid-sized songbirds as long as these are placed in suitable spots; [[American robin]] nests are commonly used by blue jays, for example.\n[[File:Blue Jay Cyanocitta cristata Fledgling.jpg|thumb|left|Fledgling in mid-June]]\n[[File:Blue Jay fledgling head.JPG|thumb|Fledgling head]]\nBlue jays typically form [[monogamy|monogamous]] pair bonds for life. Both sexes build the nest and rear the young, though only the female broods them. The male feeds the female while she is brooding the eggs. There are usually between 3 and 6 (averaging 4 or 5) eggs laid and [[avian incubation|incubated]] over 16\u201318 days. The young [[fledge]] usually between 17\u201321 days after hatching.<ref name=oiseauxnet2008/>\n\nAfter the juveniles fledge, the family travels and forages together until early fall, when the young birds disperse to avoid competition for food during the winter. Sexual maturity is reached after one year of age. Blue jays have been recorded to live for more than 26 years in captivity and one wild jay was found to have been around 16\u201317, and a half years old.<ref>{{cite web |title=Longevity Records Of North American Birds |publisher=U. S. Geological Survey: Bird Banding Laboratory |url=http://www.pwrc.usgs.gov/BBL/longevity/Longevity_main.cfm |accessdate=24 December 2012}}</ref> A more common lifespan for wild birds that survive to adulthood is around 7 years.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.canadiangeographic.ca/article/animal-facts-blue-jay | title = Animal facts: Blue Jay | date = July 26, 2006 | website = Canadian Geographic | publisher = The Royal Canadian Geographical Society | access-date = February 3, 2019}}</ref> Beyond predation and the occasional collision with man-made objects, a common cause of mortality in recent decades has been the [[West Nile virus]], to which corvids as a whole seem especially susceptible. However, despite several major local declines, overall blue jays have not seemed to have been depleted by the disease.<ref name=ADW/>\n\n==Vocalizations==\nBlue jays can make a large variety of sounds, and individuals may vary perceptibly in their calling style. Like other [[corvid]]s, they may learn to mimic human speech. Blue jays can also copy the cries of local hawks so well that it is sometimes difficult to tell which it is.<ref name=George2003/> Their voice is typical of most [[jay]]s in being varied, but the most commonly recognized sound is the alarm call, which is a loud, almost [[gull]]-like scream. There is also a high-pitched ''jayer-jayer'' call that increases in speed as the bird becomes more agitated. This particular call can be easily confused with the chickadee's song because of the slow starting ''chick-ah-dee-ee''. Blue jays will use these calls to band together to [[Mobbing behavior|mob]] potential predators such as [[hawk]]s and drive them away from the jays' nests.\n\n{{Listen\n| filename=Cyanocitta cristata - Blue Jay - XC86756.ogg\n| title=\"Rusty pump\" calls\n}}\n\nBlue jays also have quiet, almost subliminal calls which they use among themselves in proximity. One of the most distinctive calls of this type is often referred to as the \"rusty pump\" owing to its squeaky resemblance to the sound of an old hand-operated [[water pump]]. The blue jay (and other corvids) are distinct from most other songbirds for using their call as a song.\n\n==Cultural symbolism and interpretation==\nIn old [[African-American folktales|African American folklore]] of the southern United States, the blue jay was a significant metaphysical creature. In some tales the blue jay was credited with making the earth \"when all de worl' was water\" by bringing the first \"grit\" or \"dirt\". In other tales the blue jay was temporarily conscripted as a servant of the Devil to bring \"kindling\" to the \"bad place\": and \"was not encountered on a Friday as he was fetching sticks down to Hell; furthermore, he was so happy and chirpy on a Saturday as he was relieved to return from Hell\". <ref name=ingersoll23>{{cite book |last=Ingersoll |first=Ernest |authorlink=Ernest Ingersoll |title=Birds in legend, fable and folklore |publisher=Longmans, Green and Co. |location=New York |date=1923 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/birdsinlegendfab00inge/page/166 166]\u2013167 |url=https://archive.org/details/birdsinlegendfab00inge |accessdate=2009-08-08}}</ref>\n\nThe blue jay was adopted as the team symbol of the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] [[Major League Baseball]] team, as well as some of their [[Minor League Baseball|minor league]] affiliates. Their [[mascot]], [[Toronto Blue Jays mascots|Ace]], is an anthropomorphic blue jay. The blue jay is also the official mascot for [[Johns Hopkins University]], [[Elmhurst College]], and [[Creighton University]]. The latter two spell the name as one word - Bluejay. It is also the [[List of Canadian provincial and territorial symbols|provincial bird]] of the province of [[Prince Edward Island]] in Canada.\n\nIn the 1966 Western film ''[[The Shooting]]'', the blue jay is cited as a sign of good luck.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em|refs=\n<ref name=CLO>[http://www.birds.cornell.edu/AllAboutBirds/BirdGuide/Blue_Jay_dtl.html Blue Jay, Life History, All About Birds - Cornell Lab of Ornithology<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n<ref name=Frysinger>{{cite web|url=http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/site/accounts/information/Cyanocitta_cristata.html|title=ADW: Cyanocitta cristata: INFORMATION|work=Animal Diversity Web}}</ref><!-- there is some more information here e.g. on predators and status -->\n\n<ref name=George2003>George, Philip Brandt. (2003). ''In:'' Baughman, Mel M. (ed.) ''Reference Atlas to the Birds of North America''. [[National Geographic Society]], Washington, D.C., p. 279, {{ISBN|978-0-7922-3373-2}}</ref>\n* Goodwin, Derek & Gillmor, Robert (1976). ''Crows of the World'' (1st ed.) University of Washington Press, Seattle.\n<ref name=henninger1906>{{cite journal |last=Henninger |first=W. F. |date=1906 |title=A preliminary list of the birds of Seneca County, Ohio |journal=[[Wilson Bulletin]] |volume=18 |issue=2 |pages=47\u201360 |url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/wilson/v018n02/p0047-p0060.pdf }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Jones>{{cite journal |last1=Jones |first1=Thony B. |last2=Kamil |first2=Alan C. |date=1973 |title=Tool-Making and Tool-Using in the Northern Blue Jay |journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]] |volume=180 |issue=4090 |pages=1076\u20131078 |doi=10.1126/science.180.4090.1076 |url=http://digitalcommons.unl.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1066&context=bioscibehavior |pmid=17806587}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Madge>{{cite book |last1=Madge |first1=Steve |last2=Burn |first2=Hilary |title=Crows and jays: a guide to the crows, jays and magpies of the world |date=1994 |publisher=A&C Black |location=London |isbn=978-0-7136-3999-5}}</ref>\n<ref name=nero1991>{{cite web |url=http://www.ffdp.ca/hww2.asp?id=30&cid=7 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-08-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090204094824/http://www.ffdp.ca/hww2.asp?id=30&cid=7 |archivedate=2009-02-04 }}</ref>\n<ref name=oiseauxnet2008>{{cite web|url=http://www.oiseaux.net/oiseaux/passeriformes/blue.jay.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070502082729/http://www.oiseaux.net/oiseaux/passeriformes/blue.jay.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2007-05-02|title=Blue Jay}}</ref>\n<ref name=Rhymer>{{cite journal |last1=Rhymer |first1=Judith M. |last2=Simberloff |first2=Daniel |date=1996 |title=Extinction by hybridization and introgression |journal=[[Annu. Rev. Ecol. Syst.]] |doi=10.1146/annurev.ecolsys.27.1.83 |volume=27 |pages=83\u2013109}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Tarvin, K.A. & Woolfenden, G.E. (1999). Blue Jay (''Cyanocitta - cristata''). ''In:'' Poole, A. & Gill, F. (eds.): ''The Birds of North America'' p.&nbsp;469. [[Academy of Natural Sciences]], '''Philadelphia, PA''' [[American Ornithologists' Union]], Washington, DC.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons+cat|Cyanocitta cristata|Cyanocitta cristata}}\n{{Wikispecies|Cyanocitta cristata}}\n*[http://www.allaboutbirds.org/guide/blue_jay/id Blue Jay ID, including sound and video], at Cornell Lab of Ornithology\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100529193817/http://www.mbr-pwrc.usgs.gov/id/framlst/i4770id.html Blue Jay \u2013 ''Cyanocitta cristata''] \u2013 USGS Patuxent Bird Identification InfoCenter\n* {{InternetBirdCollection|blue-jay-cyanocitta-cristata|Blue Jay}}\n* [http://www.borealforest.org/birds/bluejay.htm Blue Jay] at borealforest.org\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110106020639/http://www.flmnh.ufl.edu/wwwsounds/birds/hardy47sh.wav Blue Jay Bird Sound] at Florida Museum of Natural History\n* [http://www.suitable.com/fun/bluejays/index.html Photo essay of blue jay nestlings]\n* {{VIREO|blue+jay|Blue Jay}}\n\n{{Corvidae}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q199758}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jay, Blue}}\n[[Category:Cyanocitta]]\n[[Category:Birds of North America]]\n[[Category:Birds of Canada]]\n[[Category:Native birds of Eastern Canada]]\n[[Category:Birds of the United States]]\n[[Category:Urban animals]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the Eastern United States]]\n[[Category:Tool-using animals]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1758|Blue jay]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Carl Linnaeus|Blue jay]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| image = Cyanocitta-cristata-004.jpg\n| image_caption = In [[Algonquin Provincial Park]], Canada\n| image2 = Cyanocitta cristata - Blue Jay - XC109601.ogg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22705611/0 |title=''Cyanocitta cristata'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=November 26, 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Cyanocitta\n| species = cristata\n| authority = ([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]])\n| range_map = Blue_Jay-rangemap.gif\n| range_map_caption = Global range<br/>{{leftlegend|#FFFF00|Breeding range|outline=gray}}{{leftlegend|#00BE03|Year-round range|outline=gray}}{{leftlegend|#0000FF|Wintering range|outline=gray}}See also [[#Distribution and habitat|text]] for recent range expansion.\n| subdivision_ranks = Subspecies\n| subdivision = 4 sspp., see [[#Subspecies|text]]\n| synonyms = ''Corvus cristatus'' {{small|Linnaeus,&nbsp;1758}}\n}}\n\nThe '''blue jay''' (''Cyanocitta cristata'') is a [[passerine]] [[bird]] in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Corvidae]], native to North America. It resides through most of eastern and central United States, although western populations may be migratory. Resident populations are also found in Newfoundland, Canada, while breeding populations can be found across southern Canada. It breeds in both [[deciduous]] and [[coniferous]] forests, and is common in residential areas. It is predominantly blue with a white chest and underparts, and a blue crest; it has a black, U-shaped collar around its neck and a black border behind the crest. Males and females are similar in size and plumage, and plumage does not vary throughout the year. Four subspecies of the blue jay have been recognized.\n\nThe blue jay mainly feeds on nuts and seeds such as [[acorn]]s, soft fruits, [[arthropods]], and occasionally small vertebrates. It typically [[gleaning (birds)|gleans]] food from trees, shrubs, and the ground, though it sometimes [[hawking (birds)|hawks]] insects from the air. Like squirrels, blue jays are known to hide nuts for later consumption.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.discovermagazine.com/seriouslyscience/2014/05/07/blue-jays-coming-hide-kids-hide-nuts/|title=The blue jays are coming! Hide yo kids, hide yo nuts!|work=Seriously, Science?}}</ref> It builds an open cup nest in the branches of a tree, which both sexes participate in constructing. The clutch can contain two to seven eggs, which are blueish or light brown with brown spots. Young are [[altricial]], and are brooded by the female for 8\u201312 days after hatching. They may remain with their parents for one to two months.\n\nThe name \"jay\" derives from its noisy, garrulous nature and has been applied to other birds of the same family, which are also mostly gregarious.<ref>{{cite book |last=Coues |first=Elliot |title=Key to North American birds |edition=5th |date=1890 |publisher=Estes and Lauriat |location=Boston, MA |oclc=469020022 |page=326}}</ref> It is sometimes called a \"jaybird\".<ref>{{cite web |title=jaybird \u2013 definition of jaybird by the Free Online Dictionary, Thesaurus and Encyclopedia|url=http://www.thefreedictionary.com/jaybird |accessdate=April 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe blue jay was first described as  ''Pica glandaria c\u00e6rulea cristata'' in [[England|English]] naturalist [[Mark Catesby]]'s 1731 publication of ''Natural History of Carolina, Florida, and the Bahamas''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Catesby|first=Mark|authorlink=Mark Catesby|title=Natural History of Carolina, Florida, and the Bahamas|edition=1st|date=1731|publisher=Royal Society House|location=[[London]]|page=87|url=http://dc.lib.unc.edu/cdm/compoundobject/collection/dmisc/id/1658/show/1487}}</ref> It was later described as ''Corvus cristatus'' in [[Carl Linnaeus]]' 1758 edition of ''[[Systema Naturae]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Linnaeus|first=C.|authorlink=Carl Linnaeus|title=Systema Naturae per Regna Tria Naturae, Secundum Classes, Ordines, Genera, Species, cum Characteribus, Differentiis, Synonymis, Locis. Tomus I. Editio Decima, Reformata| publisher=Laurentius Salvius|location=[[Stockholm|Holmiae]]|language=Latin| year=1758|page=106|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/727076#page/124/mode/1up}}</ref> In the 19th century, the jay was described by [[France|French]] ornithologist [[Charles Lucien Bonaparte]] in 1838 as ''Cyanocorax cristatus'' in ''A geographical and comparative list of the birds of Europe and North America'',<ref>{{cite book|last=Bonaparte|first=Charles L.|authorlink=Charles Lucien Bonaparte|title=A geographical and comparative list of the birds of Europe and North America|publisher=J. Van Voorst|location=London|year=1838|page=27|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/71558#page/39/mode/1up}}</ref> and given its modern scientific name ''Cyanocitta cristata'' by [[Hugh Edwin Strickland]] in 1845.<ref>{{cite book|title=Bulletin of the National History Survey, Issues 4-6|edition=|date=1900|publisher=Chicago Academy of Sciences|location=Chicago|page=120|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x4YbAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PA120&q=Cyanocitta%20cristata%20Linnaeus%201758}}</ref> The genus name ''Cyanocitta'' derives from the [[Greek language|Greek]] words 'kyaneos' (blue) and the 'kitta' and 'kissa' (chattering bird, jay), and the term 'blue chatterer' refers to the bright blue plumage of the head, nape, back, and tail of the bird. The specific name ''cristata'' (crested, tufted) derives from [[Latin language|Latin]] referring to the prominent blue crest of the jay.<ref name=\"Sandrock\">{{cite book|last=Sandrock|first=James|title=The Scientific Nomenclature of Birds in the Upper Midwest|publisher=University of Iowa Press|year=2014|page=48|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GsTpAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA48|isbn=978-1609382254}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:102 Blue Jay.jpg|thumb|150px|[[John James Audubon]] drawing circa 1830s]] \nThe blue jay measures {{convert|22|-|30|cm|abbr=on|0}} from bill to tail and weighs {{convert|70|-|100|g|abbr=on}}, with a wingspan of {{convert|34|-|43|cm|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"CLO\"/><ref name=\"Frysinger\"/> Consistent with [[Bergmann's rule]], jays from [[Connecticut]] averaged {{convert|92.4|g|oz|abbr=on}} in mass, while jays from warmer southern [[Florida]] averaged {{convert|73.7|g|oz|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Jewell |first=S. D. |title=Weights and wing lengths in Connecticut Blue Jays |date=1986 |journal=Connecticut Warbler |volume=6 |number=4 |pages=47\u201349}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Fisk | first1 = E.J. | year = 1979 | title = Fall and winter birds near Homestead, Florida | url = | journal = Bird-Banding | volume = 50 | issue = 3| pages = 224\u2013303 | doi=10.2307/4512458| jstor = 4512458 }}</ref> There is a pronounced [[Crest (feathers)|crest]] on the head, a crown of feathers, which may be raised or lowered according to the bird's mood. When excited or aggressive, the crest will be fully raised. When frightened, the crest bristles outwards, brushlike. When the bird is feeding among other jays or resting, the crest is flattened on the head.<ref name=\"nero1991\"/>\n\nIts plumage is lavender-blue to mid-blue in the crest, back, wings, and tail, and its face is white. The underside is off-white and the neck is collared with black which extends to the sides of the head. The [[remiges|wing primaries]] and tail are strongly barred with black, sky-blue and white. The bill, legs, and eyes are all black. Males and females are almost identical, but the male is slightly larger.<ref name=\"Frysinger\"/><ref name=\"Madge\"/>\n\nAs with most other blue-hued birds, the blue jay's coloration is not derived from [[pigment]]s but is the result of light [[Interference (wave propagation)|interference]] due to the internal structure of the feathers;<ref>{{cite web |last=Carpenter |first=Anita |title=What Color is a Bluejay? |date=February 2003 |work=Wisconsin Natural Resources Magazine |url=http://dnr.wi.gov/wnrmag/html/stories/2003/feb03/jays.htm}}</ref> if a blue feather is crushed, the blue disappears because the structure is destroyed.<ref name=\"CLO\"/> This is referred to as [[structural coloration]].\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe blue jay occurs from southern Canada (including the southern areas of provinces from Alberta eastward to Quebec and throughout the Atlantic provinces) and throughout the eastern and central United States south to [[Florida]] and northeastern [[Texas]]. The western edge of the range stops where the [[arid]] pine forest and scrub [[habitat]] of the closely related [[Steller's jay]] (''C. stelleri'') begins, generally in the eastern foothills of the Rocky Mountains. Recently, the range of the blue jay has extended northwestwards so that it is now a rare but regularly seen winter visitor along the northern US and southern Canadian [[Pacific]] Coast.<ref name=CLO/> As the two species' ranges now overlap, ''C. cristata'' may sometimes [[hybrid (biology)|hybridize]] with Steller's jay.<ref name=Rhymer/> The increase in trees throughout the Great Plains during the past century due to fire suppression and tree planting facilitated the western range expansion of the blue jay<ref>Smith GH. 1978. Range extension of the Blue Jay into western North America. Bird-Banding 49:208\u2013214.</ref><ref>Tarvin KA, Woolfenden GE. 1999. Blue Jay (''Cyanocitta cristata''), no. 469. In: A. Poole (ed.). The Birds of North America Online. Cornell Lab of Ornithology, Ithaca, New York.</ref> as well as range expansions of many other species of birds.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Livezey | first1 = KB | year = 2009a | title = Range expansion of Barred Owls, part I: chronology and distribution | url = | journal = American Midland Naturalist | volume = 161 | issue = | pages = 49\u201356 | doi=10.1674/0003-0031-161.1.49}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Livezey | first1 = KB | year = 2009b | title = Range expansion of Barred Owls, part 2: facilitating ecological changes | url = | journal = American Midland Naturalist | volume = 161 | issue = 2| pages = 323\u2013349 | doi=10.1674/0003-0031-161.2.323}}</ref><ref>Livezey KB. 2010. Killing barred owls to help spotted owls II: implications for many other range-expanding species. Northwestern Naturalist 91:251\u2013270.</ref>\n\nThe northernmost [[subspecies]] ''C. c. bromia'' is [[bird migration|migratory]], subject to necessity. It may withdraw several hundred kilometres south in the northernmost parts of its range. Thousands of blue jays have been observed to migrate in flocks along the Great Lakes and Atlantic coasts. It migrates during the daytime, in loose flocks of 5 to 250 birds. Much about their migratory behavior remains a mystery. Some are present throughout winter in all parts of their range. Young jays may be more likely to migrate than adults, but many adults also migrate. Some individual jays migrate south one year, stay north the next winter, and then migrate south again the next year. To date, no one has concretely worked out why they migrate when they do. Likely, it is related to weather conditions and how abundant the winter food sources are, which can determine whether other northern birds will move south.<ref name=eggeater/>\n\nThe blue jay occupies a variety of habitats within its large range, from the [[pine]] woods of Florida to the [[spruce]]-[[fir]] forests of northern Ontario. It is less abundant in denser forests, preferring mixed woodlands with [[oak]]s and [[beech]]es.<ref name=nero1991/> It has expertly adapted to human activity, occurring in parks and residential areas, and can adapt to wholesale [[deforestation]] with relative ease if human activity creates other means for the jays to get by.<ref name=henninger1906/>\n\n==Subspecies==\nFour [[subspecies]] are generally accepted, though the variation within this species is rather subtle and essentially [[cline (population genetics)|clinal]]. No firm boundaries can be drawn between the inland subspecies. The ranges of the coastal races are better delimited.<ref name=Madge/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Image !! Subspecies!! Common Name !! Description !!Distribution\n|-\n|[[File:Bluejay (Cyanocitta cristata) (1547) - Relic38.jpg|120px]] ||''Cyanocitta cristata bromia'' ||Northern blue jay || The largest subspecies, with fairly dull plumage. Blue is rather pale. ||Canada and northern United States.\n|-\n|[[File:Blue Jay Ash RWD5.jpg|120px]] || ''Cyanocitta cristata cristata''||Coastal blue jay || Mid-sized and vivid blue. ||Coastal USA from [[North Carolina]] to [[Texas]], except southern [[Florida]]\n|-\n|[[File:Cyanocitta cristata FWS.jpg|120px]] || ''Cyanocitta cristata cyanotephra''||Interior blue jay || Mid-sized, quite dark blue on mantle contrasting cleanly with very white underside. ||Inland USA, intergrading with ''C. c. bromia'' to the north.\n|-\n|[[File:Geai bleu.jpg|120px]] || ''Cyanocitta cristata semplei''|| Florida blue jay||The smallest subspecies, much like ''C. c. bromia'' in color. ||Southern Florida.\n|-\n|}\n\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Blue Jay-27527.jpg|''Cyanocitta cristata cristata'' in [[Johnston County, North Carolina]]\nFile:Young blue jay.jpg|''C. c. bromia'', Northern blue jay, juvenile, in [[Ontario]], Canada\nFile:Blue jay.jpg|''C. c. bromia'', Northern blue jay in Ontario, Canada\nFile:Blue Jay, Melbourne FLorida.jpg|Blue Jay, Melbourne Florida\n</gallery>\n\n==Behavior==\n[[File:MerlinchasingBlueJay08.jpg|thumb|right|[[Merlin (bird)|Merlin]] chasing a blue jay]]\nThe blue jay is a noisy, bold, and aggressive passerine. It is a moderately slow flier (roughly {{Convert|32|-|40|kph|abbr = on}}) when unprovoked.<ref>[http://www.tpwd.state.tx.us/publications/nonpwdpubs/young_naturalist/animals/animal_speeds/index.phtml Texas Parks & Wildlife]. Retrieved July 1, 2008.</ref> It flies with body and tail held level, with slow wing beats.\nDue to its slow flying speeds, this species makes easy prey for hawks and owls when flying in open areas. Virtually all the raptorial birds sympatric in distribution with the blue jay may prey upon it, especially swift bird-hunting specialists such as the ''[[Accipiter]]'' hawks. Diverse predators may prey on jay eggs and young up to their fledging stage, including [[tree squirrel]]s, [[snake]]s, [[cat]]s, [[crow]]s, [[raccoon]]s, [[opossum]]s, other jays and possibly many of the same birds of prey who attack adults.<ref name= ADW>{{cite web|url=http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/site/accounts/information/Cyanocitta%20cristata.html|title=ADW: Cyanocitta cristata: INFORMATION|work=Animal Diversity Web}}</ref>\n\nThe blue jay can be beneficial to other bird species, as it may chase [[predator]]y birds, such as [[hawk]]s and [[owl]]s, and will scream if it sees a predator within its territory. It has also been known to sound an alarm call when hawks or other dangers are near, and smaller birds often recognize this call and hide themselves away accordingly. It may occasionally impersonate the calls of raptors, especially those of the [[Red-tailed Hawk|red-tailed]] and [[red-shouldered hawk]]s, possibly to test if a hawk is in the vicinity, though also possibly to scare off other birds that may compete for food sources.<ref name=eggeater/> It may also be aggressive towards humans who come close to its nest, and if an owl roosts near the nest during the daytime the blue jay [[Mobbing behavior|mobs]] it until it takes a new roost.<ref name=oiseauxnet2008/> However, blue jays have also been known to attack or kill other smaller birds, and foliage-roosting bat species such as [[Eastern red bat]]s.<ref name=auk>{{cite web|title=Blue Jays Attack A Red Bat|url=https://academic.oup.com/auk/article/76/4/532/5224228}}</ref> Jays are very territorial birds, and they will chase others from a [[bird feeder|feeder]] for an easier meal. Additionally, the blue jay may raid other birds' nests, stealing eggs, chicks, and nests. However, this may not be as common as is typically thought, as only 1% of food matter in one study was bird material.<ref name=eggeater/> Despite this, other passerines may still mob jays who come within their breeding territories.\n\nWhen a blue jay is agitated or angry, the blue crest atop its head will rise. It will lower when the bird is relaxed or calm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freeweekly.com/2016/03/30/the-truth-about-blue-jays/|title=The Truth About Blue Jays \u2013 The Free Weekly|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-08}}</ref>\n\n[[File:C. c. bromia, in New York, NY.jpg|thumb|left|Blue jay in flight]]\nBlue jays, like other [[Corvidae|corvids]], are highly curious and are considered [[Bird intelligence|intelligent birds]]. Young individuals playfully snatch brightly coloured or reflective objects, such as bottle caps or pieces of aluminum foil, and carry them around until they lose interest.<ref name=oiseauxnet2008/> While not confirmed to have engaged in tool use in the wild, blue jays in captivity have been observed using strips of newspaper as tools to obtain food,<ref name=eggeater/><ref name=Jones/> while captive fledglings have been observed attempting to open the doors of their cages.<ref>[http://db89.tumblr.com/post/6161461898/a-clever-blue-jay-fledgling-attempts-to-open-the American Rivers]. tumblr.com</ref>\n\n==Diet==\n[[File:Blue Jay with Peanut.jpg|thumb|left|Whole [[peanut]]s and other shelled food items are carried off in the beak to be dealt with at leisure.]]\n[[File:Blue jay - nut cracking.ogv|Blue jay cracking nuts|right|Blue jay cracking nuts|thumb]]\nBlue jays have strong black bills which they use for cracking nuts, usually while holding them with their feet, and for eating corn, grains and seeds. Its food is sought both on the ground and in trees and includes virtually all known types of plant and animal sources, such as [[acorn]]s and [[beech]] mast, [[weed]] seeds, [[grain]], [[fruit]]s and other [[berry|berries]], [[peanut]]s, bread, meat, small [[invertebrate]]s of many types, scraps in town parks, [[bird-table]] food and rarely [[egg (biology)|eggs]] and nestlings.<ref name=\"eggeater\" >[http://www.birds.cornell.edu/AllAboutBirds/BirdGuide/Blue_Jay.html Blue Jay]. birds.cornell.edu</ref> Blue jays will sometimes [[cache (biology)|cache]] food, though to what extent differs widely among individuals.<ref>[http://www.allaboutbirds.org/guide/Blue_Jay/id AllAboutBirds.org \u2013 Blue Jay] The Cornell Lab of Ornithology</ref> Although seemingly contentious in their general behavior, blue jays are frequently subservient to other medium-sized birds who visit bird-feeders. In [[Florida]], blue jays were dominated at feeders by [[Eastern gray squirrel]]s, [[Florida scrub-jay]]s, [[common grackle]]s and [[red-headed woodpecker]]s, all of which were occasionally observed to aggressively prevent the jays from feeding.<ref name=eggeater/>\n\n==Reproduction==\n[[File:Blue Jays nest.jpg|thumb|right|Nest in the top of a little pine]]\n[[File:Cyanocitta cristata MWNH 1384.JPG|thumb|Eggs, Collection [[Museum Wiesbaden]]]]\nThe mating season begins in mid-March, peaks in mid-April to May, and extends into July. Any suitable tree or large bush may be used for nesting, though an evergreen is preferred. The nest is preferentially built at a height in the trees of {{convert|3|to|10|m|ft|abbr=on}}. It is cup-shaped and composed of twigs, small roots, bark strips, moss, other plant material, cloth, paper, and feathers, with occasional mud added to the cup.\n\nBlue jays are not very picky about nesting locations. If no better place is available \u2013 e.g. in a heavily [[deforestation|deforested]] area \u2013 they will even use places like the large [[Letter box|mailboxes]] typical of the rural United States.<ref name=henninger1906/> They also appropriate nests of other mid-sized songbirds as long as these are placed in suitable spots; [[American robin]] nests are commonly used by blue jays, for example.\n[[File:Blue Jay Cyanocitta cristata Fledgling.jpg|thumb|left|Fledgling in mid-June]]\n[[File:Blue Jay fledgling head.JPG|thumb|Fledgling head]]\nBlue jays typically form [[monogamy|monogamous]] pair bonds for life. Both sexes build the nest and rear the young, though only the female broods them. The male feeds the female while she is brooding the eggs. There are usually between 3 and 6 (averaging 4 or 5) eggs laid and [[avian incubation|incubated]] over 16\u201318 days. The young [[fledge]] usually between 17\u201321 days after hatching.<ref name=oiseauxnet2008/>\n\nAfter the juveniles fledge, the family travels and forages together until early fall, when the young birds disperse to avoid competition for food during the winter. Sexual maturity is reached after one year of age. Blue jays have been recorded to live for more than 26 years in captivity and one wild jay was found to have been around 16\u201317, and a half years old.<ref>{{cite web |title=Longevity Records Of North American Birds |publisher=U. S. Geological Survey: Bird Banding Laboratory |url=http://www.pwrc.usgs.gov/BBL/longevity/Longevity_main.cfm |accessdate=24 December 2012}}</ref> A more common lifespan for wild birds that survive to adulthood is around 7 years.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.canadiangeographic.ca/article/animal-facts-blue-jay | title = Animal facts: Blue Jay | date = July 26, 2006 | website = Canadian Geographic | publisher = The Royal Canadian Geographical Society | access-date = February 3, 2019}}</ref> Beyond predation and the occasional collision with man-made objects, a common cause of mortality in recent decades has been the [[West Nile virus]], to which corvids as a whole seem especially susceptible. However, despite several major local declines, overall blue jays have not seemed to have been depleted by the disease.<ref name=ADW/>\n\n==Vocalizations==\nBlue jays can make a large variety of sounds, and individuals may vary perceptibly in their calling style. Like other [[corvid]]s, they may learn to mimic human speech. Blue jays can also copy the cries of local hawks so well that it is sometimes difficult to tell which it is.<ref name=George2003/> Their voice is typical of most [[jay]]s in being varied, but the most commonly recognized sound is the alarm call, which is a loud, almost [[gull]]-like scream. There is also a high-pitched ''jayer-jayer'' call that increases in speed as the bird becomes more agitated. This particular call can be easily confused with the chickadee's song because of the slow starting ''chick-ah-dee-ee''. Blue jays will use these calls to band together to [[Mobbing behavior|mob]] potential predators such as [[hawk]]s and drive them away from the jays' nests.\n\n{{Listen\n| filename=Cyanocitta cristata - Blue Jay - XC86756.ogg\n| title=\"Rusty pump\" calls\n}}\n\nBlue jays also have quiet, almost subliminal calls which they use among themselves in proximity. One of the most distinctive calls of this type is often referred to as the \"rusty pump\" owing to its squeaky resemblance to the sound of an old hand-operated [[water pump]]. The blue jay (and other corvids) are distinct from most other songbirds for using their call as a song.\n\n==Cultural symbolism and interpretation==\nIn old [[African-American folktales|African American folklore]] of the southern United States, the blue jay was a significant metaphysical creature. In some tales the blue jay was credited with making the earth \"when all de worl' was water\" by bringing the first \"grit\" or \"dirt\". In other tales the blue jay was temporarily conscripted as a servant of the Devil to bring \"kindling\" to the \"bad place\": and \"was not encountered on a Friday as he was fetching sticks down to Hell; furthermore, he was so happy and chirpy on a Saturday as he was relieved to return from Hell\". <ref name=ingersoll23>{{cite book |last=Ingersoll |first=Ernest |authorlink=Ernest Ingersoll |title=Birds in legend, fable and folklore |publisher=Longmans, Green and Co. |location=New York |date=1923 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/birdsinlegendfab00inge/page/166 166]\u2013167 |url=https://archive.org/details/birdsinlegendfab00inge |accessdate=2009-08-08}}</ref>\n\nThe blue jay was adopted as the team symbol of the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] [[Major League Baseball]] team, as well as some of their [[Minor League Baseball|minor league]] affiliates. Their [[mascot]], [[Toronto Blue Jays mascots|Ace]], is an anthropomorphic blue jay. The blue jay is also the official mascot for [[Johns Hopkins University]], [[Elmhurst College]], and [[Creighton University]]. The latter two spell the name as one word - Bluejay. It is also the [[List of Canadian provincial and territorial symbols|provincial bird]] of the province of [[Prince Edward Island]] in Canada.\n\nIn the 1966 Western film ''[[The Shooting]]'', the blue jay is cited as a sign of good luck.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em|refs=\n<ref name=CLO>[http://www.birds.cornell.edu/AllAboutBirds/BirdGuide/Blue_Jay_dtl.html Blue Jay, Life History, All About Birds - Cornell Lab of Ornithology<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n<ref name=Frysinger>{{cite web|url=http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/site/accounts/information/Cyanocitta_cristata.html|title=ADW: Cyanocitta cristata: INFORMATION|work=Animal Diversity Web}}</ref><!-- there is some more information here e.g. on predators and status -->\n\n<ref name=George2003>George, Philip Brandt. (2003). ''In:'' Baughman, Mel M. (ed.) ''Reference Atlas to the Birds of North America''. [[National Geographic Society]], Washington, D.C., p. 279, {{ISBN|978-0-7922-3373-2}}</ref>\n* Goodwin, Derek & Gillmor, Robert (1976). ''Crows of the World'' (1st ed.) University of Washington Press, Seattle.\n<ref name=henninger1906>{{cite journal |last=Henninger |first=W. F. |date=1906 |title=A preliminary list of the birds of Seneca County, Ohio |journal=[[Wilson Bulletin]] |volume=18 |issue=2 |pages=47\u201360 |url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/wilson/v018n02/p0047-p0060.pdf }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Jones>{{cite journal |last1=Jones |first1=Thony B. |last2=Kamil |first2=Alan C. |date=1973 |title=Tool-Making and Tool-Using in the Northern Blue Jay |journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]] |volume=180 |issue=4090 |pages=1076\u20131078 |doi=10.1126/science.180.4090.1076 |url=http://digitalcommons.unl.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1066&context=bioscibehavior |pmid=17806587}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Madge>{{cite book |last1=Madge |first1=Steve |last2=Burn |first2=Hilary |title=Crows and jays: a guide to the crows, jays and magpies of the world |date=1994 |publisher=A&C Black |location=London |isbn=978-0-7136-3999-5}}</ref>\n<ref name=nero1991>{{cite web |url=http://www.ffdp.ca/hww2.asp?id=30&cid=7 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-08-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090204094824/http://www.ffdp.ca/hww2.asp?id=30&cid=7 |archivedate=2009-02-04 }}</ref>\n<ref name=oiseauxnet2008>{{cite web|url=http://www.oiseaux.net/oiseaux/passeriformes/blue.jay.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070502082729/http://www.oiseaux.net/oiseaux/passeriformes/blue.jay.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2007-05-02|title=Blue Jay}}</ref>\n<ref name=Rhymer>{{cite journal |last1=Rhymer |first1=Judith M. |last2=Simberloff |first2=Daniel |date=1996 |title=Extinction by hybridization and introgression |journal=[[Annu. Rev. Ecol. Syst.]] |doi=10.1146/annurev.ecolsys.27.1.83 |volume=27 |pages=83\u2013109}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Tarvin, K.A. & Woolfenden, G.E. (1999). Blue Jay (''Cyanocitta - cristata''). ''In:'' Poole, A. & Gill, F. (eds.): ''The Birds of North America'' p.&nbsp;469. [[Academy of Natural Sciences]], '''Philadelphia, PA''' [[American Ornithologists' Union]], Washington, DC.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons+cat|Cyanocitta cristata|Cyanocitta cristata}}\n{{Wikispecies|Cyanocitta cristata}}\n*[http://www.allaboutbirds.org/guide/blue_jay/id Blue Jay ID, including sound and video], at Cornell Lab of Ornithology\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100529193817/http://www.mbr-pwrc.usgs.gov/id/framlst/i4770id.html Blue Jay \u2013 ''Cyanocitta cristata''] \u2013 USGS Patuxent Bird Identification InfoCenter\n* {{InternetBirdCollection|blue-jay-cyanocitta-cristata|Blue Jay}}\n* [http://www.borealforest.org/birds/bluejay.htm Blue Jay] at borealforest.org\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110106020639/http://www.flmnh.ufl.edu/wwwsounds/birds/hardy47sh.wav Blue Jay Bird Sound] at Florida Museum of Natural History\n* [http://www.suitable.com/fun/bluejays/index.html Photo essay of blue jay nestlings]\n* {{VIREO|blue+jay|Blue Jay}}\n\n{{Corvidae}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q199758}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jay, Blue}}\n[[Category:Cyanocitta]]\n[[Category:Birds of North America]]\n[[Category:Birds of Canada]]\n[[Category:Native birds of Eastern Canada]]\n[[Category:Birds of the United States]]\n[[Category:Urban animals]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the Eastern United States]]\n[[Category:Tool-using animals]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1758|Blue jay]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Carl Linnaeus|Blue jay]]\n", "name_user": "100.14.63.80", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eBehavior:this bird sucks)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blue_jay"}
{"title_page": "Airport Express (MTR)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=February 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| name       = {{HK-MTR route title\n | engname = Airport Express\n | chiname = \u6a5f\u5834\u5feb\u7dab\n | line = Airport Express\n }}\n| logo =  AirportExpressMTR.svg\n| logo_width= 100px\n| image      = Airport Express Train.jpg\n| image_width= 300px\n| image_alt  =\n| caption    = An Airport Express train\n| type       = [[Airport rail link]]\n| system     = [[MTR]]\n| locale     = [[Districts of Hong Kong|Districts]]: [[Central and Western District|Central and Western]], [[Yau Tsim Mong District|Yau Tsim Mong]], [[Kwai Tsing District|Kwai Tsing]], [[Islands District, Hong Kong|Islands]]\n| start      = [[Hong Kong station|Hong Kong]]\n| end        = [[AsiaWorld\u2013Expo station|AsiaWorld\u2013Expo]]\n| stations   = 5\n| open       = {{start-date|6 July 1998}}\n| close      =\n| depot      = [[Siu Ho Wan]]\n| stock      = [[MTR Adtranz\u2013CAF EMU|Adtranz\u2013CAF EMU]]\n| linelength = {{convert|35.3|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| speed = {{convert|200\n|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n| gauge      = {{track gauge|1432mm|lk=on}}\n| electrification = 1.5 [[Volt|kV]] [[Direct current|DC]]\n| map        = [[File:Airport Express Line.svg|300px|center]]\n----{{Airport Express RDT}}\n| map_state  = expanded\n| ridership2  = 54,033 daily average (April 2019)<ref>{{cite web|title=Patronage Updates|url=http://www.mtr.com.hk/en/corporate/investor/patronage.php|publisher=Mass Transit Railway Corporation|accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Infobox Chinese|pic=|align=|picsize=|title=Airport Express|t=\u6a5f\u5834\u5feb\u7dab|s=\u673a\u573a\u5feb\u7ebf|y=G\u0113ich\u00e8uhng Faaisin|ci={{IPA-yue|k\u00e9i.ts\u02b0\u0153\u032d\u02d0\u014b f\u0101\u02d0i.s\u012b\u02d0n|}}|j=Gei1coeng4 Faai3sin3|p=J\u012bch\u00e1ng Ku\u00e0ixi\u00e0n|showflag=y}}\n\nThe '''Airport Express''' is one of the lines of the [[Hong Kong]] [[MTR]] system.  It links the principal urban areas with the [[Hong Kong International Airport]] and the [[AsiaWorld\u2013Expo]] exhibition and convention centre.\n\nIt is not primarily a [[rapid transit|rapid transit or metro]] line but a premium-fare express service for the airport and exhibition centre. It uses specially designed [[rolling stock]] intended to provide levels of comfort similar to that found on an [[airliner]].  The average maximum speed between stations is {{convert|200|km/h|mph}}.\n\nIt is the only rail link to the airport's terminal.  It runs parallel to the [[Tung Chung line]], a traditional rapid transit line, from [[Hong Kong station]] to just south of the channel between [[Lantau Island]] and [[Chek Lap Kok]] Island, on which the airport was constructed.  The line continues to the airport and terminates at AsiaWorld\u2013Expo.  The Tung Chung Line terminates in the adjacent [[Tung Chung]] new town, with bus service to various areas at the airport, including the passenger terminals.\n\nThe journey from [[Hong Kong station]] to the airport takes 24 minutes.  The line is coloured [[teal]] on MTR system maps.\n\n==History==\nIn October 1989, the [[Government of Hong Kong|Hong Kong government]] decided to replace the over-crowded [[Kai Tak Airport]], located in [[Kowloon]], with a new airport to be constructed at Chek Lap Kok. The government also invited the Mass Transit Railway Corporation to build an express line to the airport. The project began when the Chinese and British governments settled the financial and land agreements in November 1994.\n\nThe Lantau Airport Railway was developed as two separate MTR lines, the Tung Chung&nbsp;Line and the Airport Express, with the two lines sharing tracks in some sections. It cost HK$35.1 billion.<ref name=davis>{{cite news|last1=Davis|first1=Chris|title=Rail \"rocket\" set to whisk passengers in comfort|work=South China Morning Post|date=18 December 1997|page=26}}</ref> The Airport Express began service on 6 July 1998, the opening date of the new Hong Kong International Airport. The line initially terminated at [[Airport Station (MTR)|Airport Station]] and the entire journey time was 23 minutes.<ref name=davis/>\n\nWith the opening of [[Sunny Bay (MTR)|Sunny Bay Station]] on the Tung Chung Line in June 2005, the total journey time between the Airport and Hong Kong stations was increased to 24 minutes. With the opening of AsiaWorld\u2013Expo, the line was extended to [[AsiaWorld\u2013Expo Station]] on 20 December 2005 and a journey on the entire route takes 28 minutes.\n\n==Route==\n{| border=0 style=\"margin:auto\"\n|[[Image:MTR_Airport_Express_Geograpical_Map.png|center|thumb|900px|Route map showing both Airport Express and Tung Chung Line]]\n|}\nThe Airport Express line runs from [[Hong Kong station]] in the [[Central and Western District]], crosses under the harbour to [[West Kowloon]] and stops at [[Kowloon Station (MTR)|Kowloon Station]]. The line then runs along the western side of the Kowloon peninsula, crosses over the [[Tsing Lai Bridge]] to [[Tsing Yi Island]], and stops at [[Tsing Yi Station]]. The line continues on the [[Lantau Link]] and runs parallel to the North Lantau Highway to Airport Station before terminating at AsiaWorld\u2013Expo Station.\n\nThe line shares tracks with the Tung Chung Line only in the cross-harbour tunnel and from the Lantau Link through the split before reaching the airport island. The two lines have their own tracks and platforms at all stations.\n\n==Features==\n[[File:Airport check-in at Hong Kong Station.jpg|thumbnail|In-Town Check-In counters at Hong Kong station]]\n[[File:SN6418 at HK West Kowloon Station (20181004155129).jpg|thumbnail|Airport Express Shuttle Bus]]\nThe Airport Express offers more spacious and comfortable trains and stations than other MTR services.<ref name=jrtr/> On the trains, there are luggage racks next to each door, and each seat is equipped with in-seat loudspeakers for current news, advertisements and announcements shown on LCD televisions in front.\n\n===In-town check-in===\nThe Airport Express provides In-Town Check-In at the Hong Kong and Kowloon stations, where passengers on flights with selected airlines can receive [[boarding pass]]es and check luggage, and travel to the airport bags-free. Each train has a special baggage car and the luggage is scanned in bulk by a Mechanised Automatic Explosive Detection System.<ref name=jrtr>{{cite journal|last1=Budge-Reid|first1=Alastair J.|title=The Hong Kong Airport Railway|journal=Japan Railway & Transport Review|date=March 1999|issue=19|pages=36\u201343|url=http://www.jrtr.net/jrtr19/pdf/F36_Budge-Reid.pdf|access-date=11 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304115806/http://www.jrtr.net/jrtr19/pdf/F36_Budge-Reid.pdf|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nLuggage trolleys, wide fare gates, and free porter service are available at all stations except [[AsiaWorld\u2013Expo Station|AsiaWorld\u2013Expo]] to help passengers with baggage.\n\n===Shuttle bus service===\nThe Airport Express Shuttle Bus is a free service provided exclusively for Airport Express passengers at Hong Kong or Kowloon Stations, connecting them with major hotels in the Western District though Quarry Bay on Hong Kong Island and the [[Yau Tsim Mong District]] and [[Hung Hom Station]] in Kowloon. Before boarding, proof of eligibility must be shown, including Airport Express train ticket (Single Journey, Same Day Return, Round Trip, Airport Express Travel Pass), Airline ticket / boarding pass, Airport Staff Octopus card, AsiaWorld\u2013Expo entry pass or event ticket.\n\n===On-board WiFi and charging service===\n[[WiFi]] are available on all Airport Express cars, while charging service are assigned on first and last cars. USB and electric socket are provided for charging mobile electronics.<ref>{{cite web|title=COMPLIMENTARY IN-TRAIN POWER CHARGING SERVICE IN DESIGNATED CARS|url=http://www.mtr.com.hk/en/customer/services/intrain_power_charging.html|publisher=MTR|accessdate=21 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Graphic identity==\nThe Airport Express visual identity, which includes the logo, vehicle livery, signage, route maps and passenger information, was created in 1999 by Lloyd Northover, the British design consultancy founded by [[John Lloyd (graphic designer)|John Lloyd]] and Jim Northover.<ref>{{cite web|title=Archive |url=http://www.lloydnorthover.com/archive.htm |publisher=Lloyd Northover |accessdate=12 August 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150527200406/http://www.lloydnorthover.com/archive.htm |archivedate=27 May 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Fare structure==\n\n[[File:Airport Express Interior.jpg|thumb|right|Inside the Airport Express with the Entry/Exit Path, along with the Baggage Compartments. The journey status can be seen above the compartment view. The interior has since been updated, with a new indigo carpet and the grey seats replaced with purple seats.]]\n\nFares on the Airport Express are substantially higher than main line fares; a separate fare system is used for this line. Single trip or same-day return trips between the Hong Kong, Kowloon and Tsing Yi Stations to Airport Station cost [[Hong Kong dollar|HK$]]115, HK$105 and HK$70 respectively. Return tickets within 30 days cost HK$205, HK$185, and HK$120 respectively. Tickets are available at all MTR stations and the MTR online booking service.<ref>{{cite web|title=Payment method and process|url=http://www.mtr.com.hk/en/customer/buy_tickets/payment_method.html|publisher=MTR Corporation|accessdate=12 August 2015}}</ref> Although no entry gates are provided at Airport Station, travellers must still buy tickets from the ticket machines located in the Arrivals Hall, on platform 1 of the airport before boarding the train or at destination platforms.\n\nVarious discounts and rewards programmes are available, such as Group Ticket Discount, free taxi connections, Rewarding programme, [[Asia Miles]] programme, etc. Passengers may also buy discounted tickets from local travel agents. Discounts are available for groups of two to four people. Hong Kong residents can also obtain discount coupons, such as those sent from credit card companies. Discounted fares are available to airport staff to encourage commuting on the Airport Express.<ref>{{cite web|title=Airport Staff Discount Fare|url=https://extranet.hongkongairport.com/eng/transportation/airportexpress_fare.html|publisher=Airport Authority Hong Kong|accessdate=12 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nSame-day return discount will be given to [[Octopus Card]] users who have stayed in AsiaWorld\u2013Expo for at least one hour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtr.com.hk/en/customer/tickets/tf_index.html|title=MTR > Tickets and Fares|website=www.mtr.com.hk|access-date=2016-09-06}}</ref> The discounted fare costs HK$72, HK$64, and HK$42 from Hong Kong, Kowloon, and Tsing Yi Stations, and includes a free connection with other MTR lines. A single trip from the Airport to AsiaWorld\u2013Expo is HK$5.\n\nAirport Express passengers using Octopus cards can connect with all other MTR lines for free in conjunction with the Airport Express journey<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtr.com.hk/en/customer/services/complom_connections.html|title=MTR > Privileges and Complimentary Services|website=www.mtr.com.hk|access-date=2016-09-06}}</ref> within one hour of arrival at an Airport Express station.\n\nIn March 2010 the MTR began to replace the magnetic tickets used for single, group, and multiple journey tickets with new \"smart tickets\" that contain a memory chip. The new system was in full operation by 5 June 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://travel2hk.com/2010/jul/doc/Information_Update.doc |title=Information Update \u2013 July 2010 |publisher=travel2hk.com |accessdate=11 December 2010 }}</ref>\n\nDue to the high fares and small catchment areas of the Airport Express stations, some travellers may instead choose to either use the cheaper, local Tung Chung Line combined with a bus route, or make their entire journey by bus. Patronage on the Airport Express is cannibalised by the Tung Chung Line running mostly on the same track.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Moving Millions: The Commercial Success and Political Controversies of Hong Kong's Railways|last=Yeung|first=Rikkie|year=2008|publisher=[[Hong Kong University]] Press|location=Hong Kong|isbn=978-962-209-963-0}}</ref>\n\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nImage:AEL Adult toAWE SJT.jpg|A standard single journey ticket towards [[AsiaWorld\u2013Expo Station|Asia-World Expo]]\nImage:AEL Adult toCity SJT.jpg|A standard single journey ticket towards Hong Kong\n<!-- Deleted image removed: Image:AEL Groupof2.jpg|A \"Group of 2\" single journey ticket from Hong Kong Station -->\n</gallery>\n\n===Morning Express Service===\nThe Morning Express Service is a special promotional service, allowing passengers from [[Tsing Yi Station|Tsing Yi]] and [[Kowloon Station (MTR)|Kowloon]] stations to travel to Hong Kong station every day (excluding Sundays and public holidays) from 7am to 10am for HK$20.<ref>{{cite web|title=Airport Express \"Morning Express Service\"|url=http://www.mtr.com.hk/en/customer/tickets/ael_morningexpress.html|publisher=MTR Corporation|accessdate=11 August 2015}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Operation and stations==\nAirport Express trains depart every 10 minutes from the start of service (05:54 from Airport and 05:50 from Hong Kong) and every 12 minutes from 23:28 (from Airport) and 00:00 (from Hong Kong) until the last service 00:48. The Airport Express, along with other MTR metro lines, is monitored by the Operations Control Centre in Tsing Yi.<ref>{{cite web|title=OCC Migration|url=https://www.mtr.com.hk/en/corporate/projects/projects_ops_improve_occ.html|publisher=MTR Corporation|accessdate=12 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Rolling stock===\nThe Airport Express is served by 11 [[MTR Adtranz-CAF EMU|A-Stock]] trains built and assembled by [[Construcciones y Auxiliar de Ferrocarriles]] in [[Spain]] while [[Adtranz]] contributed control and traction equipment. These trains were made up of seven cars until 2003. To cope with the extra traffic demand derived from the opening of AsiaWorld-Expo Station, an additional car was added to each train to form a total of eight cars. If future demand increases, trains on the AEL are capable of running with ten cars. In service, the trains travel at a maximum speed of {{convert|135\n|km/h|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hong Kong Airport Metro|url=http://www.caf.es/en/productos-servicios/proyectos/proyecto-detalle.php?p=169|publisher=CAF|accessdate=12 August 2015}}</ref> The train interiors were refurbished after ten years in service, with the grey seat covers being replaced with purple and green ones, and a new indigo carpet installed.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ng|first1=Yuk-hang|title=10-year-old Airport Express to get a facelift|work=South China Morning Post|date=16 December 2008|page=4}}</ref>\n\n===Station list===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width: 75%; margin: 0.5em auto; text-align: center;\"\n! Name\n! [[Districts of Hong Kong|District]]\n! Connections\n! Opening date\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" style=\"border-top:5px solid #{{rcr|MTR|Airport Express}}; border-bottom:5px solid #{{rcr|MTR|Airport Express}};\"| Airport Express\n|-\n| '''[[Hong Kong station|Hong Kong]]'''\n| [[Central and Western]]\n| {{rcb|MTR|Tung Chung|yes}}<br /><small>[[Central Station (MTR)|Central Station]] for {{rcb|MTR|Tsuen Wan|yes}} and {{rcb|MTR|Island|yes}}</small>\n| rowspan=3 | 22 June 1998 <small>(Tung Chung Line)</small><br />6 July 1998 <small>(Airport Express)</small>\n|-\n| '''[[Kowloon Station (MTR)|Kowloon]]'''\n| [[Yau Tsim Mong District|Yau Tsim Mong]]\n| {{rcb|MTR|Tung Chung|yes}} <br /><small>[[Hong Kong West Kowloon railway station|Hong Kong West Kowloon station]] for [[Guangzhou\u2013Shenzhen\u2013Hong Kong Express Rail Link|Express Rail Link]]</small>\n|-\n| '''[[Tsing Yi Station|Tsing Yi]]'''\n| [[Kwai Tsing District|Kwai Tsing]]\n|{{rcb|MTR|Tung Chung|yes}}\n|-\n| '''[[Airport Station (MTR)|Airport]]'''\n| rowspan=2 | [[Islands District|Islands]]\n|\n| 6 July 1998\n|-\n| '''[[AsiaWorld\u2013Expo Station|AsiaWorld\u2013Expo]]'''\n|\n| 20 December 2005\n|}\n\n==Use in media==\nIn late 1998, [[Leon Lai]] showed a music video of MTR\u2019s Airport Express line for the song \u201cHappy 2000\u201d, which includes the interior of the A-Train.\n\n==Damage==\nIn 2019, there were many [[2019 Hong Kong anti-extradition bill protests|protests in Hong Kong because of the Chinese extradition bill]]. The Airport and the Airport Express line also saw many protests and they were also damaged. Riot police had to push the protesters away.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://time.com/5727899/hong-kong-travel-what-to-know/|website=Time|title=Traveling to Hong Kong? Here's what you need to know|date=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Design limitations==\nWhen [[British Hong Kong]] was planning to build the Airport Railway ([[Tung Chung line]] and Airport Express) in the 1990s, which was a few years before the [[Hong Kong Handover|handover to China]], the Chinese government raised concerns about the effect of the project on the territory's fiscal reserves, which eventually forced the Hong Kong government to reduce the cost of the Airport Railway. The resulting changes made to the design imposed limitations on the level of service on the line.<ref>{{in lang|zh-hk}}{{cite news|author=MTR Service Update|title=\u70ba\u751a\u9ebc\u6771\u6d8c\u7dab\u7e3d\u662f\u73ed\u6b21\u758f\u843d\uff1f|url=http://www.vjmedia.com.hk/articles/2012/11/26/24965|accessdate=2012-11-28|date=2012-11-26}}</ref>\n\n* The line was originally designed to be entirely quadruple-tracked, but as built, it narrows to two tracks within its cross-harbour section and between Tsing Yi and Tung Chung New Town due to lack of money. As a result, signal failures affect both the Tung Chung and Airport Express lines.\n* The [[Lantau Link]] section of the line (consisting of the [[Tsing Ma Bridge]], [[Ma Wan Viaduct]], and [[Kap Shui Mun Bridge]]) only allows one train to pass through each direction at the same time, raising the minimum [[headway]] between trains to 2 minutes 15 seconds. As a result, some Tung Chung Line trains terminate at Tsing Yi during peak hours, instead of travelling the entire line.\n* The signalling system is not capable of giving priority to Airport Express trains; as a result, Tung Chung Line trains stopping at [[Sunny Bay Station]] frequently impede Airport Express trains, which do not serve the station.\n* The power supply system restricts the number of trains that can run between Kowloon and Lai King at once: a maximum of one Airport Express train between Kowloon and Lai King, and two Tung Chung trains between Lai King and Olympic. As a result, the shortest headway on the Tung Chung Line is 3.5 minutes.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of areas of Hong Kong]]\n* [[Transport in Hong Kong]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Airport Express (MTR)}}\n* {{official website|http://www.mtr.com.hk/en/customer/services/airport_express_index.html}}\n\n{{Airport Express navbox}}\n{{MTR}}\n{{Eastern Guangdong & Hong Kong transit}}\n{{Crossings navbox\n|structure=Tunnel crossings\n|place=[[Victoria Harbour]]\n|bridge=[[Tung Chung line]] and Airport Express between [[Kowloon Station (MTR)|Kowloon]] and [[Hong Kong station|Hong Kong]]\n|upstream=[[Western Harbour Crossing]]\n|upstream text=West\n|downstream=[[Tsuen Wan Line]] between [[Tsim Sha Tsui Station|Tsim Sha Tsui]] and [[Admiralty (MTR)|Admiralty]]\n|downstream text=East\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Airport Express (Mtr)}}\n[[Category:1432 mm gauge railways in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Airport Express (MTR)| ]]\n[[Category:Airport rail links]]\n[[Category:Immersed tube tunnels in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:MTR lines]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 1998]]\n[[Category:Transport in Hong Kong]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=February 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| name       = {{HK-MTR route title\n | engname = Airport Express\n | chiname = \u6a5f\u5834\u5feb\u7dab\n | line = Airport Express\n }}\n| logo =  AirportExpressMTR.svg\n| logo_width= 100px\n| image      = Airport Express Train.jpg\n| image_width= 300px\n| image_alt  =\n| caption    = An Airport Express train\n| type       = [[Airport rail link]]\n| system     = [[MTR]]\n| locale     = [[Districts of Hong Kong|Districts]]: [[Central and Western District|Central and Western]], [[Yau Tsim Mong District|Yau Tsim Mong]], [[Kwai Tsing District|Kwai Tsing]], [[Islands District, Hong Kong|Islands]]\n| start      = [[Hong Kong Station|Hong Kong]]\n| end        = [[AsiaWorld\u2013Expo Station|AsiaWorld\u2013Expo]]\n| stations   = 5\n| open       = {{start-date|6 July 1998}}\n| close      =\n| depot      = [[Siu Ho Wan]]\n| stock      = [[MTR Adtranz\u2013CAF EMU|Adtranz\u2013CAF EMU]]\n| linelength = {{convert|35.3|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| speed = {{convert|200\n|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n| gauge      = {{track gauge|1432mm|lk=on}}\n| electrification = 1.5 [[Volt|kV]] [[Direct current|DC]]\n| map        = [[File:Airport Express Line.svg|300px|center]]\n----{{Airport Express RDT}}\n| map_state  = expanded\n| ridership2  = 54,033 daily average (April 2019)<ref>{{cite web|title=Patronage Updates|url=http://www.mtr.com.hk/en/corporate/investor/patronage.php|publisher=Mass Transit Railway Corporation|accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Infobox Chinese|pic=|align=|picsize=|title=Airport Express|t=\u6a5f\u5834\u5feb\u7dab|s=\u673a\u573a\u5feb\u7ebf|y=G\u0113ich\u00e8uhng Faaisin|ci={{IPA-yue|k\u00e9i.ts\u02b0\u0153\u032d\u02d0\u014b f\u0101\u02d0i.s\u012b\u02d0n|}}|j=Gei1coeng4 Faai3sin3|p=J\u012bch\u00e1ng Ku\u00e0ixi\u00e0n|showflag=y}}\n\nThe '''Airport Express''' is one of the lines of the [[Hong Kong]] [[MTR]] system.  It links the principal urban areas with the [[Hong Kong International Airport]] and the [[AsiaWorld\u2013Expo]] exhibition and convention centre.\n\nIt is not primarily a [[rapid transit|rapid transit or metro]] line but a premium-fare express service for the airport and exhibition centre. It uses specially designed [[rolling stock]] intended to provide levels of comfort similar to that found on an [[airliner]].  The average maximum speed between stations is {{convert|200|km/h|mph}}.\n\nIt is the only rail link to the airport's terminal.  It runs parallel to the [[Tung Chung Line]], a traditional rapid transit line, from [[Hong Kong Station]] to just south of the channel between [[Lantau Island]] and [[Chek Lap Kok]] Island, on which the airport was constructed.  The line continues to the airport and terminates at AsiaWorld\u2013Expo.  The Tung Chung Line terminates in the adjacent [[Tung Chung]] new town, with bus service to various areas at the airport, including the passenger terminals.\n\nThe journey from [[Hong Kong station]] to the airport takes 24 minutes.  The line is coloured [[teal]] on MTR system maps.\n\n==History==\nIn October 1989, the [[Government of Hong Kong|Hong Kong government]] decided to replace the over-crowded [[Kai Tak Airport]], located in [[Kowloon]], with a new airport to be constructed at Chek Lap Kok. The government also invited the Mass Transit Railway Corporation to build an express line to the airport. The project began when the Chinese and British governments settled the financial and land agreements in November 1994.\n\nThe Lantau Airport Railway was developed as two separate MTR lines, the Tung Chung&nbsp;Line and the Airport Express, with the two lines sharing tracks in some sections. It cost HK$35.1 billion.<ref name=davis>{{cite news|last1=Davis|first1=Chris|title=Rail \"rocket\" set to whisk passengers in comfort|work=South China Morning Post|date=18 December 1997|page=26}}</ref> The Airport Express began service on 6 July 1998, the opening date of the new Hong Kong International Airport. The line initially terminated at [[Airport Station (MTR)|Airport Station]] and the entire journey time was 23 minutes.<ref name=davis/>\n\nWith the opening of [[Sunny Bay (MTR)|Sunny Bay Station]] on the Tung Chung Line in June 2005, the total journey time between the Airport and Hong Kong Stations was increased to 24 minutes. With the opening of AsiaWorld\u2013Expo, the line was extended to [[AsiaWorld\u2013Expo Station]] on 20 December 2005 and a journey on the entire route takes 28 minutes.\n\n==Route==\n{| border=0 style=\"margin:auto\"\n|[[Image:MTR_Airport_Express_Geograpical_Map.png|center|thumb|900px|Route map showing both Airport Express and Tung Chung Line]]\n|}\nThe Airport Express line runs from [[Hong Kong Station]] in the [[Central and Western District]], crosses under the harbour to [[West Kowloon]] and stops at [[Kowloon Station (MTR)|Kowloon Station]]. The line then runs along the western side of the Kowloon peninsula, crosses over the [[Tsing Lai Bridge]] to [[Tsing Yi Island]], and stops at [[Tsing Yi Station]]. The line continues on the [[Lantau Link]] and runs parallel to the North Lantau Highway to Airport Station before terminating at AsiaWorld\u2013Expo Station.\n\nThe line shares tracks with the Tung Chung Line only in the cross-harbour tunnel and from the Lantau Link through the split before reaching the airport island. The two lines have their own tracks and platforms at all stations.\n\n==Features==\n[[File:Airport check-in at Hong Kong Station.jpg|thumbnail|In-Town Check-In counters at Hong Kong Station]]\n[[File:SN6418 at HK West Kowloon Station (20181004155129).jpg|thumbnail|Airport Express Shuttle Bus]]\nThe Airport Express offers more spacious and comfortable trains and stations than other MTR services.<ref name=jrtr/> On the trains, there are luggage racks next to each door, and each seat is equipped with in-seat loudspeakers for current news, advertisements and announcements shown on LCD televisions in front.\n\n===In-town check-in===\nThe Airport Express provides In-Town Check-In at the Hong Kong and Kowloon stations, where passengers on flights with selected airlines can receive [[boarding pass]]es and check luggage, and travel to the airport bags-free. Each train has a special baggage car and the luggage is scanned in bulk by a Mechanised Automatic Explosive Detection System.<ref name=jrtr>{{cite journal|last1=Budge-Reid|first1=Alastair J.|title=The Hong Kong Airport Railway|journal=Japan Railway & Transport Review|date=March 1999|issue=19|pages=36\u201343|url=http://www.jrtr.net/jrtr19/pdf/F36_Budge-Reid.pdf|access-date=11 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304115806/http://www.jrtr.net/jrtr19/pdf/F36_Budge-Reid.pdf|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nLuggage trolleys, wide fare gates, and free porter service are available at all stations except [[AsiaWorld\u2013Expo Station|AsiaWorld\u2013Expo]] to help passengers with baggage.\n\n===Shuttle bus service===\nThe Airport Express Shuttle Bus is a free service provided exclusively for Airport Express passengers at Hong Kong or Kowloon Stations, connecting them with major hotels in the Western District though Quarry Bay on Hong Kong Island and the [[Yau Tsim Mong District]] and [[Hung Hom Station]] in Kowloon. Before boarding, proof of eligibility must be shown, including Airport Express train ticket (Single Journey, Same Day Return, Round Trip, Airport Express Travel Pass), Airline ticket / boarding pass, Airport Staff Octopus card, AsiaWorld\u2013Expo entry pass or event ticket.\n\n===On-board WiFi and charging service===\n[[WiFi]] are available on all Airport Express cars, while charging service are assigned on first and last cars. USB and electric socket are provided for charging mobile electronics.<ref>{{cite web|title=COMPLIMENTARY IN-TRAIN POWER CHARGING SERVICE IN DESIGNATED CARS|url=http://www.mtr.com.hk/en/customer/services/intrain_power_charging.html|publisher=MTR|accessdate=21 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Graphic identity==\nThe Airport Express visual identity, which includes the logo, vehicle livery, signage, route maps and passenger information, was created in 1999 by Lloyd Northover, the British design consultancy founded by [[John Lloyd (graphic designer)|John Lloyd]] and Jim Northover.<ref>{{cite web|title=Archive |url=http://www.lloydnorthover.com/archive.htm |publisher=Lloyd Northover |accessdate=12 August 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150527200406/http://www.lloydnorthover.com/archive.htm |archivedate=27 May 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Fare structure==\n\n[[File:Airport Express Interior.jpg|thumb|right|Inside the Airport Express with the Entry/Exit Path, along with the Baggage Compartments. The journey status can be seen above the compartment view. The interior has since been updated, with a new indigo carpet and the grey seats replaced with purple seats.]]\n\nFares on the Airport Express are substantially higher than main line fares; a separate fare system is used for this line. Single trip or same-day return trips between the Hong Kong, Kowloon and Tsing Yi Stations to Airport Station cost [[Hong Kong dollar|HK$]]115, HK$105 and HK$70 respectively. Return tickets within 30 days cost HK$205, HK$185, and HK$120 respectively. Tickets are available at all MTR stations and the MTR online booking service.<ref>{{cite web|title=Payment method and process|url=http://www.mtr.com.hk/en/customer/buy_tickets/payment_method.html|publisher=MTR Corporation|accessdate=12 August 2015}}</ref> Although no entry gates are provided at Airport Station, travellers must still buy tickets from the ticket machines located in the Arrivals Hall, on platform 1 of the airport before boarding the train or at destination platforms.\n\nVarious discounts and rewards programmes are available, such as Group Ticket Discount, free taxi connections, Rewarding programme, [[Asia Miles]] programme, etc. Passengers may also buy discounted tickets from local travel agents. Discounts are available for groups of two to four people. Hong Kong residents can also obtain discount coupons, such as those sent from credit card companies. Discounted fares are available to airport staff to encourage commuting on the Airport Express.<ref>{{cite web|title=Airport Staff Discount Fare|url=https://extranet.hongkongairport.com/eng/transportation/airportexpress_fare.html|publisher=Airport Authority Hong Kong|accessdate=12 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nSame-day return discount will be given to [[Octopus Card]] users who have stayed in AsiaWorld\u2013Expo for at least one hour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtr.com.hk/en/customer/tickets/tf_index.html|title=MTR > Tickets and Fares|website=www.mtr.com.hk|access-date=2016-09-06}}</ref> The discounted fare costs HK$72, HK$64, and HK$42 from Hong Kong, Kowloon, and Tsing Yi Stations, and includes a free connection with other MTR lines. A single trip from the Airport to AsiaWorld\u2013Expo is HK$5.\n\nAirport Express passengers using Octopus cards can connect with all other MTR lines for free in conjunction with the Airport Express journey<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtr.com.hk/en/customer/services/complom_connections.html|title=MTR > Privileges and Complimentary Services|website=www.mtr.com.hk|access-date=2016-09-06}}</ref> within one hour of arrival at an Airport Express station.\n\nIn March 2010 the MTR began to replace the magnetic tickets used for single, group, and multiple journey tickets with new \"smart tickets\" that contain a memory chip. The new system was in full operation by 5 June 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://travel2hk.com/2010/jul/doc/Information_Update.doc |title=Information Update \u2013 July 2010 |publisher=travel2hk.com |accessdate=11 December 2010 }}</ref>\n\nDue to the high fares and small catchment areas of the Airport Express stations, some travellers may instead choose to either use the cheaper, local Tung Chung Line combined with a bus route, or make their entire journey by bus. Patronage on the Airport Express is cannibalised by the Tung Chung Line running mostly on the same track.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Moving Millions: The Commercial Success and Political Controversies of Hong Kong's Railways|last=Yeung|first=Rikkie|year=2008|publisher=[[Hong Kong University]] Press|location=Hong Kong|isbn=978-962-209-963-0}}</ref>\n\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nImage:AEL Adult toAWE SJT.jpg|A standard single journey ticket towards [[AsiaWorld\u2013Expo Station|Asia-World Expo]]\nImage:AEL Adult toCity SJT.jpg|A standard single journey ticket towards Hong Kong\n<!-- Deleted image removed: Image:AEL Groupof2.jpg|A \"Group of 2\" single journey ticket from Hong Kong Station -->\n</gallery>\n\n===Morning Express Service===\nThe Morning Express Service is a special promotional service, allowing passengers from [[Tsing Yi Station|Tsing Yi]] and [[Kowloon Station (MTR)|Kowloon]] stations to travel to Hong Kong Station every day (excluding Sundays and public holidays) from 7am to 10am for HK$20.<ref>{{cite web|title=Airport Express \"Morning Express Service\"|url=http://www.mtr.com.hk/en/customer/tickets/ael_morningexpress.html|publisher=MTR Corporation|accessdate=11 August 2015}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Operation and stations==\nAirport Express trains depart every 10 minutes from the start of service (05:54 from Airport and 05:50 from Hong Kong) and every 12 minutes from 23:28 (from Airport) and 00:00 (from Hong Kong) until the last service 00:48. The Airport Express, along with other MTR metro lines, is monitored by the Operations Control Centre in Tsing Yi.<ref>{{cite web|title=OCC Migration|url=https://www.mtr.com.hk/en/corporate/projects/projects_ops_improve_occ.html|publisher=MTR Corporation|accessdate=12 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Rolling stock===\nThe Airport Express is served by 11 [[MTR Adtranz-CAF EMU|A-Stock]] trains built and assembled by [[Construcciones y Auxiliar de Ferrocarriles]] in [[Spain]] while [[Adtranz]] contributed control and traction equipment. These trains were made up of seven cars until 2003. To cope with the extra traffic demand derived from the opening of AsiaWorld-Expo Station, an additional car was added to each train to form a total of eight cars. If future demand increases, trains on the AEL are capable of running with ten cars. In service, the trains travel at a maximum speed of {{convert|135\n|km/h|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hong Kong Airport Metro|url=http://www.caf.es/en/productos-servicios/proyectos/proyecto-detalle.php?p=169|publisher=CAF|accessdate=12 August 2015}}</ref> The train interiors were refurbished after ten years in service, with the grey seat covers being replaced with purple and green ones, and a new indigo carpet installed.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ng|first1=Yuk-hang|title=10-year-old Airport Express to get a facelift|work=South China Morning Post|date=16 December 2008|page=4}}</ref>\n\n===Station list===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width: 75%; margin: 0.5em auto; text-align: center;\"\n! Name\n! [[Districts of Hong Kong|District]]\n! Connections\n! Opening date\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" style=\"border-top:5px solid #{{rcr|MTR|Airport Express}}; border-bottom:5px solid #{{rcr|MTR|Airport Express}};\"| Airport Express\n|-\n| '''[[Hong Kong Station|Hong Kong]]'''\n| [[Central and Western]]\n| {{rcb|MTR|Tung Chung|yes}}<br /><small>[[Central Station (MTR)|Central Station]] for {{rcb|MTR|Tsuen Wan|yes}} and {{rcb|MTR|Island|yes}}</small>\n| rowspan=3 | 22 June 1998 <small>(Tung Chung Line)</small><br />6 July 1998 <small>(Airport Express)</small>\n|-\n| '''[[Kowloon Station (MTR)|Kowloon]]'''\n| [[Yau Tsim Mong District|Yau Tsim Mong]]\n| {{rcb|MTR|Tung Chung|yes}} <br /><small>[[Hong Kong West Kowloon railway station|Hong Kong West Kowloon station]] for [[Guangzhou\u2013Shenzhen\u2013Hong Kong Express Rail Link|Express Rail Link]]</small>\n|-\n| '''[[Tsing Yi Station|Tsing Yi]]'''\n| [[Kwai Tsing District|Kwai Tsing]]\n|{{rcb|MTR|Tung Chung|yes}}\n|-\n| '''[[Airport Station (MTR)|Airport]]'''\n| rowspan=2 | [[Islands District|Islands]]\n|\n| 6 July 1998\n|-\n| '''[[AsiaWorld\u2013Expo Station|AsiaWorld\u2013Expo]]'''\n|\n| 20 December 2005\n|}\n\n==Use in media==\nIn late 1998, [[Leon Lai]] showed a music video of MTR\u2019s Airport Express line for the song \u201cHappy 2000\u201d, which includes the interior of the A-Train.\n\n==Damage==\nIn 2019, there were many [[2019 Hong Kong anti-extradition bill protests|protests in Hong Kong because of the Chinese extradition bill]]. The Airport and the Airport Express line also saw many protests and they were also damaged. Riot police had to push the protesters away.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://time.com/5727899/hong-kong-travel-what-to-know/|website=Time|title=Traveling to Hong Kong? Here's what you need to know|date=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Design limitations==\nWhen [[British Hong Kong]] was planning to build the Airport Railway ([[Tung Chung Line]] and Airport Express) in the 1990s, which was a few years before the [[Hong Kong Handover|handover to China]], the Chinese government raised concerns about the effect of the project on the territory's fiscal reserves, which eventually forced the Hong Kong government to reduce the cost of the Airport Railway. The resulting changes made to the design imposed limitations on the level of service on the line.<ref>{{in lang|zh-hk}}{{cite news|author=MTR Service Update|title=\u70ba\u751a\u9ebc\u6771\u6d8c\u7dab\u7e3d\u662f\u73ed\u6b21\u758f\u843d\uff1f|url=http://www.vjmedia.com.hk/articles/2012/11/26/24965|accessdate=2012-11-28|date=2012-11-26}}</ref>\n\n* The line was originally designed to be entirely quadruple-tracked, but as built, it narrows to two tracks within its cross-harbour section and between Tsing Yi and Tung Chung New Town due to lack of money. As a result, signal failures affect both the Tung Chung and Airport Express lines.\n* The [[Lantau Link]] section of the line (consisting of the [[Tsing Ma Bridge]], [[Ma Wan Viaduct]], and [[Kap Shui Mun Bridge]]) only allows one train to pass through each direction at the same time, raising the minimum [[headway]] between trains to 2 minutes 15 seconds. As a result, some Tung Chung Line trains terminate at Tsing Yi during peak hours, instead of travelling the entire line.\n* The signalling system is not capable of giving priority to Airport Express trains; as a result, Tung Chung Line trains stopping at [[Sunny Bay Station]] frequently impede Airport Express trains, which do not serve the station.\n* The power supply system restricts the number of trains that can run between Kowloon and Lai King at once: a maximum of one Airport Express train between Kowloon and Lai King, and two Tung Chung trains between Lai King and Olympic. As a result, the shortest headway on the Tung Chung Line is 3.5 minutes.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of areas of Hong Kong]]\n* [[Transport in Hong Kong]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Airport Express (MTR)}}\n* {{official website|http://www.mtr.com.hk/en/customer/services/airport_express_index.html}}\n\n{{Airport Express navbox}}\n{{MTR}}\n{{Eastern Guangdong & Hong Kong transit}}\n{{Crossings navbox\n|structure=Tunnel crossings\n|place=[[Victoria Harbour]]\n|bridge=[[Tung Chung Line]] and Airport Express between [[Kowloon Station (MTR)|Kowloon]] and [[Hong Kong Station|Hong Kong]]\n|upstream=[[Western Harbour Crossing]]\n|upstream text=West\n|downstream=[[Tsuen Wan Line]] between [[Tsim Sha Tsui Station|Tsim Sha Tsui]] and [[Admiralty (MTR)|Admiralty]]\n|downstream text=East\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Airport Express (Mtr)}}\n[[Category:1432 mm gauge railways in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Airport Express (MTR)| ]]\n[[Category:Airport rail links]]\n[[Category:Immersed tube tunnels in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:MTR lines]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 1998]]\n[[Category:Transport in Hong Kong]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling correction; redirect bypass fromTung Chung LinetoTung Chung lineusingpopups", "url_page": "/