= 0\n| goals6 = 1\n| goals7 = 0\n| goals8 = 0\n| goals9 = 0\n| totalgoals = 1\n| nationalyears1 = 1992\n| nationalyears2 = 1995\n| nationalyears3 = 1996\n| nationalyears4 = 2000\u20132001\n| nationalteam1 = [[Portugal national under-18 football team|Portugal U18]]\n| nationalteam2 = [[Portugal national under-21 football team|Portugal U21]]\n| nationalteam3 = [[Portugal Olympic football team|Portugal U23]]\n| nationalteam4 = [[Portugal national football B team|Portugal B]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 1\n| nationalcaps2 = 3\n| nationalcaps3 = 5\n| nationalcaps4 = 3\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalgoals4 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 2012\u20132014\n| manageryears2 = 2014\u20132015\n| manageryears3 = 2016\u20132017\n| manageryears4 = 2017\u2013\n| managerclubs1 = [[Rio Ave F.C.|Rio Ave]]\n| managerclubs2 = [[Valencia CF|Valencia]]\n| managerclubs3 = [[FC Porto|Porto]]\n| managerclubs4 = [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]\n}}\n'''Nuno Herlander Sim\u00f5es Esp\u00edrito Santo''' ({{IPA-pt|\u02c8nunu (\u0268)\u0283\u02c8pi\u027eitu \u02c8s\u0250\u030btu}}; born 25 January 1974), known simply as '''Nuno''' as a player, is a Portuguese former [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]], and head coach of [[Premier League]] club [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]].\n\nDuring his career he first made a name for himself in Spain, playing for three teams in five years. He later returned to Portugal to represent [[FC Porto|Porto]], and also played professionally in Russia; he was part of the [[Portugal national football team|Portuguese squad]] at [[UEFA Euro 2008|Euro 2008]], but never won a [[Cap (sport)|cap]] for the national team.\n\nEsp\u00edrito Santo became a manager in 2012, leading [[Rio Ave F.C.|Rio Ave]] to both domestic cup finals in 2014 before taking the reins at [[Valencia CF|Valencia]].\n\n==Playing career==\n===Early career / Deportivo===\nBorn in [[S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9]], [[Portuguese S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe]], Nuno started his football career with [[Vit\u00f3ria S.C.]] in [[Guimar\u00e3es]], battling from age 20 with veteran [[Neno (footballer)|Neno]] for first-choice status. After a meeting with the then [[Porto]] nightclub owner [[Jorge Mendes]] he became the agent's first client in 1996;<ref>{{cite news |title=Soccer exchange: How a super-agent and a Chinese billionaire planned to trade in players |url=https://www.reuters.com/investigates/special-report/soccer-files-fosun/ |accessdate=21 August 2019 |publisher=Reuters |date=3 June 2009}}</ref> Mendes brokered a $1 million transfer the following January to [[La Liga]]'s [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lowe |first1=Sid |title=\u2018I saw a lot from the bench\u2019: how Porto\u2019s reserve goalkeeper became manager |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/sep/27/porto-leicester-champions-league-nuno-espirito-santo |accessdate=21 August 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=27 September 2016}}</ref> but Nuno would spend three of his six seasons in [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]] out on loan, backing up [[Jacques Songo'o]] (1996\u201398) and [[Jos\u00e9 Francisco Molina]] ([[2001\u201302 La Liga|2001\u201302]]) when he was part of the team.\n\nIn [[1999\u20132000 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1999\u20132000]], as he represented [[CP M\u00e9rida]] in the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|Spanish second division]], Nuno won the [[Ricardo Zamora Trophy]] and helped the side finish sixth, but it would be relegated to the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|third level]] due to irregularities.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2012/05/17/mas_futbol/1337236018_850215.html|title=El primer fichaje de la factor\u00eda Jorge Mendes|trans-title=First signing of Jorge Mendes factory|newspaper=[[Diario AS]]|first=Manu|last=Sainz|language=es|date=17 May 2012|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> [[2000\u201301 La Liga|The following season]] he was loaned to [[CA Osasuna]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rcdeportivo.es/noticia/nuno-cedido-al-osasuna|title=Nuno, cedido al Osasuna|trans-title=Nuno, loaned to Osasuna|publisher=Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a|language=es|date=11 July 2000|accessdate=3 January 2019}}</ref> going on to rank seventh in the Zamora as his team finished only one point above the relegation zone in the top tier.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nacion.com/puro-deporte/mexicano-aguirre-logra-salvar-del-descenso-a-osasuna/VYJKTW2UZZFWNLGV7U4XIRRQCI/story/|title=Mexicano Aguirre logra salvar del descenso a Osasuna|trans-title=Mexican Aguirre leads Osasuna out of relegation|newspaper=[[La Naci\u00f3n (San Jos\u00e9)|La Naci\u00f3n]]|first=Ferm\u00edn|last=Zariquiegui|language=es|date=23 June 2002|accessdate=4 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Porto===\n[[Jos\u00e9 Mourinho]]'s [[FC Porto]] paid [[Euro|\u20ac]]3 million to bring Nuno back to the country in July 2002, as part of the deal that saw [[Jorge Andrade]] join Deportivo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcporto.pt/IncFCP/PDF/Investor_Relations/FactosRelevantes/VendaJAndrade22072002.pdf|title=Venda do passe do jogador Jorge Andrade|trans-title=Player Jorge Andrade's pass sold|publisher=FC Porto|language=pt|date=22 July 2002|accessdate=4 October 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101205171120/http://www.fcporto.pt/IncFCP/PDF/Investor_Relations/FactosRelevantes/VendaJAndrade22072002.pdf|archivedate=5 December 2010}}</ref> During a 2003 [[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal]] match against [[Varzim S.C.|Varzim SC]], he was allowed by Mourinho to convert a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]], scoring the club's last goal in a [[2002\u201303 Ta\u00e7a de Portugal|7\u20130 home routing]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://jn.sapo.pt/PaginaInicial/Desporto/Interior.aspx?content_id=1023740|title=F.C. Porto: Nuno \u00e9 mais que um guarda-redes|trans-title=F.C. Porto: Nuno is more than a goalkeeper|newspaper=[[Jornal de Not\u00edcias]]|language=pt|date=8 October 2008|accessdate=14 December 2010}}</ref> In May 2004, Nuno was an unused substitute as Porto won the [[European Champion Clubs' Cup]]<ref>{{cite web|title=UEFA Champions League 2003/04&nbsp;\u2013 History|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2003/index.html|website=UEFA.com|publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]]|accessdate=2 July 2014}}</ref> final. On 12 December 2004, he replaced club great [[V\u00edtor Ba\u00eda]] during [[Overtime (sports)|extra time]] of the [[Intercontinental Cup (football)|Intercontinental Cup]] final [[Penalty shootout (association football)|penalty shootout]] [[2004 Intercontinental Cup|victory]] against [[Once Caldas]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/f-c-porto-once-caldas-0-0-8-7-nas-g-p-cronica|title=F.C. Porto-Once Caldas, 0\u20130 (8\u20137 nas g.p.) (cr\u00f3nica)|trans-title=F.C. Porto-Once Caldas, 0\u20130 (8\u20137 on p.k.) (match report)|publisher=Mais Futebol|first=Filipe|last=Caetano|language=pt|date=12 December 2004|accessdate=3 January 2019}}</ref> however, in January, he was sold to [[Russian Premier League]]'s [[FC Dynamo Moscow]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/nuno-apresentado-no-dinamo-moscovo|title=Nuno apresentado no D\u00ednamo Moscovo|trans-title=Nuno presented at Dynamo Moscow|publisher=Mais Futebol|language=pt|date=23 July 2005|accessdate=4 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nAgain in January, in 2007, Nuno returned to Portugal for a stint with [[C.D. Aves]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/d-aves-nuno-espirito-santo-reforca-leque-de-opcoes-de-neca|title=D. Aves: Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo refor\u00e7a leque de op\u00e7\u00f5es de Neca|trans-title=D. Aves: Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo strengthens Neca's options|publisher=Mais Futebol|language=pt|date=11 January 2007|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref> [[2006\u201307 Primeira Liga|eventually relegated]] from the [[Primeira Liga]]. In July he returned to Porto, backing up Brazilian [[Helton Arruda|Helton]] during most of his spell.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-nos/fc-porto/detalhe/nuno-promete-dar-luta-a-helton.html|title=Nuno promete dar luta a Helton|trans-title=Nuno promises to challenge Helton|newspaper=[[Record (newspaper)|Record]]|language=pt|date=13 July 2007|accessdate=12 January 2018}}</ref> Despite his limited involvement on the pitch, he was considered a leader of the club.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bates |first1=Pearce |title=\"O Substituto\", Jorge Mendes nightclub encounter, a Wolves love affair, the story of Nuno Espirito Santo |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/o-substituto-jorge-mendes-nightclub-14932075 |accessdate=21 August 2019 |work=Birmingham Mail |date=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nNuno again played second-fiddle to Helton during the [[2008\u201309 Primeira Liga|2008\u201309 season]] appearing in only four games, but was the starter throughout the [[2008\u201309 Ta\u00e7a de Portugal|domestic cup campaign]], including the final win (1\u20130) against [[F.C. Pa\u00e7os de Ferreira]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/helton-quem-sou-eu-para-dar-conselhos-ao-nuno-video|title=Helton: \"Quem sou eu para dar conselhos ao Nuno?\" (v\u00eddeo)|trans-title=Helton: \u00abWho am I to give advice to Nuno?\u00bb (video)|publisher=Mais Futebol|first=Nuno|last=Travassos|language=pt|date=31 May 2009|accessdate=13 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===International===\nNuno represented [[Portugal Olympic football team|Portugal]] at the [[1996 Summer Olympics]], playing four matches for the [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|fourth-placed team]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dn.pt/dossiers/desporto/jogos-olimpicos/historico/interior/atlanta1996---os-portugueses-1008872.html|title=Atlanta1996 \u2013 Os portugueses|trans-title=Atlanta1996 \u2013 The Portuguese|newspaper=[[Di\u00e1rio de Not\u00edcias]]|language=pt|date=3 September 2008|accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> [[Cap (sport)|Uncapped]], he was called to the [[Portugal national football team|full squad]] competing in [[UEFA Euro 2008]], replacing the injured [[Quim (footballer, born 1975)|Quim]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/arquivo/interior.aspx?content_id=345461|title=Nuno \u00e9 o substituto de Quim|trans-title=Nuno replaces Quim|newspaper=Record|language=pt|date=7 June 2008|accessdate=31 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110190044/http://www.record.xl.pt/arquivo/interior.aspx?content_id=345461|archive-date=10 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\n===Beginnings===\nOn 21 June 2010, Porto announced Nuno's contract would not be renewed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcporto.pt/Noticias/Futebol/noticiafutebol_futcomunicadosad_210610_53339.asp|title=Comunicado da FC Porto \u2013 Futebol, SAD|trans-title=FC Porto announcement \u2013 Football, PLSC|publisher=FC Porto|language=pt|date=21 June 2010|accessdate=4 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100625021741/http://www.fcporto.pt/Noticias/Futebol/noticiafutebol_futcomunicadosad_210610_53339.asp|archivedate=25 June 2010}}</ref> The 36-year-old said he would always support Porto as he left.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcporto.pt/Noticias/Futebol/noticiafutebol_futnunodec_210610_53347.asp|title=Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo: 'Sou e serei Porto!'|trans-title=Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo: 'I am and will be Porto!'|publisher=FC Porto|language=pt|date=21 June 2010|accessdate=4 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100625021747/http://www.fcporto.pt/Noticias/Futebol/noticiafutebol_futnunodec_210610_53347.asp|archivedate=25 June 2010}}</ref> After his retirement he rejoined former Porto manager [[Jesualdo Ferreira]], moving to [[M\u00e1laga CF]] as a goalkeeping coach; the pair signed for [[Panathinaikos FC]] in November 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.jn.pt/desporto/interior/o-tecnico-que-ja-o-era-antes-de-o-ser-5199328.html|title=O t\u00e9cnico que j\u00e1 o era antes de o ser|trans-title=The manager who was one before ever being so|newspaper=Jornal de Not\u00edcias|language=pt|date=30 May 2016|accessdate=16 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Rio Ave===\nIn May 2012, [[Rio Ave F.C.]] sacked manager [[Carlos Lu\u00eds Brito|Carlos Brito]] and announced the appointment of Esp\u00edrito Santo.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abola.pt/nnh/ver.aspx?id=331416|title=Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo \u00e9 o novo treinador|trans-title=Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo is the new manager|newspaper=[[A Bola]]|language=pt|date=15 May 2012|accessdate=24 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120518075950/http://www.abola.pt/nnh/ver.aspx?id=331416|archive-date=18 May 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> In [[2013\u201314 Primeira Liga|his second season]] in charge, the team reached both the [[2013\u201314 Ta\u00e7a de Portugal|Ta\u00e7a de Portugal]] and [[Ta\u00e7a da Liga]] finals,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/Futebol/Nacional/1a_liga/rio_ave/interior.aspx?content_id=878365|title=Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo feliz com 2.\u00aa final da \u00e9poca|trans-title=Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo happy with second final of season|newspaper=Record|language=pt|date=17 April 2014|accessdate=18 April 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017134039/http://www.record.xl.pt/Futebol/Nacional/1a_liga/rio_ave/interior.aspx?content_id=878365|archivedate=17 October 2014}}</ref> also [[2014\u201315 UEFA Europa League|leading them]] to the [[UEFA Europa League]] for the first time in their history.\n\n===Valencia===\nEsp\u00edrito Santo signed a one-year contract with [[Valencia CF]] in [[La Liga]] on 4 July 2014, replacing the fired [[Juan Antonio Pizzi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.valenciacf.com/ver/36277/benvingutnuno-nuno-espirito-santo-firma-su-contrato-como-nuevo-entrenador-del-valencia-cf.html|title=#BenvingutNuno Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo firma su contrato como nuevo entrenador del Valencia CF|trans-title=#WelcomeNuno Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo signs contract as new Valencia CF manager|publisher=Valencia CF|language=es|date=4 July 2014|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> On 12 January 2015, he agreed to an extension to keep him at the club until 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.valenciacf.com/ver/39814/comunicado-oficial.html|title=Nuno: \"It is an honour and a pleasure to be here\"|publisher=Valencia CF|date=12 January 2015|accessdate=12 January 2015}}</ref> and he eventually led them to a fourth place finish in [[2014\u201315 La Liga|his first year]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laliga.es/noticias/el-valencia-se-impone-en-la-batalla-por-la-cuarta-plaza|title=El Valencia se impone en la batalla por la cuarta plaza|trans-title=Valencia win battle for fourth place|publisher=[[La Liga]]|language=es|date=25 January 2015|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> highlights including a 2\u20131 home win over [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] and a 2\u20132 away draw against the same opponent,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/30673410|title=Valencia 2\u20131 Real Madrid|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|first=Pete|last=Oliver|date=4 January 2015|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/32589617|title=Real Madrid 2\u20132 Valencia|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Emlyn|last=Begley|date=9 May 2015|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> while he was named [[La Liga Manager of the Month]] three times;<ref name=LFP>{{cite web|url=http://www.laliga.es/en/news/bbva-awards-nuno-liga-bbva-manager-of-the-month-for-february|title=BBVA Awards: Nuno, Liga BBVA Manager of the month for February|publisher=[[Liga de F\u00fatbol Profesional]]|date=9 March 2015|accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref> he resigned on 29 November 2015, following a 0\u20131 away defeat to [[Sevilla FC]], after a poor start to both Valencia's La Liga and Champions League campaigns.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/nov/29/nuno-valencia-resigns-sevilla|title=Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo resigns as Valencia coach after Sevilla defeat|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=29 November 2015|accessdate=29 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Porto===\nOn 1 June 2016, Esp\u00edrito Santo signed a two-year contract with Porto, replacing former head coach [[Jos\u00e9 Peseiro]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcporto.pt/en/noticias/Pages/Nuno-Espirito-Santo-e-o-novo-treinador-do-FC-Porto.aspx|title=Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo is the new coach at FC Porto|publisher=FC Porto|date=1 June 2016|accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref> The following 22 May, however, after [[2016\u201317 FC Porto season|a season]] devoid of silverware which included a [[2016\u201317 Primeira Liga|second place in the league]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/porto-nuno-espirito-santo-primeira-liga/1wj6pmi3nefwu1b3nmdd9hy2ta|title=Porto boss Nuno steps down|publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|first=Dom|last=Farrell|date=22 May 2017|accessdate=15 August 2018}}</ref> he was relieved of his duties.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/1a-liga/porto/noticias/interior/nuno-espirito-santo-deixa-comando-tecnico-do-fc-porto-8497194.html|title=Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo deixa o FC Porto|trans-title=Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo leaves FC Porto|newspaper=[[O Jogo]]|first=Jos\u00e9 Manuel|last=Ribeiro|language=pt|date=22 May 2017|accessdate=22 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Wolverhampton Wanderers===\nOn 31 May 2017, Esp\u00edrito Santo was named as the new head coach of English [[EFL Championship|Championship]] side [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]], signing a three-year deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/40105588|title=Nuno Espirito Santo: Wolves appoint former Porto boss as head coach|publisher=BBC Sport|date=31 May 2017|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref> He was voted the competition's [[EFL Championship Manager of the Month|Manager of the Month]] in November as his team won all four of their games, scoring 13 times.<ref name=EFL>{{cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/news/2017/december/manager-of-the-month-nuno---wolverhampton-wanderers/|title=Championship Manager of the Month: Nuno \u2013 Wolverhampton Wanderers|publisher=[[English Football League]]|date=8 December 2017|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nEsp\u00edrito Santo led the club to the [[Premier League]] after a six-year absence, achieving promotion with four matches remaining in [[2017\u201318 EFL Championship|the season]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/43771511|title=Wolves: Championship leaders promoted to Premier League after Fulham draw with Brentford|publisher=BBC Sport|date=14 April 2018|accessdate=16 April 2018}}</ref> and being confirmed as champions with two games to spare.<ref name=CHAMPIONSHIP>{{cite news|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/sport/football/wolverhampton-wanderers-fc/2018/04/21/champions-wolves-win-the-league-after-breezing-past-bolton/|title=Champions! Wolves win the league after breezing past Bolton|newspaper=[[Express & Star]]|date=21 April 2018|accessdate=21 April 2018}}</ref> On 10 July 2018, it was announced that his contract had been extended until 2021.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/wolverhampton-wanderers/story/3561324/wolves-extend-manager-nuno-espirito-santo-contract-until-2021|title=Wolves extend manager Nuno Espirito Santo contract until 2021|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=10 July 2018|accessdate=14 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nEsp\u00edrito Santo was awarded the [[Premier League Manager of the Month]] title in his second month managing in the [[English football league system|English top division]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/877735|title=Nuno claims Barclays Manager of the Month|publisher=[[Premier League]]|date=12 October 2018|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref> after his team went unbeaten in September 2018, accruing ten points from four matches and only conceding one goal. It was the first time that a Wolverhampton Wanderers manager had secured the award, in the club's fifth season in the competition.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/45985099|title=Wolves: The science behind Premier League newcomers' record-breaking start|date=26 October 2018|access-date=5 December 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 May 2019, Esp\u00edrito Santo was awarded an Honorary Doctorate in Sport by the [[University of Wolverhampton]].<ref name=university>{{Cite news|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/sport/football/wolverhampton-wanderers-fc/2019/05/04/watch-wolves-boss-nuno-espirito-santo-receives-honorary-doctorate-from-university-of-wolverhampton/|title=WATCH: Wolves boss Nuno Espirito Santo receives honorary doctorate from University of Wolverhampton|last=Edwards|first=Joe|website=Express & Star|access-date=4 May 2019|date=4 May 2019}}</ref> His team [[2018\u201319 Premier League|finished the season in seventh]] and qualified for the Europa League for the first time since [[1980\u201381 UEFA Cup|1980\u201381]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Wolves v Braga facts |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/match/2027798--wolves-vs-braga/prematch/background/?referrer=%2Fuefaeuropaleague%2Fnews%2Fnewsid%3D2619824 |accessdate=10 March 2020 |publisher=UEFA |date=11 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|match played 12 March 2020}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefinalball.com/coach_teams.php?id=2141|title=Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo|publisher=Zerozero|accessdate=1 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Soccerway coach|nuno-herlander-simoes-espirito-santo/252341}}</ref>\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Managerial record by team and tenure\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n!rowspan=\"2\"|From\n!rowspan=\"2\"|To\n!colspan=\"5\"|Record\n|-\n!{{abbr|P|Matches played}}!!{{abbr|W|Matches won}}!!{{abbr|D|Matches drawn}}!!{{abbr|L|Matches lost}}!!{{abbr|Win %|Win percentage}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Rio Ave F.C.|Rio Ave]]\n|align=left|1 July 2012\n|align=left|30 June 2014\n{{WDL|78|31|16|31|decimals=1}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Valencia CF|Valencia]]\n|align=left|4 July 2014\n|align=left|29 November 2015\n{{WDL|62|32|16|14|decimals=1}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[FC Porto|Porto]]\n|align=left|1 June 2016\n|align=left|22 May 2017\n{{WDL|49|27|16|6|decimals=1}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]\n|align=left|31 May 2017\n|align=left|''Present''\n{{WDL|146|75|39|32|decimals=1}}\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Total\n{{WDLtot|335|165|87|83|decimals=1}}\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Player===\n'''Deportivo'''\n*[[Copa del Rey]]: [[2001\u201302 Copa del Rey|2001\u201302]]\n\n'''Porto'''\n*[[Primeira Liga]]: [[2002\u201303 Primeira Liga|2002\u201303]], [[2003\u201304 Primeira Liga|2003\u201304]], [[2007\u201308 Primeira Liga|2007\u201308]], [[2008\u201309 Primeira Liga|2008\u201309]]\n*[[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal]]: [[2002\u201303 Ta\u00e7a de Portugal|2002\u201303]], [[2008\u201309 Ta\u00e7a de Portugal|2008\u201309]]\n*[[Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira]]: [[2003 Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira|2003]], [[2004 Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira|2004]], [[2009 Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira|2009]]\n*[[UEFA Champions League]]: [[2003\u201304 UEFA Champions League|2003\u201304]]\n*[[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]: [[2002\u201303 UEFA Cup|2002\u201303]]\n*[[Intercontinental Cup (football)|Intercontinental Cup]]: [[2004 Intercontinental Cup|2004]]\n*[[Ta\u00e7a da Liga]] runner-up: [[2009\u201310 Ta\u00e7a da Liga|2009\u201310]]\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[Bobby Zamora Trophy]]: [[1999\u20132000 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1999\u20132000]] ([[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]])\n\n===Manager===\n'''Rio Ave'''\n*Ta\u00e7a de Portugal runner-up: [[2013\u201314 Ta\u00e7a de Portugal|2013\u201314]]\n*Ta\u00e7a da Liga runner-up: [[2013\u201314 Ta\u00e7a da Liga|2013\u201314]]\n\n'''Wolverhampton Wanderers'''\n*[[EFL Championship]]: [[2017\u201318 EFL Championship|2017\u201318]]<ref name=CHAMPIONSHIP/>\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[La Liga Manager of the Month]]: September 2014, December 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lfp.es/en/news/the-bbva-prizes-for-decembers-best|title=The BBVA Prizes for December's best|publisher=Liga de F\u00fatbol Profesional|date=14 January 2015|accessdate=14 January 2015}}</ref> February 2015<ref name=LFP/>\n*[[EFL Championship Manager of the Month]]: [[2017\u201318 EFL Championship#Monthly awards|November 2017]]<ref name=EFL/>\n*[[League Managers Association Awards|LMA Manager of the Year]]: [[2017\u201318 EFL Championship]]<ref>{{cite web|title = \nNuno Named Championship Manager Of The Year |url = https://www.wolves.co.uk/news/first-team/20180516-nuno-named-championship-manager-of-the-year/|website = Wolverhampton Wanderers FC|date = 16 May 2018 |accessdate = 23 March 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Premier League Manager of the Month]]: [[2018\u201319 Premier League#Monthly awards|September 2018]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.premierleague.com/managers/17863/Nuno-Esp\u00edrito%20Santo/overview|title=Manager profile: Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo|publisher=Premier League|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref>\n*[[University of Wolverhampton]]: Honorary Doctorate in Sport: 4 May 2019<ref name=university/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ForaDeJogo}}\n*{{ForaDeJogo manager|10072}}\n*{{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011002757/http://www.lfp.es/historico/primera/plantillas/historial.asp?jug=6430|title=Stats at Liga de F\u00fatbol Profesional|date=11 October 2007}} {{in lang|es}}\n*{{BDFutbol|2096}}\n*{{BDFutbol manager|2096}}\n*[https://www.fpf.pt/pt/Jogadores/Jogador/playerId/312776 National team data] {{in lang|pt}}\n*{{FIFA|183397}}\n*{{WorldFootball.net|nuno}}\n\n{{Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. squad}}\n{{Premier League managers}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Portugal squads\n| bg        = #B50000\n| fg        = gold\n| bordercolor = #006600\n| list1 = \n{{Portugal men's football squad 1996 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Portugal squad UEFA Euro 2008}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Managerial positions\n| list1 =\n{{Rio Ave F.C. managers}}\n{{Valencia CF managers}}\n{{FC Porto coaches}}\n{{Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. managers}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nuno Espirito Santo}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Portuguese people of S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe descent]]\n[[Category:People from S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9]]\n[[Category:Black Portuguese sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Portuguese footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:Vit\u00f3ria S.C. players]]\n[[Category:FC Porto players]]\n[[Category:Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a players]]\n[[Category:CP M\u00e9rida footballers]]\n[[Category:CA Osasuna players]]\n[[Category:FC Dynamo Moscow players]]\n[[Category:C.D. Aves players]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:Portuguese Second Division players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Russian Premier League players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Champions League winning players]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers who have scored]]\n[[Category:Portugal youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Portugal under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Olympic footballers of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2008 players]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate sportspeople in Russia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Russia]]\n[[Category:Portuguese football managers]]\n[[Category:Rio Ave F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:FC Porto managers]]\n[[Category:Valencia CF managers]]\n[[Category:Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga managers]]\n[[Category:La Liga managers]]\n[[Category:English Football League managers]]\n[[Category:Premier League managers]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in England]]\n[[Category:Portugal B international footballers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Portuguese football manager and former player}}\n{{Portuguese name|Sim\u00f5es|Esp\u00edrito Santo}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo\n| image = Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo.jpg\n| image_size = 280\n| caption = Esp\u00edrito Santo as manager of [[Valencia CF|Valencia]] in 2015\n| fullname = Nuno Herlander Sim\u00f5es Esp\u00edrito Santo\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1974|1|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9]], [[Portuguese S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe|S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe]]\n| height = 1.88 m\n| position = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| currentclub = [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] (manager)\n| youthyears1 = 1985\u20131986\n| youthyears2 = 1986\u20131987\n| youthyears3 = 1987\u20131991\n| youthyears4 = 1991\u20131992\n| youthclubs1 = Santoantoniense\n| youthclubs2 = Quimigal\n| youthclubs3 = Ca\u00e7adores Torreenses\n| youthclubs4 = [[Vit\u00f3ria S.C.|Vit\u00f3ria Guimar\u00e3es]]\n| years1 = 1992\u20131996\n| years2 = 1993\u20131994\n| years3 = 1997\u20132002\n| years4 = 1998\u20132000\n| years5 = 2000\u20132001\n| years6 = 2002\u20132004\n| years7 = 2005\u20132006\n| years8 = 2007\n| years9 = 2007\u20132010\n| clubs1 = [[Vit\u00f3ria S.C.|Vit\u00f3ria Guimar\u00e3es]]\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[S.C. Vila Real|Vila Real]] (loan)\n| clubs3 = [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a]]\n| clubs4 = \u2192 [[CP M\u00e9rida|M\u00e9rida]] (loan)\n| clubs5 = \u2192 [[CA Osasuna|Osasuna]] (loan)\n| clubs6 = [[FC Porto|Porto]]\n| clubs7 = [[FC Dynamo Moscow|Dynamo Moscow]]\n| clubs8 = [[C.D. Aves|Aves]]\n| clubs9 = [[FC Porto|Porto]]\n| caps1 = 34\n| caps2 = 19\n| caps3 = 4\n| caps4 = 69\n| caps5 = 33\n| caps6 = 6\n| caps7 = 11\n| caps8 = 15\n| caps9 = 8\n| totalcaps = 199\n| goals1 = 0\n| goals2 = 0\n| goals3 = 0\n| goals4 = 0\n| goals5 = 0\n| goals6 = 1\n| goals7 = 0\n| goals8 = 0\n| goals9 = 0\n| totalgoals = 1\n| nationalyears1 = 1992\n| nationalyears2 = 1995\n| nationalyears3 = 1996\n| nationalyears4 = 2000\u20132001\n| nationalteam1 = [[Portugal national under-18 football team|Portugal U18]]\n| nationalteam2 = [[Portugal national under-21 football team|Portugal U21]]\n| nationalteam3 = [[Portugal Olympic football team|Portugal U23]]\n| nationalteam4 = [[Portugal national football B team|Portugal B]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 1\n| nationalcaps2 = 3\n| nationalcaps3 = 5\n| nationalcaps4 = 3\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalgoals4 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 2012\u20132014\n| manageryears2 = 2014\u20132015\n| manageryears3 = 2016\u20132017\n| manageryears4 = 2017\u2013\n| managerclubs1 = [[Rio Ave F.C.|Rio Ave]]\n| managerclubs2 = [[Valencia CF|Valencia]]\n| managerclubs3 = [[FC Porto|Porto]]\n| managerclubs4 = [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]\n}}\n'''Nuno Herlander Sim\u00f5es Esp\u00edrito Santo''' ({{IPA-pt|\u02c8nunu (\u0268)\u0283\u02c8pi\u027eitu \u02c8s\u0250\u030btu}}; born 25 January 1974), known simply as '''Nuno''' as a player, is a Portuguese former [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]], and head coach of [[Premier League]] club [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]].\n\nDuring his career he first made a name for himself in Spain, playing for three teams in five years. He later returned to Portugal to represent [[FC Porto|Porto]], and also played professionally in Russia; he was part of the [[Portugal national football team|Portuguese squad]] at [[UEFA Euro 2008|Euro 2008]], but never won a [[Cap (sport)|cap]] for the national team.\n\nEsp\u00edrito Santo became a manager in 2012, leading [[Rio Ave F.C.|Rio Ave]] to both domestic cup finals in 2014 before taking the reins at [[Valencia CF|Valencia]].\n\n==Playing career==\n===Early career / Deportivo===\nBorn in [[S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9]], [[Portuguese S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe]], Nuno started his football career with [[Vit\u00f3ria S.C.]] in [[Guimar\u00e3es]], battling from age 20 with veteran [[Neno (footballer)|Neno]] for first-choice status. After a meeting with the then [[Porto]] nightclub owner [[Jorge Mendes]] he became the agent's first client in 1996;<ref>{{cite news |title=Soccer exchange: How a super-agent and a Chinese billionaire planned to trade in players |url=https://www.reuters.com/investigates/special-report/soccer-files-fosun/ |accessdate=21 August 2019 |publisher=Reuters |date=3 June 2009}}</ref> Mendes brokered a $1 million transfer the following January to [[La Liga]]'s [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lowe |first1=Sid |title=\u2018I saw a lot from the bench\u2019: how Porto\u2019s reserve goalkeeper became manager |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/sep/27/porto-leicester-champions-league-nuno-espirito-santo |accessdate=21 August 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=27 September 2016}}</ref> but Nuno would spend three of his six seasons in [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]] out on loan, backing up [[Jacques Songo'o]] (1996\u201398) and [[Jos\u00e9 Francisco Molina]] ([[2001\u201302 La Liga|2001\u201302]]) when he was part of the team.\n\nIn [[1999\u20132000 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1999\u20132000]], as he represented [[CP M\u00e9rida]] in the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|Spanish second division]], Nuno won the [[Ricardo Zamora Trophy]] and helped the side finish sixth, but it would be relegated to the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|third level]] due to irregularities.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2012/05/17/mas_futbol/1337236018_850215.html|title=El primer fichaje de la factor\u00eda Jorge Mendes|trans-title=First signing of Jorge Mendes factory|newspaper=[[Diario AS]]|first=Manu|last=Sainz|language=es|date=17 May 2012|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> [[2000\u201301 La Liga|The following season]] he was loaned to [[CA Osasuna]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rcdeportivo.es/noticia/nuno-cedido-al-osasuna|title=Nuno, cedido al Osasuna|trans-title=Nuno, loaned to Osasuna|publisher=Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a|language=es|date=11 July 2000|accessdate=3 January 2019}}</ref> going on to rank seventh in the Zamora as his team finished only one point above the relegation zone in the top tier.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nacion.com/puro-deporte/mexicano-aguirre-logra-salvar-del-descenso-a-osasuna/VYJKTW2UZZFWNLGV7U4XIRRQCI/story/|title=Mexicano Aguirre logra salvar del descenso a Osasuna|trans-title=Mexican Aguirre leads Osasuna out of relegation|newspaper=[[La Naci\u00f3n (San Jos\u00e9)|La Naci\u00f3n]]|first=Ferm\u00edn|last=Zariquiegui|language=es|date=23 June 2002|accessdate=4 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Porto===\n[[Jos\u00e9 Mourinho]]'s [[FC Porto]] paid [[Euro|\u20ac]]3 million to bring Nuno back to the country in July 2002, as part of the deal that saw [[Jorge Andrade]] join Deportivo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcporto.pt/IncFCP/PDF/Investor_Relations/FactosRelevantes/VendaJAndrade22072002.pdf|title=Venda do passe do jogador Jorge Andrade|trans-title=Player Jorge Andrade's pass sold|publisher=FC Porto|language=pt|date=22 July 2002|accessdate=4 October 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101205171120/http://www.fcporto.pt/IncFCP/PDF/Investor_Relations/FactosRelevantes/VendaJAndrade22072002.pdf|archivedate=5 December 2010}}</ref> During a 2003 [[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal]] match against [[Varzim S.C.|Varzim SC]], he was allowed by Mourinho to convert a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]], scoring the club's last goal in a [[2002\u201303 Ta\u00e7a de Portugal|7\u20130 home routing]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://jn.sapo.pt/PaginaInicial/Desporto/Interior.aspx?content_id=1023740|title=F.C. Porto: Nuno \u00e9 mais que um guarda-redes|trans-title=F.C. Porto: Nuno is more than a goalkeeper|newspaper=[[Jornal de Not\u00edcias]]|language=pt|date=8 October 2008|accessdate=14 December 2010}}</ref> In May 2004, Nuno was an unused substitute as Porto won the [[European Champion Clubs' Cup]]<ref>{{cite web|title=UEFA Champions League 2003/04&nbsp;\u2013 History|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2003/index.html|website=UEFA.com|publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]]|accessdate=2 July 2014}}</ref> final. On 12 December 2004, he replaced club great [[V\u00edtor Ba\u00eda]] during [[Overtime (sports)|extra time]] of the [[Intercontinental Cup (football)|Intercontinental Cup]] final [[Penalty shootout (association football)|penalty shootout]] [[2004 Intercontinental Cup|victory]] against [[Once Caldas]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/f-c-porto-once-caldas-0-0-8-7-nas-g-p-cronica|title=F.C. Porto-Once Caldas, 0\u20130 (8\u20137 nas g.p.) (cr\u00f3nica)|trans-title=F.C. Porto-Once Caldas, 0\u20130 (8\u20137 on p.k.) (match report)|publisher=Mais Futebol|first=Filipe|last=Caetano|language=pt|date=12 December 2004|accessdate=3 January 2019}}</ref> however, in January, he was sold to [[Russian Premier League]]'s [[FC Dynamo Moscow]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maisfutebol.iol.pt/nuno-apresentado-no-dinamo-moscovo|title=Nuno apresentado no D\u00ednamo Moscovo|trans-title=Nuno presented at Dynamo Moscow|publisher=Mais Futebol|language=pt|date=23 July 2005|accessdate=4 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nAgain in January, in 2007, Nuno returned to Portugal for a stint with [[C.D. Aves]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/d-aves-nuno-espirito-santo-reforca-leque-de-opcoes-de-neca|title=D. Aves: Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo refor\u00e7a leque de op\u00e7\u00f5es de Neca|trans-title=D. Aves: Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo strengthens Neca's options|publisher=Mais Futebol|language=pt|date=11 January 2007|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref> [[2006\u201307 Primeira Liga|eventually relegated]] from the [[Primeira Liga]]. In July he returned to Porto, backing up Brazilian [[Helton Arruda|Helton]] during most of his spell.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-nos/fc-porto/detalhe/nuno-promete-dar-luta-a-helton.html|title=Nuno promete dar luta a Helton|trans-title=Nuno promises to challenge Helton|newspaper=[[Record (newspaper)|Record]]|language=pt|date=13 July 2007|accessdate=12 January 2018}}</ref> Despite his limited involvement on the pitch, he was considered a leader of the club.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bates |first1=Pearce |title=\"O Substituto\", Jorge Mendes nightclub encounter, a Wolves love affair, the story of Nuno Espirito Santo |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/o-substituto-jorge-mendes-nightclub-14932075 |accessdate=21 August 2019 |work=Birmingham Mail |date=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nNuno again played second-fiddle to Helton during the [[2008\u201309 Primeira Liga|2008\u201309 season]] appearing in only four games, but was the starter throughout the [[2008\u201309 Ta\u00e7a de Portugal|domestic cup campaign]], including the final win (1\u20130) against [[F.C. Pa\u00e7os de Ferreira]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/helton-quem-sou-eu-para-dar-conselhos-ao-nuno-video|title=Helton: \"Quem sou eu para dar conselhos ao Nuno?\" (v\u00eddeo)|trans-title=Helton: \u00abWho am I to give advice to Nuno?\u00bb (video)|publisher=Mais Futebol|first=Nuno|last=Travassos|language=pt|date=31 May 2009|accessdate=13 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===International===\nNuno represented [[Portugal Olympic football team|Portugal]] at the [[1996 Summer Olympics]], playing four matches for the [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|fourth-placed team]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dn.pt/dossiers/desporto/jogos-olimpicos/historico/interior/atlanta1996---os-portugueses-1008872.html|title=Atlanta1996 \u2013 Os portugueses|trans-title=Atlanta1996 \u2013 The Portuguese|newspaper=[[Di\u00e1rio de Not\u00edcias]]|language=pt|date=3 September 2008|accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> [[Cap (sport)|Uncapped]], he was called to the [[Portugal national football team|full squad]] competing in [[UEFA Euro 2008]], replacing the injured [[Quim (footballer, born 1975)|Quim]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/arquivo/interior.aspx?content_id=345461|title=Nuno \u00e9 o substituto de Quim|trans-title=Nuno replaces Quim|newspaper=Record|language=pt|date=7 June 2008|accessdate=31 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110190044/http://www.record.xl.pt/arquivo/interior.aspx?content_id=345461|archive-date=10 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\n===Beginnings===\nOn 21 June 2010, Porto announced Nuno's contract would not be renewed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcporto.pt/Noticias/Futebol/noticiafutebol_futcomunicadosad_210610_53339.asp|title=Comunicado da FC Porto \u2013 Futebol, SAD|trans-title=FC Porto announcement \u2013 Football, PLSC|publisher=FC Porto|language=pt|date=21 June 2010|accessdate=4 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100625021741/http://www.fcporto.pt/Noticias/Futebol/noticiafutebol_futcomunicadosad_210610_53339.asp|archivedate=25 June 2010}}</ref> The 36-year-old said he would always support Porto as he left.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcporto.pt/Noticias/Futebol/noticiafutebol_futnunodec_210610_53347.asp|title=Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo: 'Sou e serei Porto!'|trans-title=Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo: 'I am and will be Porto!'|publisher=FC Porto|language=pt|date=21 June 2010|accessdate=4 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100625021747/http://www.fcporto.pt/Noticias/Futebol/noticiafutebol_futnunodec_210610_53347.asp|archivedate=25 June 2010}}</ref> After his retirement he rejoined former Porto manager [[Jesualdo Ferreira]], moving to [[M\u00e1laga CF]] as a goalkeeping coach; the pair signed for [[Panathinaikos FC]] in November 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.jn.pt/desporto/interior/o-tecnico-que-ja-o-era-antes-de-o-ser-5199328.html|title=O t\u00e9cnico que j\u00e1 o era antes de o ser|trans-title=The manager who was one before ever being so|newspaper=Jornal de Not\u00edcias|language=pt|date=30 May 2016|accessdate=16 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Rio Ave===\nIn May 2012, [[Rio Ave F.C.]] sacked manager [[Carlos Lu\u00eds Brito|Carlos Brito]] and announced the appointment of Esp\u00edrito Santo.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abola.pt/nnh/ver.aspx?id=331416|title=Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo \u00e9 o novo treinador|trans-title=Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo is the new manager|newspaper=[[A Bola]]|language=pt|date=15 May 2012|accessdate=24 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120518075950/http://www.abola.pt/nnh/ver.aspx?id=331416|archive-date=18 May 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> In [[2013\u201314 Primeira Liga|his second season]] in charge, the team reached both the [[2013\u201314 Ta\u00e7a de Portugal|Ta\u00e7a de Portugal]] and [[Ta\u00e7a da Liga]] finals,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/Futebol/Nacional/1a_liga/rio_ave/interior.aspx?content_id=878365|title=Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo feliz com 2.\u00aa final da \u00e9poca|trans-title=Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo happy with second final of season|newspaper=Record|language=pt|date=17 April 2014|accessdate=18 April 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017134039/http://www.record.xl.pt/Futebol/Nacional/1a_liga/rio_ave/interior.aspx?content_id=878365|archivedate=17 October 2014}}</ref> also [[2014\u201315 UEFA Europa League|leading them]] to the [[UEFA Europa League]] for the first time in their history.\n\n===Valencia===\nEsp\u00edrito Santo signed a one-year contract with [[Valencia CF]] in [[La Liga]] on 4 July 2014, replacing the fired [[Juan Antonio Pizzi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.valenciacf.com/ver/36277/benvingutnuno-nuno-espirito-santo-firma-su-contrato-como-nuevo-entrenador-del-valencia-cf.html|title=#BenvingutNuno Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo firma su contrato como nuevo entrenador del Valencia CF|trans-title=#WelcomeNuno Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo signs contract as new Valencia CF manager|publisher=Valencia CF|language=es|date=4 July 2014|accessdate=6 July 2014}}</ref> On 12 January 2015, he agreed to an extension to keep him at the club until 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.valenciacf.com/ver/39814/comunicado-oficial.html|title=Nuno: \"It is an honour and a pleasure to be here\"|publisher=Valencia CF|date=12 January 2015|accessdate=12 January 2015}}</ref> and he eventually led them to a fourth place finish in [[2014\u201315 La Liga|his first year]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laliga.es/noticias/el-valencia-se-impone-en-la-batalla-por-la-cuarta-plaza|title=El Valencia se impone en la batalla por la cuarta plaza|trans-title=Valencia win battle for fourth place|publisher=[[La Liga]]|language=es|date=25 January 2015|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> highlights including a 2\u20131 home win over [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] and a 2\u20132 away draw against the same opponent,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/30673410|title=Valencia 2\u20131 Real Madrid|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|first=Pete|last=Oliver|date=4 January 2015|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/32589617|title=Real Madrid 2\u20132 Valencia|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Emlyn|last=Begley|date=9 May 2015|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> while he was named [[La Liga Manager of the Month]] three times;<ref name=LFP>{{cite web|url=http://www.laliga.es/en/news/bbva-awards-nuno-liga-bbva-manager-of-the-month-for-february|title=BBVA Awards: Nuno, Liga BBVA Manager of the month for February|publisher=[[Liga de F\u00fatbol Profesional]]|date=9 March 2015|accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref> he resigned on 29 November 2015, following a 0\u20131 away defeat to [[Sevilla FC]], after a poor start to both Valencia's La Liga and Champions League campaigns.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/nov/29/nuno-valencia-resigns-sevilla|title=Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo resigns as Valencia coach after Sevilla defeat|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=29 November 2015|accessdate=29 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Porto===\nOn 1 June 2016, Esp\u00edrito Santo signed a two-year contract with Porto, replacing former head coach [[Jos\u00e9 Peseiro]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcporto.pt/en/noticias/Pages/Nuno-Espirito-Santo-e-o-novo-treinador-do-FC-Porto.aspx|title=Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo is the new coach at FC Porto|publisher=FC Porto|date=1 June 2016|accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref> The following 22 May, however, after [[2016\u201317 FC Porto season|a season]] devoid of silverware which included a [[2016\u201317 Primeira Liga|second place in the league]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/porto-nuno-espirito-santo-primeira-liga/1wj6pmi3nefwu1b3nmdd9hy2ta|title=Porto boss Nuno steps down|publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|first=Dom|last=Farrell|date=22 May 2017|accessdate=15 August 2018}}</ref> he was relieved of his duties.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/futebol/1a-liga/porto/noticias/interior/nuno-espirito-santo-deixa-comando-tecnico-do-fc-porto-8497194.html|title=Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo deixa o FC Porto|trans-title=Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo leaves FC Porto|newspaper=[[O Jogo]]|first=Jos\u00e9 Manuel|last=Ribeiro|language=pt|date=22 May 2017|accessdate=22 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Wolverhampton Wanderers===\nOn 31 May 2017, Esp\u00edrito Santo was named as the new head coach of English [[EFL Championship|Championship]] side [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]], signing a three-year deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/40105588|title=Nuno Espirito Santo: Wolves appoint former Porto boss as head coach|publisher=BBC Sport|date=31 May 2017|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref> He was voted the competition's [[EFL Championship Manager of the Month|Manager of the Month]] in November as his team won all four of their games, scoring 13 times.<ref name=EFL>{{cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/news/2017/december/manager-of-the-month-nuno---wolverhampton-wanderers/|title=Championship Manager of the Month: Nuno \u2013 Wolverhampton Wanderers|publisher=[[English Football League]]|date=8 December 2017|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nEsp\u00edrito Santo led the club to the [[Premier League]] after a six-year absence, achieving promotion with four matches remaining in [[2017\u201318 EFL Championship|the season]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/43771511|title=Wolves: Championship leaders promoted to Premier League after Fulham draw with Brentford|publisher=BBC Sport|date=14 April 2018|accessdate=16 April 2018}}</ref> and being confirmed as champions with two games to spare.<ref name=CHAMPIONSHIP>{{cite news|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/sport/football/wolverhampton-wanderers-fc/2018/04/21/champions-wolves-win-the-league-after-breezing-past-bolton/|title=Champions! Wolves win the league after breezing past Bolton|newspaper=[[Express & Star]]|date=21 April 2018|accessdate=21 April 2018}}</ref> On 10 July 2018, it was announced that his contract had been extended until 2021.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/wolverhampton-wanderers/story/3561324/wolves-extend-manager-nuno-espirito-santo-contract-until-2021|title=Wolves extend manager Nuno Espirito Santo contract until 2021|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=10 July 2018|accessdate=14 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nEsp\u00edrito Santo was awarded the [[Premier League Manager of the Month]] title in his second month managing in the [[English football league system|English top division]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/877735|title=Nuno claims Barclays Manager of the Month|publisher=[[Premier League]]|date=12 October 2018|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref> after his team went unbeaten in September 2018, accruing ten points from four matches and only conceding one goal. It was the first time that a Wolverhampton Wanderers manager had secured the award, in the club's fifth season in the competition.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/45985099|title=Wolves: The science behind Premier League newcomers' record-breaking start|date=26 October 2018|access-date=5 December 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 May 2019, Esp\u00edrito Santo was awarded an Honorary Doctorate in Sport by the [[University of Wolverhampton]].<ref name=university>{{Cite news|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/sport/football/wolverhampton-wanderers-fc/2019/05/04/watch-wolves-boss-nuno-espirito-santo-receives-honorary-doctorate-from-university-of-wolverhampton/|title=WATCH: Wolves boss Nuno Espirito Santo receives honorary doctorate from University of Wolverhampton|last=Edwards|first=Joe|website=Express & Star|access-date=4 May 2019|date=4 May 2019}}</ref> His team [[2018\u201319 Premier League|finished the season in seventh]] and qualified for the Europa League for the first time since [[1980\u201381 UEFA Cup|1980\u201381]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Wolves v Braga facts |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/match/2027798--wolves-vs-braga/prematch/background/?referrer=%2Fuefaeuropaleague%2Fnews%2Fnewsid%3D2619824 |accessdate=10 March 2020 |publisher=UEFA |date=11 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|match played 12 March 2020}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefinalball.com/coach_teams.php?id=2141|title=Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo|publisher=Zerozero|accessdate=1 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Soccerway coach|nuno-herlander-simoes-espirito-santo/252341}}</ref>\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Managerial record by team and tenure\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n!rowspan=\"2\"|From\n!rowspan=\"2\"|To\n!colspan=\"5\"|Record\n|-\n!{{abbr|P|Matches played}}!!{{abbr|W|Matches won}}!!{{abbr|D|Matches drawn}}!!{{abbr|L|Matches lost}}!!{{abbr|Win %|Win percentage}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Rio Ave F.C.|Rio Ave]]\n|align=left|1 July 2012\n|align=left|30 June 2014\n{{WDL|78|31|16|31|decimals=1}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Valencia CF|Valencia]]\n|align=left|4 July 2014\n|align=left|29 November 2015\n{{WDL|62|32|16|14|decimals=1}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[FC Porto|Porto]]\n|align=left|1 June 2016\n|align=left|22 May 2017\n{{WDL|49|27|16|6|decimals=1}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]\n|align=left|31 May 2017\n|align=left|''Present''\n{{WDL|146|75|39|32|decimals=1}}\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Total\n{{WDLtot|335|165|87|83|decimals=1}}\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Player===\n'''Deportivo'''\n*[[Copa del Rey]]: [[2001\u201302 Copa del Rey|2001\u201302]]\n\n'''Porto'''\n*[[Primeira Liga]]: [[2002\u201303 Primeira Liga|2002\u201303]], [[2003\u201304 Primeira Liga|2003\u201304]], [[2007\u201308 Primeira Liga|2007\u201308]], [[2008\u201309 Primeira Liga|2008\u201309]]\n*[[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal]]: [[2002\u201303 Ta\u00e7a de Portugal|2002\u201303]], [[2008\u201309 Ta\u00e7a de Portugal|2008\u201309]]\n*[[Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira]]: [[2003 Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira|2003]], [[2004 Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira|2004]], [[2009 Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira|2009]]\n*[[UEFA Champions League]]: [[2003\u201304 UEFA Champions League|2003\u201304]]\n*[[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]: [[2002\u201303 UEFA Cup|2002\u201303]]\n*[[Intercontinental Cup (football)|Intercontinental Cup]]: [[2004 Intercontinental Cup|2004]]\n*[[Ta\u00e7a da Liga]] runner-up: [[2009\u201310 Ta\u00e7a da Liga|2009\u201310]]\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[Ricardo Zamora Trophy]]: [[1999\u20132000 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1999\u20132000]] ([[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]])\n\n===Manager===\n'''Rio Ave'''\n*Ta\u00e7a de Portugal runner-up: [[2013\u201314 Ta\u00e7a de Portugal|2013\u201314]]\n*Ta\u00e7a da Liga runner-up: [[2013\u201314 Ta\u00e7a da Liga|2013\u201314]]\n\n'''Wolverhampton Wanderers'''\n*[[EFL Championship]]: [[2017\u201318 EFL Championship|2017\u201318]]<ref name=CHAMPIONSHIP/>\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[La Liga Manager of the Month]]: September 2014, December 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lfp.es/en/news/the-bbva-prizes-for-decembers-best|title=The BBVA Prizes for December's best|publisher=Liga de F\u00fatbol Profesional|date=14 January 2015|accessdate=14 January 2015}}</ref> February 2015<ref name=LFP/>\n*[[EFL Championship Manager of the Month]]: [[2017\u201318 EFL Championship#Monthly awards|November 2017]]<ref name=EFL/>\n*[[League Managers Association Awards|LMA Manager of the Year]]: [[2017\u201318 EFL Championship]]<ref>{{cite web|title = \nNuno Named Championship Manager Of The Year |url = https://www.wolves.co.uk/news/first-team/20180516-nuno-named-championship-manager-of-the-year/|website = Wolverhampton Wanderers FC|date = 16 May 2018 |accessdate = 23 March 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Premier League Manager of the Month]]: [[2018\u201319 Premier League#Monthly awards|September 2018]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.premierleague.com/managers/17863/Nuno-Esp\u00edrito%20Santo/overview|title=Manager profile: Nuno Esp\u00edrito Santo|publisher=Premier League|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref>\n*[[University of Wolverhampton]]: Honorary Doctorate in Sport: 4 May 2019<ref name=university/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ForaDeJogo}}\n*{{ForaDeJogo manager|10072}}\n*{{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011002757/http://www.lfp.es/historico/primera/plantillas/historial.asp?jug=6430|title=Stats at Liga de F\u00fatbol Profesional|date=11 October 2007}} {{in lang|es}}\n*{{BDFutbol|2096}}\n*{{BDFutbol manager|2096}}\n*[https://www.fpf.pt/pt/Jogadores/Jogador/playerId/312776 National team data] {{in lang|pt}}\n*{{FIFA|183397}}\n*{{WorldFootball.net|nuno}}\n\n{{Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. squad}}\n{{Premier League managers}}\n{{Navboxe