{"title_page": "Pedro S\u00e1nchez", "text_new": "{{about|the Spanish politician|other politicians|Pedro S\u00e1nchez (disambiguation)}}\n{{Spanish name|S\u00e1nchez|P\u00e9rez-Castej\u00f3n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific_prefix = [[The Most Excellent]]\n|name             = Gravedigger\n|image            = Pedro S\u00e1nchez in 2020.jpg\n|caption          = S\u00e1nchez in 2020\n|office           = [[Prime Minister of Spain]]\n|monarch          = [[Felipe VI of Spain|Felipe VI]]\n|deputy           = [[Carmen Calvo]]<br/>[[Pablo Iglesias Turri\u00f3n|Pablo Iglesias]]<br/>[[Nadia Calvi\u00f1o]]<br/>[[Teresa Ribera]]\n|term_start       = 2 June 2018\n|term_end         = \n|predecessor      = [[Mariano Rajoy]]\n|successor        = \n|office1          = [[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party|Secretary-General of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party]]\n|president1       = [[Cristina Narbona]]\n|term_start1      = 17 June 2017\n|term_end1        = \n|predecessor1     = [[Javier Fern\u00e1ndez (Spanish politician)|Javier Fern\u00e1ndez]]\n|president2       = [[Micaela Navarro]]\n|term_start2      = 26 July 2014\n|term_end2        = 1 October 2016\n|predecessor2     = [[Alfredo P\u00e9rez Rubalcaba]]\n|successor2       = [[Javier Fern\u00e1ndez (Spanish politician)|Javier Fern\u00e1ndez]]\n|office3          = [[Leader of the Opposition (Spain)|Leader of the Opposition]]\n|term_start3      = 18 June 2017\n|term_end3        = 2 June 2018\n|primeminister3   = [[Mariano Rajoy]]\n|predecessor3     = None\n|successor3       = [[Pablo Casado]]\n|term_start4      = 26 July 2014\n|term_end4        = 1 October 2016\n|primeminister4   = [[Mariano Rajoy]]\n|predecessor4     = [[Alfredo P\u00e9rez Rubalcaba]]\n|successor4       = None\n|office5          = [[Congress of Deputies (Spain)|Member of the Congress of Deputies]]\n|term_start5      = 21 May 2019\n|term_end5        = \n|constituency5    = [[Madrid (Congress of Deputies constituency)|Madrid]]\n|term_start6      = 10 January 2013\n|term_end6        = 29 October 2016\n|constituency6    = Madrid\n|term_start7      = 15 September 2009\n|term_end7        = 27 September 2011\n|constituency7    = Madrid\n|birth_name       = Pedro S\u00e1nchez P\u00e9rez-Castej\u00f3n\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1972|2|29|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Madrid]], [[Francoist Spain|Spanish State]]\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party]]\n|spouse           = {{marriage|Mar\u00eda Bego\u00f1a G\u00f3mez Fern\u00e1ndez|2006}}\n|children         = 2\n|residence        = [[Palace of Moncloa]]\n|education        = [[Complutense University of Madrid|Complutense University]]<br />[[Universit\u00e9 libre de Bruxelles]]<br />[[IESE Business School|University of Navarra]]<br />[[Universidad Camilo Jos\u00e9 Cela|Camilo Jos\u00e9 Cela University]]\n|signature        = Firma Pedro S\u00e1nchez.png\n}}\n'''Pedro S\u00e1nchez P\u00e9rez-Castej\u00f3n''' ({{IPA-es|\u02c8pe\u00f0\u027eo \u02c8sant\u0283e\u03b8 \u02c8pe\u027ee\u03b8 kaste\u02c8xon|lang}}; born 29 February 1972) is a Spanish politician who has been [[Prime Minister of Spain]] since June 2018.<ref>{{cite web|website=lamoncloa.gob.es|language=Spanish|title=Relaci\u00f3n cronol\u00f3gica de los presidentes del Consejo de Ministros y del Gobierno |url=http://www.lamoncloa.gob.es/presidente/presidentes-desde-1823/Paginas/index.aspx |access-date=5 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|publisher=Agencia Estatal Bolet\u00edn Oficial del Estado|journal=Bolet\u00edn Oficial del Estado |issue=134 |date=2 June 2018|language=Spanish|title=Real Decreto 354/2018, de 1 de junio, por el que se nombra Presidente del Gobierno a don Pedro S\u00e1nchez P\u00e9rez-Castej\u00f3n|format=pdf|url=https://www.boe.es/boe/dias/2018/06/02/pdfs/BOE-A-2018-7400.pdf|issn=0212-033X|page=57657}}</ref> He has also been Secretary-General of the [[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party]] (PSOE) since June 2017, having previously held that office from 2014 to 2016.\n\nS\u00e1nchez began his political career in 2004 as a city councillor in [[Madrid]], before being elected to the [[Congress of Deputies]] in 2009. In 2014, he was elected Secretary-General of the PSOE, becoming [[Leader of the Opposition (Spain)|Leader of the Opposition]]. He led the party through the inconclusive [[2015 Spanish general election|2015]] and [[2016 Spanish general election|2016 general elections]], but resigned as Secretary-General shortly after the latter, following public disagreements with the party's executive. He was subsequently re-elected in a [[2017 Spanish Socialist Workers' Party leadership election|leadership election]] eight months later, defeating [[Susana D\u00edaz]] and [[Patxi L\u00f3pez]].\n\nOn 1 June 2018, the PSOE called a [[2018 vote of no confidence in the government of Mariano Rajoy|vote of no confidence]] in Prime Minister [[Mariano Rajoy]], successfully passing the motion after winning the support of [[Unidas Podemos]], as well as various regionalist and nationalist parties. S\u00e1nchez was subsequently sworn in as Prime Minister by [[Felipe VI of Spain|King Felipe VI]] the following day. He went on to lead the PSOE to gain 38 seats in the [[April 2019 Spanish general election|April 2019 general election]], the PSOE's first national victory since [[2008 Spanish general election|2008]], although they fell short of a majority. After talks to form a government failed, S\u00e1nchez again won the most votes at the [[November 2019 Spanish general election|November 2019 general election]], and in January 2020 formed a [[S\u00e1nchez II Government|coalition government]] with the support of Unidas Podemos, as well as a group of independents.\n\n==Early life==\nPedro S\u00e1nchez P\u00e9rez-Castej\u00f3n was born in [[Madrid]].<ref name=\"vanitatis\">[http://www.vanitatis.elconfidencial.com/noticias/2014-06-23/pedro-sanchez-la-vida-familiar-del-politico-al-que-han-apodado-mister-psoe-2014_147991/ Pedro S\u00e1nchez, la vida familiar del pol\u00edtico al que han apodado 'm\u00edster PSOE 2014'] Published by Vanitatis, 23 June 2014, accessed 26 June 2014</ref> His father is an economist and businessman and his mother is a lawyer and public servant in the [[social security in Spain|social security]] department.<ref name=\"elpais01\"/> He graduated from Instituto Ramiro de Maeztu, a public high school where he played basketball in the [[CB Estudiantes|Estudiantes]] [[cantera]], a professional club with links to the school, reaching the U-21 team.<ref name=PSOE>{{cite web |url=http://www.psoe.es/conocenos/secretaria-general/ |title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez, Secretar\u00eda general |language=Spanish |trans-title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez, Secretary-General |work=PSOE |accessdate=27 December 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, S\u00e1nchez went to the [[Complutense University]] to study economics and business sciences. In 1993, he joined the PSOE after the victory of [[Felipe Gonz\u00e1lez]] in the [[1993 Spanish general election|elections that year]].<ref name=\"elpais01\">{{cite news|url=http://politica.elpais.com/politica/2014/06/12/actualidad/1402576371_029298.html |title=Una carrera guiada por el azar |author=Fernando Garea |language=Spanish |work=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |date=12 July 2014|access-date=27 July 2014}}</ref> S\u00e1nchez graduated in 1995. He earned a degree in Politics and Economics in 1998 after graduating from the [[Universit\u00e9 libre de Bruxelles]] (Free University of Brussels), and a degree of business leadership from [[IESE Business School]] in the [[University of Navarra]], a private university and apostolate of the [[Opus Dei]]. S\u00e1nchez received his [[Doctor of Philosophy]] degree in Business and Economics in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://politica.elpais.com/politica/2015/11/19/actualidad/1447947868_898425.html|title=\u00bfQu\u00e9 carrera tiene Pedro S\u00e1nchez?|last=Pa\u00eds|first=Ediciones El|date=19 November 2015|language=es|access-date=6 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nBefore entering a career in regional and national politics, S\u00e1nchez worked as a parliamentary assistant in the [[European Parliament]], and as chief of staff to the [[United Nations]] high representative in Bosnia during the [[Kosovo War]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.psoe.es/conocenos/secretaria-general/pedro-sanchez-perez-castejon/|title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez P\u00e9rez- Castej\u00f3n|access-date=6 September 2016}}</ref> he was also a Professor of Economics, publishing a version of his doctoral thesis \"La nueva diplomacia econ\u00f3mica europea\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sanchezcastejon.es/sobre-mi/|title=Sobre m\u00ed {{!}} Pedro S\u00e1nchez Castej\u00f3n|website=sanchezcastejon.es|access-date=6 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Madrid City Council==\nIn 2003, S\u00e1nchez stood in the [[Madrid City Council]] election on the PSOE list headed by [[Trinidad Jim\u00e9nez]]. He was 23rd on the proportional representation list, but the PSOE only won 21 seats. S\u00e1nchez did not become a city councillor until a year later, when two socialist councillors resigned. He quickly became one of the fundamental components of opposition leader Trinidad Jim\u00e9nez's team.<ref name=abc /> Between 18 May 2004 \u2013 15 September 2009, he was one of the 320 members of the [[City Council of Madrid]], representing [[PSOE]] in the city of Madrid. At the same time, he went to help the [[PSdG]] (PSOE's affiliated party in Galicia) contest the [[2005 Galician parliamentary election|2005 Galician regional election]],<ref name=PSOE /> in which PSdG won eight seats, allowing [[Emilio P\u00e9rez Touri\u00f1o]] to become president of Galicia. In 2007, he was part of the Miguel Sebasti\u00e1n campaign for Madrid's premiership.\n\n==Member of the Congress of Deputies==\nS\u00e1nchez was elected to the [[Congress of Deputies (Spain)|Congress of Deputies]] for [[Madrid (Congress of Deputies constituency)|Madrid]], replacing [[Pedro Solbes]], Minister of Economy and Finance in the [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Rodr\u00edguez Zapatero]] cabinet, after Solbes retired from politics in 2009.\n\n[[File:Candidatura de Madrid PSOE 2011.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.70|S\u00e1nchez in the PSOE campaign for the 2011 general election]]\nIn the [[2011 Spanish general election|general election of 2011]] which saw a heavy defeat for the Socialists, PSOE placed S\u00e1nchez 11th on the Proportional Representation list, while only electing 10 deputies. Having thus failed to win a seat, he returned to the [[Universidad Camilo Jos\u00e9 Cela|Camilo Jos\u00e9 Cela University]] to finish his [[Doctorate]] in Economics. He served as a consultant to a European consortium and as a university professor. He earned a [[PhD]] in Economics and Business from the [[Universidad Camilo Jos\u00e9 Cela|Camilo Jos\u00e9 Cela University]]. In 2018  S\u00e1nchez was accused  by ABC daily of plagiarism.<ref name=PSOE />\n\nIn January 2013, S\u00e1nchez returned to Congress, replacing [[Cristina Narbona]], who left her seat to enter the [[Nuclear Safety Council (Spain)|Nuclear Safety Council]]. In December 2013, after numerous Socialist leaders such as [[Elena Valenciano]], [[Trinidad Jim\u00e9nez]], [[Miguel Sebasti\u00e1n]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Blanco L\u00f3pez]] attended his new book release, his name began to be discussed as a prospective candidate for the party leadership. S\u00e1nchez officially launched his candidacy on 12 June 2014. He was elected as the Secretary-General on 13 July, after winning 49% of votes against his opponents [[Eduardo Madina]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Antonio P\u00e9rez Tapias]] (member of the Socialist Left platform).<ref name=\"PSOE\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thespainreport.com/9777/pedro-sanchez-voted-new-secretary-general-spanish-socialist-party-xx-vote/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=25 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016191139/https://www.thespainreport.com/9777/pedro-sanchez-voted-new-secretary-general-spanish-socialist-party-xx-vote/ |archivedate=16 October 2014 }}</ref> He was confirmed as Secretary-General after an Extraordinary Congress of the PSOE was held on 26\u201327 July that ratified the electoral result.<ref name=PSOE />\n\n==PSOE Secretary-General==\nRepresenting a platform based on political regeneration, S\u00e1nchez demanded constitutional reforms establishing [[federalism]] as the form of administrative organization of Spain to ensure that Catalonia would remain within the country; a new progressive fiscal policy; extending the welfare state to all citizens; joining [[labour union]]s again to strengthen economic recovery; and regaining the confidence of former Socialist voters disenchanted by the measures taken by Zapatero during his late term as Prime Minister amid an economic crisis. He also opposed the [[grand coalition]] model supported by the former Socialist Prime Minister [[Felipe Gonz\u00e1lez]], who championed the German system in case of political instability. S\u00e1nchez asked his European party caucus not to vote for the consensus candidate [[Jean-Claude Juncker]] of the [[European People's Party]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.euractiv.com/sections/eu-elections-2014/spanish-socialists-vote-against-juncker-canete-308462 |title=Spanish socialists to vote against Juncker, Ca\u00f1ete |last=Gotev |first=Georgi |date=16 September 2014 |access-date=8 January 2015 |work=[[Euractiv]]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Pedro-Sanchez-primarias-PSOE-Internacional EDIIMA20170522 0010 19.jpg|thumb|Pedro S\u00e1nchez, after winning the primary election for Secretary-General, singing ''[[The Internationale]]''.]]\n\nUpon taking office as PSOE's Secretary-General, S\u00e1nchez faced a political crisis after the formation of a new party, [[Podemos (Spanish political party)|Podemos]]. Approximately 25% of all PSOE supporters switched their loyalties to Podemos.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.europapress.es/nacional/noticia-45-votantes-iu-icv-2011-28-upyd-24-psoe-apuestan-ahora-podemos-20141105193223.html |title=\u00bfDe d\u00f3nde vienen los votos de Podemos? |language=Spanish |trans-title=Where do the votes of Podemos come from? |work=europa press |date=5 November 2014 |accessdate=29 December 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=D\u00edez |first=Anabel |url=http://politica.elpais.com/politica/2015/07/26/actualidad/1437937474_105154.html |title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez, en proceso |language=Spanish |trans-title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez, in process |work=El Pais |date=6 July 2015 |accessdate=29 December 2015 }}</ref> S\u00e1nchez's political agenda included reforming the constitution, establishing a federal model in Spain to replace the current devolution model,<ref>{{cite news |last=D\u00edez |first=Anabel |url=http://politica.elpais.com/politica/2014/11/09/actualidad/1415546589_008826.html |title=\"Ni fractura, ni independencia, una Espa\u00f1a federal para todos\" |language=Spanish |trans-title=\"No fracture, no independence, a federal Spain for all\" |work=El Pais |date=9 November 2014 |accessdate=29 December 2015 }}</ref> and further secularization of Spain's education system, including the removal of religion-affiliated public and private schools.<ref>{{cite news |last=SANZ |first=LUIS \u00c1NGEL |url=http://www.elmundo.es/espana/2015/10/19/5625237d46163f09298b460f.html |title=El PSOE eliminar\u00e1 la religi\u00f3n en colegios p\u00fablicos y privados |language=Spanish |trans-title=The PSOE to eliminate religion in all public and private schools |work=El Mundo(ES) |date=19 October 2015 |accessdate=29 December 2015 }}</ref> He named [[C\u00e9sar Luena]] as his second-in-command. On 21 June 2015, S\u00e1nchez was officially announced as the PSOE premiership candidate for the December 2015 general election. His party earned 90 seats, being second to rivals of Partido Popular (PP), who won the election with 123 representatives out of a parliament formed by 350. Since PP's leader did not stand officially for the premiership, following this S\u00e1nchez was requested by the King to form a coalition, but he was unable to obtain the support of a majority of representatives. This led to a further general election in June 2016, where he stood again as PSOE's candidate. Winning only 85 seats in a general election, he resigned in October 2016.\n\n===Leadership crisis===\n{{See also|2016 PSOE crisis}}\nAfter resigning as Secretary-General of the party, S\u00e1nchez made a tour aboard his car visiting base members in different parts of Spain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/887cedda-699d-11e8-b6eb-4acfcfb08c11|work=[[Financial Times]]|title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez, a dogged politician who grabbed his chance|first1=Michael|last1=Stothard|date=8 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eleconomista.es/politica/noticias/9179988/06/18/Sanchez-el-politico-de-las-siete-vidas.html|newspaper=El Economista|language=es|last1=Zancajo|date=3 June 2018|title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez, el pol\u00edtico de las siete vidas|trans-title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez, the politician of the seven lives|first1=Silvia}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 May 2017, S\u00e1nchez was re-elected Secretary-General for the second time with 50.2% of the votes, over his competitors [[Susana D\u00edaz]] (39.94%) and [[Patxi L\u00f3pez]] (9.85%).<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/may/21/spanish-socialists-re-elect-pedro-sanchez-to-lead-party Spanish Socialists re-elect Pedro S\u00e1nchez to lead party] TheGuardian.com</ref>\n\nS\u00e1nchez opposed the [[2017 Catalan independence referendum|Catalan independence referendum]] and supported the [[Mariano Rajoy|Rajoy]] government's decision to dismiss the [[Generalitat de Catalunya|Catalan government]] and impose direct rule on [[Catalonia]] in October 2017.<ref>{{cite news |title=Spain's Pedro S\u00e1nchez forced to confront Catalonia crisis |url=https://www.ft.com/content/36229ab2-670e-11e8-b6eb-4acfcfb08c11 |newspaper=[[Financial Times]] |date=4 June 2018 |access-date=3 September 2018 |first=Michael |last=Stothard |agency=Nikkei Company}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Catalan nationalists back in power, target secession in challenge to Sanchez |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-spain-politics-catalonia/nationalists-back-in-power-in-catalonia-say-target-independence-idUSKCN1IY0B8 |work=[[Reuters]] |date=2 June 2018 |access-date=3 September 2018 |first=Jes\u00fas |last=Aguado |first2=Ingrid |last2=Melander}}</ref>\n\n==Prime Minister of Spain==\n[[File:Mariano Rajoy felicita al nuevo presidente del Gobierno Pedro S\u00e1nchez (2018-06-01).jpg|thumb|right|Rajoy congratulates S\u00e1nchez on his successful no-confidence motion.|alt=]]\n{{See also|2018 vote of no confidence in the government of Mariano Rajoy}}\nIn May 2018, after verdicts were announced in the [[Gurtel case|G\u00fcrtel trial]], PSOE filed a successful no-confidence motion against Mariano Rajoy.<ref name=\"Gurtel\">{{Cite news |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2018/05/25/inenglish/1527237249_668560.html |title=Socialist party chief calls for transitional government |last=Garcia |first=Elsa |date=25 April 2018 |access-date=1 June 2018 |newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |location=Madrid}}</ref> Per the Constitution, the no-confidence motion proposed S\u00e1nchez as replacement Prime Minister. With the passage of the no-confidence motion, S\u00e1nchez was automatically deemed to have the confidence of the Congress of Deputies and thus ascended as Prime Minister on 1 June 2018.\n\nHe was sworn in by King Felipe VI on 2 June.<ref>{{cite news |title=Who is Spain's new prime minister Pedro Sanchez? |url=http://www.dw.com/en/who-is-spains-new-prime-minister-pedro-sanchez/a-44041431 |accessdate=1 June 2018 |work=Reuters, AFP |publisher=DW |date=1 June 2018}}</ref> S\u00e1nchez said he planned to form a government that would eventually dissolve the [[Cortes Generales]] and call for a general election, but he did not specify when he would do it<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.es/espana/abci-sanchez-llega-poder-sin-concretar-cuando-convocara-elecciones-201806010320_noticia.html |title=S\u00e1nchez llega al poder sin concretar cu\u00e1ndo convocar\u00e1 las elecciones |last=Ruiz de Almir\u00f3n |first=Victor |date=1 June 2018 |access-date=9 July 2018 |newspaper=[[ABC (Spain)|ABC]] |language=es}}</ref> while also saying that before calling for an election he intended take a series of measures like increasing unemployment benefits and proposing a law of equal pay between the sexes.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.eleconomista.es/economia/noticias/9179627/06/18/Sanchez-prioriza-la-agenda-social-y-renuncia-a-realizar-reformas-en-profundidad.html |title=S\u00e1nchez prioriza la agenda social y renuncia a realizar reformas en profundidad |last=Zancajo |first=Silvia |date=1 June 2018 |access-date=9 July 2018 |newspaper=[[El Economista (Spain)|El Economista]] |language=es |publisher=Editorial Ecoprensa, [[Sociedad An\u00f3nima|S.A.]]}}</ref> However, he also said he would uphold the 2018 budget approved by the Rajoy government, a condition the [[Basque Nationalist Party]] imposed to vote for the motion of no-confidence.<ref name=\"LV\">{{cite news |url=http://www.lavanguardia.com/politica/20180531/443963185308/pedro-sanchez-rajoy-dimita-mocion-de-censura.html |title=S\u00e1nchez ofrece di\u00e1logo a Catalunya y mantener los presupuestos al PNV |last=Merino |first=Juan Carlos |date=31 May 2018 |access-date=9 July 2018 |newspaper=[[La Vanguardia]] |language=es}}</ref>\n\n===Inauguration===\n{{See also|S\u00e1nchez government}}[[File:Primer Gobierno de Pedro S\u00e1nchez (2018-06).jpg|thumb|right|S\u00e1nchez and his new cabinet at [[La Moncloa]] in June 2018]]S\u00e1nchez took office on 2 June 2018 in the presence of former Prime Minister Rajoy, [[President of the Congress of Deputies|President of the Congress]] [[Ana Pastor Juli\u00e1n|Ana Pastor]], as well as [[King Felipe VI]].<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.boe.es/boe/dias/2018/06/02/pdfs/BOE-A-2018-7400.pdf |title=Real Decreto 354/2018, de 1 de junio, por el que se nombra Presidente del Gobierno a don Pedro S\u00e1nchez P\u00e9rez-Castej\u00f3n |work=[[Bolet\u00edn Oficial del Estado]] |issue=134 |date=2 June 2018 |access-date=9 July 2018 |page=257657 |format=PDF |last=Pastor Juli\u00e1n |first=Ana Mar\u00eda |author-link=Ana Mar\u00eda Pastor Juli\u00e1n |editor-last=R. |editor-first=Felipe |editor-link=Felipe VI of Spain |issn=0212-033X}}</ref> Spanish media noted that while S\u00e1nchez was swearing his oath of office on the [[Spanish Constitution]], no [[Bible]] nor [[crucifix]] were on display, for the first time in modern Spanish history due to S\u00e1nchez's atheism.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.eldiario.es/politica/Pedro-Sanchez-presidente-presencia-Rajoy_0_777972264.html |title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez promete su cargo de presidente ante el rey y Rajoy, sin crucifijo ni Biblia |last=Aduriz |first=\u00cd\u00f1igo |date=2 June 2018 |access-date=9 July 2018 |newspaper=[[El Diario (Spain)|El Diario]] |language=es}}</ref> After being sworn in, S\u00e1nchez announced that he would only propose measures that had considerable parliamentary support, and reaffirmed the government's compliance with the EU deficit requirements.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://politica.elpais.com/politica/2018/06/01/actualidad/1527859489_043487.html |title=El presidente solo propondr\u00e1 medidas con amplio apoyo |last=D\u00edez |first=Anabel |last2=Garc\u00eda de Blas |first2=Elsa |date=3 June 2018 |access-date=9 July 2018 |newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |language=es |location=Madrid}}</ref>\n\nThe 17 ministers of his new cabinet took office on 7 June 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rtve.es/noticias/20180607/17-nuevos-ministros-pedro-sanchez-prometen-cargos-ante-rey/1746583.shtml|publisher=[[RTVE]]|title=Gobierno de Pedro S\u00e1nchez Las \"ministras y ministros\" de Pedro S\u00e1nchez arrancan el gobierno de la \"igualdad\", el \"di\u00e1logo\" y la \"diversidad\"|date=7 June 2018}}</ref> S\u00e1nchez formed a cabinet with 11 of the 18 ministerial positions of the [[Council of Ministers (Spain)|Council]] being held by women.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jun/06/new-spanish-pm-appoints-astronaut-pedro-duque-science-minister|title=Spanish PM appoints 11 women and six men to new cabinet|last=Jones|first=Sam|date=6 June 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=20 March 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n=== European Union ===\n[[File:Pedro S\u00e1nchez conferencia \"Proteger el ideal de Europa\" 02.jpg|right|thumb|S\u00e1nchez during his speech at the event organized by the Spanish Federal Council of the European Movement on 19 March 2019.]]\n\nSince his arrival to power he has been strongly [[pro-Europeanism|pro-European]]. This is evidenced by changes including the renaming of the Foreign Ministry to the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs, European Union and Cooperation (Spain)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs, European Union and Cooperation]], and reverting the Secretary of State for European Affairs back to its original name, the [[Secretary of State for the European Union]]. He appointed [[Josep Borrell]], former [[President of the European Parliament]], as Foreign Minister, and [[Nadia Calvi\u00f1o]] as [[Ministry of Economy (Spain)|Minister of Economy]], who served as [[Directorate-General for Budget|Director-General for the EU Budget]], and [[Secretary-General of the European Economic and Social Committee]] [[Luis Planas]] as [[Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food (Spain)|Minister of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/world/europe/spains-new-pm-pedro-sanchez-unveils-pro-eu-government-dominated-by-women|title=Spain's new PM Pedro Sanchez unveils pro-EU government dominated by women|last=hermesauto|date=7 June 2018|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=20 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe also took a more active role in the international sphere, especially in the European Union, saying that \"Spain has to claim its role\" and declaring himself \"a militant pro-European\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/pedro-sanchez-sets-sights-on-brussels-spain-eu/|title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez sets sights on Brussels|date=21 November 2018|website=POLITICO|access-date=20 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 January 2019, in a speech before the [[European Parliament]], he said that the EU should be protected and turned into a global actor, and that a more social Europe is needed, with a strong monetary union.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/eu-elections-2019/news/spanish-pm-if-europe-is-to-protect-us-we-need-to-protect-europe/|title=Spanish PM: If Europe protects us, we need to protect Europe|last=Rios|first=Beatriz|date=17 January 2019|website=euractiv.com|language=en-GB|access-date=20 March 2019}}</ref> He stated in a speech in March 2019 adding that the enemies of Europe are inside of the European Union.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eldiario.es/politica/Sanchez-advierte-enemigos-Europa-fuerzas_0_879462938.html|title=S\u00e1nchez advierte de que los \"enemigos\" de Europa est\u00e1n \"dentro\" y llama a votar contra las fuerzas \"unidas por sus odios\"|last=Castro|first=Irene|website=eldiario.es|language=es|access-date=20 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration===\n[[File:2018-06-26, Pedro S\u00e1nchez se re\u00fane con Angela Merkel 4.jpg|thumb|S\u00e1nchez with German Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]], 26 June 2018]]\nIn June 2018, the ship ''[[Aquarius (NGO ship)|Aquarius]]'' carrying 629 migrants that were [[European migrant crisis|rescued near Libya]] was denied entry to the Sicilian port by Italy's new Interior Minister [[Matteo Salvini]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-44432056 |title=Italy's Matteo Salvini shuts ports to migrant rescue ship |date=11 June 2018 |access-date=9 July 2018 |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/06/spain-offers-aquarius-ship-carrying-600-refugees-180611133533958.html |title=Spain offers to take in Aquarius ship carrying over 600 refugees |date=11 June 2018 |access-date=9 July 2018 |work=[[Al Jazeera]] |publisher=[[Al Jazeera Media Network]]}}</ref> The Spanish government offered the ''Aquarius'' the chance to dock in the secure port of Valencia, Spain and the Italian navy offered full assistance and a marine escort for the trip.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2018/06/12/world/social-issues-world/boat-600-rescued-migrants-lies-mediterranean-amid-italy-malta-standoff/#.Wx8WTkiFNaQ |title=Boat with over 600 rescued migrants lies to in Mediterranean amid Italy-Malta standoff |date=12 June 2018 |access-date=9 July 2018 |newspaper=[[Japan Times]] |author=AP |author-link=Associated Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dw.com/en/spain-will-accept-migrant-ship-aquarius-after-italy-and-malta-refuse-entry/a-44150793 |title=Spain will accept migrant ship Aquarius after Italy and Malta refuse entry |date=11 June 2018 |access-date=9 July 2018 |work=[[Deutsche Welle]]}}</ref> On 4 July 2018, the Spanish government accepted another NGO vessel, in this case a Spanish NGO called [[Proactiva Open Arms|Open Arms]] carrying 60 migrants after Italy rejected again open a port for the ship.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2018/07/04/inenglish/1530690012_839181.html |title=Second migrant ship arrives in Spain after being rejected by Italy, Malta |last=Mart\u00edn |first=Mar\u00eda |date=4 July 2018 |newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |access-date=19 July 2018 |last2=L\u00f3pez-Fonseca |first2=\u00d3scar |issn=1134-6582 |last3=Garc\u00eda |first3=Jes\u00fas |publisher=Prisa}}</ref> The same happened two weeks later.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.euronews.com/2018/07/19/-open-arms-migrant-rescue-boat-heads-for-spain-amid-row-with-italy |title='Open Arms' migrant rescue boat heads for Spain amid row with Italy |date=19 July 2018 |work=[[Euronews]] |access-date=19 July 2018 |first=Alasdair |last=Sandford}}</ref>\n\n<!--[[File:Pedro S\u00e1nchez asiste a la Cumbre del G-22 en Buenos Aires 03.jpg|thumb|S\u00e1nchez with French President [[Emmanuel Macron]] and President of the European Commission [[Jean-Claude Juncker]] at the G20 Summit in Buenos Aires, 30 November 2018]]-->\nThe Prime Minister considered the immigration matter as a European matter and showed its solidarity with the German Government by accepting an agreement between Germany, Greece and Spain so this last two agreed to take care of part of the immigrants that live in Germany.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/spain-greece-and-germany-seal-migrant-swap-deal/ |title=Spain, Greece and Germany seal migrant swap deal |date=30 June 2018 |work=[[Politico]] |access-date=19 July 2018 |first=Fiona |last=Maxwell |first2=Ryan |last2=Heath}}</ref> \"Unilateralism not the answer to migrant crisis\", he said in an interview in a clear reference to the initiative of the Italian Government to close the ports while also stating: \"As effective as the inflammatory rhetoric from some Italian leaders may be in electoral terms, from the point of view of responding effectively to a humanitarian crisis like the one we're seeing in the Mediterranean and on the Italian coast, it's not the answer\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/jun/28/unilateralism-not-the-answer-to-migrant-crisis-says-spains-pm |title=Unilateralism not the answer to migrant crisis, says Spain's PM |last=Jones |first=Sam |date=28 June 2018 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=19 July 2018 |publisher=[[Guardian News and Media Limited]]}}</ref>\n\n===Gibraltar===\nS\u00e1nchez has called for [[Status of Gibraltar|joint U.K.-Spanish sovereignty]] over British-controlled [[Gibraltar]], a [[British Overseas Territories|British Overseas Territory]] in the south of the Iberian peninsula.<ref>{{cite news |title=Spain revives call for shared control over Gibraltar after Brexit |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-spain/spain-revives-call-for-shared-control-over-gibraltar-after-brexit-idUSKCN1NU0GW |agency=Reuters |date=25 November 2018}}</ref> He publicly warned that Spain will \"veto\" [[Brexit deal]] over the issue of Gibraltar.<ref>{{cite news |title=Spain PM Pedro Sanchez threatens Brexit deal over Gibraltar |url=https://www.thelocal.es/20181120/spain-pm-pedro-sanchez-threatens-brexit-deal-over-gibraltar |work=The Local |date=20 November 2018}}</ref> In November 2018, S\u00e1nchez said that \"With Brexit we all lose, especially the United Kingdom, but when it comes to Gibraltar, Spain wins.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Spanish PM: \"With Brexit we all lose, but on Gibraltar, Spain wins\" |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2018/11/26/inenglish/1543222571_685671.html |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Exhumation of Franco===\nOn 18 June 2018, S\u00e1nchez' government announced its intention to remove the remains of former dictator [[Francisco Franco]] from the ''[[Valle de los Ca\u00eddos]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2018/06/18/inenglish/1529307821_499020.html |title=Removal of Franco's remains from Valley of the Fallen one step closer |first=Natalia |last=Junquera |date=18 June 2018 |access-date=3 September 2018 |location=Madrid |language=es |newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |publisher=Prisa}}</ref> On 29 June 2018, the [[Archdiocese of Madrid]] warned the Spanish government against any plans to exhume the remains of Franco without first obtaining agreement from interested parties and formally stated it is against any move of Franco's remains without the consent of his family and before consultation with the Catholic Church. In addition, in its statement the Archdiocese of Madrid re-affirmed its position that although the Valle de los Ca\u00eddos is officially a national monument, the Catholic Church must be consulted on burial-related matters under agreements between the Spanish state and the Vatican.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.catholicherald.co.uk/news/2018/07/01/spanish-church-expresses-concern-at-plan-to-exhume-francos-remains/ |title=Spanish Church expresses concern at plan to exhume Franco's remains |magazine=[[Catholic Herald]] |date=1 July 2018 |publisher=Interconnect/it |access-date=24 August 2018}}</ref> The announcement of the Archdiocese of Madrid was made after Pedro S\u00e1nchez confirmed that it was his intention to remove the remains of Franco from the Valle de los Ca\u00eddos by the end of July.<ref>{{cite news |date=27 June 2018 |url=http://www.elmundo.es/espana/2018/06/27/5b337b48e2704ea9188b461a.html |title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez quiere sacar los restos de Franco del Valle de los Ca\u00eddos en el mes de julio |newspaper=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]] |language=es |access-date=2 September 2018 |first=Luis \u00c1ngel |last=Sanz |location=Madrid |publisher=[[Unidad Editorial]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thebostonpilot.com/article.asp?ID=182712 |title=Spanish church warns on exhumation of dictator |work=The Boston Pilot |access-date=24 August 2018 |first=Jonathan |last=Luxmoore |date=29 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 August 2018, S\u00e1nchez's cabinet approved a decree that modifies two aspects of the 2007 Historical Memory Law to allow the exhumation of Franco's remains from the Valle de los Ca\u00eddos. The decree, to become law, must be passed by a vote of the Congress of Deputies. The conservative [[People's Party (Spain)|People's Party]] (PP) and the centre-right party [[Citizens (Spanish political party)|Ciudadanos]] (Cs) have announced they will not support the decree. The PP further stated it will appeal the measure to the Constitutional Court arguing that using a decree to change the Historical Memory Law is not valid because the proposed modifications to the Historical Memory Law do not respond to a situation of urgent need. Deputy Prime Minister Carmen Calvo stated the decree law requires the exhumation of the remains of Franco to take place between 30 days and 12 months of passage by the Congress of Deputies.<ref>{{cite news |date=24 August 2018 |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2018/08/24/inenglish/1535097265_662248.html |title=Spanish Cabinet approves decree to exhume Franco's remains |newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |access-date=2 September 2018 |first=Elsa |last=Garc\u00eda de Blas |language=es |publisher=Prisa |location=Madrid}}</ref> The [[Congress of Deputies]] voted in favor of the exhumation on 13 September 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-spain-politics-franco/spanish-parliament-votes-to-exhume-remains-of-dictator-franco-idUSKCN1LT2C9?ref=hvper.com|title=Spanish parliament votes to exhume remains of dictator Franco|work=[[Reuters]]|date=13 September 2018|accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref> After a year of legal battles with Franco's descendants, the exhumation took place on 24 October 2019, and Franco was reburied at [[Mingorrubio Cemetery]] in [[El Pardo]] with his wife [[Carmen Polo, 1st Lady of Meir\u00e1s|Carmen Polo]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/23/francos-remains-to-finally-leave-spains-valley-of-the-fallen The Guardian]</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, the [[Mossos d'Esquadra]] reported the arrest of a [[Terrassa]] resident who was angry with the plans to exhume Franco and having an arsenal of 16 weapons back home{{refn|group=n.|Including a [[CETME rifle|CETME]] assault rifle, a [[Skorpion vz. 61]] and four long-range rifles able to hit a target located 1,500 m away from the sniper.<ref name=elperiodico /> The suspect also carried two guns in his car, one of them modified.<ref name=elperiodico />}} allegedly planned to kill S\u00e1nchez in order to finish, in his own words, with that \"shitty red\".<ref name=elperiodico>{{cite journal|url=https://www.elperiodico.com/es/politica/20181108/francotirador-pedro-sanchez-7135125|journal=[[El Peri\u00f3dico de Catalu\u00f1a|El Peri\u00f3dico]]|date=8 November 2018|title=Los Mossos detienen a un tirador que quer\u00eda matar a Pedro S\u00e1nchez}}</ref>\n\n===Catalan separatism===\nS\u00e1nchez said he would \"reinstate dialogue\" with the [[Catalan independence movement]].<ref name=\"LV\"/> In order to do so, the central government and the regional government reactivated intergovernmental commissions, a series of bodies composed by representatives of both governments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lavanguardia.com/politica/20180703/45608162666/govern-reactiva-comisiones-bilaterales-mixtas-generalitat-estado.html|title=El Govern reactiva las comisiones bilaterales y mixtas Generalitat-Estado|date=3 July 2018|website=La Vanguardia|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref> Although there was some progress in the economic field, these commissions were paralyzed by the [[Catalonia]] [[Executive Council of Catalonia|regional government]]'s demand to speak about a [[self-determination]] [[referendum]], something that the central government rejected and in February 2019 the central government considered the relations between the two governments broken.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eldiario.es/politica/Gobierno-asegura-independentistas-rechazado-estatales_0_865813920.html|title=El Gobierno da por rotas las negociaciones con los independentistas y se centrar\u00e1 en defender los presupuestos|website=eldiario.es|language=es|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref> In December 2018, the ''[[Financial Times|FT]]'' reported that S\u00e1nchez \"has warned Catalonia's government that he could deploy national police to the region, as tension flares up again between Madrid and Catalan separatists a year after a failed secession attempt\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Spanish prime minister warns Catalonia as tensions rise |url=https://www.ft.com/content/92e0f1b0-fe15-11e8-aebf-99e208d3e521 |work=Financial Times |date=12 December 2018}}</ref> The distance between the two governments became clear when the parliamentary opposition\u2014among which was Catalan separatism\u2014rejected the government's budget.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/pedro-sanchez-spains-parliament-rejects-2019-budget-proposal/|title=Spain's parliament rejects 2019 budget proposal|date=13 February 2019|website=POLITICO|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref> After this, the Prime Minister called a snap election.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-47251125|title=Spain PM sets snap election for April|date=15 February 2019|access-date=3 March 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===Saudi Arabia===\nIn September 2018, Defense Minister [[Margarita Robles]] cancelled sales of [[laser-guided bomb]]s to [[Saudi Arabia]] over concerns relating to the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen]]. Overruling Robles, S\u00e1nchez ordered the sale to proceed<ref>{{cite news |title=Spain not stopping arms sales to Saudi Arabia over Khashoggi killing |url = https://elpais.com/elpais/2018/10/22/inenglish/1540192063_943808.html |work = El Pais |date=22 October 2018}}</ref> because he had guaranteed [[President of Andalusia]] [[Susana D\u00edaz]] help to protect jobs in the shipyards of the [[Bay of C\u00e1diz]], highly dependent on the \u20ac1.813 billion contract with Saudi Arabia to deliver five [[corvettes]].<ref>{{Cite journal|date=24 October 2018|url=https://www.elmundo.es/espana/2018/10/24/5bcf6829e5fdeaf16b8b4644.html|journal=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez evita una crisis con Arabia Saud\u00ed por el coste electoral en Andaluc\u00eda|first=Luis \u00c1ngel|last=Sanz|first2=Marisa|last2=Cruz|first3=Susana|last3=Villaverde}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|publisher=[[RTVE]]|title=El Gobierno garantiza el contrato de Arabia Saud\u00ed con Navantia, cuyos trabajadores han cortado la A-4|date=7 September 2018|url=http://www.rtve.es/noticias/20180907/trabajadores-navantia-cortan-4-temor-se-cancele-contrato-arabia-saudi/1793562.shtml}}</ref> In response to the killing of Saudi dissident journalist [[Jamal Khashoggi]] in October 2018, S\u00e1nchez defended the decision to continue arms sales to Saudi Arabia and insisted on his government's \"responsibility\" to protect jobs in the [[arms industry]].<ref>{{cite news |title=How Saudis are getting away with Khashoggi murder |url=https://www.news.com.au/world/middle-east/how-saudis-are-getting-away-with-khashoggi-murder/news-story/4632ff5a196d9013a2b1b8e3e7139175 |work=[[News.com.au]] |date=28 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Need to keep jobs grounds for continuation of arms sales to Saudi Arabia, argues Spanish president |url=http://www.catalannews.com/politics/item/need-to-keep-jobs-grounds-for-continuation-of-arms-sales-to-saudi-arabia-argues-spanish-president |work=Catalan News |date=24 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Snap election and deadlock===\n{{see also|April 2019 Spanish general election}}\n[[File:Pedro S\u00e1nchez convoca elecciones 2019 02.jpg|thumb|Prime Minister S\u00e1nchez announcing a [[snap election]] for 28 April 2019.|alt=|left]]\nAfter the rejection of his [[General State Budget|budget]], S\u00e1nchez called an early [[April 2019 Spanish general election|general election]] for 28 April 2019, making a television announcement in which he declared that \"between doing nothing and continuing with the [former] budget and calling on Spaniards to have their say, I chose the second. Spain needs to keep advancing, progressing with tolerance, respect, moderation and common sense\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/02/15/spanish-prime-minister-calls-snap-election-after-budget-fails-to-pass.html|title=Spanish prime minister calls snap election after budget fails to pass|last=Reid|first=David|date=15 February 2019|publisher=CNBC|accessdate=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe PSOE won the election, obtaining 29% of the vote which translated into 123 seats in the Congress of Deputies, well over the 85 seats and 23% share of the vote the party obtained in the [[2016 Spanish general election|2016 election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/apr/29/spanish-socialists-win-is-latest-sign-of-europes-centre-left-upturn|title=Spanish socialists' win is latest sign of Europe's centre-left upturn|last=correspondent|first=Jon Henley European affairs|date=29 April 2019|work=The Guardian|accessdate=30 April 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> PSOE also won a majority in the [[Senate of Spain|Senate]]. Whilst the PSOE were 53 seats short of the 176 seats needed for an outright majority in the Congress of Deputies, a three-way split in the centre-right vote assured that it was the only party that could realistically form a government.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://elpais.com/politica/2019/04/28/actualidad/1556466636_096682.html|title=El PSOE gana las elecciones pero necesitar\u00e1 pactar y el PP sufre una debacle hist\u00f3rica|date=28 April 2019|work=El Pa\u00eds|language=Spanish|accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.elconfidencial.com/elecciones-generales/2019-04-29/sanchez-gana-se-hunde-casado-y-el-gobierno-dependera-de-junqueras-o-rivera_1970690/|title=S\u00e1nchez gana, se hunde Casado y Rivera se postula como l\u00edder de la oposici\u00f3n|date=28 April 2019|work=El Confidencial|language=Spanish|accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.eldiario.es/politica/PP-derrota-historica-millones-Cs_0_893461398.html|title=El PP sufre una derrota hist\u00f3rica, pierde 3,7 millones de votos y Cs se queda cerca del sorpaso|date=28 April 2019|work=eldiario.es|language=Spanish|accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 June 2019, King Felipe VI, having previously held prospective meetings with the spokespeople of the political groups with representation in the new Congress of Deputies, formally proposed S\u00e1nchez as prospective Prime Minister. S\u00e1nchez accepted the task of trying to form a government \"with honor and responsibility\".<ref>{{Cite web|work=[[La Raz\u00f3n (Madrid)|La Raz\u00f3n]]|title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez asume el encargo del Rey de formar Gobierno \"con honor y responsabilidad\"|url=https://www.larazon.es/espana/el-rey-propone-a-pedro-sanchez-como-candidato-a-la-presidencia-del-gobierno-GO23694046|date=6 June 2019}}</ref> Several weeks of negotiations with [[Podemos (Spanish political party)|Podemos]] ended in an agreement that S\u00e1nchez would appoint several Podemos members to the [[Cabinet of Spain|Cabinet]], although not the party's leader [[Pablo Iglesias Turri\u00f3n|Pablo Iglesias]].<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/21/spain-socialist-government-sanchez-iglesias-catalonia</ref> But in the final voting session, Podemos rejected the agreement and led S\u00e1nchez to try a second chance to be inaugurated in September.\n\n===Second election and coalition===\n{{See also|S\u00e1nchez II Government}}[[File:(S\u00e1nchez e Iglesias) Declaraci\u00f3n conjunta de Pablo Iglesias y Pedro S\u00e1nchez.jpg|thumb|right|S\u00e1nchez and Iglesias announcing a tentative agreement for a \"progressive\" government ([[Palacio de las Cortes]], 12 November 2019).]]\nFollowing the results of the [[November 2019 Spanish general election]], on 12 November 2019 Pedro S\u00e1nchez and Iglesias announced a preliminary agreement between PSOE and Unidas Podemos to rule together creating the first [[coalition government]] of the Spanish democracy, for all purposes a minority coalition as it did not enjoy a qualified majority at the Lower House, thus needing further support or abstention from other parliamentary forces in order to get through.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.publico.es/politica/sanchez-e-iglesias-pactan-primer-gobierno-coalicion-estructura.html |title=S\u00e1nchez e Iglesias pactan un Gobierno de coalici\u00f3n, pero la estructura se conocer\u00e1 tras la investidura |first=Manuel |last=S\u00e1nchez |first2=Beatriz |last2=Asuar |date=12 November 2019 |access-date=12 November 2019 |newspaper=[[P\u00fablico (Spain)|P\u00fablico]] |language=es |publisher=Display Connectors, SL.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.elespanol.com/espana/20191112/sanchez-negocia-iglesias-gobierno-quitaria-sueno-espanoles/443956124_0.html |title=S\u00e1nchez pacta con Iglesias el Gobierno con el que \"no dormir\u00eda\" ni \u00e9l \"ni el 95% de espa\u00f1oles\" |date=12 November 2019 |access-date=12 November 2019 |first=Joana |last=Rel |newspaper=[[El Espa\u00f1ol]] |language=es |publisher=El Le\u00f3n de El Espa\u00f1ol Publicaciones S.A.}}</ref> On 7 January 2020, Pedro S\u00e1nchez earned a second mandate as Prime Minister after receiving a plurality of votes in the second round vote of his investiture at the Congress of Deputies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.20minutos.es/noticia/4107229/0/pedro-sanchez-investido-presidente/|title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez logra ser investido presidente con 167 votos a favor y 165 en contra|last=20minutos|date=7 January 2020|website=www.20minutos.es - \u00daltimas Noticias|language=es|access-date=7 January 2020}}</ref> He was then once again sworn in as Prime Minister by King Felipe on 8 January.<ref>https://www.thelocal.es/20200108/pedro-sanchez-is-sworn-in-as-head-of-spains-first-coalition-government-since-tr</ref><ref>https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/01/08/world/europe/ap-eu-spain-politics.html</ref> Soon after, S\u00e1nchez proceeded to form a new cabinet with 22 ministers and 4 vice-presidencies, who assumed office on 13 January.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3856055|title=Spain's Sanchez unveils Cabinet, pledges 'uni...|website=Taiwan News|access-date=14 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.20minutos.es/noticia/4113371/0/ministros-pedro-sanchez-prometen-cargos-ante-rey-felipe-vi/|title=As\u00ed ha sido la toma de posesi\u00f3n de los ministros: f\u00f3rmula de promesa, sin crucifijo, \"ministros y ministras\"...|last=20minutos|date=13 January 2020|website=www.20minutos.es - \u00daltimas Noticias|language=es|access-date=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Coronavirus pandemic===\n{{main article|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain}}\nOn 13 March 2020, S\u00e1nchez announced a declaration of the constitutional state of alarm in the nation for a period of 15 days, to become effective the following day after the approval of the Council of Ministers, becoming the second time in democratic history and the first time with this magnitude.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpais.com/espana/2020-03-13/el-gobierno-debate-decretar-el-estado-de-alarma.html|title=S\u00e1nche decreta el estado de alarma durante 15 d\u00edas|last=Blas|first=Carlos E. Cu\u00e9, Claudi P\u00e9rez, Elsa Garc\u00eda de|date=2020-03-13|website=EL PA\u00cdS|language=es|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> The following day imposed a [[2020 Spain coronavirus lockdown|nationwide lockdown]], banning all trips that were not force majeure and announced it may intervene in companies to guarantee supplies.<ref>https://nationalpost.com/pmn/health-pmn/spain-to-impose-nationwide-lockdown-el-mundo</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpais.com/espana/2020-03-14/el-gobierno-prohibe-todos-los-viajes-que-no-sean-de-fuerza-mayor.html|title=El Gobierno proh\u00edbe todos los viajes que no sean de fuerza mayor|last=Cu\u00e9|first=Carlos E.|date=2020-03-14|website=EL PA\u00cdS|language=es|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\n== Ideology ==\nS\u00e1nchez ran in the 2014 PSOE primary election under what has been described as a [[centrist]] and [[social liberal]] profile, later switching to the left in his successful 2017 bid to return to the PSOE leadership in which he stood for a refoundation of [[social democracy]] in order to transition to a \"post-capitalist society\", ending with \"neoliberal capitalism\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letraslibres.com/espana-mexico/politica/pedro-sanchez-victoria-en-victoria-hasta-la-derrota|title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez: De victoria en victoria hasta la derrota|website=Letras Libres|language=es|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.diariosur.es/nacional/201705/22/pedro-sanchez-fenix-camaleonico-20170522011859-v.html|title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez, el f\u00e9nix camale\u00f3nico|date=22 May 2017|website=Diario Sur|language=es|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eldiario.es/politica/Postcapitalismo-militancia-izquierda-Pedro-Sanchez_0_614539290.html|title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez gira a la izquierda y elige al neoliberalismo como gran enemigo del PSOE|website=Eldiario.es|language=es|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letraslibres.com/espana-mexico/politica/el-psoe-y-la-fatiga-democratica|title=El PSOE y la fatiga democr\u00e1tica|website=Letras Libres|language=es|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref> A key personal idea posed in his 2019 ''Manual de Resistencia'' book is the indissoluble link between \"social democracy\" and \"Europe\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://elpais.com/politica/2019/02/20/actualidad/1550693890_133147.html|title=La ideolog\u00eda de Pedro S\u00e1nchez|last=Estefan\u00eda|first=Joaqu\u00edn|date=21 February 2019|work=El Pa\u00eds|accessdate=14 January 2020|language=es|issn=1134-6582}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nS\u00e1nchez married Mar\u00eda Bego\u00f1a G\u00f3mez Fern\u00e1ndez in 2006 and they have two daughters, Ainhoa and Carlota. The civil wedding was officiated by [[Trinidad Jim\u00e9nez]]. Aside from Spanish, S\u00e1nchez speaks fluent English and French.<ref>{{cite web |title=A Conversation with Pedro S\u00e1nchez |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G-XqGH4atTc |website=YouTube |publisher=Council on Foreign Relations |accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"abc\">{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.es/espana/20140531/abci-pedro-sanchez-psoe-desconocido-201405301642.html |title=El ascenso de Pedro S\u00e1nchez: de diputado \"desconocido\" a secretario general del PSOE |language=Spanish |trans-title=The rise of Pedro S\u00e1nchez: from \"unknown\" deputy to general secretary of the PSOE |work=ABC |date=13 July 2014 |accessdate=27 December 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"congreso\">{{cite web|url=http://www.congreso.es/portal/page/portal/Congreso/Congreso/Diputados/BusqForm?_piref73_1333155_73_1333154_1333154.next_page=/wc/fichaDiputado&idDiputado=381|title=X Legislatura (2011-Actualidad)S\u00e1nchez P\u00e9rez-Castej\u00f3n, Pedro|author=[[Congress of Deputies (Spain)]]}}</ref> He is the first prime minister who is an outspoken [[atheist]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.elplural.com/2014/09/25/pedro-sanchez-primer-aspirante-a-la-moncloa-que-se-declara-abiertamente-ateo/ |title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez, primer aspirante a La Moncloa que se declara abiertamente \"ateo\" |publisher=El Plural |date=24 September 2014 |accessdate=2 March 2016 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral history ==\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|+ Electoral history of Pedro S\u00e1nchez\n! scope=\"col\"| Election\n! scope=\"col\"| List\n! scope=\"col\"| Constituency\n! scope=\"col\"| List position\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n|-\n| [[2003 Madrid City Council election]]\n| [[Spanish Socialist Worker's Party|PSOE]]\n| align=center | {{ndash}}\n| 24th (out of 55)\n| ''Not elected''{{refn|group=lower-alpha|He became city councillor in 2004 replacing Elena Arnedo.}}\n|-\n| [[2007 Madrid City Council election]]\n| PSOE\n| align=center | {{ndash}}\n| 15th (out of 57)\n| ''Elected''\n|-\n| [[2008 Spanish general election]]\n| PSOE\n| align=center | [[Madrid (Congress of Deputies constituency)|Madrid]]\n| 21st (out of 35)\n| ''Not elected''{{refn|group=lower-alpha|He became MP in 2009, replacing [[Pedro Solbes]].}}\n|-\n| [[2011 Spanish general election]]\n| PSOE\n| align=center | [[Madrid (Congress of Deputies constituency)|Madrid]]\n| 11th (out of 36)\n| ''Not elected''{{refn|group=lower-alpha|He became MP in 2013, replacing [[Cristina Narbona]].}}\n|-\n| [[2015 Spanish general election]]\n| PSOE\n| align=center | [[Madrid (Congress of Deputies constituency)|Madrid]]\n| 1st (out of 36)\n| ''Elected''\n|-\n| [[2016 Spanish general election]]\n| PSOE\n| align=center | [[Madrid (Congress of Deputies constituency)|Madrid]]\n| 1st (out of 36)\n| ''Elected''\n|-\n| [[April 2019 Spanish general election|April 2019 Spanish general election]]\n| PSOE\n| align=center | [[Madrid (Congress of Deputies constituency)|Madrid]]\n| 1st (out of 37)\n| ''Elected''\n|-\n| [[November 2019 Spanish general election|November 2019 Spanish general election]]\n| PSOE\n| align=center | [[Madrid (Congress of Deputies constituency)|Madrid]]\n| 1st (out of 37)\n| ''Elected''\n|-\n| colspan = 5 | {{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n|}\n</center>\n\n== Distinctions ==\n* Medal of Salvador Allende (28 August 2018).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://m.cooperativa.cl/noticias/pais/relaciones-exteriores/espana/presidente-espanol-recibio-emocionado-la-medalla-de-salvador-allende/2018-08-28/140605.html |title=Presidente espa\u00f1ol recibi\u00f3 \"emocionado\" la medalla de Salvador Allende |date=28 August 2018 |access-date=3 September 2018 |work=[[Cooperativa]] |language=es}}</ref>\n* [[Grand Collar]] of the [[Order of the Condor of the Andes]] (29 August 2018).<ref>{{Cite news |newspaper=El Independiente |url=https://www.elindependiente.com/politica/2018/08/29/hermano-presidente-sanchez-alianza-bolivia-zapatero/ |title=El \"hermano presidente Pedro S\u00e1nchez\" recupera la alianza con Bolivia de Zapatero |date=29 August 2018 |first=Carmen |last=Torres |access-date=3 September 2018 |language=es}}</ref>\n* Grand Cross of the [[Order of the Sun of Peru]] (27 February 2019).<ref>[http://www.hola.com/realeza/casa_espanola/20190227138172/reyes-cena-de-gala-presidente-peru-esposa Visita de Estado]</ref>\n\n== Notable published works ==\n* Oca\u00f1a Orbis, Carlos y S\u00e1nchez P\u00e9rez-Castej\u00f3n, Pedro (2013): ''La nueva diplomacia econ\u00f3mica espa\u00f1ola''. Madrid: Delta. {{ISBN|9788415581512}}.<ref>[https://www.casadellibro.com/libro-la-nueva-diplomacia-economica-espanola/9788415581512/2237298 Casa del Libro]</ref>\n* S\u00e1nchez P\u00e9rez-Castej\u00f3n, Pedro (2019): ''Manual de resistencia''. Madrid: Pen\u00ednsula. {{ISBN|9788499427959}}.<ref>[https://www.planetadelibros.com/libro-manual-de-resistencia/291507 Planeta de Libros]</ref>\n\n=== Discussed plagiarism and authorship ===\n* ''La nueva diplomacia econ\u00f3mica espa\u00f1ola''. In 2018 a newspaper revealed that the book includes the plagiarism of six other people's texts.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chicote |first=Javier |title=S\u00e1nchez plagi\u00f3 en su libro 161 l\u00edneas con 1.651 palabras de seis textos ajenos y sin ning\u00fan tipo de cita |url=https://www.abc.es/espana/abci-sanchez-plagio-libro-161-lineas-1651-palabras-seis-textos-ajenos-y-sin-ningun-tipo-cita-201809232157_noticia.html |work=ABC |date=24 September 2018 |access-date=28 February 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref> The suspicion was made extensive to his doctoral thesis, whose authorship was questioned.<ref>{{cite web |title=Un trabajo intrigante |url=https://elpais.com/politica/2018/09/13/actualidad/1536840669_711505.html |date=14 September 2018 |access-date=6 May 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n* ''Manual de resistencia''. The authorship of this work is in doubt because S\u00e1nchez, who appears as the sole author, states in the prologue that \"This book is the result of long hours of conversation with [[Irene Lozano]], writer, thinker, politician and friend. She gave a literary form to the recordings, giving me a decisive help\".<ref>{{cite book |last=S\u00e1nchez P\u00e9rez-Castej\u00f3n |first= Pedro |year=2019 |title=Manual de resistencia |location=Madrid |publisher=Pen\u00ednsula |isbn=9788499427959 |page=13}}.</ref> The mentioned writer, for her part, affirmed that \"I made the book, but the author is the president\".<ref>{{cite web |title= Irene Lozano sobre el libro de S\u00e1nchez: \"Yo hice el libro, pero el autor es el presidente\" |url=https://www.elespanol.com/espana/politica/20190219/irene-lozano-libro-sanchez-hice-autor-presidente/377463387_0.html |work=El Espa\u00f1ol |date=19 February 2019 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=n.}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n{{Commons category|Pedro S\u00e1nchez P\u00e9rez-Castej\u00f3n}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alfredo P\u00e9rez Rubalcaba]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Leader of the Opposition (Spain)|Leader of the Opposition]]|years=2014\u20132016}}\n{{s-vac}}\n|-\n{{s-vac}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Leader of the Opposition (Spain)|Leader of the Opposition]]|years=2017\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Pablo Casado]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mariano Rajoy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Spain]]|years=2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alfredo P\u00e9rez Rubalcaba]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Secretary General of the<br />[[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party]]|years=2014\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Javier Fern\u00e1ndez (Spanish politician)|Javier Fern\u00e1ndez]] (Acting)}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Javier Fern\u00e1ndez (Spanish politician)|Javier Fern\u00e1ndez]] (Acting)}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Secretary General of the<br />[[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party]]|years=2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Spanish Socialist Workers' Party}}\n{{Prime Ministers of Spain}}\n{{Leaders of the Opposition (Spain)}}\n{{European Council}}\n{{Current NATO leaders}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sanchez, Pedro}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Complutense University of Madrid alumni]]\n[[Category:Free University of Brussels alumni]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of the Sun of Peru]]\n[[Category:Leaders of political parties in Spain]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Madrid city councillors (2003\u20132007)]]\n[[Category:Madrid city councillors (2007\u20132011)]]\n[[Category:Members of the 10th Congress of Deputies (Spain)]]\n[[Category:Members of the 11th Congress of Deputies (Spain)]]\n[[Category:Members of the 12th Congress of Deputies (Spain)]]\n[[Category:Members of the 13th Congress of Deputies (Spain)]]\n[[Category:Members of the 14th Congress of Deputies (Spain)]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Spain]]\n[[Category:Spanish atheists]]\n[[Category:Spanish Socialist Workers' Party politicians]]\n[[Category:University of Navarra alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the Spanish politician|other politicians|Pedro S\u00e1nchez (disambiguation)}}\n{{Spanish name|S\u00e1nchez|P\u00e9rez-Castej\u00f3n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific_prefix = [[The Most Excellent]]\n|name             = Pedro S\u00e1nchez\n|image            = Pedro S\u00e1nchez in 2020.jpg\n|caption          = S\u00e1nchez in 2020\n|office           = [[Prime Minister of Spain]]\n|monarch          = [[Felipe VI of Spain|Felipe VI]]\n|deputy           = [[Carmen Calvo]]<br/>[[Pablo Iglesias Turri\u00f3n|Pablo Iglesias]]<br/>[[Nadia Calvi\u00f1o]]<br/>[[Teresa Ribera]]\n|term_start       = 2 June 2018\n|term_end         = \n|predecessor      = [[Mariano Rajoy]]\n|successor        = \n|office1          = [[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party|Secretary-General of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party]]\n|president1       = [[Cristina Narbona]]\n|term_start1      = 17 June 2017\n|term_end1        = \n|predecessor1     = [[Javier Fern\u00e1ndez (Spanish politician)|Javier Fern\u00e1ndez]]\n|president2       = [[Micaela Navarro]]\n|term_start2      = 26 July 2014\n|term_end2        = 1 October 2016\n|predecessor2     = [[Alfredo P\u00e9rez Rubalcaba]]\n|successor2       = [[Javier Fern\u00e1ndez (Spanish politician)|Javier Fern\u00e1ndez]]\n|office3          = [[Leader of the Opposition (Spain)|Leader of the Opposition]]\n|term_start3      = 18 June 2017\n|term_end3        = 2 June 2018\n|primeminister3   = [[Mariano Rajoy]]\n|predecessor3     = None\n|successor3       = [[Pablo Casado]]\n|term_start4      = 26 July 2014\n|term_end4        = 1 October 2016\n|primeminister4   = [[Mariano Rajoy]]\n|predecessor4     = [[Alfredo P\u00e9rez Rubalcaba]]\n|successor4       = None\n|office5          = [[Congress of Deputies (Spain)|Member of the Congress of Deputies]]\n|term_start5      = 21 May 2019\n|term_end5        = \n|constituency5    = [[Madrid (Congress of Deputies constituency)|Madrid]]\n|term_start6      = 10 January 2013\n|term_end6        = 29 October 2016\n|constituency6    = Madrid\n|term_start7      = 15 September 2009\n|term_end7        = 27 September 2011\n|constituency7    = Madrid\n|birth_name       = Pedro S\u00e1nchez P\u00e9rez-Castej\u00f3n\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1972|2|29|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Madrid]], [[Francoist Spain|Spanish State]]\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party]]\n|spouse           = {{marriage|Mar\u00eda Bego\u00f1a G\u00f3mez Fern\u00e1ndez|2006}}\n|children         = 2\n|residence        = [[Palace of Moncloa]]\n|education        = [[Complutense University of Madrid|Complutense University]]<br />[[Universit\u00e9 libre de Bruxelles]]<br />[[IESE Business School|University of Navarra]]<br />[[Universidad Camilo Jos\u00e9 Cela|Camilo Jos\u00e9 Cela University]]\n|signature        = Firma Pedro S\u00e1nchez.png\n}}\n'''Pedro S\u00e1nchez P\u00e9rez-Castej\u00f3n''' ({{IPA-es|\u02c8pe\u00f0\u027eo \u02c8sant\u0283e\u03b8 \u02c8pe\u027ee\u03b8 kaste\u02c8xon|lang}}; born 29 February 1972) is a Spanish politician who has been [[Prime Minister of Spain]] since June 2018.<ref>{{cite web|website=lamoncloa.gob.es|language=Spanish|title=Relaci\u00f3n cronol\u00f3gica de los presidentes del Consejo de Ministros y del Gobierno |url=http://www.lamoncloa.gob.es/presidente/presidentes-desde-1823/Paginas/index.aspx |access-date=5 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|publisher=Agencia Estatal Bolet\u00edn Oficial del Estado|journal=Bolet\u00edn Oficial del Estado |issue=134 |date=2 June 2018|language=Spanish|title=Real Decreto 354/2018, de 1 de junio, por el que se nombra Presidente del Gobierno a don Pedro S\u00e1nchez P\u00e9rez-Castej\u00f3n|format=pdf|url=https://www.boe.es/boe/dias/2018/06/02/pdfs/BOE-A-2018-7400.pdf|issn=0212-033X|page=57657}}</ref> He has also been Secretary-General of the [[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party]] (PSOE) since June 2017, having previously held that office from 2014 to 2016.\n\nS\u00e1nchez began his political career in 2004 as a city councillor in [[Madrid]], before being elected to the [[Congress of Deputies]] in 2009. In 2014, he was elected Secretary-General of the PSOE, becoming [[Leader of the Opposition (Spain)|Leader of the Opposition]]. He led the party through the inconclusive [[2015 Spanish general election|2015]] and [[2016 Spanish general election|2016 general elections]], but resigned as Secretary-General shortly after the latter, following public disagreements with the party's executive. He was subsequently re-elected in a [[2017 Spanish Socialist Workers' Party leadership election|leadership election]] eight months later, defeating [[Susana D\u00edaz]] and [[Patxi L\u00f3pez]].\n\nOn 1 June 2018, the PSOE called a [[2018 vote of no confidence in the government of Mariano Rajoy|vote of no confidence]] in Prime Minister [[Mariano Rajoy]], successfully passing the motion after winning the support of [[Unidas Podemos]], as well as various regionalist and nationalist parties. S\u00e1nchez was subsequently sworn in as Prime Minister by [[Felipe VI of Spain|King Felipe VI]] the following day. He went on to lead the PSOE to gain 38 seats in the [[April 2019 Spanish general election|April 2019 general election]], the PSOE's first national victory since [[2008 Spanish general election|2008]], although they fell short of a majority. After talks to form a government failed, S\u00e1nchez again won the most votes at the [[November 2019 Spanish general election|November 2019 general election]], and in January 2020 formed a [[S\u00e1nchez II Government|coalition government]] with the support of Unidas Podemos, as well as a group of independents. \n\n==Early life==\nPedro S\u00e1nchez P\u00e9rez-Castej\u00f3n was born in [[Madrid]].<ref name=\"vanitatis\">[http://www.vanitatis.elconfidencial.com/noticias/2014-06-23/pedro-sanchez-la-vida-familiar-del-politico-al-que-han-apodado-mister-psoe-2014_147991/ Pedro S\u00e1nchez, la vida familiar del pol\u00edtico al que han apodado 'm\u00edster PSOE 2014'] Published by Vanitatis, 23 June 2014, accessed 26 June 2014</ref> His father is an economist and businessman and his mother is a lawyer and public servant in the [[social security in Spain|social security]] department.<ref name=\"elpais01\"/> He graduated from Instituto Ramiro de Maeztu, a public high school where he played basketball in the [[CB Estudiantes|Estudiantes]] [[cantera]], a professional club with links to the school, reaching the U-21 team.<ref name=PSOE>{{cite web |url=http://www.psoe.es/conocenos/secretaria-general/ |title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez, Secretar\u00eda general |language=Spanish |trans-title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez, Secretary-General |work=PSOE |accessdate=27 December 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, S\u00e1nchez went to the [[Complutense University]] to study economics and business sciences. In 1993, he joined the PSOE after the victory of [[Felipe Gonz\u00e1lez]] in the [[1993 Spanish general election|elections that year]].<ref name=\"elpais01\">{{cite news|url=http://politica.elpais.com/politica/2014/06/12/actualidad/1402576371_029298.html |title=Una carrera guiada por el azar |author=Fernando Garea |language=Spanish |work=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |date=12 July 2014|access-date=27 July 2014}}</ref> S\u00e1nchez graduated in 1995. He earned a degree in Politics and Economics in 1998 after graduating from the [[Universit\u00e9 libre de Bruxelles]] (Free University of Brussels), and a degree of business leadership from [[IESE Business School]] in the [[University of Navarra]], a private university and apostolate of the [[Opus Dei]]. S\u00e1nchez received his [[Doctor of Philosophy]] degree in Business and Economics in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://politica.elpais.com/politica/2015/11/19/actualidad/1447947868_898425.html|title=\u00bfQu\u00e9 carrera tiene Pedro S\u00e1nchez?|last=Pa\u00eds|first=Ediciones El|date=19 November 2015|language=es|access-date=6 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nBefore entering a career in regional and national politics, S\u00e1nchez worked as a parliamentary assistant in the [[European Parliament]], and as chief of staff to the [[United Nations]] high representative in Bosnia during the [[Kosovo War]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.psoe.es/conocenos/secretaria-general/pedro-sanchez-perez-castejon/|title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez P\u00e9rez- Castej\u00f3n|access-date=6 September 2016}}</ref> he was also a Professor of Economics, publishing a version of his doctoral thesis \"La nueva diplomacia econ\u00f3mica europea\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sanchezcastejon.es/sobre-mi/|title=Sobre m\u00ed {{!}} Pedro S\u00e1nchez Castej\u00f3n|website=sanchezcastejon.es|access-date=6 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Madrid City Council==\nIn 2003, S\u00e1nchez stood in the [[Madrid City Council]] election on the PSOE list headed by [[Trinidad Jim\u00e9nez]]. He was 23rd on the proportional representation list, but the PSOE only won 21 seats. S\u00e1nchez did not become a city councillor until a year later, when two socialist councillors resigned. He quickly became one of the fundamental components of opposition leader Trinidad Jim\u00e9nez's team.<ref name=abc /> Between 18 May 2004 \u2013 15 September 2009, he was one of the 320 members of the [[City Council of Madrid]], representing [[PSOE]] in the city of Madrid. At the same time, he went to help the [[PSdG]] (PSOE's affiliated party in Galicia) contest the [[2005 Galician parliamentary election|2005 Galician regional election]],<ref name=PSOE /> in which PSdG won eight seats, allowing [[Emilio P\u00e9rez Touri\u00f1o]] to become president of Galicia. In 2007, he was part of the Miguel Sebasti\u00e1n campaign for Madrid's premiership.\n\n==Member of the Congress of Deputies==\nS\u00e1nchez was elected to the [[Congress of Deputies (Spain)|Congress of Deputies]] for [[Madrid (Congress of Deputies constituency)|Madrid]], replacing [[Pedro Solbes]], Minister of Economy and Finance in the [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Rodr\u00edguez Zapatero]] cabinet, after Solbes retired from politics in 2009.\n\n[[File:Candidatura de Madrid PSOE 2011.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.70|S\u00e1nchez in the PSOE campaign for the 2011 general election]]\nIn the [[2011 Spanish general election|general election of 2011]] which saw a heavy defeat for the Socialists, PSOE placed S\u00e1nchez 11th on the Proportional Representation list, while only electing 10 deputies. Having thus failed to win a seat, he returned to the [[Universidad Camilo Jos\u00e9 Cela|Camilo Jos\u00e9 Cela University]] to finish his [[Doctorate]] in Economics. He served as a consultant to a European consortium and as a university professor. He earned a [[PhD]] in Economics and Business from the [[Universidad Camilo Jos\u00e9 Cela|Camilo Jos\u00e9 Cela University]]. In 2018  S\u00e1nchez was accused  by ABC daily of plagiarism.<ref name=PSOE />\n\nIn January 2013, S\u00e1nchez returned to Congress, replacing [[Cristina Narbona]], who left her seat to enter the [[Nuclear Safety Council (Spain)|Nuclear Safety Council]]. In December 2013, after numerous Socialist leaders such as [[Elena Valenciano]], [[Trinidad Jim\u00e9nez]], [[Miguel Sebasti\u00e1n]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Blanco L\u00f3pez]] attended his new book release, his name began to be discussed as a prospective candidate for the party leadership. S\u00e1nchez officially launched his candidacy on 12 June 2014. He was elected as the Secretary-General on 13 July, after winning 49% of votes against his opponents [[Eduardo Madina]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Antonio P\u00e9rez Tapias]] (member of the Socialist Left platform).<ref name=\"PSOE\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thespainreport.com/9777/pedro-sanchez-voted-new-secretary-general-spanish-socialist-party-xx-vote/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=25 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016191139/https://www.thespainreport.com/9777/pedro-sanchez-voted-new-secretary-general-spanish-socialist-party-xx-vote/ |archivedate=16 October 2014 }}</ref> He was confirmed as Secretary-General after an Extraordinary Congress of the PSOE was held on 26\u201327 July that ratified the electoral result.<ref name=PSOE />\n\n==PSOE Secretary-General==\nRepresenting a platform based on political regeneration, S\u00e1nchez demanded constitutional reforms establishing [[federalism]] as the form of administrative organization of Spain to ensure that Catalonia would remain within the country; a new progressive fiscal policy; extending the welfare state to all citizens; joining [[labour union]]s again to strengthen economic recovery; and regaining the confidence of former Socialist voters disenchanted by the measures taken by Zapatero during his late term as Prime Minister amid an economic crisis. He also opposed the [[grand coalition]] model supported by the former Socialist Prime Minister [[Felipe Gonz\u00e1lez]], who championed the German system in case of political instability. S\u00e1nchez asked his European party caucus not to vote for the consensus candidate [[Jean-Claude Juncker]] of the [[European People's Party]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.euractiv.com/sections/eu-elections-2014/spanish-socialists-vote-against-juncker-canete-308462 |title=Spanish socialists to vote against Juncker, Ca\u00f1ete |last=Gotev |first=Georgi |date=16 September 2014 |access-date=8 January 2015 |work=[[Euractiv]]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Pedro-Sanchez-primarias-PSOE-Internacional EDIIMA20170522 0010 19.jpg|thumb|Pedro S\u00e1nchez, after winning the primary election for Secretary-General, singing ''[[The Internationale]]''.]]\n\nUpon taking office as PSOE's Secretary-General, S\u00e1nchez faced a political crisis after the formation of a new party, [[Podemos (Spanish political party)|Podemos]]. Approximately 25% of all PSOE supporters switched their loyalties to Podemos.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.europapress.es/nacional/noticia-45-votantes-iu-icv-2011-28-upyd-24-psoe-apuestan-ahora-podemos-20141105193223.html |title=\u00bfDe d\u00f3nde vienen los votos de Podemos? |language=Spanish |trans-title=Where do the votes of Podemos come from? |work=europa press |date=5 November 2014 |accessdate=29 December 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=D\u00edez |first=Anabel |url=http://politica.elpais.com/politica/2015/07/26/actualidad/1437937474_105154.html |title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez, en proceso |language=Spanish |trans-title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez, in process |work=El Pais |date=6 July 2015 |accessdate=29 December 2015 }}</ref> S\u00e1nchez's political agenda included reforming the constitution, establishing a federal model in Spain to replace the current devolution model,<ref>{{cite news |last=D\u00edez |first=Anabel |url=http://politica.elpais.com/politica/2014/11/09/actualidad/1415546589_008826.html |title=\"Ni fractura, ni independencia, una Espa\u00f1a federal para todos\" |language=Spanish |trans-title=\"No fracture, no independence, a federal Spain for all\" |work=El Pais |date=9 November 2014 |accessdate=29 December 2015 }}</ref> and further secularization of Spain's education system, including the removal of religion-affiliated public and private schools.<ref>{{cite news |last=SANZ |first=LUIS \u00c1NGEL |url=http://www.elmundo.es/espana/2015/10/19/5625237d46163f09298b460f.html |title=El PSOE eliminar\u00e1 la religi\u00f3n en colegios p\u00fablicos y privados |language=Spanish |trans-title=The PSOE to eliminate religion in all public and private schools |work=El Mundo(ES) |date=19 October 2015 |accessdate=29 December 2015 }}</ref> He named [[C\u00e9sar Luena]] as his second-in-command. On 21 June 2015, S\u00e1nchez was officially announced as the PSOE premiership candidate for the December 2015 general election. His party earned 90 seats, being second to rivals of Partido Popular (PP), who won the election with 123 representatives out of a parliament formed by 350. Since PP's leader did not stand officially for the premiership, following this S\u00e1nchez was requested by the King to form a coalition, but he was unable to obtain the support of a majority of representatives. This led to a further general election in June 2016, where he stood again as PSOE's candidate. Winning only 85 seats in a general election, he resigned in October 2016.\n\n===Leadership crisis===\n{{See also|2016 PSOE crisis}}\nAfter resigning as Secretary-General of the party, S\u00e1nchez made a tour aboard his car visiting base members in different parts of Spain.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/887cedda-699d-11e8-b6eb-4acfcfb08c11|work=[[Financial Times]]|title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez, a dogged politician who grabbed his chance|first1=Michael|last1=Stothard|date=8 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eleconomista.es/politica/noticias/9179988/06/18/Sanchez-el-politico-de-las-siete-vidas.html|newspaper=El Economista|language=es|last1=Zancajo|date=3 June 2018|title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez, el pol\u00edtico de las siete vidas|trans-title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez, the politician of the seven lives|first1=Silvia}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 May 2017, S\u00e1nchez was re-elected Secretary-General for the second time with 50.2% of the votes, over his competitors [[Susana D\u00edaz]] (39.94%) and [[Patxi L\u00f3pez]] (9.85%).<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/may/21/spanish-socialists-re-elect-pedro-sanchez-to-lead-party Spanish Socialists re-elect Pedro S\u00e1nchez to lead party] TheGuardian.com</ref>\n\nS\u00e1nchez opposed the [[2017 Catalan independence referendum|Catalan independence referendum]] and supported the [[Mariano Rajoy|Rajoy]] government's decision to dismiss the [[Generalitat de Catalunya|Catalan government]] and impose direct rule on [[Catalonia]] in October 2017.<ref>{{cite news |title=Spain's Pedro S\u00e1nchez forced to confront Catalonia crisis |url=https://www.ft.com/content/36229ab2-670e-11e8-b6eb-4acfcfb08c11 |newspaper=[[Financial Times]] |date=4 June 2018 |access-date=3 September 2018 |first=Michael |last=Stothard |agency=Nikkei Company}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Catalan nationalists back in power, target secession in challenge to Sanchez |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-spain-politics-catalonia/nationalists-back-in-power-in-catalonia-say-target-independence-idUSKCN1IY0B8 |work=[[Reuters]] |date=2 June 2018 |access-date=3 September 2018 |first=Jes\u00fas |last=Aguado |first2=Ingrid |last2=Melander}}</ref>\n\n==Prime Minister of Spain==\n[[File:Mariano Rajoy felicita al nuevo presidente del Gobierno Pedro S\u00e1nchez (2018-06-01).jpg|thumb|right|Rajoy congratulates S\u00e1nchez on his successful no-confidence motion.|alt=]]\n{{See also|2018 vote of no confidence in the government of Mariano Rajoy}}\nIn May 2018, after verdicts were announced in the [[Gurtel case|G\u00fcrtel trial]], PSOE filed a successful no-confidence motion against Mariano Rajoy.<ref name=\"Gurtel\">{{Cite news |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2018/05/25/inenglish/1527237249_668560.html |title=Socialist party chief calls for transitional government |last=Garcia |first=Elsa |date=25 April 2018 |access-date=1 June 2018 |newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |location=Madrid}}</ref> Per the Constitution, the no-confidence motion proposed S\u00e1nchez as replacement Prime Minister. With the passage of the no-confidence motion, S\u00e1nchez was automatically deemed to have the confidence of the Congress of Deputies and thus ascended as Prime Minister on 1 June 2018.\n\nHe was sworn in by King Felipe VI on 2 June.<ref>{{cite news |title=Who is Spain's new prime minister Pedro Sanchez? |url=http://www.dw.com/en/who-is-spains-new-prime-minister-pedro-sanchez/a-44041431 |accessdate=1 June 2018 |work=Reuters, AFP |publisher=DW |date=1 June 2018}}</ref> S\u00e1nchez said he planned to form a government that would eventually dissolve the [[Cortes Generales]] and call for a general election, but he did not specify when he would do it<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.es/espana/abci-sanchez-llega-poder-sin-concretar-cuando-convocara-elecciones-201806010320_noticia.html |title=S\u00e1nchez llega al poder sin concretar cu\u00e1ndo convocar\u00e1 las elecciones |last=Ruiz de Almir\u00f3n |first=Victor |date=1 June 2018 |access-date=9 July 2018 |newspaper=[[ABC (Spain)|ABC]] |language=es}}</ref> while also saying that before calling for an election he intended take a series of measures like increasing unemployment benefits and proposing a law of equal pay between the sexes.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.eleconomista.es/economia/noticias/9179627/06/18/Sanchez-prioriza-la-agenda-social-y-renuncia-a-realizar-reformas-en-profundidad.html |title=S\u00e1nchez prioriza la agenda social y renuncia a realizar reformas en profundidad |last=Zancajo |first=Silvia |date=1 June 2018 |access-date=9 July 2018 |newspaper=[[El Economista (Spain)|El Economista]] |language=es |publisher=Editorial Ecoprensa, [[Sociedad An\u00f3nima|S.A.]]}}</ref> However, he also said he would uphold the 2018 budget approved by the Rajoy government, a condition the [[Basque Nationalist Party]] imposed to vote for the motion of no-confidence.<ref name=\"LV\">{{cite news |url=http://www.lavanguardia.com/politica/20180531/443963185308/pedro-sanchez-rajoy-dimita-mocion-de-censura.html |title=S\u00e1nchez ofrece di\u00e1logo a Catalunya y mantener los presupuestos al PNV |last=Merino |first=Juan Carlos |date=31 May 2018 |access-date=9 July 2018 |newspaper=[[La Vanguardia]] |language=es}}</ref>\n\n===Inauguration===\n{{See also|S\u00e1nchez government}}[[File:Primer Gobierno de Pedro S\u00e1nchez (2018-06).jpg|thumb|right|S\u00e1nchez and his new cabinet at [[La Moncloa]] in June 2018]]S\u00e1nchez took office on 2 June 2018 in the presence of former Prime Minister Rajoy, [[President of the Congress of Deputies|President of the Congress]] [[Ana Pastor Juli\u00e1n|Ana Pastor]], as well as [[King Felipe VI]].<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.boe.es/boe/dias/2018/06/02/pdfs/BOE-A-2018-7400.pdf |title=Real Decreto 354/2018, de 1 de junio, por el que se nombra Presidente del Gobierno a don Pedro S\u00e1nchez P\u00e9rez-Castej\u00f3n |work=[[Bolet\u00edn Oficial del Estado]] |issue=134 |date=2 June 2018 |access-date=9 July 2018 |page=257657 |format=PDF |last=Pastor Juli\u00e1n |first=Ana Mar\u00eda |author-link=Ana Mar\u00eda Pastor Juli\u00e1n |editor-last=R. |editor-first=Felipe |editor-link=Felipe VI of Spain |issn=0212-033X}}</ref> Spanish media noted that while S\u00e1nchez was swearing his oath of office on the [[Spanish Constitution]], no [[Bible]] nor [[crucifix]] were on display, for the first time in modern Spanish history due to S\u00e1nchez's atheism.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.eldiario.es/politica/Pedro-Sanchez-presidente-presencia-Rajoy_0_777972264.html |title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez promete su cargo de presidente ante el rey y Rajoy, sin crucifijo ni Biblia |last=Aduriz |first=\u00cd\u00f1igo |date=2 June 2018 |access-date=9 July 2018 |newspaper=[[El Diario (Spain)|El Diario]] |language=es}}</ref> After being sworn in, S\u00e1nchez announced that he would only propose measures that had considerable parliamentary support, and reaffirmed the government's compliance with the EU deficit requirements.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://politica.elpais.com/politica/2018/06/01/actualidad/1527859489_043487.html |title=El presidente solo propondr\u00e1 medidas con amplio apoyo |last=D\u00edez |first=Anabel |last2=Garc\u00eda de Blas |first2=Elsa |date=3 June 2018 |access-date=9 July 2018 |newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |language=es |location=Madrid}}</ref>\n\nThe 17 ministers of his new cabinet took office on 7 June 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rtve.es/noticias/20180607/17-nuevos-ministros-pedro-sanchez-prometen-cargos-ante-rey/1746583.shtml|publisher=[[RTVE]]|title=Gobierno de Pedro S\u00e1nchez Las \"ministras y ministros\" de Pedro S\u00e1nchez arrancan el gobierno de la \"igualdad\", el \"di\u00e1logo\" y la \"diversidad\"|date=7 June 2018}}</ref> S\u00e1nchez formed a cabinet with 11 of the 18 ministerial positions of the [[Council of Ministers (Spain)|Council]] being held by women.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jun/06/new-spanish-pm-appoints-astronaut-pedro-duque-science-minister|title=Spanish PM appoints 11 women and six men to new cabinet|last=Jones|first=Sam|date=6 June 2018|work=The Guardian|access-date=20 March 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n=== European Union ===\n[[File:Pedro S\u00e1nchez conferencia \"Proteger el ideal de Europa\" 02.jpg|right|thumb|S\u00e1nchez during his speech at the event organized by the Spanish Federal Council of the European Movement on 19 March 2019.]]\n\nSince his arrival to power he has been strongly [[pro-Europeanism|pro-European]]. This is evidenced by changes including the renaming of the Foreign Ministry to the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs, European Union and Cooperation (Spain)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs, European Union and Cooperation]], and reverting the Secretary of State for European Affairs back to its original name, the [[Secretary of State for the European Union]]. He appointed [[Josep Borrell]], former [[President of the European Parliament]], as Foreign Minister, and [[Nadia Calvi\u00f1o]] as [[Ministry of Economy (Spain)|Minister of Economy]], who served as [[Directorate-General for Budget|Director-General for the EU Budget]], and [[Secretary-General of the European Economic and Social Committee]] [[Luis Planas]] as [[Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food (Spain)|Minister of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/world/europe/spains-new-pm-pedro-sanchez-unveils-pro-eu-government-dominated-by-women|title=Spain's new PM Pedro Sanchez unveils pro-EU government dominated by women|last=hermesauto|date=7 June 2018|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=20 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe also took a more active role in the international sphere, especially in the European Union, saying that \"Spain has to claim its role\" and declaring himself \"a militant pro-European\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/pedro-sanchez-sets-sights-on-brussels-spain-eu/|title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez sets sights on Brussels|date=21 November 2018|website=POLITICO|access-date=20 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 January 2019, in a speech before the [[European Parliament]], he said that the EU should be protected and turned into a global actor, and that a more social Europe is needed, with a strong monetary union.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/eu-elections-2019/news/spanish-pm-if-europe-is-to-protect-us-we-need-to-protect-europe/|title=Spanish PM: If Europe protects us, we need to protect Europe|last=Rios|first=Beatriz|date=17 January 2019|website=euractiv.com|language=en-GB|access-date=20 March 2019}}</ref> He stated in a speech in March 2019 adding that the enemies of Europe are inside of the European Union.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eldiario.es/politica/Sanchez-advierte-enemigos-Europa-fuerzas_0_879462938.html|title=S\u00e1nchez advierte de que los \"enemigos\" de Europa est\u00e1n \"dentro\" y llama a votar contra las fuerzas \"unidas por sus odios\"|last=Castro|first=Irene|website=eldiario.es|language=es|access-date=20 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration===\n[[File:2018-06-26, Pedro S\u00e1nchez se re\u00fane con Angela Merkel 4.jpg|thumb|S\u00e1nchez with German Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]], 26 June 2018]]\nIn June 2018, the ship ''[[Aquarius (NGO ship)|Aquarius]]'' carrying 629 migrants that were [[European migrant crisis|rescued near Libya]] was denied entry to the Sicilian port by Italy's new Interior Minister [[Matteo Salvini]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-44432056 |title=Italy's Matteo Salvini shuts ports to migrant rescue ship |date=11 June 2018 |access-date=9 July 2018 |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/06/spain-offers-aquarius-ship-carrying-600-refugees-180611133533958.html |title=Spain offers to take in Aquarius ship carrying over 600 refugees |date=11 June 2018 |access-date=9 July 2018 |work=[[Al Jazeera]] |publisher=[[Al Jazeera Media Network]]}}</ref> The Spanish government offered the ''Aquarius'' the chance to dock in the secure port of Valencia, Spain and the Italian navy offered full assistance and a marine escort for the trip.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2018/06/12/world/social-issues-world/boat-600-rescued-migrants-lies-mediterranean-amid-italy-malta-standoff/#.Wx8WTkiFNaQ |title=Boat with over 600 rescued migrants lies to in Mediterranean amid Italy-Malta standoff |date=12 June 2018 |access-date=9 July 2018 |newspaper=[[Japan Times]] |author=AP |author-link=Associated Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dw.com/en/spain-will-accept-migrant-ship-aquarius-after-italy-and-malta-refuse-entry/a-44150793 |title=Spain will accept migrant ship Aquarius after Italy and Malta refuse entry |date=11 June 2018 |access-date=9 July 2018 |work=[[Deutsche Welle]]}}</ref> On 4 July 2018, the Spanish government accepted another NGO vessel, in this case a Spanish NGO called [[Proactiva Open Arms|Open Arms]] carrying 60 migrants after Italy rejected again open a port for the ship.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2018/07/04/inenglish/1530690012_839181.html |title=Second migrant ship arrives in Spain after being rejected by Italy, Malta |last=Mart\u00edn |first=Mar\u00eda |date=4 July 2018 |newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |access-date=19 July 2018 |last2=L\u00f3pez-Fonseca |first2=\u00d3scar |issn=1134-6582 |last3=Garc\u00eda |first3=Jes\u00fas |publisher=Prisa}}</ref> The same happened two weeks later.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.euronews.com/2018/07/19/-open-arms-migrant-rescue-boat-heads-for-spain-amid-row-with-italy |title='Open Arms' migrant rescue boat heads for Spain amid row with Italy |date=19 July 2018 |work=[[Euronews]] |access-date=19 July 2018 |first=Alasdair |last=Sandford}}</ref>\n\n<!--[[File:Pedro S\u00e1nchez asiste a la Cumbre del G-22 en Buenos Aires 03.jpg|thumb|S\u00e1nchez with French President [[Emmanuel Macron]] and President of the European Commission [[Jean-Claude Juncker]] at the G20 Summit in Buenos Aires, 30 November 2018]]-->\nThe Prime Minister considered the immigration matter as a European matter and showed its solidarity with the German Government by accepting an agreement between Germany, Greece and Spain so this last two agreed to take care of part of the immigrants that live in Germany.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/spain-greece-and-germany-seal-migrant-swap-deal/ |title=Spain, Greece and Germany seal migrant swap deal |date=30 June 2018 |work=[[Politico]] |access-date=19 July 2018 |first=Fiona |last=Maxwell |first2=Ryan |last2=Heath}}</ref> \"Unilateralism not the answer to migrant crisis\", he said in an interview in a clear reference to the initiative of the Italian Government to close the ports while also stating: \"As effective as the inflammatory rhetoric from some Italian leaders may be in electoral terms, from the point of view of responding effectively to a humanitarian crisis like the one we're seeing in the Mediterranean and on the Italian coast, it's not the answer\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/jun/28/unilateralism-not-the-answer-to-migrant-crisis-says-spains-pm |title=Unilateralism not the answer to migrant crisis, says Spain's PM |last=Jones |first=Sam |date=28 June 2018 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=19 July 2018 |publisher=[[Guardian News and Media Limited]]}}</ref>\n\n===Gibraltar===\nS\u00e1nchez has called for [[Status of Gibraltar|joint U.K.-Spanish sovereignty]] over British-controlled [[Gibraltar]], a [[British Overseas Territories|British Overseas Territory]] in the south of the Iberian peninsula.<ref>{{cite news |title=Spain revives call for shared control over Gibraltar after Brexit |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-spain/spain-revives-call-for-shared-control-over-gibraltar-after-brexit-idUSKCN1NU0GW |agency=Reuters |date=25 November 2018}}</ref> He publicly warned that Spain will \"veto\" [[Brexit deal]] over the issue of Gibraltar.<ref>{{cite news |title=Spain PM Pedro Sanchez threatens Brexit deal over Gibraltar |url=https://www.thelocal.es/20181120/spain-pm-pedro-sanchez-threatens-brexit-deal-over-gibraltar |work=The Local |date=20 November 2018}}</ref> In November 2018, S\u00e1nchez said that \"With Brexit we all lose, especially the United Kingdom, but when it comes to Gibraltar, Spain wins.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Spanish PM: \"With Brexit we all lose, but on Gibraltar, Spain wins\" |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2018/11/26/inenglish/1543222571_685671.html |work=El Pa\u00eds |date=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Exhumation of Franco===\nOn 18 June 2018, S\u00e1nchez' government announced its intention to remove the remains of former dictator [[Francisco Franco]] from the ''[[Valle de los Ca\u00eddos]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2018/06/18/inenglish/1529307821_499020.html |title=Removal of Franco's remains from Valley of the Fallen one step closer |first=Natalia |last=Junquera |date=18 June 2018 |access-date=3 September 2018 |location=Madrid |language=es |newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |publisher=Prisa}}</ref> On 29 June 2018, the [[Archdiocese of Madrid]] warned the Spanish government against any plans to exhume the remains of Franco without first obtaining agreement from interested parties and formally stated it is against any move of Franco's remains without the consent of his family and before consultation with the Catholic Church. In addition, in its statement the Archdiocese of Madrid re-affirmed its position that although the Valle de los Ca\u00eddos is officially a national monument, the Catholic Church must be consulted on burial-related matters under agreements between the Spanish state and the Vatican.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.catholicherald.co.uk/news/2018/07/01/spanish-church-expresses-concern-at-plan-to-exhume-francos-remains/ |title=Spanish Church expresses concern at plan to exhume Franco's remains |magazine=[[Catholic Herald]] |date=1 July 2018 |publisher=Interconnect/it |access-date=24 August 2018}}</ref> The announcement of the Archdiocese of Madrid was made after Pedro S\u00e1nchez confirmed that it was his intention to remove the remains of Franco from the Valle de los Ca\u00eddos by the end of July.<ref>{{cite news |date=27 June 2018 |url=http://www.elmundo.es/espana/2018/06/27/5b337b48e2704ea9188b461a.html |title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez quiere sacar los restos de Franco del Valle de los Ca\u00eddos en el mes de julio |newspaper=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]] |language=es |access-date=2 September 2018 |first=Luis \u00c1ngel |last=Sanz |location=Madrid |publisher=[[Unidad Editorial]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thebostonpilot.com/article.asp?ID=182712 |title=Spanish church warns on exhumation of dictator |work=The Boston Pilot |access-date=24 August 2018 |first=Jonathan |last=Luxmoore |date=29 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 August 2018, S\u00e1nchez's cabinet approved a decree that modifies two aspects of the 2007 Historical Memory Law to allow the exhumation of Franco's remains from the Valle de los Ca\u00eddos. The decree, to become law, must be passed by a vote of the Congress of Deputies. The conservative [[People's Party (Spain)|People's Party]] (PP) and the centre-right party [[Citizens (Spanish political party)|Ciudadanos]] (Cs) have announced they will not support the decree. The PP further stated it will appeal the measure to the Constitutional Court arguing that using a decree to change the Historical Memory Law is not valid because the proposed modifications to the Historical Memory Law do not respond to a situation of urgent need. Deputy Prime Minister Carmen Calvo stated the decree law requires the exhumation of the remains of Franco to take place between 30 days and 12 months of passage by the Congress of Deputies.<ref>{{cite news |date=24 August 2018 |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2018/08/24/inenglish/1535097265_662248.html |title=Spanish Cabinet approves decree to exhume Franco's remains |newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |access-date=2 September 2018 |first=Elsa |last=Garc\u00eda de Blas |language=es |publisher=Prisa |location=Madrid}}</ref> The [[Congress of Deputies]] voted in favor of the exhumation on 13 September 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-spain-politics-franco/spanish-parliament-votes-to-exhume-remains-of-dictator-franco-idUSKCN1LT2C9?ref=hvper.com|title=Spanish parliament votes to exhume remains of dictator Franco|work=[[Reuters]]|date=13 September 2018|accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref> After a year of legal battles with Franco's descendants, the exhumation took place on 24 October 2019, and Franco was reburied at [[Mingorrubio Cemetery]] in [[El Pardo]] with his wife [[Carmen Polo, 1st Lady of Meir\u00e1s|Carmen Polo]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/23/francos-remains-to-finally-leave-spains-valley-of-the-fallen The Guardian]</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, the [[Mossos d'Esquadra]] reported the arrest of a [[Terrassa]] resident who was angry with the plans to exhume Franco and having an arsenal of 16 weapons back home{{refn|group=n.|Including a [[CETME rifle|CETME]] assault rifle, a [[Skorpion vz. 61]] and four long-range rifles able to hit a target located 1,500 m away from the sniper.<ref name=elperiodico /> The suspect also carried two guns in his car, one of them modified.<ref name=elperiodico />}} allegedly planned to kill S\u00e1nchez in order to finish, in his own words, with that \"shitty red\".<ref name=elperiodico>{{cite journal|url=https://www.elperiodico.com/es/politica/20181108/francotirador-pedro-sanchez-7135125|journal=[[El Peri\u00f3dico de Catalu\u00f1a|El Peri\u00f3dico]]|date=8 November 2018|title=Los Mossos detienen a un tirador que quer\u00eda matar a Pedro S\u00e1nchez}}</ref>\n\n===Catalan separatism===\nS\u00e1nchez said he would \"reinstate dialogue\" with the [[Catalan independence movement]].<ref name=\"LV\"/> In order to do so, the central government and the regional government reactivated intergovernmental commissions, a series of bodies composed by representatives of both governments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lavanguardia.com/politica/20180703/45608162666/govern-reactiva-comisiones-bilaterales-mixtas-generalitat-estado.html|title=El Govern reactiva las comisiones bilaterales y mixtas Generalitat-Estado|date=3 July 2018|website=La Vanguardia|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref> Although there was some progress in the economic field, these commissions were paralyzed by the [[Catalonia]] [[Executive Council of Catalonia|regional government]]'s demand to speak about a [[self-determination]] [[referendum]], something that the central government rejected and in February 2019 the central government considered the relations between the two governments broken.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eldiario.es/politica/Gobierno-asegura-independentistas-rechazado-estatales_0_865813920.html|title=El Gobierno da por rotas las negociaciones con los independentistas y se centrar\u00e1 en defender los presupuestos|website=eldiario.es|language=es|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref> In December 2018, the ''[[Financial Times|FT]]'' reported that S\u00e1nchez \"has warned Catalonia's government that he could deploy national police to the region, as tension flares up again between Madrid and Catalan separatists a year after a failed secession attempt\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Spanish prime minister warns Catalonia as tensions rise |url=https://www.ft.com/content/92e0f1b0-fe15-11e8-aebf-99e208d3e521 |work=Financial Times |date=12 December 2018}}</ref> The distance between the two governments became clear when the parliamentary opposition\u2014among which was Catalan separatism\u2014rejected the government's budget.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/pedro-sanchez-spains-parliament-rejects-2019-budget-proposal/|title=Spain's parliament rejects 2019 budget proposal|date=13 February 2019|website=POLITICO|access-date=3 March 2019}}</ref> After this, the Prime Minister called a snap election.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-47251125|title=Spain PM sets snap election for April|date=15 February 2019|access-date=3 March 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===Saudi Arabia===\nIn September 2018, Defense Minister [[Margarita Robles]] cancelled sales of [[laser-guided bomb]]s to [[Saudi Arabia]] over concerns relating to the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen]]. Overruling Robles, S\u00e1nchez ordered the sale to proceed<ref>{{cite news |title=Spain not stopping arms sales to Saudi Arabia over Khashoggi killing |url = https://elpais.com/elpais/2018/10/22/inenglish/1540192063_943808.html |work = El Pais |date=22 October 2018}}</ref> because he had guaranteed [[President of Andalusia]] [[Susana D\u00edaz]] help to protect jobs in the shipyards of the [[Bay of C\u00e1diz]], highly dependent on the \u20ac1.813 billion contract with Saudi Arabia to deliver five [[corvettes]].<ref>{{Cite journal|date=24 October 2018|url=https://www.elmundo.es/espana/2018/10/24/5bcf6829e5fdeaf16b8b4644.html|journal=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez evita una crisis con Arabia Saud\u00ed por el coste electoral en Andaluc\u00eda|first=Luis \u00c1ngel|last=Sanz|first2=Marisa|last2=Cruz|first3=Susana|last3=Villaverde}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|publisher=[[RTVE]]|title=El Gobierno garantiza el contrato de Arabia Saud\u00ed con Navantia, cuyos trabajadores han cortado la A-4|date=7 September 2018|url=http://www.rtve.es/noticias/20180907/trabajadores-navantia-cortan-4-temor-se-cancele-contrato-arabia-saudi/1793562.shtml}}</ref> In response to the killing of Saudi dissident journalist [[Jamal Khashoggi]] in October 2018, S\u00e1nchez defended the decision to continue arms sales to Saudi Arabia and insisted on his government's \"responsibility\" to protect jobs in the [[arms industry]].<ref>{{cite news |title=How Saudis are getting away with Khashoggi murder |url=https://www.news.com.au/world/middle-east/how-saudis-are-getting-away-with-khashoggi-murder/news-story/4632ff5a196d9013a2b1b8e3e7139175 |work=[[News.com.au]] |date=28 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Need to keep jobs grounds for continuation of arms sales to Saudi Arabia, argues Spanish president |url=http://www.catalannews.com/politics/item/need-to-keep-jobs-grounds-for-continuation-of-arms-sales-to-saudi-arabia-argues-spanish-president |work=Catalan News |date=24 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Snap election and deadlock===\n{{see also|April 2019 Spanish general election}}\n[[File:Pedro S\u00e1nchez convoca elecciones 2019 02.jpg|thumb|Prime Minister S\u00e1nchez announcing a [[snap election]] for 28 April 2019.|alt=|left]]\nAfter the rejection of his [[General State Budget|budget]], S\u00e1nchez called an early [[April 2019 Spanish general election|general election]] for 28 April 2019, making a television announcement in which he declared that \"between doing nothing and continuing with the [former] budget and calling on Spaniards to have their say, I chose the second. Spain needs to keep advancing, progressing with tolerance, respect, moderation and common sense\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/02/15/spanish-prime-minister-calls-snap-election-after-budget-fails-to-pass.html|title=Spanish prime minister calls snap election after budget fails to pass|last=Reid|first=David|date=15 February 2019|publisher=CNBC|accessdate=3 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe PSOE won the election, obtaining 29% of the vote which translated into 123 seats in the Congress of Deputies, well over the 85 seats and 23% share of the vote the party obtained in the [[2016 Spanish general election|2016 election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/apr/29/spanish-socialists-win-is-latest-sign-of-europes-centre-left-upturn|title=Spanish socialists' win is latest sign of Europe's centre-left upturn|last=correspondent|first=Jon Henley European affairs|date=29 April 2019|work=The Guardian|accessdate=30 April 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> PSOE also won a majority in the [[Senate of Spain|Senate]]. Whilst the PSOE were 53 seats short of the 176 seats needed for an outright majority in the Congress of Deputies, a three-way split in the centre-right vote assured that it was the only party that could realistically form a government.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://elpais.com/politica/2019/04/28/actualidad/1556466636_096682.html|title=El PSOE gana las elecciones pero necesitar\u00e1 pactar y el PP sufre una debacle hist\u00f3rica|date=28 April 2019|work=El Pa\u00eds|language=Spanish|accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.elconfidencial.com/elecciones-generales/2019-04-29/sanchez-gana-se-hunde-casado-y-el-gobierno-dependera-de-junqueras-o-rivera_1970690/|title=S\u00e1nchez gana, se hunde Casado y Rivera se postula como l\u00edder de la oposici\u00f3n|date=28 April 2019|work=El Confidencial|language=Spanish|accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.eldiario.es/politica/PP-derrota-historica-millones-Cs_0_893461398.html|title=El PP sufre una derrota hist\u00f3rica, pierde 3,7 millones de votos y Cs se queda cerca del sorpaso|date=28 April 2019|work=eldiario.es|language=Spanish|accessdate=30 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 June 2019, King Felipe VI, having previously held prospective meetings with the spokespeople of the political groups with representation in the new Congress of Deputies, formally proposed S\u00e1nchez as prospective Prime Minister. S\u00e1nchez accepted the task of trying to form a government \"with honor and responsibility\".<ref>{{Cite web|work=[[La Raz\u00f3n (Madrid)|La Raz\u00f3n]]|title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez asume el encargo del Rey de formar Gobierno \"con honor y responsabilidad\"|url=https://www.larazon.es/espana/el-rey-propone-a-pedro-sanchez-como-candidato-a-la-presidencia-del-gobierno-GO23694046|date=6 June 2019}}</ref> Several weeks of negotiations with [[Podemos (Spanish political party)|Podemos]] ended in an agreement that S\u00e1nchez would appoint several Podemos members to the [[Cabinet of Spain|Cabinet]], although not the party's leader [[Pablo Iglesias Turri\u00f3n|Pablo Iglesias]].<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/21/spain-socialist-government-sanchez-iglesias-catalonia</ref> But in the final voting session, Podemos rejected the agreement and led S\u00e1nchez to try a second chance to be inaugurated in September.\n\n===Second election and coalition===\n{{See also|S\u00e1nchez II Government}}[[File:(S\u00e1nchez e Iglesias) Declaraci\u00f3n conjunta de Pablo Iglesias y Pedro S\u00e1nchez.jpg|thumb|right|S\u00e1nchez and Iglesias announcing a tentative agreement for a \"progressive\" government ([[Palacio de las Cortes]], 12 November 2019).]]\nFollowing the results of the [[November 2019 Spanish general election]], on 12 November 2019 Pedro S\u00e1nchez and Iglesias announced a preliminary agreement between PSOE and Unidas Podemos to rule together creating the first [[coalition government]] of the Spanish democracy, for all purposes a minority coalition as it did not enjoy a qualified majority at the Lower House, thus needing further support or abstention from other parliamentary forces in order to get through.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.publico.es/politica/sanchez-e-iglesias-pactan-primer-gobierno-coalicion-estructura.html |title=S\u00e1nchez e Iglesias pactan un Gobierno de coalici\u00f3n, pero la estructura se conocer\u00e1 tras la investidura |first=Manuel |last=S\u00e1nchez |first2=Beatriz |last2=Asuar |date=12 November 2019 |access-date=12 November 2019 |newspaper=[[P\u00fablico (Spain)|P\u00fablico]] |language=es |publisher=Display Connectors, SL.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.elespanol.com/espana/20191112/sanchez-negocia-iglesias-gobierno-quitaria-sueno-espanoles/443956124_0.html |title=S\u00e1nchez pacta con Iglesias el Gobierno con el que \"no dormir\u00eda\" ni \u00e9l \"ni el 95% de espa\u00f1oles\" |date=12 November 2019 |access-date=12 November 2019 |first=Joana |last=Rel |newspaper=[[El Espa\u00f1ol]] |language=es |publisher=El Le\u00f3n de El Espa\u00f1ol Publicaciones S.A.}}</ref> On 7 January 2020, Pedro S\u00e1nchez earned a second mandate as Prime Minister after receiving a plurality of votes in the second round vote of his investiture at the Congress of Deputies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.20minutos.es/noticia/4107229/0/pedro-sanchez-investido-presidente/|title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez logra ser investido presidente con 167 votos a favor y 165 en contra|last=20minutos|date=7 January 2020|website=www.20minutos.es - \u00daltimas Noticias|language=es|access-date=7 January 2020}}</ref> He was then once again sworn in as Prime Minister by King Felipe on 8 January.<ref>https://www.thelocal.es/20200108/pedro-sanchez-is-sworn-in-as-head-of-spains-first-coalition-government-since-tr</ref><ref>https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/01/08/world/europe/ap-eu-spain-politics.html</ref> Soon after, S\u00e1nchez proceeded to form a new cabinet with 22 ministers and 4 vice-presidencies, who assumed office on 13 January.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3856055|title=Spain's Sanchez unveils Cabinet, pledges 'uni...|website=Taiwan News|access-date=14 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.20minutos.es/noticia/4113371/0/ministros-pedro-sanchez-prometen-cargos-ante-rey-felipe-vi/|title=As\u00ed ha sido la toma de posesi\u00f3n de los ministros: f\u00f3rmula de promesa, sin crucifijo, \"ministros y ministras\"...|last=20minutos|date=13 January 2020|website=www.20minutos.es - \u00daltimas Noticias|language=es|access-date=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Coronavirus pandemic===\n{{main article|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Spain}}\nOn 13 March 2020, S\u00e1nchez announced a declaration of the constitutional state of alarm in the nation for a period of 15 days, to become effective the following day after the approval of the Council of Ministers, becoming the second time in democratic history and the first time with this magnitude.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpais.com/espana/2020-03-13/el-gobierno-debate-decretar-el-estado-de-alarma.html|title=S\u00e1nche decreta el estado de alarma durante 15 d\u00edas|last=Blas|first=Carlos E. Cu\u00e9, Claudi P\u00e9rez, Elsa Garc\u00eda de|date=2020-03-13|website=EL PA\u00cdS|language=es|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> The following day imposed a [[2020 Spain coronavirus lockdown|nationwide lockdown]], banning all trips that were not force majeure and announced it may intervene in companies to guarantee supplies.<ref>https://nationalpost.com/pmn/health-pmn/spain-to-impose-nationwide-lockdown-el-mundo</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://elpais.com/espana/2020-03-14/el-gobierno-prohibe-todos-los-viajes-que-no-sean-de-fuerza-mayor.html|title=El Gobierno proh\u00edbe todos los viajes que no sean de fuerza mayor|last=Cu\u00e9|first=Carlos E.|date=2020-03-14|website=EL PA\u00cdS|language=es|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\n== Ideology ==\nS\u00e1nchez ran in the 2014 PSOE primary election under what has been described as a [[centrist]] and [[social liberal]] profile, later switching to the left in his successful 2017 bid to return to the PSOE leadership in which he stood for a refoundation of [[social democracy]] in order to transition to a \"post-capitalist society\", ending with \"neoliberal capitalism\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letraslibres.com/espana-mexico/politica/pedro-sanchez-victoria-en-victoria-hasta-la-derrota|title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez: De victoria en victoria hasta la derrota|website=Letras Libres|language=es|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.diariosur.es/nacional/201705/22/pedro-sanchez-fenix-camaleonico-20170522011859-v.html|title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez, el f\u00e9nix camale\u00f3nico|date=22 May 2017|website=Diario Sur|language=es|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eldiario.es/politica/Postcapitalismo-militancia-izquierda-Pedro-Sanchez_0_614539290.html|title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez gira a la izquierda y elige al neoliberalismo como gran enemigo del PSOE|website=Eldiario.es|language=es|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letraslibres.com/espana-mexico/politica/el-psoe-y-la-fatiga-democratica|title=El PSOE y la fatiga democr\u00e1tica|website=Letras Libres|language=es|accessdate=14 January 2020}}</ref> A key personal idea posed in his 2019 ''Manual de Resistencia'' book is the indissoluble link between \"social democracy\" and \"Europe\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://elpais.com/politica/2019/02/20/actualidad/1550693890_133147.html|title=La ideolog\u00eda de Pedro S\u00e1nchez|last=Estefan\u00eda|first=Joaqu\u00edn|date=21 February 2019|work=El Pa\u00eds|accessdate=14 January 2020|language=es|issn=1134-6582}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nS\u00e1nchez married Mar\u00eda Bego\u00f1a G\u00f3mez Fern\u00e1ndez in 2006 and they have two daughters, Ainhoa and Carlota. The civil wedding was officiated by [[Trinidad Jim\u00e9nez]]. Aside from Spanish, S\u00e1nchez speaks fluent English and French.<ref>{{cite web |title=A Conversation with Pedro S\u00e1nchez |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G-XqGH4atTc |website=YouTube |publisher=Council on Foreign Relations |accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"abc\">{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.es/espana/20140531/abci-pedro-sanchez-psoe-desconocido-201405301642.html |title=El ascenso de Pedro S\u00e1nchez: de diputado \"desconocido\" a secretario general del PSOE |language=Spanish |trans-title=The rise of Pedro S\u00e1nchez: from \"unknown\" deputy to general secretary of the PSOE |work=ABC |date=13 July 2014 |accessdate=27 December 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"congreso\">{{cite web|url=http://www.congreso.es/portal/page/portal/Congreso/Congreso/Diputados/BusqForm?_piref73_1333155_73_1333154_1333154.next_page=/wc/fichaDiputado&idDiputado=381|title=X Legislatura (2011-Actualidad)S\u00e1nchez P\u00e9rez-Castej\u00f3n, Pedro|author=[[Congress of Deputies (Spain)]]}}</ref> He is the first prime minister who is an outspoken [[atheist]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.elplural.com/2014/09/25/pedro-sanchez-primer-aspirante-a-la-moncloa-que-se-declara-abiertamente-ateo/ |title=Pedro S\u00e1nchez, primer aspirante a La Moncloa que se declara abiertamente \"ateo\" |publisher=El Plural |date=24 September 2014 |accessdate=2 March 2016 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral history ==\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|+ Electoral history of Pedro S\u00e1nchez\n! scope=\"col\"| Election\n! scope=\"col\"| List\n! scope=\"col\"| Constituency\n! scope=\"col\"| List position\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n|-\n| [[2003 Madrid City Council election]]\n| [[Spanish Socialist Worker's Party|PSOE]]\n| align=center | {{ndash}}\n| 24th (out of 55)\n| ''Not elected''{{refn|group=lower-alpha|He became city councillor in 2004 replacing Elena Arnedo.}}\n|-\n| [[2007 Madrid City Council election]]\n| PSOE\n| align=center | {{ndash}}\n| 15th (out of 57)\n| ''Elected''\n|-\n| [[2008 Spanish general election]]\n| PSOE\n| align=center | [[Madrid (Congress of Deputies constituency)|Madrid]]\n| 21st (out of 35)\n| ''Not elected''{{refn|group=lower-alpha|He became MP in 2009, replacing [[Pedro Solbes]].}}\n|-\n| [[2011 Spanish general election]]\n| PSOE\n| align=center | [[Madrid (Congress of Deputies constituency)|Madrid]]\n| 11th (out of 36)\n| ''Not elected''{{refn|group=lower-alpha|He became MP in 2013, replacing [[Cristina Narbona]].}}\n|-\n| [[2015 Spanish general election]]\n| PSOE\n| align=center | [[Madrid (Congress of Deputies constituency)|Madrid]]\n| 1st (out of 36)\n| ''Elected''\n|-\n| [[2016 Spanish general election]]\n| PSOE\n| align=center | [[Madrid (Congress of Deputies constituency)|Madrid]]\n| 1st (out of 36)\n| ''Elected''\n|-\n| [[April 2019 Spanish general election|April 2019 Spanish general election]]\n| PSOE\n| align=center | [[Madrid (Congress of Deputies constituency)|Madrid]]\n| 1st (out of 37)\n| ''Elected''\n|-\n| [[November 2019 Spanish general election|November 2019 Spanish general election]]\n| PSOE\n| align=center | [[Madrid (Congress of Deputies constituency)|Madrid]]\n| 1st (out of 37)\n| ''Elected''\n|-\n| colspan = 5 | {{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n|}\n</center>\n\n== Distinctions ==\n* Medal of Salvador Allende (28 August 2018).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://m.cooperativa.cl/noticias/pais/relaciones-exteriores/espana/presidente-espanol-recibio-emocionado-la-medalla-de-salvador-allende/2018-08-28/140605.html |title=Presidente espa\u00f1ol recibi\u00f3 \"emocionado\" la medalla de Salvador Allende |date=28 August 2018 |access-date=3 September 2018 |work=[[Cooperativa]] |language=es}}</ref>\n* [[Grand Collar]] of the [[Order of the Condor of the Andes]] (29 August 2018).<ref>{{Cite news |newspaper=El Independiente |url=https://www.elindependiente.com/politica/2018/08/29/hermano-presidente-sanchez-alianza-bolivia-zapatero/ |title=El \"hermano presidente Pedro S\u00e1nchez\" recupera la alianza con Bolivia de Zapatero |date=29 August 2018 |first=Carmen |last=Torres |access-date=3 September 2018 |language=es}}</ref>\n* Grand Cross of the [[Order of the Sun of Peru]] (27 February 2019).<ref>[http://www.hola.com/realeza/casa_espanola/20190227138172/reyes-cena-de-gala-presidente-peru-esposa Visita de Estado]</ref>\n\n== Notable published works ==\n* Oca\u00f1a Orbis, Carlos y S\u00e1nchez P\u00e9rez-Castej\u00f3n, Pedro (2013): ''La nueva diplomacia econ\u00f3mica espa\u00f1ola''. Madrid: Delta. {{ISBN|9788415581512}}.<ref>[https://www.casadellibro.com/libro-la-nueva-diplomacia-economica-espanola/9788415581512/2237298 Casa del Libro]</ref>\n* S\u00e1nchez P\u00e9rez-Castej\u00f3n, Pedro (2019): ''Manual de resistencia''. Madrid: Pen\u00ednsula. {{ISBN|9788499427959}}.<ref>[https://www.planetadelibros.com/libro-manual-de-resistencia/291507 Planeta de Libros]</ref>\n\n=== Discussed plagiarism and authorship ===\n* ''La nueva diplomacia econ\u00f3mica espa\u00f1ola''. In 2018 a newspaper revealed that the book includes the plagiarism of six other people's texts.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chicote |first=Javier |title=S\u00e1nchez plagi\u00f3 en su libro 161 l\u00edneas con 1.651 palabras de seis textos ajenos y sin ning\u00fan tipo de cita |url=https://www.abc.es/espana/abci-sanchez-plagio-libro-161-lineas-1651-palabras-seis-textos-ajenos-y-sin-ningun-tipo-cita-201809232157_noticia.html |work=ABC |date=24 September 2018 |access-date=28 February 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref> The suspicion was made extensive to his doctoral thesis, whose authorship was questioned.<ref>{{cite web |title=Un trabajo intrigante |url=https://elpais.com/politica/2018/09/13/actualidad/1536840669_711505.html |date=14 September 2018 |access-date=6 May 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n* ''Manual de resistencia''. The authorship of this work is in doubt because S\u00e1nchez, who appears as the sole author, states in the prologue that \"This book is the result of long hours of conversation with [[Irene Lozano]], writer, thinker, politician and friend. She gave a literary form to the recordings, giving me a decisive help\".<ref>{{cite book |last=S\u00e1nchez P\u00e9rez-Castej\u00f3n |first= Pedro |year=2019 |title=Manual de resistencia |location=Madrid |publisher=Pen\u00ednsula |isbn=9788499427959 |page=13}}.</ref> The mentioned writer, for her part, affirmed that \"I made the book, but the author is the president\".<ref>{{cite web |title= Irene Lozano sobre el libro de S\u00e1nchez: \"Yo hice el libro, pero el autor es el presidente\" |url=https://www.elespanol.com/espana/politica/20190219/irene-lozano-libro-sanchez-hice-autor-presidente/377463387_0.html |work=El Espa\u00f1ol |date=19 February 2019 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=n.}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n{{Commons category|Pedro S\u00e1nchez P\u00e9rez-Castej\u00f3n}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alfredo P\u00e9rez Rubalcaba]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Leader of the Opposition (Spain)|Leader of the Opposition]]|years=2014\u20132016}}\n{{s-vac}}\n|-\n{{s-vac}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Leader of the Opposition (Spain)|Leader of the Opposition]]|years=2017\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Pablo Casado]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mariano Rajoy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Spain]]|years=2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alfredo P\u00e9rez Rubalcaba]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Secretary General of the<br />[[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party]]|years=2014\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Javier Fern\u00e1ndez (Spanish politician)|Javier Fern\u00e1ndez]] (Acting)}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Javier Fern\u00e1ndez (Spanish politician)|Javier Fern\u00e1ndez]] (Acting)}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Secretary General of the<br />[[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party]]|years=2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Spanish Socialist Workers' Party}}\n{{Prime Ministers of Spain}}\n{{Leaders of the Opposition (Spain)}}\n{{European Council}}\n{{Current NATO leaders}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sanchez, Pedro}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Complutense University of Madrid alumni]]\n[[Category:Free University of Brussels alumni]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of the Sun of Peru]]\n[[Category:Leaders of political parties in Spain]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Madrid city councillors (2003\u20132007)]]\n[[Category:Madrid city councillors (2007\u20132011)]]\n[[Category:Members of the 10th Congress of Deputies (Spain)]]\n[[Category:Members of the 11th Congress of Deputies (Spain)]]\n[[Category:Members of the 12th Congress of Deputies (Spain)]]\n[[Category:Members of the 13th Congress of Deputies (Spain)]]\n[[Category:Members of the 14th Congress of Deputies (Spain)]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Spain]]\n[[Category:Spanish atheists]]\n[[Category:Spanish Socialist Workers' Party politicians]]\n[[Category:University of Navarra alumni]]\n", "name_user": "178.197.226.201", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(New information added)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pedro_S%C3%A1nchez"}
{"title_page": "1918 VPI Gobblers football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox college sports team season\n| mode = football\n| year = 1918\n| team = VPI Gobblers\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_caption = \n| conference = South Atlantic Intercollegiate Athletic Association\n| short_conf   = SAIAA\n| record = 7\u20130\n| conf_record = 3\u20130\n| head_coach         = [[Charles Bernier]]\n| hc_year = 2nd\n| off_scheme =\n| def_scheme =\n| captain = [[Hank Crisp]]<br/>Harry Douglas Roden<br/>[[William L. Younger]]\n| stadium = [[Miles Field (Virginia Tech)|Miles Field]]\n| champion = SAIAA champion\n}}\n{{1918 SAIAA football standings}}\nThe '''1918 VPI Gobblers football team''' represented [[Virginia Tech|Virginia Polytechnic Institute]],<ref group=note>In 1918, the official name of the university that is now commonly known as Virginia Tech was [[Virginia Tech#History#College Reorganizations|\"Virginia Agricultural and Mechanical College and Polytechnic Institute\"]]. That name was not used in any newspapers of the period. \"Virginia Polytechnic Institute\" was used by the school, its students, and newspapers.  VPI and Virginia Tech were also commonly used shortened names in newspapers.</ref> now known as [[Virginia Tech Hokies football|Virginia Tech]], in the [[1918 college football season]]. The 1918 team went 7\u20130 and claims a [[South Atlantic Intercollegiate Athletic Association]] (SAIAA) championship.<ref name=\"cfb warehouse\">[http://cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/conference_champs/champions.php?conid=171 Conference Champions of the South Atlantic Intercollegiate Athletic Association],''College Football Data Warehouse''</ref>  It is the only team in Virginia Tech history that finished the season with a perfect record.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/virginia-tech/|title=Virginia Tech Hokies School History|website=Sports Reference CB|access-date=March 22, 2019}}</ref><ref group=\"note\">The 1999 team went 11-0 in regular season play before losing the [[BCS National Championship Game|National Championship game]] played in the [[1999 Sugar Bowl|2000 Sugar Bowl]].</ref>\n\nLed by second-year head coach [[Charles Bernier]], the team allowed only two [[touchdown]]s during its seven games. Tech's star player  was [[Hank Crisp|Henry Crisp]], a man without a right hand, who was ineligible for military service in [[World War I]].  He was voted MVP of the South Atlantic conference.\n\n==Before the season==\n===World War I and the Spanish Flu===\nIn the summer of 1918, the United States was not only in the midst of World War I, a worldwide flu pandemic (referred to as [[Spanish flu]]) began to impact the colleges of the United States. These two factors had a significant impact on the 1918 college football season. \n\nA huge military offensive was planned by the Allied countries in the spring of 1919, so all able-bodied men of ages 18 to 20 were scheduled to be enlisted in the fall of 1918. As an alternative, the men were offered the option of enlisting in the [[Student Army Training Corps]], known as SATC, which would give them a chance to pursue (or continue pursuing) their educations at the same time as they participated in a 12-week war-training session. This was essentially an alternative to boot camp. The colleges were paid by the government to train the future soldiers, which enabled many of them to avoid closure. The program began on October 1, 1918. Most of the students who were potential football players were under the auspices of the War Department's SATC program.\n\nIn an early September meeting between college and War Department officials in [[Plattsburg, Missouri]] it became clear that the training regimen envisioned for the soldiers could be incompatible with participation in intercollegiate athletics.<ref name=\"Detroit\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29942079/detroit_free_press_opinion_piece_on/|title=War Department's action makes serious problem for college athletics: Whether usual sports can be continued is question that must be threshed out; Difficult problem faces colleges on account of military training edict|last=Bushnell|first=Edward R.|date=September 8, 1918|work=Detroit Free Press|access-date=March 26, 2019}}</ref>  Coach Charles Bernier was one of those who successfully argued that athletics training was an important part of military training.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29896334/opinion_piece_of_football_for_satc/|title=Sports Review|last=Tranter|first=Edward|date=September 13, 1918|work=The Buffalo Enquirer|access-date=March 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29896202/general_story_about_football_in_1918/|title=Football season opens this week:  Gridiron game will prosper in all of Uncle Sam's camps|last=|first=|date=September 22, 1918|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29703566/|title=Football season in United States to open within very short time:|last=|first=|date=September 26, 1918|work=Winston-Salem Journal|access-date=}}</ref> Virginia Tech made plans to continue its football program in conjunction with the [[Student Army Training Corps|SATC]] program.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29739318/announcement_that_virginia_tech_would/|title=Tech will play football schedule as planned:  Coach Bernier says athletics important part of military training|last=|first=|date=August 18, 1918|work=Times Dispatch - Richmond|access-date=March 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nNotably, since Tech was an all-male military school in 1918, it did not have to make as many adjustments as other colleges which had to cooperate with the military to have football programs, or even remain open.\n\n====Original schedule====\nTech originally had a nine-game schedule which was supposed to start the first weekend of October. Due to the upheaval involving the war preparations and the deaths happening in the United States due to the pandemic (being censored from the public due to national security concerns),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://quod.lib.umich.edu/f/flu/5150flu.0005.515/1|title=War Conditions Coupled With Epidemic Have Big Effect On 1918 Sports|date=2016-02-03|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203014916/http://quod.lib.umich.edu/f/flu/5150flu.0005.515/1|archivedate=February 3, 2016|url-status=dead|access-date=2016-02-03}}</ref> only three of the originally scheduled games were played.\n\n*[[List of Hampden\u2013Sydney Tigers football seasons|Hampden-Sydney]] in Blacksburg on October 5  (team played only 3 games and is listed as having no coach)\n*[[Emory and Henry Wasps|Emory & Henry]] in Blacksburg on October 12 (no record of any games played)\n*[[Georgetown Hoyas footbal|Georgetown]] in Washington on October 19 (cancelled game with Tech early in year, but played 5 games according to conference standings)\n*[[Maryland Terrapins football|Maryland State]] in College Park October 26  (played six games)\n*[[1918 Georgia Tech Golden Tornado football team|Georgia Tech]] in Atlanta on November 2 (distance cited as reason for cancellation)\n*'''[[1918 Wake Forest Baptists football team|Wake Forest]] in Blacksburg on November 9 (played on this date)'''\n*'''[https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/north-carolina-state/1918.html North Carolina State]  in Norfolk on November 16 (played on this date)'''\n*[[Roanoke Maroons|Roanoke]] in Blacksburg on November 23 (scheduled for October 19 in place of the Georgetown game, but Roanoke College did not play)\n*'''[https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/virginia-military-institute/1918.html VMI] in Roanoke on November 28 (played on this date)'''\n*<small>Source: Spalding's Official Foot Ball Guide 1918.<ref name=\"camp1918\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/officialfootball19181nati|title=Spalding's Official Foot Ball Guide 1919|editor-last=Camp|editor-first=Walter|publisher=|year=1918|}}</ref> </small>\n\n====Building a new schedule====\nTech leaders attempted to schedule games with two groups on the dates that opened: 1) military bases, which were fielding teams of young men who were football players that were away from their home campuses or had recently graduated after playing football; and 2) college teams for  that had SATC programs, whose students were encouraged to participate in athletic programs along with the more traditional athletes. This not only enabled colleges to justify the inclusion of football in the SATC regimen, it also helped fill the gaps left by some of their star athletes. For instance, at Virginia Tech, one of the team captains, [[Monk Younger]], was actually in the military in France during the season. He was captain of Hospital No. 41, but the \"Techs,\" (the common nickname for  VPI sports teams in newspapers at the time) were still referred to as \"Younger's team.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29738675/monk_younger_in_1918_france/|title=Tech's football star is playing over there:  \"Monk\" Younger captain of Hospital No. 41 team in France|last=|first=|date=October 27, 1918|work=|access-date=March 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nWashington and Lee and the University of North Carolina were in the first category.  Camp Humphreys and Aero Squadron of Richmond were in the second (although the Aero Squadron of Richmond game was scheduled but never played).\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n| timezone = Eastern\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 19 \n| time = \n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| opponent = Belmont Athletic Club\n| site_stadium = [[Miles Field (Virginia Tech)|Miles Field]]\n| site_cityst = [[Blacksburg, Virginia|Blacksburg, VA]]\n| score = 30\u20130.<ref name =Belmont1918>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29663503/belmont_athletic_club_1918/|title=Gridiron season opens at Virginia \"Tech\": \"Poly\" defeats Athletic Club of Roanoke 30 to 0|last=|first=|date=October 20, 1918|work=Richmond Times-Dispatch|access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref>\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 26\n| time = \n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| opponent = [[Fort Belvoir#History|Camp Humphreys]]\n| site_stadium = Miles Field\n| site_cityst = Blacksburg, VA\n| score = 33\u20136 \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 2\n| time = 2:30 p.m.<ref name=generals>{{cite news |title=\"Generals\" Clash With \"Gobblers\" at Fair Grounds|url=http://virginiachronicle.com/cgi-bin/virginia?a=d&d=TWN19181102.1.7&e=------191-en-20--1-byDA.rev-txt-txIN-foot+ball----1918--|publisher=Library of Virginia|newspaper=The World News|date=November 2, 1918|page=7|accessdate=December 13, 2015}}</ref>\n| w/l = w\n| neutral = y\n| opponent = [[1918 Washington and Lee Generals football team|Washington and Lee]]\n| site_stadium = Fair Grounds<ref name=generals />\n| site_cityst = [[Roanoke, Virginia|Roanoke, VA]]\n| score = 13\u20130 <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29995459/washington_lee_v_virginia_tech/|title=V .P. I. defeats Generals by count of 13 to 0: Tech fights for every inch of ground in first game with W. & L. since 1915|last=Associated Press|first=|date=November 3, 1918|work=The Times Dispatch - Richmond|access-date=April 1, 2019}}</ref>\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 9\n| time = \n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| opponent = [[1918 Wake Forest Baptists football team|Wake Forest]]\n| site_stadium = Miles Field\n| site_cityst = Blacksburg, VA\n| score = 27\u20130 <ref name= wake1918 />\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 16\n| time = \n| w/l = w\n| neutral = y\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1918|team=NC State Aggies|title=NC State}}\n| site_stadium = \n| site_cityst = [[Norfolk, Virginia|Norfolk, VA]]\n| score = 25\u20130\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 23\n| time = \n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| away = y\n| opponent = North Carolina (unsanctioned) \n| site_stadium = [[Boshamer Stadium|Emerson Field]]\n| site_cityst = [[Chapel Hill, North Carolina|Chapel Hill, NC]]\n| score = 18\u20137<ref name=unc/>\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 28\n| time = 3:00 p.m.<ref name=vmi>{{cite news |title=Rain Fails to Dampen The Football Spirit|url=http://virginiachronicle.com/cgi-bin/virginia?a=d&d=TWN19181128.1.1&e=------191-en-20--1-byDA.rev-txt-txIN-foot+ball----1918--|publisher=Library of Virginia|newspaper=The World News|date=November 28, 1918|page=1|accessdate=December 13, 2015}}</ref>\n| w/l = w\n| neutral = y\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1918|team=VMI Keydets|title=VMI}}\n| site_stadium = Fair Grounds<ref name=vmi />\n| site_cityst = Roanoke, VA\n| gamename = [[VMI\u2013Virginia Tech football rivalry|rivalry]]\n| score = 6\u20130<ref name=vmidown>{{cite news |title=V.M.I. Goes Down in Defeat Before the V.P.I. Eleven|url=http://virginiachronicle.com/cgi-bin/virginia?a=d&d=TWN19181129.1.3&e=------191-en-20--1-byDA.rev-txt-txIN-foot+ball----1918--#|publisher=Library of Virginia|newspaper=The World News|date=November 29, 1918|page=3|accessdate=December 13, 2015}}</ref>\n| attend = 2,500 \n}}\n}}\n*<small>Source: The Bugle 1919 (VPI Yearbook with information on 1918 football) <ref name=Bugle19>{{Cite book|url=https://vtechworks.lib.vt.edu/bitstream/handle/10919/11389/1919_BUGLE.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y|title=The Bugle 1919|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref></small>\n\n==Game Summaries==\n===Belmont Athletic Club===\nTech opened the season at Miles Field with a 30\u20130 win over Belmont Athletic Club, an organization in [[Roanoke, Virginia]]. Tech completed 9 of 16 [[forward pass]]es for 157 yards.<ref name =Belmont1918 />\n\nTech's starting lineup against Belmont: Roden (left end), Hardwick (left tackle), Camper (left guard), Copenhaver (center), Quarles (right guard), Hitchens (right tackle), Huddle (right end), Siegel (quarterback), McCann (left halfback), Bock (right halfback), Conners (fullback).<ref name =Belmont1918 />\n\n===Camp Humphreys===\nCamp Humphreys was one of the teams fielded by military bases that played against college opponents in 1918.  Originally the Gobblers were scheduled to face another military team, the Aero Squadron of Richmond, but there was a change during the week before the game.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29738604/information_about_vpi_scheduled_game/|title=Aero to play Techs:  Squadron eleven from Richmond will go to Tech Saturday|last=|first=|date=October 23, 1918|work=Times Dispatch - Richmond|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29738638/|title=Tech and Camp Humphries (sic) will meet on Saturday; Game called off for that date with Aero Squadron of Richmond|last=|first=|date=October 25, 1918|work=Times Dispatch - Richmond|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref> Camp Humphreys was a semi-temporary cantonment built on the Belvoir peninsula in Fairfax County, VA in 1918.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.belvoir.army.mil/history/Humphreys.htm|title=Forrt Belvoir History}}</ref> When the men on the Camp Humphreys team came to Blacksburg, they were coming from a place where over 50 men per day had been dying of the Spanish flu and related pneumonia. The flu was said to have been \"conquered\" by the week of the game;  the number of deaths per day had fallen to 10.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://virginiachronicle.com/?a=d&d=AG19181026.1.1&srpos=9&e=22-10-1918-30-10-1918--en-20--1--txt-txIN-%22Camp+Humphreys%22------|title=City news in brief|last=|first=|date=October 26, 1918|work=Alexandria Gazette|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref> \n\nTech won the game 33\u20136, allowing one of the two touchdowns it allowed all year.  <ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47822605/vpi-33-at-camp-humphries-6-1918/|title=Camp Humpries downed by the onset of the Techs:  Service men take short end of 33-6 count at Blacksburg|date=October 26, 1918|work=Richmond Times Dispatch|access-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nTech's starting lineup against Camp Humphreys: Hardwick (left end), Rangely (left tackle), Tilson (left guard), Resh (center), Quarles (right guard), Pierce (right tackle), Camper (right end), Hurst (quarterback), Bock (left halfback), McCann (right halfback), Crisp (fullback).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://virginiachronicle.com/?a=d&d=RTD19181027.1.19&e=-------en-20--1--txt-txIN--------|title=Camp Humphries Downed By Onset Of The Techs|last=|first=|date=October 27, 1918|work=[[Richmond Times-Dispatch]]|access-date=October 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Washington and Lee===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Title = '''VPI vs. Washington & Lee'''\n| Visitor = '''VPI'''\n| Host = W&L\n| V1 = 0| V2 =0| V3 =0| V4 =13\n| H1 = 0| H2 =0| H3 =0| H4 =0\n| Date = November 2\n| Location = Fair Gounds<br />[[Roanoke, VA]]\n| StartTime =2:30 p.m.\n| ElapsedTime =\n| Attendance =\n| Weather =\n| Referee =Gass\n}}\n*'''Sources:'''<ref name=generals/>\n{{AFB game box end}}\nTech played [[1918 Washington and Lee Generals football team|Washington & Lee]] in Roanoke for the first time since 1915. After fighting to a 0\u20130 draw after three quarters, Bock and Crisp each scored a touchdown as the Gobblers beat the Generals 13\u20130.\n\nTech's starting lineup against W&L: Hardwick (left end), Rangsley (left tackle), Tilson (left guard), Resh (center), Quarles (right guard), Pierce (right tackle), Camper (right end), Bonney (quarterback), Crocker (left halfback), McCann (right halfback), Crisp (fullback).<ref name=generals />\n\n===Wake Forest===\nIt was [[1918 Wake Forest Baptists football team|Wake Forest']]<nowiki/>s first game of the year.  Tech beat the Baptists (the nickname of the team at the time, owing to the school's affiliation with the church) by a score of either 27\u20130 (the school yearbook, the Bugle) or 25\u20130 (the Associated Press).  The Gobblers ran up a three-touchdown halftime lead, and then scored once in the second half.\n\nTech's starting lineup against UNC: Roden (left end), Rangley (left tackle), Tilson (left guard), Resh (center), Quarles (right guard), Pierce (right tackle), Comper (right end), Bonney (quarterback), Crocker (left halfback), McCann (right halfback), Crisp (fullback).<ref name= wake1918>{{cite news|url=https://virginiachronicle.com/?a=d&d=RTD19181110&e=16-11-1918-18-11-1918-191-en-20--1-byDA.rev-txt-txIN-football----1918--|date=November 10, 1918|work=Richmond Times-Dispatch|title=Virginia Tech Takes Victory from Wake Forest|page=17}}</ref>\n\n===NC State===\nVPI beat NC State 25&ndash;0 in Norfolk. Tech's Crocker scored the game's first touchdown just five minutes into the game and the Gobblers never looked back.<ref name = NCState1918>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29995889/nc_state_v_vpi_football_1918/|title=V.P.I gives Tarheels tremendous trouncing: Coach Berrier's boys defeat North Carolina A&E by 25-0 count|last=|first=|date=November 17, 1918|work=Richmond Times Dispatch|access-date=April 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===North Carolina ===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Title = '''VPI at North Carolina'''\n| Visitor = '''VPI'''\n| Host = UNC\n| V1 = 0| V2 =6| V3 =6| V4 =6\n| H1 = 0| H2 =7| H3 =0| H4 =0\n| Date =November 23\n| Location = [[Emerson Field]]<br />[[Chapel Hill, NC]]\n| StartTime =\n| ElapsedTime =\n| Attendance =\n| Weather =\n| Referee =\n}}\n*'''Sources:'''<ref name=unc/>\n{{AFB game box end}}\nVPI beat the North Carolina Tar Heels, though the game is not counted as official by UNC. 18&ndash;7. (University of North Carolina officials did not recognize the 1918 football team as a varsity program because it was under the auspices of the SATC).<ref name=unc>{{cite news|url=https://virginiachronicle.com/?a=d&d=RTD19181124.1.27&srpos=2&e=23-11-1918-25-11-1918-191-en-20--1-byDA.rev-txt-txIN-football+carolina----1918--|title=Virginia Tech's String of Victories Unbroken|date=November 24, 1918|work=Richmond Times-Dispatch}}</ref> Tech outweighed UNC by 15 pounds per man. drove to the 10-yard line in the first three minutes, but was unable to score. In the second quarter, Crisp scored a touchdown on a fake end run from the 6-yard line. UNC's Bristol had a 70-yard run soon after, to the 20-year line. A forward pass from Pharr to Fearrington resulted in a touchdown for UNC.<ref name=unc/>\n\nIn the third quarter a series of passes from UNC toot the Tar Heels to the 15-yard line, then Crocker intercepted a pass a ran 90 yards for the touchdown. Rangley of UNC plunged for the final score in the fourth quarter.<ref name=unc/>\n\nTech's starting lineup against UNC: Roden (left end), Rangley (left tackle), Tilson (left guard), Resh (center), Quarles (right guard), Pierce (right tackle), Hardwick (right end), Crisp (quarterback), Robinson (left halfback), Maddox (right halfback), Bonney (fullback).<ref name=unc/>\n\n===VMI===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Title = '''VPI vs. VMI'''\n| Visitor = '''VPI'''\n| Host = VMI\n| V1 = 0| V2 =0| V3 =6| V4 =0\n| H1 = 0| H2 =0| H3 =0| H4 =0\n| Date =November 28\n| Location = Fair Grounds<br />Roanoke, VA\n| StartTime =3:00 p.m.\n| ElapsedTime =\n| Attendance =2,500\n| Weather =\n| Referee =[[Bob Peck (American football)|Bob Peck]]\n}}\n*'''Sources:'''<ref name=vmidown/>\n{{AFB game box end}}\nThe season closed against VMI on Thanksgiving Day. The [[Norfolk and Western Railway|Norfolk and Western Railroad]] ran two special trains for VPI and VMI students to attend the game in Roanoke.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://virginiachronicle.com/?a=d&d=TWN19181118.1.3&srpos=2&e=16-11-1918-18-11-1918-191-en-20--1-byDA.rev-txt-txIN-football----1918--|work=World News|date=November 18, 1918|title=Two Special Trains}}</ref> Tech defeated VMI 6\u20130. In the third quarter, Harry Roden blocked a VMI [[Punt (gridiron football)|punt]] at the 10-yard line. Three runs [[Off-tackle run|off tackle]] by Crisp resulted in the game's lone touchdown.<ref name=vmidown/>\n\nTech's starting lineup against VMI: Roden (left end), Hardwick (left tackle), Tilson (left guard), Resh (center), Quarles (right guard), Pierce (right tackle), Camper (right end), Crisp (quarterback), Crocker (left halfback), Mattox (right halfback), Bonney (fullback).<ref name=vmidown/>\n\n==After the season==\n[[File:CrispatVPI.jpg|thumb|upright=0.75|Hank Crisp was co-captain of the only Virginia Tech football team to go undefeated.|alt=]]Coach Bernier wrote a story in the 1919 [[Walter Camp]]-edited ''Spalding Foot Ball Guide'' praising Crisp, one of the team's captains:<ref name=\"camp\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/officialfootball19181nati|title=Spalding's Official Foot Ball Guide 1919|editor-last=Camp|editor-first=Walter|publisher=|year=1919|isbn=|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/officialfootball19181nati/page/53 53]}}</ref>{{Quote | style=font-size: 100%; |\"[[Uncle Sam]] could not use a one-hand man, so Henry Crisp, much to Tech's good fortune, played the next biggest game [referring to football compared to war fighting], and to him, more than anyone else, goes the glory for a driving, consistent attack.  This big fellow, playing in the back-field for the first time, literally mowed them all down...\"<ref name=camp />}}Crisp was the captain of the All-South Atlantic Eleven team (league MVP), and was joined on that team by the Gobblers' James Hardwick (end), Walter Wrangley (tackle), and Charles Quarles (center).<ref name=\"camp\" />\n\n==Players==\nThe following players were members of the 1918 football team according to the roster published in the 1919 edition of ''The Bugle'', the Virginia Tech yearbook.<ref name = Bugle19 />\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"text-align: left;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"9\" style=\"background:#660000;color:#FF6600;text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"color:#FF6600;\">'''VPI 1918 roster'''</span>\n|-\n|\n| style=\"font-size:95%; vertical-align:top;\"|'''[[Quarterback]]'''\n* Wesley Leroy Bonney\n'''[[Guard (American and Canadian football)|Guards]]'''\n* Charles Walthall Quarles\n* [[Sumner D. Tilson]]\n'''[[Tackle (gridiron football position)|Tackles]]'''\n* Walter Morgan Pierce\n* Walter Weiss Rangely\n'''[[Center (gridiron football)|Center]]'''\n* Franklin Senatre Resh\n| style=\"width: 25px;\" |\n|  style=\"font-size:95%; vertical-align:top;\"|'''[[End (gridiron football)|Ends]]'''\n* Julian Jessings Camper\n* James Thomas Hardwick\n* Harry Douglas Roden (Capt.)\n* [[Monk Younger|William Lee Younger (Capt.)]]\n'''[[Halfback (American football)|Halfbacks]]'''\n* [[Hank Crisp]] (Capt.)\n* Philip Crocker\n* Harry Lee McCann\n| style=\"width: 25px;\" |\n|  style=\"font-size:95%; vertical-align:top;\"|'''[[Fullback (gridiron football)|Fullback]]'''\n* William Hurst\n'''[[Substitution (sport)|Substitutes]]'''\n* Eugene Darrington Bock\n* John Kelly Copenhaver\n* Hitchens\n* Huddle\n* Samuel Anderson McConkey\n* Seigle\n* Charles Evans Whitmore\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Virginia Tech Hokies football navbox}}\n{{SAIAA football champions}}\n\n[[Category:1918 South Atlantic Intercollegiate Athletic Association football season|VPI]]\n[[Category:Virginia Tech Hokies football seasons]]\n[[Category:South Atlantic Intercollegiate Athletic Association football champion seasons]]\n[[Category:College football undefeated seasons]]\n[[Category:1918 in sports in Virginia|VPI Football]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox college sports team season\n| mode = football\n| year = 1918\n| team = VPI Gobblers\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_caption = \n| conference = South Atlantic Intercollegiate Athletic Association\n| short_conf   = SAIAA\n| record = 7\u20130\n| conf_record = 3\u20130\n| head_coach         = [[Charles Bernier]]\n| hc_year = 2nd\n| off_scheme =\n| def_scheme =\n| captain = [[Hank Crisp]]<br/>Harry Douglas Roden<br/>[[William L. Younger]]\n| stadium = [[Miles Field (Virginia Tech)|Miles Field]]\n| champion = SAIAA champion\n}}\n{{1918 SAIAA football standings}}\nThe '''1918 VPI Gobblers football team''' represented [[Virginia Tech|Virginia Polytechnic Institute]],<ref group=note>In 1918, the official name of the university that is now commonly known as Virginia Tech was [[Virginia Tech#History#College Reorganizations|\"Virginia Agricultural and Mechanical College and Polytechnic Institute\"]]. That name was not used in any newspapers of the period. \"Virginia Polytechnic Institute\" was used by the school, its students, and newspapers.  VPI and Virginia Tech were also commonly used shortened names in newspapers.</ref> now known as [[Virginia Tech Hokies football|Virginia Tech]], in the [[1918 college football season]]. The 1918 team went 7\u20130 and claims a [[South Atlantic Intercollegiate Athletic Association]] (SAIAA) championship.<ref name=\"cfb warehouse\">[http://cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/conference_champs/champions.php?conid=171 Conference Champions of the South Atlantic Intercollegiate Athletic Association],''College Football Data Warehouse''</ref>  It is the only team in Virginia Tech history that finished the season with a perfect record.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/virginia-tech/|title=Virginia Tech Hokies School History|website=Sports Reference CB|access-date=March 22, 2019}}</ref><ref group=\"note\">The 1999 team went 11-0 in regular season play before losing the [[BCS National Championship Game|National Championship game]] played in the [[1999 Sugar Bowl|2000 Sugar Bowl]].</ref>\n\nLed by second-year head coach [[Charles Bernier]], the team allowed only two [[touchdown]]s during its seven games. Tech's star player  was [[Hank Crisp|Henry Crisp]], a man without a right hand, who was ineligible for military service in [[World War I]].  He was voted MVP of the South Atlantic conference.\n\n==Before the season==\n===World War I and the Spanish Flu===\nIn the summer of 1918, the United States was not only in the midst of World War I, a worldwide flu pandemic, (referred to as [[Spanish flu]]) began to impact the colleges of the United States. These two factors had a significant impact on the 1918 college football season. \n\nA huge military offensive was planned by the Allied countries in the spring of 1919, so all able-bodied men of ages 18 to 20 were scheduled to be enlisted in the fall of 1918. As an alternative, the men were offered the option of enlisting in the [[Student Army Training Corps]], known as SATC, which would give them a chance to pursue (or continue pursuing) their educations at the same time as they participated in a 12-week war-training session. This was essentially an alternative to boot camp. The colleges were paid by the government to train the future soldiers, which enabled many of them to avoid closure. The program began on October 1, 1918. Most of the students who were potential football players were under the auspices of the War Department's SATC program.\n\nIn an early September meeting between college and War Department officials in [[Plattsburg, Missouri]] it became clear that the training regimen envisioned for the soldiers could be incompatible with participation in intercollegiate athletics.<ref name=\"Detroit\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29942079/detroit_free_press_opinion_piece_on/|title=War Department's action makes serious problem for college athletics: Whether usual sports can be continued is question that must be threshed out; Difficult problem faces colleges on account of military training edict|last=Bushnell|first=Edward R.|date=September 8, 1918|work=Detroit Free Press|access-date=March 26, 2019}}</ref>  Coach Charles Bernier was one of those who successfully argued that athletics training was an important part of military training.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29896334/opinion_piece_of_football_for_satc/|title=Sports Review|last=Tranter|first=Edward|date=September 13, 1918|work=The Buffalo Enquirer|access-date=March 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29896202/general_story_about_football_in_1918/|title=Football season opens this week:  Gridiron game will prosper in all of Uncle Sam's camps|last=|first=|date=September 22, 1918|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29703566/|title=Football season in United States to open within very short time:|last=|first=|date=September 26, 1918|work=Winston-Salem Journal|access-date=}}</ref> Virginia Tech made plans to continue its football program in conjunction with the [[Student Army Training Corps|SATC]] program.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29739318/announcement_that_virginia_tech_would/|title=Tech will play football schedule as planned:  Coach Bernier says athletics important part of military training|last=|first=|date=August 18, 1918|work=Times Dispatch - Richmond|access-date=March 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nNotably, since Tech was an all-male military school in 1918, it did not have to make as many adjustments as other colleges which had to cooperate with the military to have football programs, or even remain open.\n\n====Original schedule====\nTech originally had a nine-game schedule which was supposed to start the first weekend of October. Due to the upheaval involving the war preparations and the deaths happening in the United States due to the pandemic (being censored from the public due to national security concerns),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://quod.lib.umich.edu/f/flu/5150flu.0005.515/1|title=War Conditions Coupled With Epidemic Have Big Effect On 1918 Sports|date=2016-02-03|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203014916/http://quod.lib.umich.edu/f/flu/5150flu.0005.515/1|archivedate=February 3, 2016|url-status=dead|access-date=2016-02-03}}</ref> only three of the originally scheduled games were played.\n\n*[[List of Hampden\u2013Sydney Tigers football seasons|Hampden-Sydney]] in Blacksburg on October 5  (team played only 3 games and is listed as having no coach)\n*[[Emory and Henry Wasps|Emory & Henry]] in Blacksburg on October 12 (no record of any games played)\n*[[Georgetown Hoyas footbal|Georgetown]] in Washington on October 19 (cancelled game with Tech early in year, but played 5 games according to conference standings)\n*[[Maryland Terrapins football|Maryland State]] in College Park October 26  (played six games)\n*[[1918 Georgia Tech Golden Tornado football team|Georgia Tech]] in Atlanta on November 2 (distance cited as reason for cancellation)\n*'''[[1918 Wake Forest Baptists football team|Wake Forest]] in Blacksburg on November 9 (played on this date)'''\n*'''[https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/north-carolina-state/1918.html North Carolina State]  in Norfolk on November 16 (played on this date)'''\n*[[Roanoke Maroons|Roanoke]] in Blacksburg on November 23 (scheduled for October 19 in place of the Georgetown game, but Roanoke College did not play)\n*'''[https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/virginia-military-institute/1918.html VMI] in Roanoke on November 28 (played on this date)'''\n*<small>Source: Spalding's Official Foot Ball Guide 1918.<ref name=\"camp1918\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/officialfootball19181nati|title=Spalding's Official Foot Ball Guide 1919|editor-last=Camp|editor-first=Walter|publisher=|year=1918|}}</ref> </small>\n\n====Building a new schedule====\nTech leaders attempted to schedule games with two groups on the dates that opened: 1) military bases, which were fielding teams of young men who were football players that were away from their home campuses or had recently graduated after playing football; and 2) college teams for  that had SATC programs, whose students were encouraged to participate in athletic programs along with the more traditional athletes. This not only enabled colleges to justify the inclusion of football in the SATC regimen, it also helped fill the gaps left by some of their star athletes. For instance, at Virginia Tech, one of the team captains, [[Monk Younger]], was actually in the military in France during the season. He was captain of Hospital No. 41, but the \"Techs,\" (the common nickname for  VPI sports teams in newspapers at the time) were still referred to as \"Younger's team.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29738675/monk_younger_in_1918_france/|title=Tech's football star is playing over there:  \"Monk\" Younger captain of Hospital No. 41 team in France|last=|first=|date=October 27, 1918|work=|access-date=March 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nWashington and Lee and the University of North Carolina were in the first category.  Camp Humphreys and Aero Squadron of Richmond were in the second (although the Aero Squadron of Richmond game was scheduled but never played).\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n| timezone = Eastern\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 19 \n| time = \n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| opponent = Belmont Athletic Club\n| site_stadium = [[Miles Field (Virginia Tech)|Miles Field]]\n| site_cityst = [[Blacksburg, Virginia|Blacksburg, VA]]\n| score = 30\u20130.<ref name =Belmont1918>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29663503/belmont_athletic_club_1918/|title=Gridiron season opens at Virginia \"Tech\": \"Poly\" defeats Athletic Club of Roanoke 30 to 0|last=|first=|date=October 20, 1918|work=Richmond Times-Dispatch|access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref>\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 26\n| time = \n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| opponent = [[Fort Belvoir#History|Camp Humphreys]]\n| site_stadium = Miles Field\n| site_cityst = Blacksburg, VA\n| score = 33\u20136 \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 2\n| time = 2:30 p.m.<ref name=generals>{{cite news |title=\"Generals\" Clash With \"Gobblers\" at Fair Grounds|url=http://virginiachronicle.com/cgi-bin/virginia?a=d&d=TWN19181102.1.7&e=------191-en-20--1-byDA.rev-txt-txIN-foot+ball----1918--|publisher=Library of Virginia|newspaper=The World News|date=November 2, 1918|page=7|accessdate=December 13, 2015}}</ref>\n| w/l = w\n| neutral = y\n| opponent = [[1918 Washington and Lee Generals football team|Washington and Lee]]\n| site_stadium = Fair Grounds<ref name=generals />\n| site_cityst = [[Roanoke, Virginia|Roanoke, VA]]\n| score = 13\u20130 <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29995459/washington_lee_v_virginia_tech/|title=V .P. I. defeats Generals by count of 13 to 0: Tech fights for every inch of ground in first game with W. & L. since 1915|last=Associated Press|first=|date=November 3, 1918|work=The Times Dispatch - Richmond|access-date=April 1, 2019}}</ref>\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 9\n| time = \n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| opponent = [[1918 Wake Forest Baptists football team|Wake Forest]]\n| site_stadium = Miles Field\n| site_cityst = Blacksburg, VA\n| score = 27\u20130 <ref name= wake1918 />\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 16\n| time = \n| w/l = w\n| neutral = y\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1918|team=NC State Aggies|title=NC State}}\n| site_stadium = \n| site_cityst = [[Norfolk, Virginia|Norfolk, VA]]\n| score = 25\u20130\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 23\n| time = \n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| away = y\n| opponent = North Carolina (unsanctioned) \n| site_stadium = [[Boshamer Stadium|Emerson Field]]\n| site_cityst = [[Chapel Hill, North Carolina|Chapel Hill, NC]]\n| score = 18\u20137<ref name=unc/>\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 28\n| time = 3:00 p.m.<ref name=vmi>{{cite news |title=Rain Fails to Dampen The Football Spirit|url=http://virginiachronicle.com/cgi-bin/virginia?a=d&d=TWN19181128.1.1&e=------191-en-20--1-byDA.rev-txt-txIN-foot+ball----1918--|publisher=Library of Virginia|newspaper=The World News|date=November 28, 1918|page=1|accessdate=December 13, 2015}}</ref>\n| w/l = w\n| neutral = y\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1918|team=VMI Keydets|title=VMI}}\n| site_stadium = Fair Grounds<ref name=vmi />\n| site_cityst = Roanoke, VA\n| gamename = [[VMI\u2013Virginia Tech football rivalry|rivalry]]\n| score = 6\u20130<ref name=vmidown>{{cite news |title=V.M.I. Goes Down in Defeat Before the V.P.I. Eleven|url=http://virginiachronicle.com/cgi-bin/virginia?a=d&d=TWN19181129.1.3&e=------191-en-20--1-byDA.rev-txt-txIN-foot+ball----1918--#|publisher=Library of Virginia|newspaper=The World News|date=November 29, 1918|page=3|accessdate=December 13, 2015}}</ref>\n| attend = 2,500 \n}}\n}}\n*<small>Source: The Bugle 1919 (VPI Yearbook with information on 1918 football) <ref name=Bugle19>{{Cite book|url=https://vtechworks.lib.vt.edu/bitstream/handle/10919/11389/1919_BUGLE.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y|title=The Bugle 1919|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref></small>\n\n==Game Summaries==\n===Belmont Athletic Club===\nTech opened the season at Miles Field with a 30\u20130 win over Belmont Athletic Club, an organization in [[Roanoke, Virginia]]. Tech completed 9 of 16 [[forward pass]]es for 157 yards.<ref name =Belmont1918 />\n\nTech's starting lineup against Belmont: Roden (left end), Hardwick (left tackle), Camper (left guard), Copenhaver (center), Quarles (right guard), Hitchens (right tackle), Huddle (right end), Siegel (quarterback), McCann (left halfback), Bock (right halfback), Conners (fullback).<ref name =Belmont1918 />\n\n===Camp Humphreys===\nCamp Humphreys was one of the teams fielded by military bases that played against college opponents in 1918.  Originally the Gobblers were scheduled to face another military team, the Aero Squadron of Richmond, but there was a change during the week before the game.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29738604/information_about_vpi_scheduled_game/|title=Aero to play Techs:  Squadron eleven from Richmond will go to Tech Saturday|last=|first=|date=October 23, 1918|work=Times Dispatch - Richmond|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29738638/|title=Tech and Camp Humphries (sic) will meet on Saturday; Game called off for that date with Aero Squadron of Richmond|last=|first=|date=October 25, 1918|work=Times Dispatch - Richmond|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref> Camp Humphreys was a semi-temporary cantonment built on the Belvoir peninsula in Fairfax County, VA in 1918.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.belvoir.army.mil/history/Humphreys.htm|title=Forrt Belvoir History}}</ref> When the men on the Camp Humphreys team came to Blacksburg, they were coming from a place where over 50 men per day had been dying of the Spanish flu and related pneumonia. The flu was said to have been \"conquered\" by the week of the game;  the number of deaths per day had fallen to 10.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://virginiachronicle.com/?a=d&d=AG19181026.1.1&srpos=9&e=22-10-1918-30-10-1918--en-20--1--txt-txIN-%22Camp+Humphreys%22------|title=City news in brief|last=|first=|date=October 26, 1918|work=Alexandria Gazette|access-date=March 31, 2019}}</ref> \n\nTech won the game 33\u20136, allowing one of the two touchdowns it allowed all year.  <ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47822605/vpi-33-at-camp-humphries-6-1918/|title=Camp Humpries downed by the onset of the Techs:  Service men take short end of 33-6 count at Blacksburg|date=October 26, 1918|work=Richmond Times Dispatch|access-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nTech's starting lineup against Camp Humphreys: Hardwick (left end), Rangely (left tackle), Tilson (left guard), Resh (center), Quarles (right guard), Pierce (right tackle), Camper (right end), Hurst (quarterback), Bock (left halfback), McCann (right halfback), Crisp (fullback).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://virginiachronicle.com/?a=d&d=RTD19181027.1.19&e=-------en-20--1--txt-txIN--------|title=Camp Humphries Downed By Onset Of The Techs|last=|first=|date=October 27, 1918|work=[[Richmond Times-Dispatch]]|access-date=October 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Washington and Lee===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Title = '''VPI vs. Washington & Lee'''\n| Visitor = '''VPI'''\n| Host = W&L\n| V1 = 0| V2 =0| V3 =0| V4 =13\n| H1 = 0| H2 =0| H3 =0| H4 =0\n| Date = November 2\n| Location = Fair Gounds<br />[[Roanoke, VA]]\n| StartTime =2:30 p.m.\n| ElapsedTime =\n| Attendance =\n| Weather =\n| Referee =Gass\n}}\n*'''Sources:'''<ref name=generals/>\n{{AFB game box end}}\nTech played [[1918 Washington and Lee Generals football team|Washington & Lee]] in Roanoke for the first time since 1915. After fighting to a 0\u20130 draw after three quarters, Bock and Crisp each scored a touchdown as the Gobblers beat the Generals 13\u20130.\n\nTech's starting lineup against W&L: Hardwick (left end), Rangsley (left tackle), Tilson (left guard), Resh (center), Quarles (right guard), Pierce (right tackle), Camper (right end), Bonney (quarterback), Crocker (left halfback), McCann (right halfback), Crisp (fullback).<ref name=generals />\n\n===Wake Forest===\nIt was [[1918 Wake Forest Baptists football team|Wake Forest']]<nowiki/>s first game of the year.  Tech beat the Baptists (the nickname of the team at the time, owing to the school's affiliation with the church) by a score of either 27\u20130 (the school yearbook, the Bugle) or 25\u20130 (the Associated Press).  The Gobblers ran up a three-touchdown halftime lead, and then scored once in the second half.\n\nTech's starting lineup against UNC: Roden (left end), Rangley (left tackle), Tilson (left guard), Resh (center), Quarles (right guard), Pierce (right tackle), Comper (right end), Bonney (quarterback), Crocker (left halfback), McCann (right halfback), Crisp (fullback).<ref name= wake1918>{{cite news|url=https://virginiachronicle.com/?a=d&d=RTD19181110&e=16-11-1918-18-11-1918-191-en-20--1-byDA.rev-txt-txIN-football----1918--|date=November 10, 1918|work=Richmond Times-Dispatch|title=Virginia Tech Takes Victory from Wake Forest|page=17}}</ref>\n\n===NC State===\nVPI beat NC State 25&ndash;0 in Norfolk. Tech's Crocker scored the game's first touchdown just five minutes into the game and the Gobblers never looked back.<ref name = NCState1918>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29995889/nc_state_v_vpi_football_1918/|title=V.P.I gives Tarheels tremendous trouncing: Coach Berrier's boys defeat North Carolina A&E by 25-0 count|last=|first=|date=November 17, 1918|work=Richmond Times Dispatch|access-date=April 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===North Carolina ===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Title = '''VPI at North Carolina'''\n| Visitor = '''VPI'''\n| Host = UNC\n| V1 = 0| V2 =6| V3 =6| V4 =6\n| H1 = 0| H2 =7| H3 =0| H4 =0\n| Date =November 23\n| Location = [[Emerson Field]]<br />[[Chapel Hill, NC]]\n| StartTime =\n| ElapsedTime =\n| Attendance =\n| Weather =\n| Referee =\n}}\n*'''Sources:'''<ref name=unc/>\n{{AFB game box end}}\nVPI beat the North Carolina Tar Heels, though the game is not counted as official by UNC. 18&ndash;7. (University of North Carolina officials did not recognize the 1918 football team as a varsity program because it was under the auspices of the SATC).<ref name=unc>{{cite news|url=https://virginiachronicle.com/?a=d&d=RTD19181124.1.27&srpos=2&e=23-11-1918-25-11-1918-191-en-20--1-byDA.rev-txt-txIN-football+carolina----1918--|title=Virginia Tech's String of Victories Unbroken|date=November 24, 1918|work=Richmond Times-Dispatch}}</ref> Tech outweighed UNC by 15 pounds per man. drove to the 10-yard line in the first three minutes, but was unable to score. In the second quarter, Crisp scored a touchdown on a fake end run from the 6-yard line. UNC's Bristol had a 70-yard run soon after, to the 20-year line. A forward pass from Pharr to Fearrington resulted in a touchdown for UNC.<ref name=unc/>\n\nIn the third quarter a series of passes from UNC toot the Tar Heels to the 15-yard line, then Crocker intercepted a pass a ran 90 yards for the touchdown. Rangley of UNC plunged for the final score in the fourth quarter.<ref name=unc/>\n\nTech's starting lineup against UNC: Roden (left end), Rangley (left tackle), Tilson (left guard), Resh (center), Quarles (right guard), Pierce (right tackle), Hardwick (right end), Crisp (quarterback), Robinson (left halfback), Maddox (right halfback), Bonney (fullback).<ref name=unc/>\n\n===VMI===\n{{AFB game box start\n| Title = '''VPI vs. VMI'''\n| Visitor = '''VPI'''\n| Host = VMI\n| V1 = 0| V2 =0| V3 =6| V4 =0\n| H1 = 0| H2 =0| H3 =0| H4 =0\n| Date =November 28\n| Location = Fair Grounds<br />Roanoke, VA\n| StartTime =3:00 p.m.\n| ElapsedTime =\n| Attendance =2,500\n| Weather =\n| Referee =[[Bob Peck (American football)|Bob Peck]]\n}}\n*'''Sources:'''<ref name=vmidown/>\n{{AFB game box end}}\nThe season closed against VMI on Thanksgiving Day. The [[Norfolk and Western Railway|Norfolk and Western Railroad]] ran two special trains for VPI and VMI students to attend the game in Roanoke.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://virginiachronicle.com/?a=d&d=TWN19181118.1.3&srpos=2&e=16-11-1918-18-11-1918-191-en-20--1-byDA.rev-txt-txIN-football----1918--|work=World News|date=November 18, 1918|title=Two Special Trains}}</ref> Tech defeated VMI 6\u20130. In the third quarter, Harry Roden blocked a VMI [[Punt (gridiron football)|punt]] at the 10-yard line. Three runs [[Off-tackle run|off tackle]] by Crisp resulted in the game's lone touchdown.<ref name=vmidown/>\n\nTech's starting lineup against VMI: Roden (left end), Hardwick (left tackle), Tilson (left guard), Resh (center), Quarles (right guard), Pierce (right tackle), Camper (right end), Crisp (quarterback), Crocker (left halfback), Mattox (right halfback), Bonney (fullback).<ref name=vmidown/>\n\n==After the season==\n[[File:CrispatVPI.jpg|thumb|upright=0.75|Hank Crisp was co-captain of the only Virginia Tech football team to go undefeated.|alt=]]Coach Bernier wrote a story in the 1919 [[Walter Camp]]-edited ''Spalding Foot Ball Guide'' praising Crisp, one of the team's captains:<ref name=\"camp\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/officialfootball19181nati|title=Spalding's Official Foot Ball Guide 1919|editor-last=Camp|editor-first=Walter|publisher=|year=1919|isbn=|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/officialfootball19181nati/page/53 53]}}</ref>{{Quote | style=font-size: 100%; |\"[[Uncle Sam]] could not use a one-hand man, so Henry Crisp, much to Tech's good fortune, played the next biggest game [referring to football compared to war fighting], and to him, more than anyone else, goes the glory for a driving, consistent attack.  This big fellow, playing in the back-field for the first time, literally mowed them all down...\"<ref name=camp />}}Crisp was the captain of the All-South Atlantic Eleven team (league MVP), and was joined on that team by the Gobblers' James Hardwick (end), Walter Wrangley (tackle), and Charles Quarles (center).<ref name=\"camp\" />\n\n==Players==\nThe following players were members of the 1918 football team according to the roster published in the 1919 edition of ''The Bugle'', the Virginia Tech yearbook.<ref name = Bugle19 />\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"text-align: left;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"9\" style=\"background:#660000;color:#FF6600;text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"color:#FF6600;\">'''VPI 1918 roster'''</span>\n|-\n|\n| style=\"font-size:95%; vertical-align:top;\"|'''[[Quarterback]]'''\n* Wesley Leroy Bonney\n'''[[Guard (American and Canadian football)|Guards]]'''\n* Charles Walthall Quarles\n* [[Sumner D. Tilson]]\n'''[[Tackle (gridiron football position)|Tackles]]'''\n* Walter Morgan Pierce\n* Walter Weiss Rangely\n'''[[Center (gridiron football)|Center]]'''\n* Franklin Senatre Resh\n| style=\"width: 25px;\" |\n|  style=\"font-size:95%; vertical-align:top;\"|'''[[End (gridiron football)|Ends]]'''\n* Julian Jessings Camper\n* James Thomas Hardwick\n* Harry Douglas Roden (Capt.)\n* [[Monk Younger|William Lee Younger (Capt.)]]\n'''[[Halfback (American football)|Halfbacks]]'''\n* [[Hank Crisp]] (Capt.)\n* Philip Crocker\n* Harry Lee McCann\n| style=\"width: 25px;\" |\n|  style=\"font-size:95%; vertical-align:top;\"|'''[[Fullback (gridiron football)|Fullback]]'''\n* William Hurst\n'''[[Substitution (sport)|Substitutes]]'''\n* Eugene Darrington Bock\n* John Kelly Copenhaver\n* Hitchens\n* Huddle\n* Samuel Anderson McConkey\n* Seigle\n* Charles Evans Whitmore\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Virginia Tech Hokies football navbox}}\n{{SAIAA football champions}}\n\n[[Category:1918 South Atlantic Intercollegiate Athletic Association football season|VPI]]\n[[Category:Virginia Tech Hokies football seasons]]\n[[Category:South Atlantic Intercollegiate Athletic Association football champion seasons]]\n[[Category:College football undefeated seasons]]\n[[Category:1918 in sports in Virginia|VPI Football]]\n", "name_user": "Deanrah", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWorld War I and the Spanish Flu", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1918_VPI_Gobblers_football_team"}
{"title_page": "1st Company Massachusetts Sharpshooters", "text_new": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name= 1st Company Massachusetts Sharpshooters\n|image=\n|dates= September 2, 1861, to September 6, 1864\n|country= {{flagicon|USA|1861}}[[United States]]\n|allegiance= [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch= [[United States Army]]\n|type= [[Sharpshooters]]\n|equipment= \n<!-- Culture and history -->\n|battles= [[Battle of Ball's Bluff]]<br/>[[Siege of Yorktown (1862)|Siege of Yorktown]]<br/>[[Battle of Fair Oaks]]<br/>[[Seven Days Battles]]<br/>[[Battle of Antietam]]<br/>[[Battle of Fredericksburg]]<br/>[[Battle of Chancellorsville]]<br/>[[Battle of Gettysburg]]<br/>[[Mud March (American Civil War)|Mud March]]<br/>[[Mine Run Campaign]]<br/>[[Battle of the Wilderness]]<br/>[[Battle of Spotsylvania Court House]]<br/>[[Battle of Cold Harbor]]<br/>[[Siege of Petersburg]]<br/>[[First Battle of Deep Bottom]]<br/>[[Second Battle of Deep Bottom]]<br/>[[Second Battle of Ream's Station]]\n|commander1= John Saunders\n|commander1_label= [[Captain (United States)|Captain]]\n|commander2= William Plumer\n|commander2_label= [[Captain (United States)|Captain]]\n}}\n\n[[File:1st Co. Andrew Sharp Shooters on Round Top Avenue - Mumper & Co., photo. artists, Baltimore St., Gettysburg, Pa. LCCN2017660648.jpg|thumb|Monument to the 1st Massachusetts Sharpshooters at Gettysburg]]\n \nThe '''1st Company Massachusetts Sharpshooters''' was a [[sharpshooter]] unit in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]].\n\n==Service==\nThe 1st Company Massachusetts Sharpshooters was organized in [[Lynn, Massachusetts|Lynn]], [[Massachusetts]] and mustered in for three years service on September 2, 1861<ref name=\"Dyer\">Dyer</ref>. The company was originally recruited for [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]] [[Hiram Berdan]]'s sharpshooter regiments. When the men were informed that they would lose their enlistment bounty, they declined to join Berdan's regiments and instead remained independent<ref name=\"Ellis\">Ellis</ref>. Most of the recruits tended to be skilled workmen who were competitive shooters tending to be older than the average Union soldier, and these men also tended to be of the larger physical size<ref name=\"de la Roche\">de la Roche</ref>. They were armed with heavy, custom target rifles and Sharps rifles during their service.<ref name=\"de la Roche\" /><ref name=\"Wieland2011\">{{cite book|last=Wieland|first=Terry|title=Gun Digest Book of Classic American Combat Rifles|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k_VdJewva78C&pg=PT188|year=2011|publisher=[[Krause Publications]]|location=Iola, Wisconsin|isbn=1-4402-3017-X|page=188}}</ref>\n\nThe company was attached to 3rd Brigade, 2nd Division, [[II Corps (Union Army)|II Corps]], [[Army of the Potomac]], but nominally operated with the [[15th Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry|15th Massachusetts Infantry]] to July 1864, and with the [[19th Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry|19th Massachusetts Infantry]] to September 1864<ref name=\"Ellis\" />.\n\nThe 1st Company Massachusetts Sharpshooters mustered out September 6, 1864.\n\n===Detailed service===\n\n====1861====\n* Left Massachusetts for Washington, D.C., September 2. \n* Picket and outpost duty on the Upper Potomac River from Conrad's Ferry to Harrison's Island until October 20. \n* Operations on the Potomac River October 21\u201324. \n* [[Battle of Ball's Bluff]] October 21. \n* At Harpers Ferry and Bolivar Heights until March 7, 1862.\n\n====1862====\n* At Charlestown until March 10. ''Capt. John Saunders of Salem, MA commanding''\n* At Berryville until March 13. \n* Movement toward Winchester and return to Bolivar Heights March 13\u201315. \n* The [[Peninsula campaign]] (March 17-August 4)\n** Moved to [[Fortress Monroe]] March 22-April 1. \n** [[Siege of Yorktown (1862)|Siege of Yorktown]] April 5-May 4.  \u2014 ''Attached to [[Willis A. Gorman|Gorman]]'s 1st Brigade, [[John Sedgwick|Sedgwick]]'s 2nd Division, [[Edwin Vose Sumner|Sumner]]'s [[II Corps (Union Army)|II Corps]], [[George B. McClellan|McClellan]]'s [[Army of the Potomac]]''<ref name=\"OoB\">''Official Records, Series I, Volume XXVII, Part 1, [http://ebooks.library.cornell.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=moawar&cc=moawar&idno=waro0043&node=waro0043%3A2&view=image&seq=175&size=100 pages 155-168]; [http://www.nps.gov/gett/historyculture/aop-orderofbattle.htm Gettysburg National Military Park-Army of the Potomac] ''</ref>\n** [[Battle of Seven Pines|Battle of Fair Oaks, Seven Pines]], May 31-June 1.\n** [[Seven Days Battles|Seven Days before Richmond]] June 25-July 1. \u2014 ''Attached to [[Alfred Sully|Sully]]'s 1st Brigade, Sedgwick's 2nd Division, Sumner's II Corps''<ref name=\"OoB\" />\n*** Peach Orchard and [[Battle of Savage's Station]] June 29. \n*** [[Battle of White Oak Swamp|White Oak Swamp]] and [[Battle of Glendale|Glendale]] June 30.\n*** [[Battle of Malvern Hill]] July 1. \n** At Harrison's Landing until August 15. \n* Movement to Alexandria August 15\u201328\n* To Centreville, [[Second Battle of Bull Run]] August 29\u201330. \n* Cover Pope's retreat August 31-September 1. \n* [[Battle of Antietam]], September 16\u201317. \u2014 ''Attached to Gorman's 1st Brigade, Sedgwick's 2nd Division, Sumner's II Corps''<ref name=\"OoB\" /> \u2014 ''Supported II Corps attack, sniping at opposing officers and snipers. Captain Sanders killed with nine others.''\n* Moved to Harpers Ferry September 22 and duty there until October 30. \n* Movement to Falmouth, Va., October 30-November 20.\n* On Picket, Falmouth to 12 December \u2014 ''9 December, eighteen men on muster roll. Captain William Plummer of Cambridge, MA, arrived with forty recruits and took command of the company.''<ref name=\"Ellis\" /> \n* [[Battle of Fredericksburg]] December 12\u201315. \u2014 ''Attached to Sully's 1st Brigade, [[Oliver O. Howard|Howard]]'s 2nd Division, [[Darius N. Couch|Couch]]'s II Corps''<ref name=\"OoB\" /> \u2014 ''Provided counter-sniper fire during construction of pontoon bridges and crossing 11 and 12 December. Set up positions on outskirts of city below Marye's Heights targeting artillerymen on the heights.''\n\n====1863====\n* \"Mud March\" January 20\u201324. \n* [[Chancellorsville Campaign]] April 27-May 6. \u2014 ''Attached to [[John Gibbon|Gibbon]]'s 2nd Division, Couch's II Corps, [[Joseph Hooker|Hooker]]'s Army of the Potomac''<ref name=\"OoB\" />\n** Maryes Heights, [[Second Battle of Fredericksburg]], May 3. \n** Salem Heights May 3\u20134. \n** Banks' Ford May 4. \n* [[Battle of Gettysburg]]<ref name=\"Dyer\" />, July 2\u20134. \u2014 ''Attached to [[John Gibbon|Gibbon]]'s/[[William Harrow|Harrow]]'s 2nd Division, [[Winfield S. Hancock|Hancock]]'s/Gibbon's/[[William Hays (general)|Hays]]'<ref name=\"Hancock\">After the death of General Reynolds, General Hancock was assigned to the command of all troops on the field of battle [http://ebooks.library.cornell.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=moawar&cc=moawar&idno=waro0045&node=waro0045%3A5&frm=frameset&view=image&seq=463], relieving General Howard, who had succeeded General Reynolds. General Gibbon, of the Second Division, assumed command of the corps. These assignments terminated on the evening of July 1. Similar changes in commanders occurred during the battle of the 2nd, when General Hancock was put in command of the Third Corps in addition to that of his own. He was wounded on the 3rd, and Brigadier General William Hays [http://ebooks.library.cornell.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=moawar&cc=moawar&idno=waro0045&node=waro0045%3A5&frm=frameset&view=image&seq=505] was assigned to the command of the corps.</ref> II Corps, [[George G. Meade|Meade]]'s Army of the Potomac''<ref name=\"OoB\" /> \u2014\n''Arrived morning 2 July, positioned at rock wall on the north end of Cemetery Ridge, several squads were detached and sent to different parts of the line. Cleared out Confederate snipers occupying Bliss farm. In late afternoon, when II Corps retook Bliss farm, a squad went with them to snipe from the farm. No losses 2 July.''<br>\n''On 3 July, unit dueled with Confederate snipers in buildings in Gettysburg facing Cemetery Hill and Ridge. During Pickett's Charge, unit concentrated targeting on officers. Suffered four dead, three wounded.''<ref name=\"Elmore\">{{Cite web|title = First Company Massachusetts \u201cAndrew Sharpshooters\u201d at Gettysburg|url = https://civilwartalk.com/threads/first-company-massachusetts-%E2%80%9Candrew-sharpshooters%E2%80%9D-at-gettysburg.144393/|website = civilwartalk.com|accessdate = 2018-09-28}}</ref>\n* Advance from the Rappahannock to the Rapidan September 13\u201317. \n* [[Bristoe Campaign]] October 9\u201322. \u2014 ''Attached to [[Alexander S. Webb|Webb]]'s 2nd Division, [[Gouverneur K. Warren|Warren]]'s II Corps, Meade's Army of the Potomac''<ref name=\"OoB\" />\n** [[Battle of Bristoe Station]] October 14. \n* Advance to line of the Rappahannock, [[Second Battle of Rappahannock Station]] November 7\u20138. \n* [[Mine Run Campaign]] November 26-December 2. \u2014 ''Attached to Morehead 3rd Brigade, Webb's 2nd Division, Warren's II Corps, Meade's Army of the Potomac''<ref name=\"OoB\" /> \n* Robertson's Tavern or Locust Grove November 27.\n\n====1864====\n* Morton's Ford February 6\u20137. \n* Picketing Rapidan River until May 1. \n* The Overland Campaign May 4 \u2013 June 24\n** [[Battle of the Wilderness|Battle of the Wilderness May 5\u20137]]. \n** Laurel Hill May 8. \n** [[Battle of Spotsylvania Court House|Battle of Spotsylvania Court House, May 8\u201321]]. \n*** Po River May 10. \n*** Assault on the Salient at Spotsylvania Court House May 12. \n** [[Battle of North Anna|Battle of North Anna River May 23-26]] \n** Line of the Pamunkey May 26\u201328. \n** [[Battle of Totopotomoy Creek]] May 28\u201331. \n** [[Battle of Cold Harbor]] June 1\u201312. \n** Before Petersburg June 16\u201318. \n** [[Siege of Petersburg]] June 16-July 12. \n** [[Battle of Jerusalem Plank Road]] June 22\u201323. \n* Demonstration north of the James River July 27\u201329. \n* [[Battle of Deep Bottom]] July 27\u201328. \n* Strawberry Plains, Deep Bottom, August 14\u201318. \n* Ream's Station August 25.\n\n===Casualties===\nThe company lost a total of 39 men during service; 3 officers and 21 enlisted men killed or mortally wounded, 15 enlisted men due to disease.\n\n===Commanders===\n* [[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]] John Saunders - killed in action at the Battle of Antietam\n* Captain William Plumer\n\n==Armament==\n[[File:Sharps 1852 Verschluss offen.JPG|thumb|left|Sharps Model 1852 \"Slanting Breech\" Carbine, open for loading, two primer-tapes]]\n[[File:Berdan Sharps rifle.jpg|thumb|300px|Sharps rifle in [[.50-70 Government]].]]\n\nThroughout their service, the company was armed with custom, heavy target rifles equipped with telescopic sights running the length of the barrel. The larger than average physical size of the unit members proved an asset in carrying these weapons<ref name=\"de la Roche\" />. \n\nStarting at Antietam, they also carried [[Sharps rifle|Sharps rifles]] in the field firing over the iron sights. The Sharps Rifle was produced by the [[Sharps Rifle Manufacturing Company]] in Hartford, Connecticut.<ref name=\"Flatnes2014\">{{cite book|last=Flatnes|first=Oyvind|title=From Musket to Metallic Cartridge: A Practical History of Black Powder Firearms|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8I48nwEACAAJ|year=2014|publisher=Crowood Press, Limited|isbn=978-1-84797-593-5|pages=123\u2013125}}</ref> The Sharps made a superior [[sniper]] weapon of greater accuracy than the more commonly issued [[Muzzleloader|muzzle-loading]] [[rifled musket]]s. This was due mainly to the higher rate of fire of the [[Breech-loading weapon|breech loading]] mechanism and superior quality of manufacture, as well as the ease of which it could be reloaded from a kneeling or prone position.<ref name=\"Wieland2011\"/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* [http://www.civilwarhome.com/gettysburgorderofbattle%28union%29.htm Civilwarhome - Gettysburg Union order of battle]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110603055742/http://www.civilwar.org/battlefields/gettysburg/gettysburg-history-articles/order-of-battle-aop-gettysburg.html Civil War Trust - Gettysburg Union order of battle]\n* Dyer, Frederick H. ''A Compendium of the War of the Rebellion'' (Des Moines, IA:  Dyer Pub. Co.), 1908.\n* Eicher, John H. [http://www.gdg.org/Research/OOB/EicherOOB.htm \"Gettysburg Order of Battle\"] at Gettysburg Discussion Group website.\n* Ellis, Alden C. Jr. ''The Massachusetts Andrew Sharpshooters: A Civil War History and Roster'' (Jefferson, NC: McFarland & Company, Inc.), 2012. {{ISBN|0-7864-6489-5}}\n* [ttps://civilwartalk.com/threads/first-company-massachusetts-%E2%80%9Candrew-sharpshooters%E2%80%9D-at-gettysburg.144393/ First Company Massachusetts \u201cAndrew Sharpshooters\u201d at Gettysburg]\n* [http://www.gdg.org/research/OOB/Union/gburg_un.html Gettysburg Discussion Group - Union order of battle]\n* [http://www.nps.gov/gett/historyculture/aop-orderofbattle.htm Gettysburg National Military Park - The Army of the Potomac at Gettysburg]\n* {{cite book|author=Oyvind Flatnes|title=From Musket to Metallic Cartridge: A Practical History of Black Powder Firearms|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/From-Musket-Metallic-Cartridge-Practical/dp/1847975933|year=2013|publisher=Crowood Press|isbn=978-1847975935|pages=123\u2013125}}\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Senechal de la Roche |editor1-first=Roberta |title=\"Our Aim Was Man\": Andrew's Sharpshooters in the American Civil War |date=2016 |publisher=University of Massachusetts Press |location=Amherst, Massachusetts |isbn=978-1-62534-248-5}}\n* U.S. War Department, [http://cdl.library.cornell.edu/moa/browse.monographs/waro.html ''The War of the Rebellion'']: ''a Compilation of the [[Official Records of the American Civil War|Official Records]] of the Union and Confederate Armies''. Washington, DC: U.S. Government Printing Office, 1880&ndash;1901.\n\n;Attribution\n* {{CWR}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|American Civil War|United States}}\n* [[15th Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry]]\n* [[19th Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry]]\n* [[120th Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry]]\n* [[List of Massachusetts Civil War units]]\n* [[Massachusetts in the American Civil War]]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://gettysburg.stonesentinels.com/union-monuments/massachusetts/1st-massachusetts-sharp-shooters/ 1st Company Massachusetts Sharpshooters monument at Gettysburg]\n\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1861]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1864]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Civil War regiments]]\n[[Category:Sharpshooter units and formations of the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:1861 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name= 1st Company Massachusetts Sharpshooters\n|image=\n|dates= September 2, 1861, to September 6, 1864\n|country= {{flagicon|USA|1861}}[[United States]]\n|allegiance= [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\n|branch= [[United States Army]]\n|type= [[Sharpshooters]]\n|equipment= \n<!-- Culture and history -->\n|battles= [[Battle of Ball's Bluff]]<br/>[[Siege of Yorktown (1862)|Siege of Yorktown]]<br/>[[Battle of Fair Oaks]]<br/>[[Seven Days Battles]]<br/>[[Battle of Antietam]]<br/>[[Battle of Fredericksburg]]<br/>[[Battle of Chancellorsville]]<br/>[[Battle of Gettysburg]]<br/>[[Mud March (American Civil War)|Mud March]]<br/>[[Mine Run Campaign]]<br/>[[Battle of the Wilderness]]<br/>[[Battle of Spotsylvania Court House]]<br/>[[Battle of Cold Harbor]]<br/>[[Siege of Petersburg]]<br/>[[First Battle of Deep Bottom]]<br/>[[Second Battle of Deep Bottom]]<br/>[[Second Battle of Ream's Station]]\n|commander1= John Saunders\n|commander1_label= [[Captain (United States)|Captain]]\n|commander2= William Plumer\n|commander2_label= [[Captain (United States)|Captain]]\n}}\n\n[[File:1st Co. Andrew Sharp Shooters on Round Top Avenue - Mumper & Co., photo. artists, Baltimore St., Gettysburg, Pa. LCCN2017660648.jpg|thumb|Monument to the 1st Massachusetts Sharpshooters at Gettysburg]]\n \nThe '''1st Company Massachusetts Sharpshooters''' was a [[sharpshooter]] unit in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]].\n\n==Service==\nThe 1st Company Massachusetts Sharpshooters was organized in [[Lynn, Massachusetts|Lynn]], [[Massachusetts]] and mustered in for three years service on September 2, 1861<ref name=\"Dyer\">Dyer</ref>. The company was originally recruited for [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]] [[Hiram Berdan]]'s sharpshooter regiments. When the men were informed that they would lose their enlistment bounty, they declined to join Berdan's regiments and instead remained independent<ref name=\"Ellis\">Ellis</ref>. Most of the recruits tended to be skilled workmen who were competitive shooters tending to be older than the average Union soldier, and these men also tended to be of the larger physical size<ref name=\"de la Roche\">de la Roche</ref>. They were armed with heavy, custom target rifles and Sharps rifles during their service.<ref name=\"de la Roche\" /><ref name=\"Wieland2011\">{{cite book|last=Wieland|first=Terry|title=Gun Digest Book of Classic American Combat Rifles|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k_VdJewva78C&pg=PT188|year=2011|publisher=[[Krause Publications]]|location=Iola, Wisconsin|isbn=1-4402-3017-X|page=188}}</ref>\n\nThe company was attached to 3rd Brigade, 2nd Division, [[II Corps (Union Army)|II Corps]], [[Army of the Potomac]], but nominally operated with the [[15th Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry|15th Massachusetts Infantry]] to July 1864, and with the [[19th Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry|19th Massachusetts Infantry]] to September 1864<ref name=\"Ellis\" />.\n\nThe 1st Company Massachusetts Sharpshooters mustered out September 6, 1864.\n\n===Detailed service===\n\n====1861====\n* Left Massachusetts for Washington, D.C., September 2. \n* Picket and outpost duty on the Upper Potomac River from Conrad's Ferry to Harrison's Island until October 20. \n* Operations on the Potomac River October 21\u201324. \n* [[Battle of Ball's Bluff]] October 21. \n* At Harpers Ferry and Bolivar Heights until March 7, 1862.\n\n====1862====\n* At Charlestown until March 10. ''Capt. John Saunders of Salem, MA commanding''\n* At Berryville until March 13. \n* Movement toward Winchester and return to Bolivar Heights March 13\u201315. \n* The [[Peninsula campaign]] (March 17-August 4)\n** Moved to [[Fortress Monroe]] March 22-April 1. \n** [[Siege of Yorktown (1862)|Siege of Yorktown]] April 5-May 4.  \u2014 ''Attached to [[Willis A. Gorman|Gorman]]'s 1st Brigade, [[John Sedgwick|Sedgwick]]'s 2nd Division, [[Edwin Vose Sumner|Sumner]]'s [[II Corps (Union Army)|II Corps]], [[George B. McClellan|McClellan]]'s [[Army of the Potomac]]''<ref name=\"OoB\">''Official Records, Series I, Volume XXVII, Part 1, [http://ebooks.library.cornell.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=moawar&cc=moawar&idno=waro0043&node=waro0043%3A2&view=image&seq=175&size=100 pages 155-168]; [http://www.nps.gov/gett/historyculture/aop-orderofbattle.htm Gettysburg National Military Park-Army of the Potomac] ''</ref>\n** [[Battle of Seven Pines|Battle of Fair Oaks, Seven Pines]], May 31-June 1.\n** [[Seven Days Battles|Seven Days before Richmond]] June 25-July 1. \u2014 ''Attached to [[Alfred Sully|Sully]]'s 1st Brigade, Sedgwick's 2nd Division, Sumner's II Corps''<ref name=\"OoB\" />\n*** Peach Orchard and [[Battle of Savage's Station]] June 29. \n*** [[Battle of White Oak Swamp|White Oak Swamp]] and [[Battle of Glendale|Glendale]] June 30.\n*** [[Battle of Malvern Hill]] July 1. \n** At Harrison's Landing until August 15. \n* Movement to Alexandria August 15\u201328\n* To Centreville, [[Second Battle of Bull Run]] August 29\u201330. \n* Cover Pope's retreat August 31-September 1. \n* [[Battle of Antietam]], September 16\u201317. \u2014 ''Attached to Gorman's 1st Brigade, Sedgwick's 2nd Division, Sumner's II Corps''<ref name=\"OoB\" /> \u2014 ''Supported II Corps attack, sniping at opposing officers and snipers. Captain Sanders killed with nine others.''\n* Moved to Harpers Ferry September 22 and duty there until October 30. \n* Movement to Falmouth, Va., October 30-November 20.\n* On Picket, Falmouth to 12 December \u2014 ''9 December, eighteen men on muster roll. Captain William Plummer of Cambridge, MA, arrived with forty recruits and took command of the company.''<ref name=\"Ellis\" /> \n* [[Battle of Fredericksburg]] December 12\u201315. \u2014 ''Attached to Sully's 1st Brigade, [[Oliver O. Howard|Howard]]'s 2nd Division, [[Darius N. Couch|Couch]]'s II Corps''<ref name=\"OoB\" /> \u2014 ''Provided counter-sniper fire during construction of pontoon bridges and crossing 11 and 12 December. Set up positions on outskirts of city below Marye's Heights targeting artillerymen on the heights.''\n\n====1863====\n* \"Mud March\" January 20\u201324. \n* [[Chancellorsville Campaign]] April 27-May 6. \u2014 ''Attached to [[John Gibbon|Gibbon]]'s 2nd Division, Couch's II Corps, [[Joseph Hooker|Hooker]]'s Army of the Potomac''<ref name=\"OoB\" />\n** Maryes Heights, [[Second Battle of Fredericksburg]], May 3. \n** Salem Heights May 3\u20134. \n** Banks' Ford May 4. \n* [[Battle of Gettysburg]]<ref name=\"Dyer\" />, July 2\u20134. \u2014 ''Attached to [[John Gibbon|Gibbon]]'s/[[William Harrow|Harrow]]'s 2nd Division, [[Winfield S. Hancock|Hancock]]'s/Gibbon's/[[William Hays (general)|Hays]]'<ref name=\"Hancock\">After the death of General Reynolds, General Hancock was assigned to the command of all troops on the field of battle [http://ebooks.library.cornell.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=moawar&cc=moawar&idno=waro0045&node=waro0045%3A5&frm=frameset&view=image&seq=463], relieving General Howard, who had succeeded General Reynolds. General Gibbon, of the Second Division, assumed command of the corps. These assignments terminated on the evening of July 1. Similar changes in commanders occurred during the battle of the 2nd, when General Hancock was put in command of the Third Corps in addition to that of his own. He was wounded on the 3rd, and Brigadier General William Hays [http://ebooks.library.cornell.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=moawar&cc=moawar&idno=waro0045&node=waro0045%3A5&frm=frameset&view=image&seq=505] was assigned to the command of the corps.</ref> II Corps, [[George G. Meade|Meade]]'s Army of the Potomac''<ref name=\"OoB\" /> \u2014\n''Arrived morning 2 July, positioned at rock wall on the north end of Cemetery Ridge, several squads were detached and sent to different parts of the line. Cleared out Confederate snipers occupying Bliss farm. In late afternoon, when II Corps retook Bliss farm, a squad went with them to snipe from the farm. No losses 2 July.''<br>\n''On 3 July, unit dueled with Confederate snipers in buildings in Gettysburg facing Cemetery Hill and Ridge. During Pickett's Charge, unit concentrated targeting on officers. Suffered four dead, three wounded.''<ref name=\"Elmore\">{{Cite web|title = First Company Massachusetts \u201cAndrew Sharpshooters\u201d at Gettysburg|url = https://civilwartalk.com/threads/first-company-massachusetts-%E2%80%9Candrew-sharpshooters%E2%80%9D-at-gettysburg.144393/|website = civilwartalk.com|accessdate = 2018-09-28}}</ref>\n* Advance from the Rappahannock to the Rapidan September 13\u201317. \n* [[Bristoe Campaign]] October 9\u201322. \u2014 ''Attached to [[Alexander S. Webb|Webb]]'s 2nd Division, [[Gouverneur K. Warren|Warren]]'s II Corps, Meade's Army of the Potomac''<ref name=\"OoB\" />\n** [[Battle of Bristoe Station]] October 14. \n* Advance to line of the Rappahannock, [[Second Battle of Rappahannock Station]] November 7\u20138. \n* [[Mine Run Campaign]] November 26-December 2. \u2014 ''Attached to Morehead 3rd Brigade, Webb's 2nd Division, Warren's II Corps, Meade's Army of the Potomac''<ref name=\"OoB\" /> \n* Robertson's Tavern or Locust Grove November 27.\n\n====1864====\n* Morton's Ford February 6\u20137. \n* Picketing Rapidan River until May 1. \n* The Overland Campaign May 4 \u2013 June 24\n** [[Battle of the Wilderness|Battle of the Wilderness May 5\u20137]]. \n** Laurel Hill May 8. \n** [[Battle of Spotsylvania Court House|Battle of Spotsylvania Court House, May 8\u201321]]. \n*** Po River May 10. \n*** Assault on the Salient at Spotsylvania Court House May 12. \n** [[Battle of North Anna|Battle of North Anna River May 23-26]] \n** Line of the Pamunkey May 26\u201328. \n** [[Battle of Totopotomoy Creek]] May 28\u201331. \n** [[Battle of Cold Harbor]] June 1\u201312. \n** Before Petersburg June 16\u201318. \n** [[Siege of Petersburg]] June 16-July 12. \n** [[Battle of Jerusalem Plank Road]] June 22\u201323. \n* Demonstration north of the James River July 27\u201329. \n* [[Battle of Deep Bottom]] July 27\u201328. \n* Strawberry Plains, Deep Bottom, August 14\u201318. \n* Ream's Station August 25.\n\n===Casualties===\nThe company lost a total of 39 men during service; 3 officers and 21 enlisted men killed or mortally wounded, 15 enlisted men due to disease.\n\n===Commanders===\n* [[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]] John Saunders - killed in action at the Battle of Antietam\n* Captain William Plumer\n\n==Armament==\n[[File:Sharps 1852 Verschluss offen.JPG|thumb|left|Sharps Model 1852 \"Slanting Breech\" Carbine, open for loading, two primer-tapes]]\n[[File:Berdan Sharps rifle.jpg|thumb|300px|Sharps rifle in [[.50-70 Government]].]]\n\nThroughout their service, the company was armed with custom, heavy target rifles equipped with telescopic sights running the length of the barrel. The larger than average physical size of the unit members proved an asset in carrying these weapons<ref name=\"de la Roche\" />. \n\nStarting at Antietam, they also carried [[Sharps rifle|Sharps rifles]] in the field firing over the iron sights. The Sharps Rifle was produced by the [[Sharps Rifle Manufacturing Company]] in Hartford, Connecticut.<ref name=\"Flatnes2014\">{{cite book|last=Flatnes|first=Oyvind|title=From Musket to Metallic Cartridge: A Practical History of Black Powder Firearms|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8I48nwEACAAJ|year=2014|publisher=Crowood Press, Limited|isbn=978-1-84797-593-5|pages=123\u2013125}}</ref> The Sharps made a superior [[sniper]] weapon of greater accuracy than the more commonly issued [[Muzzleloader|muzzle-loading]] [[rifled musket]]s. This was due mainly to the higher rate of fire of the [[Breech-loading weapon|breech loading]] mechanism and superior quality of manufacture, as well as the ease of which it could be reloaded from a kneeling or prone position.<ref name=\"Wieland2011\"/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* [http://www.civilwarhome.com/gettysburgorderofbattle%28union%29.htm Civilwarhome - Gettysburg Union order of battle]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110603055742/http://www.civilwar.org/battlefields/gettysburg/gettysburg-history-articles/order-of-battle-aop-gettysburg.html Civil War Trust - Gettysburg Union order of battle]\n* Dyer, Frederick H. ''A Compendium of the War of the Rebellion'' (Des Moines, IA:  Dyer Pub. Co.), 1908.\n* Eicher, John H. [http://www.gdg.org/Research/OOB/EicherOOB.htm \"Gettysburg Order of Battle\"] at Gettysburg Discussion Group website.\n* Ellis, Alden C. Jr. ''The Massachusetts Andrew Sharpshooters: A Civil War History and Roster'' (Jefferson, NC: McFarland & Company, Inc.), 2012. {{ISBN|0-7864-6489-5}}\n* [ttps://civilwartalk.com/threads/first-company-massachusetts-%E2%80%9Candrew-sharpshooters%E2%80%9D-at-gettysburg.144393/ First Company Massachusetts \u201cAndrew Sharpshooters\u201d at Gettysburg]\n* [http://www.gdg.org/research/OOB/Union/gburg_un.html Gettysburg Discussion Group - Union order of battle]\n* [http://www.nps.gov/gett/historyculture/aop-orderofbattle.htm Gettysburg National Military Park - The Army of the Potomac at Gettysburg]\n* {{cite book |editor1-last=Senechal de la Roche |editor1-first=Roberta |title=\"Our Aim Was Man\": Andrew's Sharpshooters in the American Civil War |date=2016 |publisher=University of Massachusetts Press |location=Amherst, Massachusetts |isbn=978-1-62534-248-5}}\n* U.S. War Department, [http://cdl.library.cornell.edu/moa/browse.monographs/waro.html ''The War of the Rebellion'']: ''a Compilation of the [[Official Records of the American Civil War|Official Records]] of the Union and Confederate Armies''. Washington, DC: U.S. Government Printing Office, 1880&ndash;1901.\n\n;Attribution\n* {{CWR}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|American Civil War|United States}}\n* [[15th Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry]]\n* [[19th Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry]]\n* [[120th Regiment Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry]]\n* [[List of Massachusetts Civil War units]]\n* [[Massachusetts in the American Civil War]]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://gettysburg.stonesentinels.com/union-monuments/massachusetts/1st-massachusetts-sharp-shooters/ 1st Company Massachusetts Sharpshooters monument at Gettysburg]\n\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1861]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1864]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Civil War regiments]]\n[[Category:Sharpshooter units and formations of the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:1861 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "Hhfjbaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1st_Company_Massachusetts_Sharpshooters"}
